<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9274 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GRAMMYS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-26 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTENING TO THE GRAMMYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(bl) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans bought an estimated $14 billion or more of recorded
music last year. And music, arguably even more than movies or
television, has been the vanguard of the post-World War II American
cultural onslaught that has swept through the world.
</P>
<P>
   So it's odd, in a way, that the annual Grammy Awards show, which
was broadcast last week to a domestic audience of over 27 million
people, is a kind of musical Land That Time Forgot, a place where,
as they used to say at the Holiday Inn, the best surprise is no
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the music business tries to place its imprimatur
on the ungovernable energies of American pop culture. ``Old people
_ the Grammy voters _ like to be reminded that the young people
aren't taking over, which is ironic when you're talking about pop
music,'' notes Robert Wilonsky, popular culture critic for the
Dallas Observer.
</P>
<P>
   Wilonsky's observation, given that this is an organization that
awarded Petula Clark a Grammy over the Beatles, makes sense. ``You
can't assume that the Grammys take place in a universe similar to
our own,'' Wilonsky continues. ``The Grammys take place in the
Bizarro Universe.''
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that the Grammys probably won't play the
favorite tunes of a hip 15-year-old California skateboarder, or a
hip-hop crazy girl from East Flatbush, Brooklyn. Instead, you'll
get a snapshot of the sounds that have migrated from the cutting
edge to the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with 52-year-old Carlos Santana lugging home eight of
the miniature gramophone statuettes for his album ``Supernatural''
_ one wondered if he was going to somehow pull off a Best New
Artist award _ we learned that age does come before beauty. Sting
walked off with two of the Grammys that Santana wasn't up for, and
Cher and Tony Bennett were also winners in the ceremony. (Best
Female Rock Performance winner Sheryl Crow had the good sense to
thank Santana for not mucking around in her category.)
</P>
<P>
   Santana. Sting. Cher. Will Smith _ the Artist Formerly Known as
the Fresh Prince. Madonna (who won for a collaboration with William
Orbit). Whitney Houston. With the exception of Best New Artist, and
the welcome new blood of the Latin movement, this year's ceremonies
could've taken place in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   And thank God for that. There was apprehension in the music
business this year, that the kids who took all of the tension and
heat out of what Billboard magazine calls Black music _ funk, R &AMP; B
and rap _ and turned it into product, acts like Limp Bizkit and
former New Mouseketeers like Britney Spears, would dominate the
awards.
</P>
<P>
   Santana also represented another, more intriguing trend in this
year's Grammys, the interest in Latin music. Once solely the
province of musician/ethnographers like Ry Cooder, Latin pop now
has grown as a musically and commercially vibrant sector hospitable
to both the heat of youth culture and the grace of age.
</P>
<P>
   The growing acceptance of world music and an exploding Hispanic
demographic presence in much of the country were spurs to its
success, as were the return of salsa and meringue dance clubs. Kids
may go for the flash of party-people like Ricky Martin and Jennifer
Lopez, but they may also find themselves listening to well-regarded
crooners like Marc Anthony, all of whom reach mainstream audiences
by singing in English.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, grown ups will find Ibrahim Ferrer, 72 years old and
a member of the gracefully aging Buena Vista Social Club, singing
and gesturing like he owns the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Buena Vista Social Club didn't just catch on because Wim
Wenders made an engrossing Oscar-nominated documentary film about
them. Instead, this warrior class of musicians, long ago discarded
by Cuban official culture as remnants of the nightclub era of
Batista, the pre-Castro dictator, performed as if they hadn't
missed a day. And their intensely emotional and melodic stew was
released just as Latin dance music was finally starting to catch on
in the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Latin wave has grown so large that the Grammy
people have decided to run a Latin Grammy broadcast later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Best New Artist, Christina Aguilera, reflects the
Latin revolution, but she's also part of the jailbait-under-glass
syndrome that is somewhat less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, little girls flocked to Madonna shows, dressed
just like their idol. Now, those girls, exemplified by Aguilera and
Spears, are the performers and are pushing down the age of sexual
suggestiveness in music, just like the rest of our commercial
culture. The bobby-soxers just keep getting younger. In the end,
the snapshot of America this year's Grammy's provided show a
country still dominated by Baby Boomers reluctant to cede center
stage to the sounds and the singers they grew up with. And while
rap music has been safely commoditized, a new and energetic Latin
sound has found a place in the national cacophony. Finally,
children are being told to grow up faster than ever. That's what
the Top 40 charts told us this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
