<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9278 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-MONEYLAUNDER     02-26 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MONEYLAUNDER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'S LAIRD TO YOU, MISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(bl) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no longer very hard to enjoy the trappings of a financial
mogul or earn an aristocratic title conveying pomp and privilege.
Just visit the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is filled with outfits that cater to these desires. For
example, type in ``offshoresecrets.com'' and enter a world
promising ``fast, safe, private and affordable offshore services.''
</P>
<P>
   Those services include banking charters in such obscure locales
as Nauru and Vanuatu for a fee of about $20,000. ``Yes! I want to
order my own bank now!'' the site encourages visitors, noting that
such banks allow users to take deposits, give loans and ``operate
free of tax on profit,'' with no ``need to maintain a physical
presence'' in the host country.
</P>
<P>
   To top it off, the site can help you get a college degree or
even a legal title of nobility. ``With a Title in front of your
name you will experience a difference in people's attitudes,'' the
site notes. ``The moment they know you are a `Sir, Lady, Lord,
etc.' you'll be treated like some sort of royalty or famous film
star.''
</P>
<P>
   An individual identified as Eytan Gold, who operates
offshoresecrets.com from Israel, declined to be interviewed.
Neither he nor his site have ever been charged with wrongdoing. But
his site and others like it have drawn the attention of U.S.
regulators and legislators, who suspect they may be fronts for
money laundering and other financial shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sole purpose of many of these banks is to provide havens
for criminals,'' said Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., in an
interview. ``Any criminal worth his salt knows that if you want to
avoid detection, you go offshore _ and with the Internet, you can
point, click and launder.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $5 trillion to $6 trillion is sheltered in offshore
accounts, according to reports from the International Monetary
Fund, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and the State Department. Schumer and
Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., have introduced money-laundering
legislation that targets ``instant banks'' being peddled on the
Internet. The legislation would prevent those kinds of banks from
having transactions with U.S. financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at one site, offshoreprofit.com, operated from
Venezuela by an individual identified as Lord Antonio D. Gonzalez,
suggests how easy it is for just about anyone to shelter money
abroad. For $399, the site will establish an account in ``one of
Estonia's largest banks'' and throw in a free ``Maestro Card.''
</P>
<P>
   The site's ``Millennium Freedom Package,'' bargain-priced at
$2,299, offers an offshore trust account in Belize, an ``ID Free
Visa card,'' a mail-drop address and a ``full year of personalized
advice'' that includes information on where to get ``a second, or
even third diplomatic passport.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Web site, privacyworld.com, also offers offshore trusts
and bank accounts, ``legal tax avoidance'' services, press or
travel agent identification and international driver's licenses.
</P>
<P>
   For the very ambitious, the site will establish ``anonymous,
bearer share'' corporations that will let owners bank abroad using
encrypted telephone, fax or e-mail connections.
</P>
<P>
   The site, operated from Switzerland by Third World Trading
Corp., says it allows clients to ``get rid of lawyers, spouses,
etc., forever.'' The operators of privacyworld.com could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some offshore operators scoff at the notion that they are
selling anything more than a sought-after luxury: privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet makes it easy to protect our and our clients'
privacy,'' an individual calling himself Robert Smith said in an
e-mail response to questions about his site, offshoreprofit.com.
``We are located outside the U.S., our actual location being a
secret to avoid interference and sabotage attempts, which have
destroyed or are in the process of destroying other, more
high-profile offshore operators.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith also observed that most illegal activities occur in
onshore banks. In fact, the biggest money-laundering investigation
in history is underway at the Bank of New York, where $7 billion in
suspect funds from Russia are being examined. The bank has not been
charged with wrongdoing and is cooperating with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, some offshore banks and services are used by those who
want to break the law,'' he said. ``However the same thing is true
for onshore banks. In fact, the vast majority of international
money laundering doesn't take place in the Caribbean or in Austria,
but in New York and London. That's where the truly powerful people
launder their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you aren't interested in stashing away money, the sites
point out that many of their products make great gifts. For just
$495 ($795 for couples), offshoresecrets.com will make you a laird,
knecht, viscount or marchioness. And the cachet that comes with
that title, you'll discover, is just priceless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines will often upgrade you,'' the site promises. ``Bank
managers just can't help you enough. It says more about you than a
Gold or Platinum credit card. For personal confidence and
self-esteem a title will change your life for the better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
