<HEADLINE>
THE $12 MILLION MAN: BUCHANAN WAITS FOR THE PARTY TO BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For all the money and fury being invested in the
parallel primary campaigns of the two major parties, there is
another presidential war game going on under the radar, among the
mud-spattered troops of the Reform party slogging through their own
wilderness campaign. Sooner or later, however, the winners of the
Democratic and Republican fights will have to pay attention. For,
barring direct intrusion by Ross Perot himself, the current
expectation among political professionals is that the Reform line
could very well be resurrected this fall by none other than Pat
Buchanan, the turncoat Republican and chronic presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   For the past five months, Buchanan has been quietly laboring to
build his own Reform machine and get a lock on the nomination. No
small attraction in his quest is the $12.6 million federal election
subsidy that is the Reform nominee's entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buchanan's waiting in the weeds for the primaries to end,''
said Jim Jordan, a Democratic campaign strategist who anticipates
serious tri-corner mischief if Buchanan manages to seize the third
line. ``Pat knows how to use a political wedge better than anybody
in the business,'' Jordan added, wondering, for example, whether
the GOP's right-wing Christian bloc might become miffed enough in
the current Republican fray to be tempted by a Buchanan alternative
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Following Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura's angry departure from
the party, speculation is growing that Perot might try to dictate a
nominee. But Buchanan, deep into Reform politics by now, insists he
is ready for any eventuality, including recent speculation that
Perot might seek to give his party's blessing to Sen. John McCain,
or that Perot might decide to run again himself.
</P>
<P>
   More an impulse than an organization, the party that Perot built
is out of season right now, shards of ill-managed klatches in 21
states, each hoping for someone to unite it into a once more
fearsome vehicle. The Bush family remembers well that fearsomeness;
President George Bush saw his potential margin of re-election
siphoned off in 1992 when Perot drew 19 percent of the vote to the
Reform line and Bill Clinton was elected as a plurality President.
Now the son, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, is suffering a healthy
dose of insurgency from McCain and neither can afford to focus on
the Perot reformers conspiring on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   As he retreated, Ventura described the Reform Party as
``hopelessly dysfunctional.'' But actually he was quitting
preemptively, having failed to win the national party leadership.
In a way, the party proved quite functional, for the Perot
loyalists reclaimed the party gavel in Nashville at a raucous
convention shoving match worthy of the Moscow Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Reform party enthusiasts heart-stricken at the spectacle should
remember that big money has a way of focusing the attention of even
the most obstreperous politician. And the early teasing about this
prize is ending.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump, as self-fantasized a politician as ever trod the
tabloid runway, instantly withdrew his pompadour from the ring when
his sole patron, Ventura, was pinned by the Perot forces. And
political specialists point to election laws and impenetrable
Reform procedures that would make a McCain endorsement difficult,
if not impossible. More to the point, the idea of being the Reform
Party nominee has been rejected outright by McCain, who cites the
Bull Moose folly of his hero, Theodore Roosevelt, and says he would
welcome all sorts of endorsements, Reformers included, once he wins
the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Reform Party is in its familiar Godot mode, waiting
for Perot. Associates who claim to know his mind say that Perot may
try something new. He ran a second time in 1996 with some
embarrassing results. His popular support was halved at the polls
as critics judged him less of a reformer and more of a
laughingstock.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one is watching more intently for the hand of Perot
than Buchanan. He jumped to the Reformers when his serial campaign
for the GOP nomination lagged into single-digit polling doldrums.
Since his conversion, Buchanan has been laboring to build his own
personal Reform machine, state by state. With Ventura now gone,
Buchanan counts one fewer dragon to slay on the road to the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm that troll still waiting out there under the bridge,''
Buchanan likes to laughingly announce.
</P>
<P>
   His core strategy is to win the $12.6 million and use it as a
credential with which he could not be fairly denied entry into the
real prize for him, next fall's televised debates. There, he likes
his chances as the quick-witted populist who delights in contrarian
polemics.
</P>
<P>
   But first Buchanan must hack his new side-door path to the
political arena where he last stunned the Republican establishment
by defeating Bob Dole in the 1996 New Hampshire primary. Buchanan
is spending $2 million organizing petition drives and field workers
in the 29 states that do not now have Reform ballot lines. In the
other 21 states, he has been courting disparate gatherings of
uncertain Reformers, right down to a bowling alley caucus one night
in Fleetwoods, W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   When he opportunistically jumped his life-long Republican
traces, Buchanan predicted, ``Ross Perot will be a benign
neutral.'' Now he admits he has to wonder what might happen as the
quixotic Texan silently weighs McCain's success in tapping voter
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about footsteps,'' Buchanan insisted of
Perot as he claimed his first Reform victory of sorts in Ventura's
quitting the party. ``I always said this would be like running an
Iroquois gantlet,'' Buchanan said, beginning to savor and so far
master the wayward politics of his new party. ``It's a volatile
situation in America,'' the newly minted Reformer said, smiling at
the possibilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
