<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Feb. 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DISCORD (Kosovska Mitrovica, Yugoslavia) _ As a first
gesture _ largely dismissed here as cosmetic _ the U.N. authorities
and NATO's peacekeepers are building a pedestrian bridge across the
Ibar as part of a new plan for an ``open city.'' The plan is a
response to intense pressure from shocked NATO capitals at the
violence in Mitrovica and its symbolism of the failure thus far of
the Western effort here to bring any real measure of security,
justice or freedom of movement to minorities in Kosovo. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-MOVIES-EXTORTION (Bombay, India) _ In India, the men who
make movies find themselves caught in a Catch-22: If their films
bomb _ as most do _ they lose their shirts. But in the unlikely
event that they produce a blockbuster, they become targets for
underworld extortionists. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   SENEGAL-ELECTION (Dakar, Senegal) _ The presidential election on
Sunday in Senegal has one critical difference that sets it apart
from past votes and that offers a snapshot of the evolution of
democracy in sub-Saharan Africa: No one knows who will win. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-FLOODS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Several weeks of
torrential rains and floods, made worse when a deadly storm lashed
Southern Africa this week, have killed more than 150 people and
swept away the homes and livelihoods of more than 1 million in
three countries, relief agencies and government officials say. By
Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-EGYPT (Mount Sinai, Egypt) _ Saying he felt ``great joy and
deep emotion,'' Pope John Paul II prayed Saturday at the spot where
tradition says Moses once stood, and called himself a pilgrim ``in
the footsteps of God.'' By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE-ASSESS (Abu Dis, West Bank) _ The
Israeli-Palestinian peace effort, which U.S. envoys have been busy
trying to revive this week, is deadlocked over the fate of this
unprepossessing Arab town on the eastern outskirts of Jerusalem. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-WOMEN (Prague, Czech Republic) _ After almost two years of
total exclusion from the government, some Czech women feel the time
has come to break into the old boys' club.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA (Washington) _ U.S. policy toward China. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WESLEYAN-ADMISSIONS (Middletown, Conn.) _ Raphael Figueroa, an
admissions officer, is an anxious sentry at Wesleyan's front gate
these days, and like those doing similar work at dozens of other
selective colleges and universities, his job has never been harder.
Fueled by an increase in the number of high school graduates and a
growing perception that top educational credentials create the best
job opportunities, this college admissions season is on track to
break many of last year's records. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-COMMANDMENTS (Chicago) _ Trying to make the Ten Commandments
part of public school life in ways that could survive
constitutional challenges, Indiana has passed a bill that permits
schools to post the religious edicts as historical documents, and
nine other states are pondering similar measures. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-SOUTH-BEACH (Miami Beach, Fla.) _ Vaulting into celebrity as
the backdrop of ``Miami Vice,'' the hit television series in the
1980s, this oceanside gem of Art Deco whimsy has joined the company
of the nation's most impudent and indulgent trend-setting
societies, like Greenwich Village or Berkeley or Venice, Calif. But
South Beach has also inspired precarious excesses, especially among
the young who frequent night clubs and the after-hours clubs. By
Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-ILLEGAL-IMMIG (Harsens Island, Mich.) _ Illegal immigration
is picking up in this rural Michigan area because of an unusual
cross-cultural criminal alliance. According to federal court papers
filed in Detroit, a ring of Canadian Indians from Walpole Island,
just across the river from here, have linked up with Chinese
smugglers to bring Asian immigrants into this rural region 35 miles
northeast of Detroit. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Port St. Lucie, Fla.) _ As Congress wrestles
with the white-hot political issue of Medicare drug benefits, many
Republicans find themselves on the hot seat at home. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DISCOMFORT (Comfort, Texas) _ When the Civil War broke out
in 1861, a group of nearly 100 immigrant German intellectuals now
known as ``freethinkers,'' opposed to slavery and secession, fled
south from here toward the Mexican border to join the Union forces
or wait out the war in Mexico. Caught en route by Confederate
militiamen, 36 were killed in two battles. But recent efforts to
build a memorial to them has set off yet another battle. In
addition to their outspoken support for equal rights and free
speech, many freethinkers were atheists or agnostics, a fact that
some of their descendants in this highly religious community find
distasteful. By Ross E. Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   TENN-LYNCH-REVISITED (Chattanooga, Tenn.) _ In 1906, a young
black man named Ed Johnson was lynched. Just before he was hung by
the neck to die, he had said to the crowd of white men, women and
children who were watching with a kind of collective glee, ``God
bless you all. I am innocent.'' Almost 100 years later, in a
downtown courtroom here packed with a sober crowd of black and
white men, women and children, and with television news cameras
faithfully recording every moment, Johnson's last words to the mob
that brutally murdered him were vindicated. Criminal Court Judge
Douglas A. Meyers set aside Johnson's conviction of raping a white
woman. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   NYPD-DIALLO (New York) _ The death of Amadou Diallo last year
became a defining event for the New York Police Department. The
shooting of the unarmed African immigrant by four white officers
prompted various examinations of the department's admittedly
aggressive tactics, and attracted so much attention that police
officials blamed the media for a sudden timidity among the
rank-and-file. Today, the Street Crime Unit _ once a jewel in the
administration's law-enforcement efforts _ bears only a trace
resemblance to what it was when four of its members killed Diallo
that infamous night in the Bronx. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   HOWDY-DISPUTE (New York) _ In a splashy ceremony at Rockefeller
Center earlier this month, an adoring throng applauded as a humble
puppet ascended into the television pantheon. Surviving cast
members, writers and producers of ``The Howdy Doody Show'' gathered
to see a bronze star uncovered for the redheaded, freckle-faced
marionette on NBC-TV's ``Walk of Fame.'' But Howdy wasn't there. He
was locked in a trunk in a bank vault in New London, Conn., where
he has been for the last year, and it may take a judge's order to
get him out. By Corey Kilgannon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-BACKGROUND (Washington) _ The past is central to Sen.
John McCain's campaign, yet paradoxically his most remarkable
metamorphosis, from a battered ex-pilot on crutches to a new
congressman, is among the least-known chapters of his life. By
Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-PHONE-CALLS (Cleveland) _ It was a handful of political
amateurs _ Michigan volunteers for Sen. John McCain _ who began the
telephone campaign that helped change the complexion of the
Republican presidential contest last week. Five days before the
Michigan primary, they began calling friends and neighbors who
belonged to Catholic parishes in Michigan, telling them that
McCain's opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, had given a speech
at Bob Jones University, a bastion of the Christian right whose
leaders have espoused harshly anti-Catholic views. By David
Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   WASH-PRIMARIES (Seattle) _ When the Election 2000 presidential
campaign began, the Republican and Democratic primaries that will
be held in Washington state on Tuesday were hardly more than blips
on the political horizon. But because the early months of the
campaign have been so unexpectedly topsy-turvy, suddenly the
Washington primaries, with their quirky rules and oft-quirky
voters, loom large, and candidates have been forced to change plans
and divert scarce resources and time to compete. By B. Drummond
Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-REPUBS (Detroit) _ Gov. George W. Bush's unexpected loss in
Michigan's primary last Tuesday, despite strong support from
virtually all of the Republican establishment here, has left the
state's Republican leaders divided over what went wrong. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-DELEGATES (Washington) _ Eventually, the quest for
presidential nominations comes down to delegates. Numbers start
counting for more than buzz, bump and momentum. For Sen. John
McCain, eventually is just around the corner. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Dollars to doughnuts. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Blue chip round trip. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
