<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2368 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-DIALLO-POLICE-REVIEW-     02-26 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-POLICE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO IF YOU'RE STOPPED BY THE POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(bl) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The four New York City police officers who shot an
unarmed African immigrant last year were acquitted of murder
charges Friday. Nevertheless, their testimony was particularly
instructive in one aspect of police-community relations: How police
officers expect you to behave when they confront you.
</P>
<P>
   Speak when asked to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Stop when ordered to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Keep hands in plain view.
</P>
<P>
   And never _ ever _ make any sudden move.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in recounting that fateful February night in the Bronx
last year, the four white officers still seem baffled by Amadou
Diallo's behavior when they approached the black man outside his
building after midnight. His response, which began when he turned
away and ended when he reached for what they thought was a gun,
sealed his fate _ no matter that he was reaching for his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers were members of the Street Crime Unit; their
mission was to anticipate crime and, most of all, remove illegal
guns from the street. The plainclothes assignment carried both
considerable power and a measure of danger.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Edward McMellon, one of the defendants, said he
approached Diallo by holding out his badge and asking to have a
word with him. Instead, he said, Diallo, who worked as a street
vendor, turned away and began digging into his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the policemen's response say Diallo was probably
frightened by the four strangers, and may have been trying to find
his keys to open the building's door. But Officer Sean Carroll said
he saw it this way: ``I believed he was possibly carrying a firearm
and trying to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying, `Police, police, show me your hands,'' Carroll
said. ``He just didn't want to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, McMellon said he shouted, ``What are you
doing?''
</P>
<P>
   A slight move here, the appearance of a black object there, and
Diallo was dead, struck by 19 of 41 bullets fired. Bennett Epstein,
Carroll's lawyer, summed it up by saying, ``If he had stopped, this
whole thing would have ended peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of any institutional training of the public, such
police expectations seem based on the assumption that law-abiding
residents _ including Diallo _ have street smarts. Americans, such
expectations infer, have learned how to respond to law enforcement
officers from television programs like ``Law and Order'' and ``NYPD
Blue.'' (Of course, the police on these shows are often heroic, the
residents usually suspicious.)
</P>
<P>
   But such expectations have long played havoc with the minds, if
not the lives, of black and Hispanic residents. Parents routinely
instruct their children to obey every police command _ a lesson
less commonly taught in mostly white suburbs. Several years ago,
the NAACP, Allstate Insurance Co. and the National Organization of
Black Law Enforcement Executives published a brochure on
``guidelines for interacting with law enforcement officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Perkins, a New York city councilman whose district includes
a part of Harlem, said he has directed his 18-year-old son to be
extremely careful when dealing with police _ a perversion, he says,
of the traditional view that a police officer is a friend and
protector.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might think, `Let me get my ID out right away,''' Perkins
said, ``and that could lead to him getting shot. That's dangerous.
And I'm not talking about criminal kids. I'm talking about average
kids. Like Diallo.''
</P>
<P>
   David Paterson, a state senator from Harlem, said the police
officers' expectations in the Diallo incident were in full play
even before they left their car. In addition to a preconceived
notion that Diallo was armed, he said, ``the police had an
expectation in street clothes that they should be treated as if
they had their uniforms on.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Paterson said, ``Everything that he did, every
motion that he took, was taken by them to be antagonistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert J. Louden, a former New York police officer and the
director of the Criminal Justice Center at John Jay College of
Criminal Justice, said law enforcement is based on the basic
premise that society gives the police certain powers over the rest
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people who are put into positions of authority,'' he
said, ``and the rest of us are supposed to heed them and seek
resolution in the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   To counter the potential for abuse or accidents, police officers
are trained in how to talk to people _ how to approach, for
example, the driver of a car pulled over for speeding. But Louden
acknowledged that people are not trained in how to be stopped by
the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach police what we want them to do and in a way we expect
citizens to do what the police tell them,'' Louden said.
``Sometimes it is implied in the law and often it is explicit in
the law. Unfortunately, it doesn't always work that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
