opinion with a campaign redolent of the old Soviet Union's most
xenophobic propaganda. And the military, liberated rather than
restrained by popular feeling, has pursued victory with
disturbingly vicious abandon.
</P>
<P>
   So far, at least, success has begotten success. ``In the
beginning, there was an attempt to depict it as a no-casualty war,
like Kosovo,'' Pavel Felgengauer, a military analyst and former
journalist, said last week. ``You could notice that now this theme
has virtually disappeared from Russian propaganda. Now the theme
is, `We've won, and the enemy is defeated, and everything's
fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   It is another indicator, as if another were needed, that Russia
views Western concepts like democratic rule and consent of the
governed through the opposite end of the telescope. And it is
another spadeful of dirt on the notion, naive in retrospect, that
either smart bombs or representative government would transform war
into something more humane.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is to say, of course, that either Russians or their
government are inured to body counts or television footage of
coffins coming home. The Soviet Union quit its long war in
Afghanistan 12 years ago in no small part because the sheer number
of combat deaths had elevated the conflict to an unavoidable
political issue, even before the advent of democracy. Russia's
botched effort to subdue Chechnya four years ago, and the
casualties that stemmed from it, were pillars of the public's
overwhelming support for impeaching President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest Chechen war, military leaders have sought to
emulate NATO's own careful strategy of relentless bombing from afar
_ a strategy that allowed the West to win the war without a ground
offensive or even a single combat death among its own forces.
</P>
<P>
   Most independent observers believe _ and according to polls, so
does the Russian public _ that the government has lowballed its
tally of combat deaths. Officially the toll is more than 1,500, but
it is widely suspected to be twice that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the option of keeping war politically palatable by
limiting the body count has never been a serious one here.
Chechnya's Islamic guerrillas could not be bombed out of existence
without leveling the entire region _ something the Russian military
has come perilously close to achieving. Even so, the Russians have
not been able to avoid a ground war, house-to-house firefights and
heavy casualties.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the big differences between Kosovo and Chechnya.
The West relied on an arsenal of smart bombs to limit civilian
deaths and high-tech aircraft and equipment to keep its troops out
of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's military has neither, and its troops, a mix of
conscripts, soldiers of fortune and career officers, is woefully
short of discipline. The result has been a civilian death toll and
a record of apparent atrocities that is internationally mortifying
_ and that would trigger a political revolt in most societies.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, it has not. Indeed, after six months of war, 7 in 10
Russians favor continuing the Chechen war to the bitter end,
according to a survey by the Public Opinion Foundation, a respected
Moscow polling organization.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that is surely because Russians truly see Chechnya's
rebels, with a long list of kidnappings and grisly executions to
their credit, as entirely deserving of extermination. In part, it
is because terrorist bombings that killed more than 300 people last
year galvanized the country behind the extermination of the Islamic
radicals who are blamed for _ if not yet charged with _ the
killings. In part, it is simple racism: dark-skinned Caucasians
remain doormats in a nation that has a long way to go to achieve
any measure of tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But as much as anything, perhaps, it is because of the way this
war has been cast by its Kremlin authors: as a test of Russian
manhood, if not of the nation's very existence. Senior Russian
officials and their political allies more and more equate criticism
of the Chechen war with treason. Western complaints about human
rights issues are branded as anti-Russian agitprop.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a German video tape was released showing Russian
troops doing a mass burial of bound Chechen soldiers. Such things
are dismissed not just as lies, but as malicious interference in
Russia's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   All this harkens to Kosovo, a war that is still seen in the
Kremlin and among ordinary Russians as poaching on Russian turf. No
doubt the theme of Russia reasserting its sphere of influence is an
effective way to marshal Russian support for the Chechen war _ and,
maybe, to score electoral points in the process. The xenophobic
image of Fortress Russia, beleaguered and under assault by enemies
near and far, is a popular theme in Russian history.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a theme at loggerheads with the Kremlin's stated
intention of hauling Russia out of its Soviet-era trance and
propelling it into the international community. That goal would be
especially poorly served if the price for sustaining the war's
popularity turns out to be a return to Soviet-style manipulation of
opinionand truth, however much Fortress Russia is reinvigorated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
