<P>
   FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ When the phone rang at her desk,
she would answer it in her slow and distinctive voice, ``Mis-ter
Ro-zelle's off-ice.'' For four decades, Thelma Elkjer, who died
recently at age 77, was the late Pete Rozelle's executive
assistant, but in and outside the National Football League
headquarters, she was much more. By Dave Anderson. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ In the old days, Kobe Bryant would
have been a college senior. In these new days, he is a co-owner of
a basketball team. Bryant recently spent a few of Jerry Buss' lire
to buy half of Olimpia Milano, his father's old team when the
Bryant family was based in Italy. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   LIPSYTE-COLUMN (New York) _ Who listens to a fan? We scamper
along the sides of the eternal triangle _ athlete, agent, owner _
and sometimes get hung on the points. Who cares about us? By Robert
Lipsyte.
</P>
<P>
   SFX-SPORTS (New York) _ You are SFX Entertainment, and you are
dominating the world of live entertainment. In three years, you
have bought your way into concert tours, touring Broadway shows and
family entertainment. You have shaken up an industry of small
independent firms, consolidated them and recast them as a behemoth.
What do you do next? Which other fragmented industry will accept
your cash, your stock and your covetous appetite for growth?
Sports. By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
