<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9351 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NYPD-DIALLO-ART-2TAKE     02-26 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYPD-DIALLO-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIALLO CASE HAS PROFOUND IMPACT ON NEW YORK POLICE DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The death of Amadou Diallo last year became a
defining event for the New York Police Department. The shooting of
the unarmed West African immigrant by four white officers spurred
protests, prompted various examinations of the department's
admittedly aggressive tactics, and attracted so much attention that
police officials blamed the news media for a sudden timidity among
the rank-and-file.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a jury in Albany, N.Y., capped a riveting and often
tense trial by finding the four officers not guilty of murder and
several lesser charges. But the shooting and its aftermath continue
to reverberate.
</P>
<P>
   The Diallo family, dismayed by the verdict, is expected to file
a multimillion-dollar lawsuit against the city. The state attorney
general's office is critically examining the department's
``stop-and-frisk'' policy. The officers may still face internal
misconduct charges. The U.S. attorney for the Southern District of
New York will review the evidence to determine whether the shooting
violated federal civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   And the Street Crime Unit _ once a jewel in the Giuliani
administration's law-enforcement efforts and now Exhibit A in
critics' charges that aggressive stop-and-frisk tactics violate
basic rights _ today bears only a trace resemblance to what it was
when four of its members killed Diallo that infamous night in the
Bronx. The days of an elite corps of plainclothes officers roaming
the city to prevent crime and seize guns are over.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the administration has altogether
forsaken the police tactics that helped to lower crime and, it
maintains, lay the foundation for the city's resurgence. As if to
signal that aggressive policing is back, last month the Police
Department began Operation Condor, a crackdown on street-level drug
trafficking that has already cost millions of dollars in overtime
and led to the arrests of thousands of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir shut the Street Crime Unit's
base on Randalls Island four months ago and divided its 350 members
into eight units reporting to regional commanders. Although he
denied that the Diallo shooting had played a role in his decision,
several criminologists said no other conclusion could be reached:
The connection between Diallo and the Street Crime Unit is now
inextricable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The totality of the tragedy is such that I think a responsible
official would err on the side of being cautious,'' said Dr. Robert
J. Louden, a former New York police officer and a criminologist at
the John Jay College of Criminal Justice in Manhattan. ``If there
is a perception by some people that A, B and C seriously
contributed to this event, maybe we should temporarily change A, B
and C.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Louden said, ``policing is not static.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other experts suggest that despite the verdict, there are
serious questions still to be answered about how street crime units
should operate.
</P>
<P>
   When four officers from the Street Crime Unit headed for the
Bronx in a maroon Ford in February last year, they belonged to a
squad that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Safir had repeatedly praised,
particularly for its success in seizing illegal guns and restraint
in shooting its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But the unit was already displaying symptoms of dysfunction, its
critics say. It was heavily relying on the stop-and-frisk
technique: the temporary but lawful detention, questioning and
occasional searching of civilians on the street. Although the
method had significantly contributed to the increase in gun
seizures, many blacks and Hispanics argued that they were being
harassed by an abuse of the technique.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer's civil rights bureau later
reported that 62.7 percent of all people stopped by the unit were
black, and that for every 16 blacks stopped, one was arrested,
compared with 10 whites stopped for every one arrested. In
defending the unit last year, Safir said that the ``unfortunate
truth is that communities of color are disproportionately
victimized by violent street crime.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other problems. The unit had counted only nine black
officers among its 380-odd members. Members muttered about
maintaining quotas on gun seizures and arrests. And the unit's
veterans were still furious with Safir's decision in 1997 to triple
its numbers, which they said had diluted the intensity of its
specialized training.
</P>
<P>
   The training and experience of the four officers cruising the
Bronx that night would later come into question. In testifying
before the City Council last April, Safir said that at the time of
the shooting, the unit's members had undergone 12.5 days of extra
training that addressed everything from ``search and seizure'' to
``gun disarming.''
</P>
<P>
   But a person involved in mounting the officers' defense said
that the four officers had received virtually no specialized
training beyond what they had learned in the Police Academy. In
addition, three had been in the unit less than four months; the
fourth, Sean Carroll, had been in for a year, a period that
included several months of desk duty.
</P>
<P>
   The officers testified that while they drove down Wheeler Avenue
one night last February, Carroll spotted Diallo acting suspiciously
in front of a building that turned out to be his home. Officer
Kenneth Boss, the driver, shifted the car into reverse, and
Officers Carroll and Edward McMellon stepped out to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of Diallo, a 22-year-old street vendor from Guinea,
quickly unnerved the officers, they said. He did not acknowledge
McMellon's prominently held badge or requests to have a word.
Instead, he turned and darted into the small vestibule, they said,
but he was unable to open the building door. When they demanded
that he stop and show his hands, the officers said, he reached into
his pocket and turned in a manner that led them to believe he was
possibly pulling a gun.
</P>
<P>
   And when Carroll mistook the black wallet in Diallo's hand for a
weapon, he shouted ``Gun!'' and fired. In a few seconds of
confusion, the four officers fired a total of 41 bullets, striking
Diallo 19 times. It was left to the prosecution to suggest that
Diallo might have acted the way he did because he feared the four
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James J. Fyfe, a criminologist at Temple University in
Philadelphia and a former New York City police officer who often
testifies against police departments, this time testified in the
four officers' defense. He said that the defendants had broken no
departmental guidelines and had found themselves making
split-second decisions in what was a police officer's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Fyfe said in an interview last week that the
Diallo case raised several questions about the Street Crime Unit
and its tactics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, the shooting highlights the need for
better ways for police officers in street clothes to approach the
public. Although they need such clothing for surveillance, he said,
perhaps they could don some identifying garb _ a sweater with the
NYPD logo, for example _ before approaching people they simply want
to question.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, the Police Department seems to have
flirted with trouble by tripling the size of the specialized unit.
``They should have a healthy culture, with new members schooled
into the culture and mentored,'' he said. ``But when you increase
it by that magnitude, there's no opportunity for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Fyfe said, a team of four officers who have not worked
much with one another is less desirable than a team of two or three
officers who know one another's habits and strengths.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Police Department's most important challenge,
several critics say, is to address the assumptions of white
officers in minority neighborhoods. ``White guys have to understand
this: You get out of a car and approach a black man in a black
neighborhood, do not assume he knows that you're a cop,'' one
former police supervisor said. ``Because it's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   David Paterson, a state senator from Harlem, was one of many
black leaders who found the testimony of the officers to be
unbelievable, to be more reminiscent of the old television show
``Adam 12'' than of reality. He also said that their testimony
reflected a preconceived notion that Diallo was armed, and that
they responded to those assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single thing he did was considered antagonistic,''
Paterson said of Diallo. ``The unit certainly did encourage that
type of thinking, if not promote it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the Diallo shooting, the Giuliani
administration and the Police Department instituted changes that
some considered to be progressive and others found to be pandering.
They issued palm cards to officers that reminded them to be
respectful to the public; they created a Board of Visitors to
review the department's training and recruitment practices.
</P>
<P>
   At times they were defensive, blaming the news media for a small
rise in homicides and a sudden drop in the number of guns seized.
The anti-police sentiment fomented by coverage of the Diallo
shooting had cowed officers from doing their duty, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Safir gradually redefined the Street Crime Unit. In March, he
ordered the unit's members to wear uniforms (a decision he later
modified, on the grounds that it had contributed to the plummeting
of gun seizures). He also appointed a black commander and assigned
dozens of black officers to the unit's ranks. And in October, he
decentralized the unit and dispatched its members to various
commands throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   Louden of John Jay College said that, the verdicts in the murder
trial notwithstanding, the Police Department would learn from the
Diallo shooting and incorporate change. He said that other
tragedies in the past have led to major reforms, from ending the
practice of firing at moving cars to changing the way that officers
approach the emotionally disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NYPD is very self-critical,'' he said, and added, ``When
they see that's not what they want to do anymore, they change it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
