<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Feb. 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday will begin with widespread low clouds and patchy drizzle
in the Northeast from the crest of the Appalachians to the coast.
During the day, winds from the south will begin to mix drier air
from aloft causing clouds to break in most areas although some
clouds will linger near the east slopes of the Appalachians as the
moist winds ascend the sloping terrain. Where the sun breaks
through the clouds, temperatures will surge into the 60s and 70s,
while overcast areas stay mainly in the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   A band of showers and some thunderstorms will precede a
slow-moving cold front from the eastern Great Lakes to the interior
Southeast. Locally heavy rain will occur in parts of the Southeast
where high-level winds from the south will cause thunderstorms to
move repeatedly across the same locations. In the wake of the
front, it will be noticeably cooler, but temperatures will still be
several degrees above the seasonal average in the Ohio Valley and
Great Lakes States. Some showers of wet snow area expected near
eastern Lake Superior as colder air arrives on breezes from the
northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Plains will be bathed in plentiful sunshine as a
ridge of high pressure crosses the region. Increasing winds from
the south will renew unseasonably mild conditions particularly over
central and southern sections.
</P>
<P>
   A tandem of low pressure zones will keep unsettled weather in
much of the West. Coastal rain, mountain snow will be common from
the West Coast to the western slopes of the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Night Blindness
</P>
<P>
   Each night from late February until early April meteorologists
are blinded when, for two hours, the satellites that serve North
America lose power. During that time, from the point of view of the
satellites, there is a solar eclipse. The solar-powered satellites
are in geostationary orbit 22,500 miles over the equator. Each year
around the spring and fall equinoxes, the earth passes between the
satellite and the sun. This limited data loss is usually not a
major problem over the land masses, since radar and other weather
observations from ground-based instruments help fill the void.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
