<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDIA-MOVIES-EXTORT-2     02-26 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-MOVIES-EXTORT-2TAKES(1040)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANGS PREY ON BOMBAY'S FILMMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India _ India's hottest new movie star _ a young man
with a smile like Elvis and a body like Hercules _ was doing bicep
curls in a friend's private gym when his mobile phone trilled one
evening late last month. It was his movie producer father,
hysterical with fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't move!'' cried Rakesh Roshan, whose frothy, newly
released film, starring his son Hrithik (pronounced Ri-tick), had
become India's biggest hit in over a year. ``I've just gotten
shot!''
</P>
<P>
   Here in India's movie capital, a dream factory both seedy and
glamorous, the men who make movies find themselves caught in a
Catch-22: If their films bomb _ as most do _ they lose their
shirts. In the unlikely event that they produce a blockbuster, they
become targets for underworld extortionists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You already have enough tension, worrying if your movie will
flop,'' said 26-year-old Hrithik Roshan, in his first interview
since the attack on his father. ``But now you have another worry.
What if you have a hit movie and get killed?''
</P>
<P>
   The out-of-nowhere ambush of Rakesh Roshan was eerily similar to
the celluloid shooting of Hrithik in their new movie, ``Say You
Love Me.'' The police suspect it may have been ordered by a
notorious gangster, Abu Salem, who once lived in Bombay but is now
believed to live as a fugitive somewhere in the Middle East and
preys on the movie industry through flunkies here. He generally
makes his threats over untraceable satellite phones.
</P>
<P>
   Roshan survived a bullet that pierced his arm and lodged in his
chest, but the hit job has created what people here in Bollywood
call a ``fear psychosis.'' The underworld's message to the movie
industry came through loud and clear: Pay up or we'll kill you.
</P>
<P>
   The Roshans are now among more than 50 movie people getting
round-the-clock protection from the Bombay police. Plainclothes
officers toting machine guns sit outside stars' opulent homes and
in movie company lobbies festooned with posters of bosomy starlets
and lovers embracing in sunny, flowering fields.
</P>
<P>
   The police say the underworld has deeply penetrated the movie
industry, and some in the industry say the police are in league
with gangsters _ and therein lies a bigger issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not just endemic to film,'' said Fareed Kazmi,
a professor of political science at the University of Allahabad and
author of ``The Politics of India's Conventional Cinema'' (Sage
Publications, 1999). ``This is a societal problem. The underworld
is present in politics, in cinema or in any other field.''
</P>
<P>
   The film industry is a particularly juicy target. People making
piles of money are vulnerable to extortion. And those making flops
can be tempted to take dirty money to dig themselves out of debt
and finance new films.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole lot of shady types trying to whitewash their money are
investing in the industry or trying to extort money from it,''
Kazmi said.
</P>
<P>
   And here in greater Bombay, where a population of more than 14
million lives surrounded by stark extremes of wealth and poverty,
an army of alienated youths make ready recruits for the gangs.
``Millions of youngsters are unemployed,'' said D. Sivanandhan, the
joint commissioner of police for crime. ``Give them 5,000 rupees''
_ about $120 _ ``and they will pull the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Hrithik Roshan said his father had described his two assailants
as boys so young and thin that ``if you just blew, they might fly
away.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to imagine a young man further from the slums
than Hrithik. At 26, he still lives at home with his parents (he
has his own car and DVD player), but his movie career, promoted by
his father, has just begun. Overnight, Hrithik has become a
superstar heartthrob who is mobbed by teen-age girls, even on
visits to his father in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after the shooting, Hrithik sat down in the family's
plush living room to talk about the trauma. Dressed in a tight
apple green T-shirt that showed off his bulging biceps and
occasionally flashing the crooked smile that makes his fans swoon,
he detailed the series of threats and demands that preceded the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The outlaws were not just after cash, he said. These days, the
17 million Indians living abroad, as well as millions of other fans
all over the world, have become one of the most lucrative markets
for Hindi films _ and the criminals demanded overseas film rights
to ``Say You Love Me.'' They called four or five months ago,
claiming to be from the Abu Salem gang, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not in a very good financial situation,'' Hrithik
said. ``My father's previous film had flopped at the box office.
Now he was making a film with newcomers. He had to hype it up,
spend a lot of money. The film was over budget. He didn't have
money and he didn't want to start talking to these people, so he
banged the phone down.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hrithik finished his account, his father, home from the
hospital that day, hobbled into the room, his chest still bandaged,
and offered a somewhat different version.
</P>
<P>
   He said the threatening calls came on his mobile phone eight or
nine months ago, then again two months ago. He, too, said the men
claimed to be from Abu Salem's gang. But Roshan said he hung up, or
passed the phone to a friend _ and never found out what the men
wanted. He is an honest man who wanted nothing to do with
criminals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take the calls seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the police think Roshan knows more than he is letting on.
They note that he did not ask for their protection until after he
was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless he comes and tells us the truth, we will not solve the
mystery,'' said Sivanandhan, the joint police commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the movie people and the police are prickly,
to put it mildly. Police officers are often depicted as buffoons or
crooks in Bollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   In Rakesh Roshan's latest film, ``Kaho Na Pyaar Hai'' in Hindi,
one police officer hammily squeezes his legs together and winds up
urinating on himself, then smiles in comic relief. Two others are
errand boys and hit men for a big-time smuggler.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hindi movies are basically rubbish,'' Sivanandhan said
contemptuously. ``Such cheap violence and sex. They portray the
police as clowns.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the police have provided guards for all the movie
people who have asked for them _ and no one under the official
shield has yet been injured, Sivanandhan said, asking that one
thing be made clear: ``If they come to us, we are willing to give
them 100 percent protection.''
</P>
<P>
   S. Chopra, a well-known movie producer whose 28-year-old
director son, Yash, is one of Hrithik's best friends, has been
under guard for months and lives in a barely suppressed state of
terror. ``This is not life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a blue and white striped button-down shirt and pressed
blue jeans, Chopra, 68, started a conversation with a date that is
seared in his memory: Aug. 12, 1997, when his friend, the music
cassette mogul Gulshan Kumar, was killed by gangsters believed to
have been working for the infamous Salem.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Salem denied any part in the killing in an
interview from Dubai with the magazine India Today. ``No, no,'' he
was quoted as saying. ``We have excellent relations with many
filmwallahs. If we want to kill, we kill. We've done that many
times. But Gulshan was among our good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kumar's killing, the complaints about extortion calmed
down _ and some in the industry say that is because terrorized
movie people paid up.
</P>
<P>
   But the nasty calls have started up in the last six months or
so. Chopra said it is Salem himself who phones. ``You pay income
tax, right?'' Salem tells him calmly. ``This is my tax. If you
don't pay, I'll kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chopra says he has not given him any money. ``There are a
lot of gangs,'' he said. ``You pay one, there's no end to it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Manmohan Shetty, whose company, AdLabs Films, processes more
than half the Hindi movies made in Bombay, has been getting the
same calls from Salem. So far, on advice from the police, he has
strung him along without outright refusing to pay. On Dec. 29, a
gunman tried to kill Shetty as he was leaving his office, but the
weapon misfired and the assailant fled.
</P>
<P>
   Shetty's life has become a claustrophobic shuttling from work to
home and back. He has stopped going to parties. He no longer takes
his nightly walk on the beach along the Arabian Sea.
</P>
<P>
   In his rundown office, with its water-stained window shades and
grubby walls, a closed circuit black-and-white television gives him
a view of who is in his lobby and who is at the building's
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the grim circumstances, a portrait of Groucho Marx gives
a clue to Shetty's ironic style. He described running into a man in
the movie business who was surrounded by four armed guards. The
next time he saw the same man, the guards were gone. ``You don't
need a large intelligence to know what happened,'' Shetty said.
</P>
<P>
   And with a wry grin he said, ``The next time you see me without
security, assume I've paid up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
