u p BC-REPUBS-DELEGATES-NYT &LR;      02-26 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-DELEGATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH HURDLES AWAIT MCCAIN IN THE ALL-IMPORTANT RACE FOR GOP
DELEGATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eventually, the quest for presidential nominations
comes down to delegates. Numbers start counting for more than buzz,
bump and momentum.
</P>
<P>
   For Sen. John McCain, eventually is just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Through this weekend, including the 12 chosen Saturday in Guam,
the Virgin Islands and American Samoa, 214 of 2,066 delegates to
the Republican national convention have been chosen _ 10 percent of
the total. By March 14, a little more than two weeks from now,
1,374 will have been chosen _ 67 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   The four biggest states will choose the four biggest convention
delegations in March, with California and New York voting on March
7, Texas and Florida on March 14. And McCain of Arizona, who has
staged such an astonishing insurgent campaign for the nomination,
faces built-in barricades in each one.
</P>
<P>
   At this crucial moment, McCain will be ceding the home field
edge, and then some, to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, his main
rival.
</P>
<P>
   Start with Texas. It alone will elect 124 delegates, 12 percent
of the 1,034 needed for the nomination. A juicy plum, indeed, but
McCain is highly unlikely to make a big effort in Bush's home
state; when Bush tried to embarrass McCain this week in Arizona,
all he got to show for $2 million in television spending was a
24-percentage-point drubbing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is well liked in Texas, even by many Democrats, which
should narrow the only apparent opening for McCain in the state's
election laws, which permit crossover voting of the kind that
helped McCain in New Hampshire and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizonan might win a delegate or two anyway. Complex
Republican rules in Texas allot 34 delegates to the statewide
victor on a winner-take-all basis, unless no candidate polls 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In that case they are allotted proportionally, but even with
Alan Keyes, the former State Department official, in the race,
political pros in the state expect Bush to get a majority pretty
easily, and hence all the at-large delegates.
</P>
<P>
   However, McCain might conceivably hold Bush under 50 percent in
a few of the 30 congressional districts. Each of those gets three
delegates, all allotted to the winner if he gets a majority; if no
one gets a majority and the runner-up exceeds 20 percent, a very
modest threshold, the winner gets two and the runner-up one.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, which chooses 80 delegates, is structurally more
difficult for McCain. Only registered Republicans can vote in the
Republican primary, and runners-up get nothing: 11 delegates go to
the statewide winner, three to the winner in each of 23
congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brother Jeb is, of course, the governor of Florida and
will presumably go all-out for him. But the failure of Sen. Judd
Gregg of New Hampshire and Gov. John M. Engler of Michigan to blunt
McCain's drive in their states has raised questions about the clout
of office-holders.
</P>
<P>
   That question also hangs over the head of Gov. George Pataki of
New York, another keen Bush booster, who tried until the very last
minute, with an adverse court judgment looming, to use the state's
arcane election laws to keep McCain off the ballot in as many
districts as possible.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will no doubt try to turn the widespread resentment
engendered by the effort to exclude him to his own advantage in the
fight for New York's 93 elected delegates (eight others are chosen
by the Republican state committee).
</P>
<P>
   Votes are cast in New York directly for delegates, not for
presidential hopefuls, whose names appear in tiny type on the
ballots. Bush's delegate candidates are party wheel horses, by and
large, whose names are at least locally well known, while McCain's
candidates are by and large political neophytes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, New York's primary is a Republicans-only affair.
</P>
<P>
   But New York's Republicans are more moderate than those in any
of the states that have voted so far, particularly on social
issues, and there are large numbers of Roman Catholics among them.
The McCain camp, there as elsewhere, intends to remind those
Catholics of the anti-Catholic statements of leaders of Bob Jones
University, an ultra-conservative evangelical institution in
Greenville, S.C., which Bush visited.
</P>
<P>
   The senator will hope to draw many Republicans to the polls who
have not often participated in primaries, which are not common in
their party in New York. The excitement he has brought to the
campaign has helped to spur big turnouts everywhere _ double the
size of four years ago in both South Carolina and Michigan _ and
hope the newcomers are mostly moderates friendly to him, not
conservatives loyal to Bush, as in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, McCain faces an uphill battle in New York, one he can
win only if sheer voter exuberance batters down the defensive walls
built by Pataki and his allies.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar could be said of California, whose huge block
of 162 delegates constitutes more than 15 percent of the total
needed to win the nomination. There, too, only the votes of
registered Republicans will count in allocating Republican
delegates, though there is also a ``beauty contest'' in which all
candidates from all parties are listed on one ballot, and voters of
any party can choose any candidate they like, regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   All 156 of the district delegates and all six of the at-large
delegates go to the statewide winner, with nothing allocated for
the loser.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been identifying himself as a Ronald Reagan
conservative with increasing frequency since his Michigan victory,
obviously hoping to inherit some of Reagan's undying popularity in
California. His iconoclastic stand on campaign financing and his
image as a maverick ought to play well in the state, and the
endorsement of Bush by state Republican leaders could backfire;
they do not have much credibility left after six years of losses in
major races.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, McCain trails by about 2-to-1 in recent
polls. But at least he should have no trouble capturing the
attention of the electorate, a vital element in any insurgency.
Reporting on a recent survey by the nonpartisan Public Policy
Institute of California, its survey director, Mark Baldassare, said
that ``voters are engaged in a way they haven't been for years.''
If the candidates speak to their concerns, he added, ``they'll find
the voters all ears.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has often rallied from far back, of course, but he has
not previously faced difficulties of the dimensions now confronting
him.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, McCain is the underdog in each of the four big
states. He almost certainly could not survive losses in all of
them, which would give Bush so many delegates that not even a
highly improbable sweep by McCain in such states as Ohio, Illinois,
Massachusetts, Georgia, Missouri and Colorado, all of which vote by
March 21, could stop the Texan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
