<SLUG> BC-POPE-EGYPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE VISITS MOUNT SINAI AND ITS RELICS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOUNT SINAI, Egypt _ Saying he felt ``great joy and deep
emotion,'' Pope John Paul II prayed Saturday at the spot where
tradition says Moses once stood, and called himself a pilgrim ``in
the footsteps of God.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip was a personal triumph for the 79-year-old pope who had
long dreamed of visiting the Holy Lands. But it was shadowed by
some disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who spoke at St. Catherine's, the monastery at the
foothills of Mount Sinai that is one of the most revered in the
Greek Orthodox Church, had once hoped to gather there Christian,
Muslim and Jewish leaders to symbolize religious reconciliation in
the new millennium. Objections by the Greek Orthodox monks, among
others, dashed that plan.
</P>
<P>
   Poignantly, the pope alluded to his unfulfilled dream.
Describing the wind from Mount Sinai as a sign from God, the pope
said, ``It carries an insistent invitation to dialogue between the
followers of the great monotheistic religions.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope spoke to several hundred cheering believers who were
crammed in an olive grove on the monastery grounds. He was seated
underneath a tent beside a pink-budded almond tree, Mount Sinai's
jagged, rusty peaks at his back.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd shouted, ``John Paul II, we love you!'' so often that
the pope at one point replied, ``John Paul II loves you too.'' When
the crowd waved olive branches as he left, the pope waved back with
his cane.
</P>
<P>
   Before the prayer service, the pope toured the sixth century
monastery, asking questions about its icons and collection of
illuminated manuscripts _ the world's second largest after the
Vatican's.
</P>
<P>
   When Archbishop Damianos, abbot of the monastery, took him to
the chapel, which tradition says was built on top of the roots of
Moses' burning bush, the pope fell to his knees and prayed alone
for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When he reached the relics of St. Catherine, a fourth century
Christian martyr, the pope, in an ancient ritual, took a ring,
placed it on the bones of her finger and skull and then kissed the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   The visit was the emotional high point of John Paul three-day
trip _ the first papal visit to Egypt ever. The pope, who looked
tired and weak during much of the journey, Saturday delivered his
speech in a clear, forceful voice.
</P>
<P>
   Greek Orthodox monks helped him down the steps to the podium,
but his spokesman said he needed no assistance to kneel at the site
of the burning bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek Orthodox Church does not recognize the authority of
the pope, and its leaders are wary of ecumenical rapprochement.
Damianos embraced the pope as he arrived, but he did not pray with
him. ``It is impossible, it is against our canon law,'' the
archbishop explained later. He said that, for his faith, unity
between Roman Catholics and Orthodox was ``possible, but it would
take a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Theological differences got in the way of the desired ceremony
with Muslims and Jews. Greek Orthodox Christians are wary of
suggesting that all these religions are equal. Damianos also cited
political realities of the Middle East. ``Perhaps such dialogue
could be possible, but not in an Islamic country,'' he said. ``It
is very difficult because of the mentality of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican repeatedly described the pope's visit as a purely
personal pilgrimage, but inevitably political tensions surfaced
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Before the pope left Rome, the Vatican signed an agreement with
the Palestine Liberation Organization that guarantees Christian
property and legal rights in a future Palestinian state. It also
declared that any unilateral decision on the status of Jerusalem is
illegal and immoral.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement angered Israel, and while the pope was in Cairo,
Israeli religious leaders said they opposed his plan to hold a
Catholic service on a Saturday in Nazareth when he visits Israel
next month, suggesting that the necessary security arrangements
would violate the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, however, the pope focused intently on the Old
Testament, and savored his solemn private moments in the Sinai
Desert. There were a few distractions. As the pope's Mercedes drove
through the desolate desert canyon toward the monastery, a group of
young pilgrims from his native Poland waited on a rock on the other
side of the canyon, shouting and waving in his direction. The pope
waved at them as he drove by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
