<SLUG> BC-MICH-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S LOSS IN MICHIGAN FORCES DEBATE ON OPEN PRIMARIES 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Gov. George W. Bush's unexpected loss in Michigan's
primary last Tuesday, despite strong support from virtually all of
the Republican establishment here, has left the state's Republican
leaders divided over what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Engler, who has dominated Michigan's Republican Party
for 17 years, mounted an enormous effort to get out the vote on
Bush's behalf. But his candidate lost to Sen. John McCain's tiny
and relatively disorganized campaign here, which claimed 51 percent
of the vote to Bush's 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans here try to figure out how to make sure such an
embarrassment never happens again, the main split lies in whether
to end the practice of allowing Democrats and independents to vote
in the party's open primary. Exit polls found that 40 to 51 percent
of the voters in the Republican primary were actually crossovers,
compared with about 30 percent in most years. Democrats and
independents favored McCain overwhelmingly while Bush prevailed
among Republicans alone.
</P>
<P>
   Several state senators and one of the state's members of the
Republican National Committee, Chuck Yob, have called publicly for
the party to abandon open primaries unless Democrats resume holding
open primaries on the same day, which might reduce the number of
crossover voters. ``We can't let this happen again, and I'm not
talking about Bush losing, I'm talking about Democrats' voting in
huge numbers,'' Yob said. ``It's not fair that they determine who
we put up against them in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's Democrats plan to hold closed caucuses on March 11.
Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley pulled their
names off last Tuesday's primary ballot to comply with a Democratic
National Committee rule limiting the use of open primaries to
allocate delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Engler helped ignite support for a closed primary on Tuesday
evening, when he accused McCain of having borrowed Democrats to use
in the open primary. ``We probably ought to conclude that's not a
very good way to hold a primary,'' Engler said then.
</P>
<P>
   But he said at a news conference on Thursday that an open
primary remained the best option, because it could lure
independents and Democrats to the Republican Party. A telephone
poll by The Detroit Free Press, published Thursday, found that 60
percent of the Democrats and 63 percent of the independents who
voted for McCain were very or somewhat certain that they would vote
for him again in November.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Spencer Abraham, a Republican seeking re-election this
year, wants to keep the primary open to independents and Democrats,
but also wants the party to study whether Michigan should resume
holding its election late in the primary season. Early primaries
should be held in states where only Republicans are allowed to
vote, which might make the contests less bruising, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have derived some solace from the fact that
Bush beat McCain here by 2-to-1 among Republicans. Rusty Hills, a
longtime political lieutenant of Engler's, estimated that 300,000
of the 548,000 votes that Bush received were the direct result of
efforts by Engler and his political organization to get out the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine what the final result would have been without Engler
going to the mat for him,'' Hills said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1514EST &QL; 
