<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-WASH-PRIMARIES-ART-NY     02-26 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASH-PRIMARIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MINI-TUESDAY NOW LOOMS LARGER FOR BOTH PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When the 2000 presidential campaign began, the
Republican and Democratic primaries that will be held in Washington
state on Tuesday were hardly more than blips on the political
horizon, arcane little contests lying somewhere out on the trail
between the first-in-the nation Iowa caucuses and the
could-end-it-all mass of 13 primaries scheduled for Titanic
Tuesday, March 7.
</P>
<P>
   But because the early months of the campaign have been so
unexpectedly topsy-turvy, the Washington primaries, with their
quirky rules and oft-quirky voters, suddenly loom large, and the
candidates have been forced to change plans and divert scarce
resources and time to compete.
</P>
<P>
   There is opportunity, and danger, for all candidates in these
contests, but especially for Sen. John McCain of Arizona, still
trying to forge ahead of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas on the
Republican side, and for former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey,
still badly trailing Vice President Al Gore on the Democratic side.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has no party registration and voters may choose on
primary day to vote in either contest. Both McCain and Bradley have
been going after party switchers and independent voters, McCain
particularly, while their opponents have been concentrating mainly
on the hard-core base within their parties.
</P>
<P>
   Given that an unusually large number of Washington voters, 50
percent or more, claim to be independents (many maintain that
ideology is a private matter), there has often been a lot of voting
flux in primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be a very tricky state when it comes to politics and
voting,'' said David Brine, the communications director for the
office of the secretary of state, which regulates state elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is fixed in stone here,'' Brine said. ``There's a long
tradition of switching around in parties and on issues.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Bradley are chasing after independents and party
switchers so hard that they find themselves in competition for some
of the same votes, particularly when they are talking up one of
their favorite issues, government reform. In fact, Bradley has
concluded that Washington not only offers him a big chance to go
after independent voters but also offers what may be his last
chance, with the help of independent votes, to post a victory over
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Such a victory would come in a race that under party rules is
essentially a beauty contest, with no convention delegations to be
won. But Bradley nevertheless is committing huge amounts of time
and money to what amounts to a bet-it-all gamble _ win a contest,
any contest, anywhere, of whatever nature.
</P>
<P>
   The actual choosing of the state's allotment of 75 delegates to
the Democratic National Convention will take place in a March 7
round of caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, comfortably ahead in most recent Washington polls, has
been forced to match the Bradley effort to protect his flank,
something he had not anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also committing significant resources to the contest
here and, much to Bradley's frustration, seems to be dominating the
chase after independents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, like Gore, is responding in kind with money and manpower.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican contest is part beauty contest, part real primary
and, like the Democratic contest, will be followed by a round of
caucuses on March 7. Twelve of the party's allotment of 37
delegates to the Republican National Convention will be chosen on
Tuesday, the rest on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show the Bush-McCain competition too close to call,
just as it was too close to call on the eve of voting in several
earlier contests.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, coming off his surprise victory on Tuesday in
Michigan, a Washington victory would add to the momentum he has
been building as he seeks to overcome Bush's huge earlier lead over
most of the country. This would be especially true if he were to
win both the beauty contest and the 12-delegates contest, though he
and Bush very well might end up splitting those contests because of
the complex rules that govern them.
</P>
<P>
   But if a McCain victory here is to have truly significant
meaning, the senator must not only beat Bush but demonstrate in
beating him that he can pull large numbers of conservative
Republican votes _ the ultimate key to the party's nomination _ not
just the votes of Republican moderates, dissident Democrats and
independents, his victory mix so far.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been very successful in doing that in other states,
no matter how hard he has tried. But now that he has retooled his
pitch _ ``I am a Reagan Republican,'' became his mantra after
Michigan _ he may have a better shot at it, particularly here in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Republicans tend to be more moderate than Republicans
in many other states, though there are plenty of conservatives
here. Certainly Washington Republicans are likely to be more
receptive to the new McCain pitch than Republicans in Virginia, a
conservative bastion and Bush stronghold that also will hold a
primary on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is a McCain kind of state,'' said Kris Wilder, the
director of the McCain effort here. ``More than in most states, the
Washington state voter has a mind of his own, of her own, just like
John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, needs to regain momentum in Tuesday's
voting. He badly needs a success here to twin with a presumed
victory in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is a tough one but we feel good about the
outcome,'' said Mike McKay, a chairman of the Bush effort here.
``We feel we have the support and we're confident we have the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns are filling the airwaves with a round of
last-minute television and radio advertisements, mailing out
thousands and thousands of campaign fliers and inundating voters
with telephone calls. The senator flew here for a day of
campaigning just hours after his Michigan triumph and will return
for another visit just a few hours before the polls open. The
governor will visit over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley, the Democratic contest here could be his last
hurrah, because a loss in Washington would lengthen Gore's string
of victories over him to four in a row. So unlike the other
candidates, who are dipping in and out of the state so that they
can also work the other states in the March 7 primaries, Bradley is
remaining here almost the entire week leading up to Tuesday's vote.
His main pitch: Gore is a conservative whereas he is the true
liberal and Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win this primary or have a very strong showing,'' Mo
Elleithee, Bradley's spokesman, said the other day, ``it will be a
signal to the rest of the country that Bill Bradley is viable and
this thing is not wrapped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, confident momentum on his side, plans to visit the state
briefly over the weekend but otherwise is leaving his campaign
effort here up to surrogates, many of them top labor leaders and
members of the state's Democratic establishment, like Paul Berendt,
the Democratic state chairman. They have kept up a drumbeat of
charges that Bradley is engaging in negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking the low road,'' Berendt said, ``and what he's
going to find is that Washington voters are going to punish him for
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
