<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-PHONE-CALLS-NY     02-26 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-PHONE-CALLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN ALLIES REMINDED VOTERS OF BUSH SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ In the past week, the Republican presidential race
was stirred by a telephone campaign in Michigan criticizing Gov.
George W. Bush for speaking at a college whose leaders have
espoused harshly anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   Aides for Sen. John McCain, who have acknowledged making the
calls, Saturday said the inspiration for them came from a handful
of political amateurs, and McCain acknowledged that he had
personally approved of the phone bank operation.
</P>
<P>
   Five days before the Michigan primary, a group of McCain
volunteers began calling Catholic friends and neighbors, the aides
said, telling them that Bush had given a speech at Bob Jones
University, a bastion of the Christian right whose leaders have
called the pope the anti-Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, immediately after Bush had defeated McCain in a
bitter South Carolina primary with the help of Christian Coalition
and antiabortion phone banks, the McCain campaign recognized the
effectiveness of the Michigan phone calls and decided to expand on
the tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Aides drafted a telephone script, purchased lists of Catholic
voters and contracted with a telemarketing company that on Monday,
the day before the primary, called between 15,000 and 20,000 Roman
Catholic households in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   While all of McCain's television commercials and print materials
clearly state that they are paid for by the McCain campaign, the
taped telephone messages did not reveal that the McCain campaign
was behind them.. But Bush quickly caught wind of them, and as he
was falling to defeat on primary day, he bitterly accused McCain's
campaign of orchestrating the calls, which he said unfairly implied
that he shares the anti-Catholic views of Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, a McCain spokesman denied that the campaign
had anything to do with the calls, but later in the day a top aide
acknowledged that they had been made by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, responding to frequent questions about them from both
reporters and voters, has tried to use the issue to lump Bush with
the forces of the far right. Though conceding that Bush ``is not a
bigot,'' McCain has repeatedly asked how Bush could have spoken at
the university without repudiating its anti-Catholic teachings or
its ban on interracial dating. Had he been invited to speak at the
university, he told a crowd in Sacramento, ``I'd have told them,
`Get out of the 16th Century and into the 21st Century.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now some of Bush's own supporters, such as New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, are saying the visit to Bob Jones University was
a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush has countered by saying the calls reveal
the hypocrisy behind two of McCain's signature pledges _ his
promises to suspend all negative advertising and to always tell the
truth to the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Murphy, senior strategist for McCain, suggested it was a
matter of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between 20,000 advocacy phones calls and $8
million in negative TV advertising is the difference between a
grain of sand and the Rock of Gibraltar,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has lately been vigorously denouncing what he says are
McCain's deceptive campaign tactics, and he has said he is a victim
of ``guilt by association.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm running against a man,'' Bush said Friday on a swing
through Virginia, ``who on the one hand says he's going to run a
clean campaign and on the other hand makes phone calls in Michigan
that talk about anti-Catholic bias.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his staff refused to rule out more such phone calls
in the coming primaries and have even expressed glee that Bush's
criticism of the calls draws more attention to Bob Jones
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they squealed about it, the more an issue it
became,'' McCain's spokesman, Howard Opinsky, said.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Molinari, borough president of Staten Island, the
co-chairman of McCain's New York campaign, has promised to
highlight Bush's visit to Bob Jones University with the state's
Republican voters, almost half of whom are Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, after a rally in San Diego, McCain expressed
irritation when a reporter pressed him on how his campaign's
telephone calls were any different from the telephone calls that
Pat Robertson made, in which Robertson referred indirectly to a
McCain adviser, Warren Rudman, and called him ``a vicious bigot''
because of statements he had made about the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that you don't get the difference,'' McCain said
tartly. ``The calls that Pat Robertson made called Warren Rudman a
bigot. That's entirely different from factual phone calls that
describe exactly what the facts are.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a script from the Bush campaign, the McCain calls
stated: ``Gov. George Bush has campaigned against Sen. John McCain
by seeking the support of Southern fundamentalists who have
expressed anti-Catholic views. Bob Jones has made strong
anti-Catholic statements, including calling the pope anti-Christ,
the Catholic Church a satanic cult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has stayed silent,'' the script read.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the day of the primary, as voters were still going
to the polls, Opinsky denied the campaign had been behind the
calls. Later in the day, other aides said they may have been made
by over-exuberant volunteers. After the polls closed, with McCain's
victory assured, the campaign manager, Rick Davis, acknowledged the
phone calls had been paid for by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, in defense of Bush's appearance, noted that a
string of Republican leaders have given speeches at Bob Jones
University, including Rep. Lindsey Graham, McCain's most prominent
supporter in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lindsey Graham isn't running for president of the United
States,'' McCain said in an interview Friday night on a flight from
California to Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1528EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-950&AMP;AD     02-26 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERLY PAY DEARLY FOR CONGRESSIONAL INACTION ON DRUG COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ When the last health maintenance
organization in this working-class town pulled out two months ago,
it cut a vital lifeline to prescription drugs for hundreds of
retirees like Mary Elizabeth Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 83, has Medicare, but the federal program does not
cover drug costs for people outside the hospital. So Johnson, whose
HMO partly offset the cost of her drugs, must now pay nearly $84 a
month from her $850-a-month Social Security check for medications
to lower her blood pressure and treat a thyroid condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely not poor, but I'm not rich,'' Johnson told her
congressman, Rep. Mark A. Foley, who met with two dozen retirees at
a senior center here. ``When the HMO was here, I paid a $10
co-payment for each prescription. That was OK. Now, one day, I
won't be able to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   As Congress wrestles with the white-hot political issue of
Medicare drug benefits, Republicans like Foley, a popular
three-term centrist with a strong health care record, are in the
hot seat at home.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed expanding Medicare to give
prescription drug benefits to all of the program's 39 million
beneficiaries. Currently, one-third of Medicare recipients have no
drug coverage, and the remainder often face inadequate coverage or
must make expensive co-payments. The cost of drugs in recent years
has skyrocketed, outstripping the ability of many retirees to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has riveted the attention of voters here in south
Florida, as well as across the country, and it is not hard to see
why. People 65 or older make up nearly one-quarter of Foley's
district, which has the seventh-largest number of retirees of any
congressional district in the country. And while they make up 12
percent of the nation's population, they use one-third of all drugs
prescribed each year.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on Capitol Hill agree that Medicare recipients need
legislative relief this year, but they have stumbled in their
response to Clinton's initiative, which would cost more than $160
billion over 10 years. Speaker J. Dennis Hastert last month
appointed a task force to draft a House Republican alternative, but
the effort has yet to get off the ground. Republican senators are
also working on their own version.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meantime, sense a political winner and are turning up
the heat on Republicans. House Democrats are using a parliamentary
tactic to try to force a vote on drug coverage for all Medicare
beneficiaries. Democratic candidates in border states are taking
busloads of retirees to Canada and Mexico, where having a
prescription filled costs one-third to one-half of what it costs in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have engaged earlier,'' conceded Foley, a member of
the House Ways and Means Committee, which has jurisdiction over
Medicare. ``But the Democrats, rather than being constructive, are
trying to box us in.''
</P>
<P>
   In a day of meetings with retirees, doctors and health care
providers throughout his district, Foley accused Clinton and his
supporters in Congress of pandering to older voters. At the risk of
being the skunk at the garden party, Foley said he was trying to
inject some badly needed common sense in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be a drug benefit for those who desperately need
it and can't afford it, and for those with life-threatening illness
like cancer or diabetes,'' said Foley, 45, who speaks fluently on
complex health issues. ``But I'm upset that we're talking about
creating a new entitlement for the guy who lives in a
million-dollar ocean front condo, drives a Mercedes, and has a
$50,000 membership at the golf club.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the president's proposal, Medicare would pay half of a
beneficiary's drug expenses, up to certain limits. The maximum
federal payment would start at $1,000 a year and would rise
gradually to $2,500 in 2008. Beyond that basic benefit, Clinton is
also asking Congress to set aside $35 billion to help protect
Medicare beneficiaries with extremely high drug costs in the years
2006 to 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's concern struck a chord with many in this disparate
district, whose demographics range from the super rich in Palm
Beach to transplanted New Yorkers at the Century Village retirement
complex in West Palm Beach to citrus growers and cattle ranchers in
the rural western reaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the problem with the Clinton program: It's one size
fits all,'' said Dr. Peter Dayton, an obstetrician in Stuart, Fla.,
who along with several other doctors and nurses met with Foley
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than expanding Medicare, several doctors and health-care
providers said they prefer an approach favored by many Republicans
to use private health plans or block grants to states to provide
drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But no one disputed that Congress and the White House need to
act quickly. Indeed, doctors poured out heart-rending stories of
uninsured elderly patients who cannot afford the drugs to keep them
alive or manage their pain.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nicholas O. Iannotti, a cancer specialist whose thriving
practice is made up of 90 percent Medicare recipients, said the
program covers the cost of drugs given to patients in hospitals or
his office, but not prescriptions they buy on their own. Many
patients do not buy the drugs they need, and end up back in the
hospital, which Iannotti said ``costs a fortune compared to a $15
pill they could have taken. It's wasteful.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his terminally ill Medicare patients have given up
treating their cancer altogether and are turning to hospice care,
which will provide pain-killing medication at no cost. ``They'll
die sooner, but at least they will be out of pain,'' Iannotti told
Foley.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chris Lundstrom, who operates a 21-person assisted-living center
in Fort Pierce, said his residents were increasingly having to
choose between spending their fixed incomes on food or prescription
drugs. He urged Foley to fight for price controls on drugs, a step
Foley is wary of taking. ``Some are foregoing their meds to pay for
food,'' said Lundstrom. ``We need some controls in the medications.
The prices are outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Even retirees who buy supplemental policies to plug the gap in
their Medicare benefits worry that caps on annual drug spending _
for seniors here, $750 to $1,000 a year _ ultimately mean they will
have to pay more out-of-pocket costs for their medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to pay our share, but we still need some help,''
said Mary Vorees, an 85-year-old former school teacher from
Otisville, N.Y., who retired here and has a $221-a-month
prescription drug bill.
</P>
<P>
   Foley takes in all the comments, nodding, occasionally jotting
himself a note. When the give-and-take starts getting a bit too
heated, he injects a little humor: ``The good news is, you live
longer. The bad news is, you die broke.''
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of the issue is not lost on him. ``Why waste money
on a kidney transplant if you're not going to pay for the
anti-rejection drug?'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   And he expressed confidence that Congress would set aside
partisanship to pass a remedy. ``Things are achievable,'' he said.
``We're not going to be trapped into saying no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
