<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-TAX-REVOLT-2TA     02-26 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TAX-REVOLT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISING TAX BILLS FUEL ANGER IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In a hotel restaurant here, Jordan switched her cell
phone to voice mail, nibbled on a slice of cold salmon, and then
spun a libertarian view of taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work strictly on a cash basis, so I don't get bit on the
tax,'' said the 28-year-old college graduate, who prefers to go by
her first name when talking about her ``escort'' work, a business
that is growing rapidly in Canadian cities.
</P>
<P>
   On the Pacific Coast, marijuana growers have propelled their
illicit exports to the United States into a $1 billion-a-year
business, making it one of British Columbia's top exports. And for
Toronto's button-down professionals, Caribbean tax havens have
become such popular winter vacation spots that Revenue Canada has
increased its international auditors by sixfold, reaching 300 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   A tax bite is transforming the Great White North. Long seen by
Americans as law-abiding Dudley Do-Rights, Canadians today
increasingly dodge taxes in ways more commonly associated with
Brazilians, Italians or even Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians are not in the same league as the Italians or
Brazilians,'' said David Giles, a University of Victoria economist,
who estimates that Canada's under-the-table economy now approaches
20 percent of gross domestic product. ``Canadians are clumsy. But
they are blushing less and less. In fact, they are becoming brazen
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, more cautious Canadians, who once sniffed that
their unruly neighbor to the south was born of a tax revolt, are
now undergoing a very un-Canadian experience: a tax revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five years, payroll taxes increased by an average
of 26 percent and the government's total take of personal and
corporate income jumped by almost 40 percent. Here in Quebec, home
to North America's highest income tax rates, 51.7 percent, the tax
bite means that the average resident works for the government until
July 6. Shoppers in Canada also pay a sales tax that averages about
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 28, when the federal government's new budget is
introduced, the governing Liberal Party promises to offer a modest
tax cut, probably around $32 billion spread over five years. Much
of Canada's tax load, government officials say, comes from paying
interest on debts inherited from past Conservative and Liberal
governments. The Liberals add that taxes pay for benefits _
Canada's health care and inexpensive college education. Finally,
they argue, Canada's tax load is about average for the 29 countries
of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at only one aspect of life, maybe you would prefer
living elsewhere. There is nothing forcing you to stay here,''
Prime Minister Jean Chretien told a reporter last year, drawing
political sustenance from public opinion polls that indicated
Canadians cared more about improving health care than about cutting
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But public sentiment appears to be changing. A new national
anti-tax coalition is gaining ground, and leaders of the tax revolt
contend that Canadians do not compare themselves with Swedes and
Finns.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look across the border at New Hampshire, where there is
no sales tax, no state income tax and a low federal rate _ and
people become pretty envious,'' said Martin Solberg, tax critic for
the Reform Party, the largest opposition party and a leader of the
new tax-cutting movement. Speaking from his home in Alberta, in the
west, he said: ``When we do 85 percent of your trade with the U.S.,
it is really important that we are competitive with the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Tax Foundation, a Toronto-based research group, has
calculated that during the 1990s, partly because of the tax load,
average disposable income for Canadians declined 12 percent, while
average American disposable income expanded about 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '90s will go down in history as the worst decade since the
Great Depression in terms of GDP per capita,'' Joe Martin, chairman
of the National History Society, wrote recently in Canada's leading
history magazine, The Beaver.
</P>
<P>
   Smelling blood, the Reform Party moved out of its western
stronghold in February and started forming a nationwide
conservative political coalition. First, it adopted a radical
central plank: the reduction of top federal income tax rates to 17
percent from 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This new coalition, the Canadian Alliance, is growing on bases
in Ontario and Alberta, two voter-rich provinces already ruled by
tax-cutting conservatives. In Ontario, Mike Harris easily won
re-election last May, after he cut provincial taxes 30 percent
during his first term. In Alberta, Stockwell Day, the provincial
treasurer, plans to carry out by next January Canada's first
provincial flat tax, a top rate of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the emergence of this coalition, Canada's finance minister,
Paul Martin, ended a self-imposed silence during the pre-budget
season to criticize the opposition's flat tax idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 17 percent proposal would clearly either put our health
care system or our education system into jeopardy, or it would put
us back into deficit,'' Martin told reporters. ``We're simply not
going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said: ``We are going to reduce taxes, and we believe that
we must reduce taxes. However, we believe that it must be done in a
fair and balanced way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, news leaks about impending tax cuts reflect a political
recognition that many Canadians want tax cuts. In mid-January, the
Liberal government proposed a government subsidy to keep National
Hockey League teams in Canada. Public anger was so intense that the
proposal was dropped in three days. No sooner had that uproar died
away when the government became tangled in one of the most
embarrassing political crises of its seven-year rule. An audit
showed sloppy or nonexistent accounting for $2.2 billion in ``job
creation'' grants doled out by the government's biggest department,
Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   In moving public opinion, tax cutters have found a powerful new
ally in The National Post, a 16-month-old newspaper edited by
imported British journalists who seem intent on conquering Canada
with Margaret Thatcher's ideology.
</P>
<P>
   In a typically scathing essay, Conrad Black, the
British-Canadian owner of The Post, recently belittled Ottawa's
success in erasing an inherited deficit of $29 billion, writing
that ``70 percent of the progress has just been piggybacking on
American prosperity.'' Black and other critics say that much of
Ottawa's budget balancing has come by cutting health and education
transfer payments to provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of urging Canadians to compare themselves with
Scandinavia, The Post suggests Ireland. Twenty years ago, a Post
columnist noted recently, Ireland had half of Canada's per-capita
income. After embarking on radical tax cuts, Irish per capita
income is now 15 percent higher than Canada's.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tax resistance seems to cross the economic spectrum here.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders stress that among the top industrialized
countries, Canada's average corporate income tax, 43 percent, is
only topped by Japan's rate of 48 percent. Canada's maximum capital
gains rate of 37.7 percent is almost double the top American rate
of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Internet entrepreneurs bridle under this country's
system of taxing stock options when they are granted, as against
the American approach of taxing them when they are exercised.
</P>
<P>
   ``You trigger a tax without having the money to pay for it,''
said David B. Perry, a senior research associate at the Canadian
Tax Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   For personal income taxes, Canada's top federal rate, 29
percent, affects income over $40,834. By comparison, the 28 percent
tax bracket in the United States affects income over $43,850 for
married couples and the maximum rate of 39.6 percent kicks in at
$288,350. Largely because Canada uncoupled tax rates from inflation
a decade ago, more taxpayers have shifted into higher brackets. And
in contrast to the United States, there is no deduction for
interest paid on home mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   High taxes also contribute to Canada's century-old problem of a
brain drain to the United States. With higher salaries and wider
opportunities contributing to the American lure, a poll taken in
December found that about a third of Canadian Internet users
surveyed said they expected a family member to move to the United
States in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   A separate survey of Canadian MBA graduates of the Harvard
Business School found that the portion returning to Canada had
plummeted to 25 percent of the class of 1998 from 58 percent in the
late '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians earn less and pay higher taxes for generally
inferior public services than Americans,'' The Globe and Mail, a
newspaper that generally backs the Liberal government, said in a
recent editorial.
</P>
<P>
   With tax evasion increasingly mainstream here, few eyebrows were
raised when Statistics Canada reported in January that spending on
house renovation had dropped by almost 40 percent during the 1990s.
Canadians are not letting their houses fall down. They are cutting
cash deals with contractors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
