<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SUMMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MAKING SUMMER SCHOOL SUCCEED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, February 27:
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three months, Harold Levy, the interim schools
chancellor, faces the challenge of organizing a summer school
program for an estimated 320,000 students in New York City. Among
his duties are notifying students who need to show up for summer
session, hiring 17,000 teachers, providing transportation and
helping district superintendents develop programs that will allow
the lowest-achieving students to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Whether prepared or not, there is no turning back now. The Board
of Education's policy to end social promotion in grades 3 to 12
means that all students with very low test scores will have to
attend summer school and pass an exam at the end of the summer in
order to enter the next grade.
</P>
<P>
   Levy clearly will have to improve on last summer's dismal
experience. Last year, in the first phase of ending social
promotion, only 35,000 third, sixth and eighth graders were
required to attend summer school (about 190,000 students attended
summer school voluntarily). Yet of the mandatory attendance group,
14,000 students did not show up. About 21,000 students in just
those three grades had to repeat a grade because they missed summer
session, or missed or failed the exam.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the mandatory attendance number will be many times
higher. If the summer school programs are ineffective, tens of
thousands of failing students will return to the same classrooms
that failed to educate them in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, district superintendents and central
administrators will be putting together educational plans for the
summer sessions. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has pushed to have 20
percent of the summer programs run by private educational firms.
The school board has put out requests for private sector
involvement, but there may not be that level of interest in the
private sector. Even with private management, it will still be up
to the school board to recruit qualified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Finding 17,000 teachers for summer school, up from 11,000 last
year, will be hard. Making sure that they are experienced,
certified teachers will be even more of a challenge. Drawing more
qualified teachers may mean offering incentives, including perhaps
higher pay. Another potential problem is a lack of adequate summer
school busing, which would lower student attendance. Both needs
require more money than is now in the mayor's proposed budget,
which provides $160 million for summer school instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Additional state funds may be available eventually. But
``eventually'' will not be soon enough, since the schools must make
crucial recruitment and transportation decisions in the coming
weeks. The mayor and the school board therefore need to resolve
these issues quickly so that the huge summer school project can
proceed on a sound footing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1550EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0078 </DOCNO>
