u k BC-EDIT-WASH-VOTE-NYT &LR;      02-26 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WASH-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ON TO WASHINGTON STATE   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, February 27:
</P>
<P>
   Now that the presidential race is reaching full throttle, each
new election barrels down on the candidates before they can even
catch their breath from the one just past. The three states voting
Tuesday _ Washington, Virginia and North Dakota _ pose the toughest
challenges for former Sen. Bill Bradley and Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since New Hampshire, they will now be
scrambling with each other for crossover votes from all parties.
But since Bradley has not won a primary yet, he is fighting hardest
to hang on. Washington is the place he has chosen for a showdown
with Vice President Al Gore. With the state's prosperous
high-tech-oriented voters likely to be receptive to his appeal,
Bradley needs to do well, or risk falling back even further.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is known as a place for free-thinking independents
with a soft spot for thoughtful interlopers. To appeal to them,
Bradley is taking a major risk of campaigning there for five days,
a step that will invite political pundits and professionals to
question the viability of his candidacy if he fails to produce a
big turnout.
</P>
<P>
   For the last six weeks, Bradley has had the misfortune of seeing
McCain usurp what he hoped would be his role as outsider and
reformer. Now in Washington, his main problem is that McCain could
pull away the independents and crossover Democrats that Bradley
needs to offset Gore's strength among core Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the Washington vote is strictly a
``beauty contest,'' with actual delegates to be selected later. But
it is still of vital importance to the former senator, and in
response, Vice President Gore has stepped up his own campaigning in
the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for his part, is looking for real-Republican credentials
in the West. He has put up a new television ad in Washington and
several other states invoking Ronald Reagan's name. With its
Western setting and references to the former president, the ad is
designed to build McCain up for the important California primary on
March 7. On that date, he also faces Gov. George W. Bush in 11
other primary states, including New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is considered the favorite in North Dakota and Virginia
because he is once again counting on the local Republican
establishment. But Virginia, which combines an open primary and
very conservative regular Republicans, could offer some surprises.
McCain is trying hard at the last minute to convince traditional
Republicans that he has a better chance of winning in November than
Bush. A Bush defeat _ or even a narrower-than-expected win _ could
harm the Texan among GOP elders already grumbling about his
tactical blunders and underwhelming vote totals. A weak Bush
showing would also suggest that even establishment Republicans are
disenchanted by his sudden transmutation from compassionate
conservative to expedient right-winger.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to advance an argument for the symbolic or numerical
importance of the caucus in North Dakota on Tuesday. The state's
Republicans will pick 19 of the 1,034 delegates needed for the
nomination. The selection process has long been wired for Bush. But
even out in the plains, the excitement of this year's race is being
felt.
</P>
<P>
   Curly Haugland, the state Republican chairman, told a reporter
with some degree of incredulity, ``We could have somewhat of an
impact, much more than we maybe thought earlier.'' It has been that
kind of year. Everyone wants a part of the action, and everyone is
having a great time _ except, perhaps, for the candidates who face
harrowing tests every time a Tuesday rolls around. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1554EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
