<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-SMITH-NYT &LR;      02-26 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SMITH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL COLUMN: BRUCE SMITH KNOWS THINGS HAPPEN FOR A REASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day last week Bruce Smith sat in his new office in Norfolk,
Va., signing payroll checks. Smith has a new team. Actually, he has
two.
</P>
<P>
   The Norfolk Nighthawks of the Arena Football League II _ not to
be confused with the original Arena Football League, which
suspended its 2000 season on Friday _ make their debut in early
April. Smith, along with his partner Kenny Easley, a former Seattle
Seahawks safety, own the Nighthawks. Smith's debut as a Washington
Redskins defensive end will come later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we fought and struck for as players a few years ago _
free agency _ we never realized would haunt us in this fashion,''
said Smith, the sack leader among all active National Football
League players, who gained all 173.5 of those sacks in 15 seasons
with the Buffalo Bills. ``In some ways, this situation has left a
bad taste in my mouth. I am not mad and bitter, but when you have
built a home and long-term relationships and then your time is cut
short in a place because of salary-cap issues, it is unfortunate.
This situation is doing some bad things around the league with guys
like myself and Dan Marino and Deion Sanders. I still look back in
disbelief. Buffalo was a place imbedded in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But free agency and salary-cap-minded moves continue to roll
forward and create drastic change in today's NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Galloway is out of Seattle and in Dallas. Jeff Blake left
Cincinnati for New Orleans. Hardy Nickerson, no longer in Tampa
Bay, is in Jacksonville. Shannon Sharpe fled Denver for Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Do fans really care? Of course they do. Do players want to move?
Many do.
</P>
<P>
   When free agency was introduced to the NFL as part of the
collective-bargaining agreement with players for the 1993 season,
two vital questions were pondered.
</P>
<P>
   Would players move to smaller markets like Green Bay and
Cincinnati or would all players want to jump to larger cities like
New York and Miami? ``We've seen the answer to that one,'' Smith
said. ``A large market is anywhere Super Bowls and the George
Washingtons make their home.''
</P>
<P>
   Another question: Since free agency was instituted with a salary
cap for each team attached, would players in the twilight of their
careers be cut so that teams could spend less on younger players
and make their annual cap fit more amenable?
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo answered that question in the most astonishing statement
in the six-year history of free agency. It released Smith, running
back Thurman Thomas and receiver Andre Reed _ the remnants of its
four 1990's Super Bowl teams _ because, it said, of cap reasons. A
major identity of the Bills, in many ways their soul, vanished in
one swipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had the opportunity to play in front of our fans one
more time knowing that it was my last time,'' Smith said. ``After
15 years in one place, the fans deserved better. I never got a
chance to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three days before the Bills had to be under the cap, they
asked me to take a pay cut for this season from $4.68 million to
$2.2 million. A lot of times players are asked to restructure their
deals, but this was a pure and simple cut. We were $11 million over
the cap a year ago so they knew this situation would come to a head
when it was time to get it down. Maybe if they had talked to me a
year ago I could have warmed up to the idea; I would have given it
some thought. But, doing it that way, it took me all of a second to
say no.''
</P>
<P>
   On the morning he was released _ Feb. 11 _ Smith and his agent,
Leigh Steinberg, said that 11 other teams were interested. Later
that night, Smith signed a five-year, $24 million contract with
Washington that included a $4.25 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was searching for a team that had a chance to win it all,''
Smith said. ``I wanted to play on grass. I wanted to play closer to
my hometown, Virginia Beach. I wanted to be a missing piece, and
the Redskins were second in offense and 30th in defense last year.
The Redskins had everything I was looking for even though other
teams offered more money. This turned out to be a blessing in
disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a combination of a lot of things going on in
Buffalo. It was poor planning. It was a perfect time for them to
install the new age they wanted to get in there, anyway. That is
fine and so be it. I'm a grown man able to handle being told the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Free agency and the salary cap ruin opportunities. They create
new ones. It is a push and pull, a shove and tug. The key in this
system for NFL teams is not just whom they lose, but whom they
gain. Making it work means finding answers and replacements,
whether old or new. The key in this system for players is embracing
new opportunities whether with old teams or with new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Smith plans to make it work in Washington, where he is expected
to be used on early and late downs, stopping the run and chasing
the quarterback. He turns 37 on June 18. Will the knees last? Will
the power persist? He has played 237 games and 11 Pro Bowls. He is
6 feet 4 inches and weighs 273 pounds. Still massive, still
impressive, still churning for more greatness, say the Redskins. He
and his wife, Carmen, have already bought a new home in Washington.
They are selling their Buffalo home. Sunday is special _ their son,
Alston, turns 6.
</P>
<P>
   Things happen for a reason, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven years ago the doctors told me my father could die any
day,'' Smith said. ``He is 78 now and from the neck up is as sharp
as any politician. I went to visit Derrick Thomas when he was in
the hospital, and when I walked into the room it was chilling. I
started to cry. I walked over and sat in a chair and he saw me
emotional. He started joking. And you know what he told me? `Things
happen for a reason, Bruce.' His death shook me. At his funeral and
since then, when I think about my changes, I've thought about what
he said. All things do happen for a reason.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
