<HEADLINE>
O'NEILL AND BROSIUS: COMING TO TERMS WITH THE SILENCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ore., Fla.)   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Maury Brosius lived just a couple of minutes from
his son's family in the hamlet of McMinnville, Ore., and it was
habit to include him in the smallest snippets of life. If one of
Scott Brosius' young children said something funny, well, you
picked up the phone and called Dad. If you went somewhere, you
called Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius has felt a need to reach for the phone in recent
months, and then he would realize, again, that his father was not
there to be called, and grief would pass through him.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius and Paul O'Neill, whose fathers died last year in the
last days of the Yankees' season, are not sure if the grieving ever
ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was harder for me because I've never gone through anything
like that,'' O'Neill said. ``I really never knew my grandparents,
so this was the first death of anyone that I really loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Their fathers were sick throughout last season. Maury Brosius
had a prolonged battle with cancer. Charles O'Neill was ailing with
heart trouble. There were several times when each man took a turn
for the worse, and their sons were left to stand on a baseball
field and play a game and wonder if they would ever speak to their
fathers again.
</P>
<P>
   Neither O'Neill, the Yankees' right fielder, nor Brosius, the
third baseman, played up to their usual standards last year, and
Manager Joe Torre is certain that their concern and grief over
their fathers weighed on them heavily as they tried to do their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius mostly went about his business as if he were OK, Torre
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to be lighthearted; he made jokes, like always,''
Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually Brosius asked to leave the team on several
occasions, and missed perhaps 12 to 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill tends to internalize, his manager said, and as the
player struggled _ with his feelings and subsequently, his batting
average _ he tried harder and harder, sometimes to his professional
detriment.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of spring training, after O'Neill's father had become
ill, doctors told Torre he had prostate cancer and he called
O'Neill in to tell him. O'Neill, overwhelmed, asked, ``Where does
all this come from?''
</P>
<P>
   Maury Brosius died in September, and the night before the final
game of the World Series, Charles O'Neill died.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves' Keith Lockhart popped to left field for the
final out, and Paul O'Neill was overcome by his emotion as he
hugged teammates and raced off the field, covering his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius followed shortly thereafter, his own emotions jumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're proud and you're excited about what we accomplished,''
Brosius said. ``Then you look over at Paul and you're hit right
square in the face again, as if I needed it, that this isn't the
most important thing in your life. By the time I got in the
clubhouse I was pretty numb. I didn't know what to feel: happy,
sad, both.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi, their teammate, had arranged for a restaurant in
White Plains to stay open, and he and O'Neill and Brosius and their
families went to dinner well after midnight. Brosius was glad that
O'Neill had family around.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius felt relief that the season was over, and that he could
go back to his family, go back to Oregon, to ``decompress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to slow down,'' he said, ``try to come to
terms with everything that's happened and everything I still had to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   He was surprised by how exhausted he was. Brosius, the oldest of
three children, was the executor of his father's estate, and there
were details to tend to. But mostly, he and his wife, Jennifer
Brosius, worked on projects around the house. Thoughts of his
father came in waves, one of his senses triggering a memory.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius felt fortunate because as his father's health
ebbed, Torre and General Manager Brian Cashman gave him permission
to leave the team for a week, and he and his father had spent those
days together in conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't replace that time I had with him,'' Brosius
said. ``I could certainly make the case for looking at last year
and having some sort of bitterness about the game, keeping me away
from home at a time like that. But because they allowed me to go
back, look at last year with no regrets. I felt I maximized my time
with him as much as I could, and did the things I felt I needed to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never trade the time I had with him. But you always
want more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius' children _ 8-year-old Allison, 6-year-old Megan
and David, who is 3 _ called their grandfather the Boogie Man,
because Maury Brosius liked to sneak up on them. He would sit in
the brown recliner in his son's house and play with his
grandchildren. The recliner was empty at the holidays last year,
the house seemed empty, and there was a silence, Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You move on,'' he said, ``and you have a good time, but you
just know that there's a piece missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're trying to get yourself through it, but at the same
time, you're trying to get your kids through it. You're trying to
help them understand, while you're trying to understand yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said: ``You just try to live the life that he taught
you. He had six children, their children. His deposit on the world
is still here, is the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill and his siblings have tried to keep in touch a little
more, he said, and spent more time talking with his mother,
Virginia. She came to Florida for spring training.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill arrived in camp last week, typically in great shape,
typically fretting about his swing, eager to hit. Brosius arrived,
too, looking forward to a new season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a point of being as fresh as I could in the off-season,
to come back with a clear mind,'' he said, ``to just come back and
play baseball again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brosius family moved the brown recliner into the bedroom of
David, and on those nights he wakes up, Jennifer Brosius is using
the Boogie Man's chair to comfort her son, the grandson of Maury
Brosius. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
