<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-ART     02-26 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT, AT THE AGE OF 21, IS TRANSCENDING BORDERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the old days, Kobe Bryant would have been a college senior.
</P>
<P>
   In these new days, he is a co-owner of a basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant recently spent a few of Jerry Buss' lire to buy half of
Olimpia Milano, his father's old team when the Bryant family was
based in Italy. He may be the first active player to own a major
piece of another team, albeit in another country.
</P>
<P>
   Although he insisted his purchase of Olimpia was ``mostly
business,'' Bryant talks of living in Italy again some day. It will
not be any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   With the National Basketball Association rooting for the next
generation of marketable stars to coalesce, Bryant shows signs of
becoming positively Pippenesque.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 21, he is already an explosive star with glorious
moves, linked, as Scottie Pippen once was, to a superstar who makes
him all the more lethal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the big brother and he's the little brother,'' said
Shaquille O'Neal, who may be playing the role of Michael Jordan in
this West Coast performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant may not love that viewpoint, but with the big man
clogging up the middle, Bryant has become a significant offensive
and defensive force.
</P>
<P>
   In four seasons with the Lakers, his average has risen from 7.6
to 15.4 to 19.9 and now to 22 after Friday night's game with the
Celtics, as the Lakers won at home for their 10th straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   With his long arms, Bryant has also become a defensive power.
Last Sunday in Philadelphia _ another of his homes _ Bryant stuck
his willowy 6-foot-7 frame in the way of Allen Iverson, helping to
hold the league's leading scorer without a point in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant never claimed to have personally shut down Iverson, but
that's how it came across in the accounts of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a good job of staying in front of Iverson and bringing
him to me,'' O'Neal said last week in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   On coaching instructions, Bryant had planted himself to
Iverson's side, denying him the middle-range shot, and forcing him
to move in toward O'Neal, who is more than a full foot taller than
the 6-0 Sixer guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I tried to do was put myself in his shoes,'' Bryant said.
``In the past when I've had games where I'm struggling, any moment
I could go off. I'm sure he was thinking the same way, so I just
played him.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson shot 0 for 11 in the second half, and later he gave some
credit to Bryant, saying: ``It's always tough playing against
somebody quick and tall because they can kind of back up off you
and get a hand in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is a joy to watch, with his quick steals, his pogo-stick
jump shots and electric drives, and an instinct for jamming home
rebounds from far above the basket. He missed the first 15 games
this season with a broken right hand, but is fourth on his team in
total assists and tied for fourth in rebounds _ and also was second
on the team in turnovers with an average of nearly three a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has his moments when he tries to penetrate too much,''
Coach Phil Jackson said the other night. ``I'd say it's two steps
forward and half a step backward.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal acknowledged that Bryant, who passed up college, is
learning more all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran rap artist and the aspiring young rapper, about to
release his first CD, may not be close, but they put it together on
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and coach have a good relationship,'' O'Neal said. ``Coach
gives him a plan and he executes it.''
</P>
<P>
   With his exotic name _ which stems from an obviously
unforgettable Japanese steak dinner his parents enjoyed during the
gestation period _ Kobe Bryant is a fixture with the Lakers. He is
currently in the second year of a six-year contract extension,
believed to be worth nearly $71 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is in the very top of the line of players who went
directly from high school to the NBA: Kevin Garnett, Shawn Kemp,
Moses Malone, Darryl Dawkins. Dozens of others have come out way
too young, and never adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Kobe Bryant was not the normal teen-ager even when
he was a senior at Lower Merion High outside Philadelphia. He had
observed basketball up close in the friendly environment of Italy,
where his father, Joe (Jelly Bean) Bryant, played for eight seasons
after an eight-year career in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, the kids in America, they don't do the work that Kobe
did,'' Magic Johnson once said. ``That's the problem with the young
people now. They don't have the fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant absorbed the game in Italy, going to practice with
his dad, getting on the court, listening to his father talk about
the game on the leisurely afternoons off.
</P>
<P>
   The family went home when it was time for Kobe to play high
school ball, but he still speaks Italian, and talks with reverence
about the three imported Dutch stars, Marco Von Basten, Ruud Gullit
and Frank Rijkaard, who made AC Milan the soccer powerhouse when he
was living there.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother wouldn't let me go to the games,'' he said with a
sigh. ``She said it was too dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   He could surely go back now and watch from the sedate tribuna
d'onore, the VIP box, but he has his own sport during the Italian
soccer season. Milan may have a hold on Kobe Bryant, but there are
championships to be pursued in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1609EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
