<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS, FOR A CHANGE, WEAR THEIR RALLYING CAPS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Usually it is the New York Knicks who experience a
second-half freeze, turning a game they once had in control into a
nip-and-tuck affair and sometimes even a loss. It happened as
recently as Wednesday, when Vince Carter and the Toronto Raptors
made a 10-point third-quarter lead vanish in a matter of minutes en
route to winning at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, with the fire-hot Phoenix Suns appearing on
their way to certain victory, the Knicks reversed their trend and
became the ones to rally. A nearly flawless seven-minute stretch at
the end of the game gave the Knicks an 84-79 victory over a Phoenix
team that had won its previous eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The key for the Knicks, who have lost five games this season in
which they led by double figures, was a defense that advanced from
solid to outstanding near the midway point of the fourth quarter.
Trailing by 11 points three minutes into the fourth, and by 74-65
with 7 minutes 11 seconds remaining, the Knicks' stoppers held the
Suns to only five points the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   With Patrick Ewing becoming a ferocious defensive rebounder and
the rest of the club aggressively challenging shots and passes, the
Knicks held the Suns scoreless on nine straight possessions and to
just two free throws on 11 possessions. And with Chris Childs
scoring seven of his 11 points and Ewing four of his game-high 25,
the Knicks outscored Phoenix by 19-5, including a 13-0 run, over
the second half of the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that when you play hard and play with the type of
intensity that we are able to bring that we can pretty much hold
great teams down,'' said Latrell Sprewell, who recorded 21 points
and a career-high tying 11 rebounds. ``A big part of our defense at
the end was the crowd. The crowd really got into the game once we
got close and it helped us get over the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   A clear sign of the Knicks' increased resolve down the stretch
was their rebounding. The third-worst rebounding team in the
league, they had been manhandled on the backboard all night, being
outrebounded by 33-23 through three quarters. But in the fourth,
the Knicks outrebounded Phoenix by 13-9. Ewing grabbed five of his
10 rebounds in the fourth and Sprewell secured three.
</P>
<P>
   While Ewing and Sprewell carried the Knicks through the first 3
1-2 quarters, keeping them within range of victory, it was Childs
who became the hero in the end. Outplaying the heralded Jason Kidd,
Childs gave the Knicks their first lead since the first quarter by
burying a 3-pointer that made it 76-74 with 2:26 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty seconds later, after Kidd missed a 3-pointer, Childs hit
a 21-footer to put the Knicks up by four points and give them the
momentum. With the Suns sending them to the foul line in hopes of
salvaging a game they led by as many as 11 points in the fourth
quarter, the Knicks made six of six free throws in the final 20
seconds to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just waited my turn,'' Childs said. ``I haven't had the type
of year that I wanted, but I'm not going to stop shooting.
Eventually, when you keep your confidence and keep shooting,
they're going to go in. I was ready to shoot it and you have to be
ready with these guys, because they will get you the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs' late-game heroics gave Ewing and Sprewell the support
they needed. Playing on a left knee that had been bumped badly in
Wednesday's loss to Toronto, Ewing and Sprewell lifted the Knicks
on a night when Allan Houston (14 points, 5-of-14 shooting) did
little.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning, whirling, dipping and fading away, the 37-year-old
Ewing looked like the star of old. He scored 10 of the Knicks' 21
points in the third quarter. His dominant performance continued a
surge that has seen him play at an All-Star level over the past 10
games, a stretch in which he has averaged 18.2 points and 10.7
rebounds. ``We just need him to keep carrying us,'' Kurt Thomas
said of Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Since returning from his Achilles' injury earlier this season,
Ewing has refused to give credence to the argument that his
offensive ability has declined, and he used Friday night's
performance as more evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age has nothing to do with this,'' said Ewing, who said his
knee did not bother him against Phoenix. ``It's all mental.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy was pleased with the Knicks' play,
particularly a defense that held the Suns to 68 points over the
final 45:20 of play. After falling behind by 11-2 early on, the
Knicks' defense, except for a few short-lived lapses, was stifling.
Phoenix, which entered the game averaging 98.5 points, scored only
17 in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we showed a lot of resilience there in the fourth
quarter, particularly being down 9 or 11,'' Van Gundy said. ``This
is as good as any other win we have had this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1611EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
