<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-26 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A VOICELESS FAN LONGS FOR MESSIER'S RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I want Mark Messier and I want him now. Don't tell me
about salary caps, dunce caps, capped teeth. Just go buy Mark
Messier and stuff him back in a Ranger uniform and push him out on
the prime line with Adam Graves. Do it before baseball melts the
ice.
</P>
<P>
   Who listens to a fan? We scamper along the sides of the eternal
triangle _ athlete, agent, owner _ and sometimes get hung on the
points. Who cares about us? The week began with news that Mariano
Rivera had lost his arbitration case and would get only $7.25
million to pitch this season instead of the $9.25 million he asked
for. Mariano kept smiling. A good sport. Maybe the Yankees could
use the spared $2 million to hire a team of psychiatrists to work
with their minor leaguers; too late for poor Darryl Strawberry, but
then it was the Mets who brought him up too soon and with too
little counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Marvin Miller's biographer is beating a drum to have
rules so interpreted that the retired labor leader can be inducted
into baseball's Hall of Fame. C'mon. A co-op in Cooperstown for one
of the guys who made sure you can't afford to go to games? And they
are keeping Pete Rose out? At least Pete gave me pleasure. I say,
Marvin and Pete go in together or leave 'em both on the curb.
</P>
<P>
   Who listens to a fan? Am I scandalized that Erick Barkley's life
was improved by switching cars? St. John's gave him a platinum
athletic scholarship so he could get them television gigs. I don't
watch the Red Storm to see Erick read or drive. People have been
giving Erick stuff ever since he picked up a basketball. It looks
as though Riverside Church, where he once played, helped him with
his prep school tuition. God helps those who have game.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the National Collegiate Athletic Association so picky?
Does it feel it's losing ground? The Amateur Athletic Union, once
the power in American sports, but moribund the past few decades, is
making a comeback with sneaker company money, running teams often
coached by street agents, who, truth be told, probably do more for
more young athletes than college coaches do.
</P>
<P>
   Should I, Fan, care?
</P>
<P>
   Ask Dennis Perrin, who is my new role model as a funny, smart
and mean-spirited fan. His new book, ``American Fan: Sports Mania
and the Culture That Feeds It'' (Spike/Avon), is hilariously
vicious at the expense of Spike Lee, George Will, sportswriters,
Michael Jordan, Nike and Jack Tatum. (``Were Tatum really great he
would have crippled some fans as well.'') Every fan should read it
for moral support, then send it to Erick. If he can pass a test on
it, he should get a brand new car.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jay Weiner, who is my new role model as a thoughtful,
precise and idealistic fan. (I inadvertently maligned Weiner, a
Minneapolis journalist, here several weeks ago when I had him
jailed in the Patty Hearst case for harboring fugitives; he was
jailed for refusing to testify against his friends.) Weiner's new
book, ``Stadium Games: Fifty Years of Big League Greed and Bush
League Boondoggle'' (University of Minnesota), is a lesson in
politics and economics by a writer who believes that a city may
well need a major league team to be major league. But Weiner goes
on with pragmatic suggestions on how fans can make this all work in
their own best interests.
</P>
<P>
   Ask me.
</P>
<P>
   If I were writing a book for fans, I'd call it ``SkyBoxer: In
the Arena but Above the Fray.'' That should be our goal, to watch
all games over television, while eating and drinking in bed, with
company, in a luxury box. This is the future of fandom. Who wants
to get close to those brutes? If Reggie Miller isn't talking dirty,
you might get hurt the next time a Marty McSorley forgets that the
violence he gets paid for has certain boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   But to be suspended for the rest of the season just for
concussing a guy he has been fighting for years? I think McSorley
should be replaced by Tonya Harding, the prototype skating goon,
arrested last week for whacking her boyfriend with a hubcap.
</P>
<P>
   What would bring me downstairs?
</P>
<P>
   Mark Messier. I want Captain Dad back in town. I want to reclaim
my inner puck, to see again that scream of a face floating over the
Garden ice. Wiser heads say I'm wrong, that Messier is 39 and his
$6 million contract (not even as much as the marked down Rivera!)
and his powerful personality will upset the Rangers. I want them
upset! I am a fan! The Rangers stink!
</P>
<P>
   And Cablevision can afford Messier; it was ready to buy the
Jets. Actually, if Marvin Miller wants my vote for the Hall of
Fame, he should explain how Cablevision can be allowed to own the
venue (Madison Square Garden), the teams (Knicks, Rangers) and the
television channels, and still not satisfy my needs.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, I want Coach Mike Keenan and I want him
now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
