<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS AND CUBS PREPARE FOR JAPAN  
 WHOM OLERUD WILL MISS  
 LIKE FATHER, LIKE SON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Members of the Baltimore Orioles, notably Albert
Belle, have complained that the team's trip to Cuba last March
served as a distraction and caused their team to start the season
poorly. Rickey Henderson, the Mets' problem child, said he doesn't
want to go and won't go to Japan, where the Mets and the Chicago
Cubs open the 2000 season in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Don Baylor will have none of it. He is the Cubs' new manager,
and he will not allow his players to view the lengthy trip as a
distraction and use it as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two games and we have 160 after that,'' Baylor said. ``So
let's not let a few days dictate the entire season for us. I read
some of the Orioles' comments when they got off to a bad start,
when the pitchers got off to a bad start. I look at it as, `Let's
not make an excuse going there to play.' You have to look at it as
it's baseball; it's an honor to go over there.''
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented opening in Japan is part of Major League
Baseball's plan to go global, expanding interest in itself with an
eye toward the increased revenue that interest could generate. The
other major sports have done it; baseball, slow to see the
possibilities, is playing catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in baseball would like the increased revenue, but not
everyone is willing to contribute to the effort. The Japanese
sponsors of the games, for example, preferred St. Louis because of
Mark McGwire, but the Cardinals, with McGwire voicing his objection
to the trip, declined the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The trip will broaden horizons for some of the players. ``We
have some guys who have never had a passport,'' said Baylor, who is
preparing for his eighth visit to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Because he has often made the 13-hour flight, Baylor knows what
a grind it is. But, he said, with sensible planning, it becomes
manageable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks prior to breaking camp,'' he said, ``we're going to
start the indoctrination of telling people what to expect, what to
do, leading up to that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Lee, the Cubs' Pacific rim scouting coordinator, is in the
team's camp and will aid in preparing the players. ``He has made
over 100 trips over there,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee played in Japan for 10 years, scouted for a Japanese team
and has done consulting work in Japan for Major League Baseball and
the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   As if the flight weren't long enough, Baylor said the ride from
the airport to the hotel takes two-and-a-half hours. ``Los Angeles
traffic and New York traffic aren't even close,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The key, once the team lands in Japan, the manager said, is for
the players to stay awake as long as they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you arrive there,'' he counseled, ``don't try to go to
sleep. You'll be up all night fighting it. Stay up as long as you
can. Go out and have dinner. You'll wear down. Your body will tell
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs' trek will begin at 5:45 a.m. March 24, when luggage is
brought to HoHoKam Park, site of the Cubs' spring games. At 8:20
a.m., they will fly to San Francisco, where they will have a
14-hour layover before leaving for Tokyo at 11:15 p.m. They are
scheduled to arrive in Tokyo at 3:10 p.m. March 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets begin their day at 6 a.m. March 24 with luggage
check-in at their park in Port St. Lucie. They will fly from West
Palm Beach at 8:45 a.m. and connect in Chicago to a 1:15 p.m.
flight to Tokyo. They are scheduled to arrive at 5:20 p.m. March
25.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the teams will work out at the Tokyo Dome, then
play exhibition games March 27 and 28, each playing the Tokyo
Giants and the Seibu Lions. They will open the season with a night
game at the Tokyo Dome March 29. The season's first pitch is
scheduled for 4:10 a.m. Chicago time, 5:10 a.m. New York time.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs and the Mets will play again the following evening,
then leave for home March 31. ``The toughest one is coming back,''
Baylor said. ``That beats you up for a day, maybe two. After that
you're fine.''
</P>
<P>
   While 28 other teams play exhibition games Saturday and a
handful have their final exhibition games Sunday, the Cubs and the
Mets will have no more games until Monday, April 3, the domestic
opening day for everyone. But the Cubs will not be finished
traveling. They will fly to St. Louis Sunday while the Mets sleep
at home Sunday night before their opener at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will impress on the players not to use the trip as an
excuse,'' Baylor said. ``I guarantee you Bobby Valentine will tell
his team the exact same thing. They're in a division with the
Braves and can't have this affect the 160 games left.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor said he was looking forward to the trip. ``We never
thought this was possible,'' he said. ``But the world has come
closer because of technology. It's a smaller place than it was 20,
25 years ago. I look at it as being on the frontier of what's going
to happen to our game later.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Infield of Dreams
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud does not expect to have any regrets over leaving the
Mets, because he felt Seattle would be the best place for his
family. But that does not mean he won't miss his remarkable infield
partners, Robin Ventura, Rey Ordonez and Edgardo Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a lot of fun, being part of that infield,'' Olerud
said. ``Watching those guys day in and day out, the plays that
Robin and Rey would make over there and the great plays that
Edgardo would make. They're a special group of guys. The part I
liked best about them was I always got good throws. Very rarely did
I have to make a tough catch or anything. They always seemed to
make good throws to me so that was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he ever surprised by a play one of the infielders made after
he thought the ball was going through for a hit, and left
unprepared for a throw to first?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rey cured me of that pretty soon,'' the first baseman said.
``Yeah, he did surprise me a couple times. Then Robin surprised me
on a couple plays. I'm still covering the base, but you see the
play: It's a bunt, it looks like it's a good bunt; he's probably
not going to have a chance on a ball down the line, but he gets it.
Those guys surprised me, not only with the spectacular plays but
how solid they were day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sons Surpassing Fathers
</P>
<P>
   From Earle Mack (Connie) to Justin Speier (Chris), about 160
sons of former major leaguers have played in the majors. But their
success in recent years has been far greater than in the past.
About 20 percent of the total, more than 30, are in training camps
now preparing for the coming season. Others are waiting for their
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Why have sons of this generation become more successful than
their predecessors?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past,'' Sandy Alomar Sr. said, ``there weren't many
because of the pressure that was on them. Now, when they're
younger, they go with their fathers to the ballpark. People are
allowed to bring kids into the clubhouse. They're raised in the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I was playing with Bobby Bonds, my kids were
playing with Barry. I used to see Tony Perez's kid playing with
Griffey. I think that by getting into the environment, they knew
all the players and they felt like they were at home. They didn't
feel the pressure. I think their parents probably prepared them
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar is the Chicago Cubs' new bullpen coach this year; his
sons, Sandy Jr. and Roberto, play for Cleveland. Ken Griffey Jr. is
with his father, a coach, in Cincinnati. Aaron Boone is the Reds'
third baseman; his father, Bob, is a special assistant to the Reds'
general manager. Brother and son Bret plays second base for San
Diego. David Bell plays second base for Seattle; Buddy Bell manages
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my dad was growing up,'' said David Bell, the grandson of
Gus, ``I don't think he was at the park as much. Back then I think
they tried to keep things more normal. When I was growing up, it
was so easy to go to the park with your dad. I think that's the
biggest advantage I had, being around the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became obsessed with playing in the big leagues and doing
exactly what my dad had done. It was because I got a chance to be
around and see how much I wanted to do it. Just having the
opportunity to do it and teams allowing it. It seems like
everywhere we went we'd look around the field and there were other
players' sons out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar recalled that Sandy Jr. quit playing baseball for about
three years in his early teens, preferring to spend his time with
tae kwon do and dirt bikes. But when he returned to the game at the
age of 15, his father said, he was as passionate about playing as
his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Robby would play,'' the father said. ``He kept telling
me day in and day out he was going to be better than me. I told him
that it wasn't going to be any challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The thing is, they were with me all the time. We
prepared them mentally, made sure they understood the things that
people were going to be saying to them, the things that people were
going to try to compare them with.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Alomar brothers, the Indians have Speier, Jaret
Wright (Clyde) and Chris Haney (Larry), giving them the most sons
of former major leaguers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
