<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-CUBS-GIRARDI-NYT &LR;      02-26 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-GIRARDI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRARDI PREFERS SECURITY TO ANOTHER RING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ He could have been across the country in Tampa,
Fla., preparing for perhaps his fourth World Series in five years,
but instead Joe Girardi was here, preparing for a season with those
lovable losers, the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four years, Girardi played for the New York
Yankees; now he will play for the team that had the second-worst
record in the National League last season. The veteran catcher,
however, was not prepared to plead insanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the role that they had for me was not the role I
really wanted,'' Girardi said, discussing his departure from the
Yankees as a free agent. ``They offered me a one-year deal to be
the backup. To me, that wasn't a good deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not when the Cubs offered $5.5 million for three years, dwarfing
the Yankees' six-figure offer for the 2000 season only.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get an opportunity to play every day and somebody offers
you a three-year deal, you gotta take it,'' Girardi said in his new
spring clubhouse. ``You have a baby, you take the one year as a
backup, then you have to worry where are you going to be next year.
When you have a family, you want to be a little bit more stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Opting, at the age of 35, for security over the possibility of
another World Series ring, Girardi also preferred the prospect of
playing regularly over a role as Jorge Posada's backup. Not that he
won't feel a twinge of nostalgia if the Yankees do play in the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees hadn't reached and won the World Series in his
first, third and fourth seasons with them, Girardi said, ``It
probably would have made it easier to leave because I wouldn't have
known what it was like. I think having the three World Series made
it harder for me to leave, but I knew I had to do what was best for
my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi was no insignificant contributor to the Yankees'
success. When Bob Watson became the general manager and Joe Torre
the manager after the 1995 season, they targeted Girardi as one of
the first players they wanted to obtain. They felt they had to
shore up the catching if the Yankees were to have a chance to
become a contender.
</P>
<P>
   When Don Baylor became the Cubs' manager last Nov. 1, he
similarly identified Girardi as a catcher to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the first guys I thought about as a free
agent,'' said Baylor, for whom Girardi caught for three seasons in
Colorado. ``I figured Joe would have one last dance close to home.
I said let's see if we can make it work, and Ed went to work on him
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Girardis live in Chicago made it easier for Ed
Lynch, the Cubs' general manager, to make Baylor's idea work.
Baylor had lost Girardi in Colorado four years earlier because of
Girardi's outspoken union views after the 1994-95 players strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make no bones about it; I made a mistake,'' Girardi said.
``I think that's the reason I was gone. I got on some people in
management about the way they were treating some of the players,
the pressure they were receiving to cross the line. I made a
mistake blasting management a little bit. You learn and you go on.
I learned a valuable lesson. But it was a blessing for me to go to
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi served the Yankees well. He hit a career-high .294 in
his first season with them and quickly became the catcher the
pitchers wanted to pitch to. He also displayed a high level of
class by helping the young and inexperienced Posada even though it
was obvious the Yankees planned to make him their No. 1 catcher.
</P>
<P>
   The past two seasons Posada caught the bulk of the games, but
Girardi continued to catch David Cone and Andy Pettitte. His
experience with the crafty Cone is one he has taken with him to the
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed catching Coney because of his uniqueness,''
Girardi said. ``There was always something different every day. For
a catcher he allows you to be very creative. That's enjoyable. He's
the ultimate competitor. Everyone knows the type of pitcher he is.
He's a big-game pitcher that just enjoys everything that he does.
He's the best example of a pitcher who doesn't have his best stuff
but finds a way of getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi acknowledged that he will miss Cone and the rest of the
friends he leaves behind. He has taken with him, though, his
memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about my four years there,'' he said. ``They've been
the best four years I've had in the game. You definitely cherish
the moments from the World Series. The final games stand out the
most. It's an end to a wonderful season. It's something you know
you're going to reflect on. It's something you know you're going to
hold onto. I think my best moments as a Yankee were jumping into
the pitchers' arms when that last out was recorded.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the arms belonged to John Wetteland; in 1998, they were
Mariano Rivera's. The Cubs will have to make a remarkable
improvement over last season's 67-95 record for Girardi to find
himself in someone else's arms next October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1621EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
