<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9440 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-NYT &LR;      02-26 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR METS' WILSON, ARM INJURIES PUT A NEW SPIN ON PITCHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ The signs read like the morals of the
stories in a series of children's sports books.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates Count on Each Other. Give, Share and You'll Receive.
Only Your Best Counts. Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Those sayings and others hang from the ceiling in the locker
room of the Mets' minor league complex here, ever-present reminders
of the fundamentals of teamwork. Paul Wilson, who should be
entering his fifth season in the major leagues, saw those signs
last season day after day, when he went to work in that minor
league clubhouse he calls a dungeon.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he should have put that place behind him long ago. ``I
still think of myself as a major leaguer,'' Wilson, 26, said. ``But
it's just not that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson went 5-12 with a 5.38 earned run average for the Mets in
1996, two years after the club made him the first overall selection
in the amateur draft after a standout career at Florida State. He
has pitched in 17 minor league games the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery to repair a torn labrum in his right (pitching) shoulder
cost Wilson most of 1997 and '98. But he pitched well for Class AAA
Norfolk at the end of '98, and last year started spring training
with nine scoreless innings. He was devastated when he was optioned
to Norfolk, but a week later, things got much worse: Wilson learned
he had torn a ligament in his pitching elbow. He had reconstructive
surgery April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson could have begun throwing Aug. 1, but the Mets waited an
extra month because there was no reason to rush. The recovery has
been slow but sure. Wilson is throwing without pain, and recovering
well the days after he throws. Mike Herbst, the Mets'
rehabilitation coordinator, said Wilson is 90 percent to 95 percent
healthy. The Mets are still being extremely cautious. They will
reduce Wilson's workload at the first sign of discomfort, Herbst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is throwing consistently at 86 mph and expects to be back
to the low 90s with more innings. The Mets may have him start the
season at Class A Port St. Lucie, to take advantage of the warm
weather, or he could begin at Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well there, he may be in Shea Stadium sometime after
midseason. Waiting for him there will be the left-hander Al Leiter,
who missed most of two seasons as a young pitcher with shoulder and
elbow injuries. Leiter has taken to Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to success _ and I've talked to Paul about it a few
times _ is instead of thinking of yourself in terms of what could
have been and should have been, think about the new Paul Wilson,''
Leiter said. ``Forget about the old Paul Wilson _ you are who you
are now. Deal with the stuff you have now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing for guys that had great stuff pre-injury is
that when you come back from an operation, in your own mind you see
something differently. So you lose confidence. You don't think it's
enough to get major league hitters out, and you adjust accordingly,
in a negative way.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's rehabilitation was so monotonous that the Mets varied
his routine just so he would not be bored. He did not watch
baseball on television last season _ ``It wasn't helping me at all
to watch everybody else doing what I wanted to do,'' he said _ and
focused on other goals.
</P>
<P>
   His progress has been aided by his overall athleticism. Wilson
had the fastest time among pitchers in the 300-yard shuttle run
this spring. Athleticism is important; some believe that another
No. 1 overall pick, the Yankees' Brien Taylor, never recovered from
a serious shoulder injury in part because he was not athletic
enough to adjust after the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he works hard on his running, but believes he will
come back mostly because he understands pitching better. After
averaging more than a strikeout an inning in his first two years in
the Mets' system, Wilson has discovered the joys of relearning his
craft. He has learned a changeup, is throwing more curveballs and
has better mechanics. He is a new Paul Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the longest time, I'd always gotten away with God-given
ability,'' Wilson said. ``I always thought I was a good pitcher,
but when I got hurt, I really had to pick my spots, think about
what I'm doing out there and learn _ not just learn pitching but
learn the hitters, learn everything about this game, even the
business side of it, just learn this whole entire system. You'd be
surprised what that does for your comfort level and your
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have learned, too, from the example of Wilson, Bill
Pulsipher and Jason Isringhausen, the young pitching trio that was
supposed to resurrect the team in the mid-1990s. Their success in
the farm system helped put up another sign in the minor league
clubhouse: Organization of the Year, 1995. But then all three
developed elbow injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed our philosophy as far as relying solely on young
prospects to be the savior of our organization,'' said Jim
Duquette, the Mets' assistant general manager for player personnel.
``Now, with some of the trades we make, we look for guys with
established major league careers and supplement them with one or
two guys from our own system.''
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen was traded to the Oakland Athletics last summer,
but Pulsipher, who was traded away and then reacquired last month,
is the leading candidate to be the Mets' fifth starter this year.
Wilson said that no matter what happens _ even if he reinjures
himself and has to spend another year in the dungeon _ he will keep
coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all I know,'' Wilson said. ``I've always been good at
this; I've always been good at being a ballplayer. I've just always
felt comfortable. I mean, I do not know what I'd do if I wasn't
playing ball. It scares the hell out of me thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leiter was 26, he had just missed five months with an elbow
injury. Eight years later, he is an established veteran and one of
baseball's more effective starters. He has lived a comeback story,
and believes Wilson can do the same. ``He'll make it,'' Leiter said
of Wilson. ``He works as hard as anybody I've ever seen. He
cares.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
