<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-ART-2TAK     02-26 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER HYPE RAISES CONCERNS ABOUT HIM 
MICROPHONES A UNION ISSUE 
DEVELOPING A LEAGUE
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They tried pawning off Anfernee Hardaway and Shaquille O'Neal in
1995 as Michael Jordan's successors. Kobe Bryant came in 1998.
Fresh, young, he would be the face of the next millennium. Grant
Hill got air time, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill was honest enough to acknowledge that the hype was
silly. He called it the Larry Holmes syndrome. ``You come after the
greatest, there's no way you'll ever live up to it,'' Hill said.
``None of us could be Michael. None of us ever will.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Carter makes his national network debut Sunday, skywalking
into living rooms at 12:30 p.m., Eastern time, against the Phoenix
Suns. NBC thinks so highly of the Toronto Raptors' second-year
forward, they bumped the Knicks-76ers game back to 3 p.m. to ensure
that all of America would see him.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to say Air Apparent because that is the curse,
worse than winding up on the cover of Sports Illustrated, which
Carter did last week. Still, there he was Wednesday night at
Madison Square Garden, detonating for 33 points, nine rebounds and
nine assists against the Knicks. The slam-dunk champion showed
substance as much as style 24 hours after appearing on the ``Late
Show with David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it was frightening _ another North Carolina kid who
had left school after his junior year, taking jaded NBA fans with
him as he levitated near the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it dangerous for him to be the future?'' Charles Oakley,
his veteran teammate, asked rhetorically after the Knicks' game.
``It's always dangerous when you market young kids before their
time, when you try to make them be somebody you want them to be
before they're ready to be that person. But Vince knows what time
it is. He knows what this is about. He's handling it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter is gracious and candid in interviews, if slightly
prepackaged and a bit overmanaged.
</P>
<P>
   Of his growing celebrity, he said: ``It's crazy sometimes, but
as much stuff as I do, I always put basketball first and foremost.
I understand I am where I am because of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter is clearly a player worthy of the hype. But with all the
pressure being putting on him by NBC, the NBA and his own marketing
people to be the next suitable ambassador for the game, the
question arises whether Carter will be allowed to grow enough in
the present to indeed become the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't sit around and say, `Here's who we sell and here's
who we don't sell,''' Russ Granik, the league's deputy
commissioner, said. ``It just happens on the court. He's a
spectacular, exciting player. Were you there at the Garden the
other night? I was. The NBA didn't make Vince Carter score five
times in a row in the third quarter and dunk the way he dunked.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Historically, in some ways, Michael became a
phenomenon even quicker. Shaq as well. Occasionally, you get that
special combination of personality and a game that attract more
attention than anybody else. Right now, Vince is that person.''
</P>
<P>
   Microphones a Union Issue
</P>
<P>
   During the 76ers-Lakers game last Sunday, coach Larry Brown
could easily be heard giving Allen Iverson words of encouragement
after an atrocious offensive performance in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's decision to install miniature microphones on one coach and
the lead referee for their featured weekly game was done with the
utmost sensitivity toward players and coaches. They use edited
snippets sparingly and have yet to pander to shock value, instead
giving the lead announcers, Bob Costas and Doug Collins, a chance
to lend perspective to what is being said on the court.
</P>
<P>
   But Billy Hunter and several players are worried that the NBA
and the network are walking a fine line between access and
intrusion. Hunter, the executive director of the players
association, plans to speak to Commissioner David Stern and the
deputy commissioner, Russ Granik, this week about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a couple things that bother me about it, the first
being that they seem to be altering work conditions without any
approval from the players,'' Hunter said. ``These are
across-the-board changes no one even asked us about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secondly, it is somewhat of an intrusion. They've got
microphones all over the court now, so that someone, somewhere can
hear everything that's going on. It's like Big Brother watching
over you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said Shaquille O'Neal complained to him about the NBA's
total-access policies during All-Star Weekend. Several players were
miked for the game on a voluntary basis. What's more, O'Neal was
one of a handful of players who often ended up on nba.com
television, the league's 24-hour news network that one Internet
mogul described as ``like Bloomberg News on steroids.''
</P>
<P>
   At one juncture O'Neal jokingly used profanity, apparently
unaware that the nba.com broadcast was live.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several players actually enjoyed the extra exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a former coach, there are certain things that you cannot
do,'' Collins said. ``I don't think in any way we'd try to
embarrass somebody, to try to make it look like somebody is
incompetent or in some way try to do something to upstage
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``There's still a player-coach confidence that can't
be breached. If we do that, then in essence, we will wipe out
anything we've tried to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter is also worried about outtakes ending up in the wrong
hands _ and whether the game is influenced when players understand
that what they say to a referee can be heard by everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's to say if the players are acting out what they're
thinking about a referee who is miked?'' he said. ``I'm not saying
those tapes will be used to fine and suspend players, but it just
takes away some of the spirit of the game when you know you're
being heard. It's something I'd like to address.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Developing a League
</P>
<P>
   With more and more teen-agers migrating to the draft under the
illusion that they are already prepared to play, the NBA has
targeted the start-up date for its developmental league for the
fall of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not 100 percent sure we can't do something next
fall, but for right now we're exploring a lot of possibilities,''
Russ Granik, the deputy commissioner, said.
</P>
<P>
   The league recently named Rob Levine its senior vice president
for new league development. With the goal of placing teams in
smaller cities, Levine is scouring the country for potential
investors. The teams would ultimately be operated by NBA teams,
serving almost like a minor league club in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The league would run from the fall to the spring, with the idea
that players could be brought up during the season. Salaries would
be small compared to NBA salaries, though it is unclear how the
union and the NBA plan to negotiate an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the union would not tolerate players being sent down on
a whim. Shipping off a veteran who is not playing much, like Chris
Dudley, would not be allowed. But sending down a young foreign
player like Mirsad Turckan, recently waived by the Knicks and
picked up by Milwaukee, might have merit.
</P>
<P>
   Isiah Thomas, the owner of the Continental Basketball
Association and a person who has often implored the NBA to take a
more serious look at the issue of young players turning pro, has
had talks with the league about a potential deal. Though the NBA
has yet to close the door on that, it appears the league will look
elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
