<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CONN-BLOTTER-ART-(TRI     02-26 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-BLOTTER-ART-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUNG READERS SAY A NEWSPAPER TELLS TOO MUCH OF THE TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Conn. _ When protests erupt over news gathering, the
usual complaint is that someone printed fiction instead of fact,
rumor rather than truth. But not here.
</P>
<P>
   In this boutique-size town, where stone fences and woods
surround large homes on Connecticut's southern shore, residents are
condemning the local newspaper for publishing what they believe is
an overkill of truth.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three weeks, petitions have been circulating here
and in a neighboring town, Guilford, calling on the local
government to force The Shore Line Times, a small 123-year-old
paper published twice weekly, to stop printing its police blotter.
The blotter, which starts on Page 2, provides the name, age,
address and alleged offense of everyone arrested in Madison and
Guilford in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   To an outsider, the blotter seems as blandly innocuous as the
paper's weekly notices for the local arthritis support group. But
to the 35,000 people who live in Madison and Guilford _ especially
teenagers, whose names pile up in the blotter like driftwood on
Madison's private beach _ Page 2 of the newspaper is an
embarrassing record of who got arrested and for what.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the blotter is a record of petty crimes: underage liquor
possession and speeding tickets flecked with a burglary here, a
felony drug offense there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's about time they got rid of it,'' Meaghan
Egan, 16, a junior at Daniel Hand High School in Madison, said
moments before signing the petition at the Madison Gourmet Beanery.
``It's a gossip column more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the whole town seems to read it religiously, she said,
``It could affect your reputation in many ways at work, in
school.''
</P>
<P>
   The petitions, which sprouted anonymously a few weeks ago,
demand that town selectmen in Madison and Guilford force The Shore
Line Times to halt publishing the police blotter. Some 200
residents have signed them, endorsing the assertion that the
blotter constitutes an ``invasion of privacy'' and sparks
``needless gossip'' among residents.
</P>
<P>
   Like police blotters in hundreds of other newspapers across the
country, the one published by The Shore Line Times is drawn from
police files that by law are open to public inspection. Unlike
other community papers that withhold the names of underage
offenders and the exact addresses of those charged with crimes, The
Shore Line Times publishes all the details it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here, that's the first thing they do is open the paper
and look to see who's in the blotter,'' said Leesa Sonnichsen, 49,
of Madison. ``My son got into an accident, and the first thing he
said when he got home was, `I'm glad it wasn't in Madison; it would
have been in the blotter.'''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Young, the paper's exasperated editor, vowed to
continue printing the police log. ``As much as there are people who
don't like it, I think there are many more people that do like
it,'' she said in an interview on Thursday. ``People like to call
it gossip, but it does let you know what is happening in town. It's
not meant to hurt people.''
</P>
<P>
   Town officials acknowledge they have no authority to stop
publication of the blotter. But Madison's acting first selectman,
Ron Piombino, said that he would support an official resolution
urging the paper ``to really exercise discretion'' about what it
prints. Like other residents interviewed last week, Piombino has no
problem reading about serious crimes. But, he said, printing every
teen-age beer or marijuana arrest, every no-turn-on-red traffic
ticket, every barking-dog citation ``probably isn't the most
responsible way to act.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's really incumbent on The Shore Line Times to
consider whether that's responsible journalism to continue to
publish that.''
</P>
<P>
   That people under 25 hate the blotter so much is no mystery;
they commit about a third of the alleged crimes in it, and they
despise the inevitable taunts from their friends or the wrath of
their parents every Wednesday and Saturday when the paper is
published.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It just, like, rubs people's faces in it,'' said Sarah
Terribile, a Hand High School student whose friends have been in
the blotter.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Vinci, 19, a high school senior, for example, signed a
petition at the Madison Gourmet Beanery three times, presumably
after the blotter ran an item about his Jan. 7 arrest on a
marijuana possession charge.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Word of the petition surprised some professional critics of the
news gathering process.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosenstiel, director of the Project for Excellence in
Journalism in Washington, said he had never heard of complaints
against a newspaper for printing too much accurate information.
``What makes it unusual is that you would have a newspaper who
wants to publish this stuff and a community that says, `No, don't
tell us, keep us in the dark,''' he said in a telephone interview
on Thursday. But he said newspapers that print charges against
individuals should also publish exonerations and favorable court
rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Young, editor of The Shore Line Times, said she would gladly
publish exonerations and acquittals if someone sent the documents
to her office. But most people don't bother, she said, ``because
they don't want their names ever in the paper again.''
</P>
<P>
   The blotter is such a must-read for the town's busybodies that
Young said she was often accosted with bribes or threats, tears or
pleas for mercy from those recently arrested. It never works.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person looked me straight in the eye and said, `You're not
putting that in, are you?''' she recalled. ``I looked the person in
the eye right back and said, `Yes, I am.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
