</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GALLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUZANNE GALLO, A DESIGNER   OF DANCE COMPANY COSTUMES, DIES AT 46  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Suzanne Gallo, a designer who created costumes for
many of Merce Cunningham's major recent works, died on Feb. 19 at
her home in Manhattan. She was 46.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said David Vaughan, the archivist for the
Merce Cunningham Dance Company.
</P>
<P>
   In a relatively short career in design, Gallo became known for
handsome, sometimes luminously pretty costumes that allowed the
body to move and captured the often intangible qualities of
Cunningham's dances without intruding on the choreography itself.
Robert Greskovic, writing in The Wall Street Journal last year
about Gallo's costumes for Cunningham's ``Pond Way,'' described her
work as ``consistently inspired.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brooklyn, Gallo received a bachelor's degree in theater
and textiles from the State University of New York. She joined the
Cunningham company as a wardrobe superviser in 1982 and worked as a
costume builder _ constructing the costumes from the designs _
before creating her first design for Cunningham in 1993. Among the
Cunningham works for which she designed costumes were ``Ground
Level Overlay,'' ``Windows'' and ``Biped.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo also worked as a costume builder or designer with such
choreographers as Neil Greenberg, Meredith Monk, Lucinda Childs and
Trisha Brown and with companies like the White Oak Dance Project,
Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater and Ballet Hispanico.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her parents, Frank and Joan Gallo of
Lakewood, N.J., and three brothers, Steven, of Lindenhurst, N.Y.,
Anthony, of Levittown, N.Y., and Philip, of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
