</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ISSELBACHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALFRED ISSELBACHER, A DEALER   WHO SPECIALIZED IN ART PRINTS, DIES
AT 73  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alfred Isselbacher, an art dealer who specialized in
19th- and 20th-century prints, died on Feb. 15 at a hospital in the
Bronx. He was 73 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Isselbacher was born in Isselbach, Germany, in 1926. His family
emigrated to the United States in 1938 and settled in Manhattan.
After graduating from high school, he served in the U.S. Coast
Guard during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Isselbacher worked at different jobs until the
late 1950s, when he opened a stationery and bookstore in the Inwood
section of Manhattan. He gradually began to sell prints at his
shop, starting with a lithograph by Ossip Zadkin.
</P>
<P>
   Isselbacher opened a gallery at 1225 Madison Ave. in 1965,
moving in 1970 to 1223 Madison Ave. and in 1980 to 41 E. 78th St.
Although he exhibited paintings, drawings and sculpture, prints
remained his main focus. Over the years he had exhibitions of
prints by Matisse, Picasso, Bonnard, Dubuffet, Miro, Escher and
Frank Stella. He closed the gallery in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He was an active member of the Art Dealers Association of
America, serving on its board of directors and exhibiting in its
annual Art Show at the Seventh Regiment Armory from its inception
in 1989 until 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Carmen; a daughter, Audrey Liebman;
and two grandchildren, all of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
