u a BC-MASON-ARRESTED-NYT     02-26 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASON-ARRESTED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-KNICK MASON IS CHARGED WITH ASSAULT IN BAR   BRAWL
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anthony Mason, the former New York Knick, was charged
with assault early Saturday after he and a group of friends were
involved in a barroom brawl that left three people injured, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who has a criminal record for assault and other charges
in New York, was arrested with four friends at about 4:30 a.m.
Saturday in Harlem, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   All five were charged with third-degree assault, said Officer
Chris Cottingham, a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Mason now plays for the Charlotte Hornets, who were in town to
play the New Jersey Nets on Saturday night at the Continental
Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said that Mason might not appear
before a judge for arraignment until late Saturday night and that
it was unlikely he would be able to make his team's 7:30 p.m. game,
even if he was cleared.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Mason's friends _ William Leary, 26; Anthony
Kelly, 24; Mason's cousin, William Duggins, 26; and Paul Boling, 34
_ live in Queens, where Mason grew up. Mason now lives in North
Carolina. It was unclear if any of the five were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, 33, got to the bar sometime after midnight, the police
said. The fight broke out around 4:20 a.m. after Mason and his
friends began arguing with three other patrons at Perks Bar, at the
corner of Manhattan Avenue and 123rd Street in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   After breaking up the fight, the police took Mason and his
friends to a precinct about a block away. The three victims, all
men between 30 and 32, were taken to a hospital to be treated for
cuts, bruises and other injuries, law enforcement officials said.
Their names had not been released Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Few details were available on what sparked the altercation.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the precinct Saturday, Don Cronson, Mason's lawyer and
agent, declined to comment other than to say that the charges and
the details were unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Lewis, 44, a longtime friend of Mason's who was at Perks at
the time of the fight, said that the basketball player was ``if
anything, trying to break up the fight'' that had started between
Duggins and one of the other men.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to get into the limo,'' Lewis said. ``Then a group
of about 25 people started jumping people, I got hit in the face, I
turned around and swung, then I got into the car. Mason went back
in to get my coat.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason has had several run-ins with the law in New York. In 1998,
Mason and Duggins were charged with the third-degree rape of 14-
and 15-year-old girls at a party in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who admitted to consensual sex with the girls, pleaded
guilty to two misdemeanor counts of endangering the welfare of a
child. The Queens district attorney's office dropped the rape and
sexual abuse charges after DNA testing did not link Mason to the
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Mason was ordered to do 200 hours of community service with the
homeless. Duggins pleaded guilty to statutory rape and to
endangering the welfare of a child and was sentenced to five years
of probation and 800 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the New York police charged Mason with gun possession
and he was sentenced to probation and community service.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, he was charged with assault, menacing and
resisting arrest after a fight with two New York police officers
over a summons. The police said it took 10 officers to subdue Mason
who is 6 foot 8 and 280 pounds. He pleaded guilty to disorderly
conduct and was sentenced to 120 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks after he was charged in that case, Mason was
traded by the Knicks to Charlotte. Mason has played in the National
Basketball Association for 10 seasons, five with the Knicks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
