A9454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAFEAT0227-COX     02-26 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEAT0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bull's eye no longer
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Of all the weird sights in the NBA, nothing was more
awkward than John Starks in a Chicago Bulls uniform. Outside of the
cow that kicked over the lantern, hardly anyone was more despised
there than the fiery Starks.
</P>
<P>
   The former Knicks guard _ traded from Golden State to the Bulls
Feb. 16 in the three-team deal that shipped Toni Kukoc to
Philadelphia _ gained the city's disdain by doing something few
did: He physically challenged Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   During the heated Knicks-Bulls rivalry of the
early-to-mid-1990s, Starks repeatedly lost the one-on-one battle
with Jordan, but not because he backed down. Rather, he challenged
Jordan at every turn. And in a 1993 playoff game, when he said
Jordan used elbows on him, Starks went ballistic in Chicago
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to fight Jordan and was held back by teammates as he
charged toward His Airness. The sellout crowd looked on in horror.
Starks got ejected. Afterward, he said: ``I don't care who he is.
You elbow me, I'm not going to take it. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since then, Starks was roundly booed and cursed _ and even
objects were thrown at him _ each time he touched the ball in a
game at Chicago. Interestingly, Starks gained Jordan's respect for
his toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Starks is with the Bulls. And just to show how fickle fans
are, a sold-out crowd at the United Center chanted ``We want
Starks!'' during the fourth quarter of a 85-81 loss to the
Grizzlies Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' said Starks, who had 17 points off the bench.
``Whenever you come into a situation like this, you don't know what
to expect. But when you go out there and you play well, that
changes people's minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Elton Brand said, ``It shows that Chicago appreciates a
hard worker.''
</P>
<P>
   And so do the players. ``I think they have accepted him,''
Chicago coach Tim Floyd said. ``When you got good guys, they'll
accept Atilla the Hun. Of course, in John's case, he's not Atilla
the Hun, in spite of what some people will want to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Starks said all the right things after the trade, but he was not
happy. First of all, he was informed about the deal by a reporter.
Secondly, he had asked the Warriors to send him to a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just common courtesy to give me a call, first and
foremost, and let me know what was going down,'' he said. ``Right
now, I'm at a point in my career where I want to be in contention
to win a title.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he was not sent to Miami, which would have reunited him
with coach Pat Riley, or another contender by Thursday's trade
deadline, Starks will have to wait until the offseason to hope for
a trade that will make him happy. In the meantime, he'll do what
he's always done: play with fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I got some good basketball left in me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1645EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-FREEAGENT     02-26 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FREEAGENTS0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brief, decisive courtship put newcomers in Falcons fold
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The way Ashley Ambrose and Shawn Jefferson planned it,
Friday, Feb. 11, was supposed to be normal.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Atlanta Falcons got involved.
</P>
<P>
   Almost before anyone could say, ``It's the first day of the
NFL's free-agency period,'' Ambrose, a cornerback, skipped his
flight from New Orleans to Cincinnati for a friend's wedding, and
flew to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, both men were off the unemployment line. They
agreed to contracts with the Falcons. Jefferson, a wide receiver,
did it without setting foot in Georgia. Ambrose arrived in town
Saturday, and got so lost that he ended up at the Georgia World
Congress Center looking for team headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Friday also began oddly for Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sleeping, and (Falcons vice president for pro personnel)
Ron Hill called and woke me up,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said, ``I said, `Get on the phone and call your dog and do
some recruiting,'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dog'' is what Buchanan calls his best friend, Ambrose, and
vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons always acted as decisively as they did Feb. 11,
they probably would have more than eight winning seasons in 34.
</P>
<P>
   Their race to keep Ambrose and Jefferson off the open market
began about 7 a.m., when the telephone of Ambrose's agent, Kennard
McGuire, rang in the dark near Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let him know we were very serious,'' general manager Harold
Richardson said. ``I waited to call Jefferson's (agent, Gary
Uberstine), because he's in California. I still woke him up.''
</P>
<P>
   For a change, the Falcons had generous room under the salary
cap, about $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   And they had some glaring needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be satisfied taking any one of, say, four
cornerbacks, you're not going to spend as much as if you target one
guy and go forward with it,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I would use the word 'fun.' It's the same . .
. as before a game. There's emotion, tension, anticipation.''
</P>
<P>
   SECOND TIME'S A CHARM
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons tried to sign Ambrose, 29, in 1999, after he left
the Bengals as a free agent. They didn't have enough money. Ambrose
ended up playing for his hometown Saints.
</P>
<P>
   But New Orleans didn't pick up the option on Ambrose's contract,
even though he had an outstanding season, because it called for
more than $5 million in compensation.
</P>
<P>
   That Friday, Ambrose, wife Monica and 15-month-old daughter
Aisha were getting ready to travel to Cincinnati for a Sunday
wedding of a former teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent called and said I had a flight to Atlanta,'' Ambrose
said. ``He said we got a chance to get a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray called right after that. Ray is crazy. He was so excited.
He started doing a rap song, throwing down a beat, `Boom, cha-cha,
my boyz coming to town, I hope he signs, we gonna get down, boom,
cha-cha.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose's wife and daughter went to Cincinnati. He went to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson and McGuire went to work. ``My agent told me some
numbers, and before I even left the (Atlanta) airport, I knew I was
going to be a Falcon,'' Ambrose said.
</P>
<P>
   The basics of a five-year, $22.5 million contract, including a
$7.5 million guaranteed signing bonus had been agreed upon. As
Ambrose left the Atlanta airport in a car with Falcons pro
personnel assistant Les Snead. A physical, formalities and food
were all that remained. Ambrose's wife arrived Saturday morning
from Cincinnati. He signed the contract, and the Falcons held a
news conference at 10 a.m. Saturday.THE RUN-AROUND
</P>
<P>
   That Friday, when Richardson and Hill weren't on the phone with
McGuire, they usually were on the phone with Uberstine, Jefferson's
agent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal for the former San Diego and New England wide receiver
_ for four years, $14.2 million and a $4.5 million signing bonus _
was worked out quickly, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call on Friday morning, (from) my agent,'' Jefferson
said. ``He said Atlanta was interested. I said, `Man. Wow! Are they
seriously interested? That would be a great fit.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson is co-owner of the `Any Occasion Catering Company' in
Marietta, an Atlanta suburb. Atlanta also is close to Jacksonville,
where Jefferson and his wife, Marla, grew up and live in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Uberstine) called back and said,' Shawn, they want you,''
said Jefferson, who has played for the Chargers and most recently
the Patriots. `` `I'm telling you, they want you.' I said, `Work it
out. Don't take any more calls. This is where I want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson went to pick up his son, Shawn Jr., 3, from preschool,
and his daughter, Paige, 7, from school.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my way, (Uberstine) called on a cell phone. He said the way
it stands now, you're a Falcon,'' Jefferson said. ``Then, my
daughter said, `When are we moving?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson wanted to drive to Atlanta. His wife persuaded him to
take a Saturday-morning flight.
</P>
<P>
   Snead and Falcons officials were at Ambrose's news conference
about the time Jefferson's flight landed.
</P>
<P>
   So the Jeffersons took a cab. Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawn was so late,'' Reeves said. ``We kept waiting and
waiting. I try never to get excited until they're signed, because
so many times we've thought we had somebody and ended up
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson didn't change his mind. He was losing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the cab driver to take me to the Falcons headquarters,
and he took me to the Georgia Dome,'' Jefferson said. ``They had
that big sports show (the Super Show) next door. They kept saying,
`I don't see a name tag; you can't come in here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'm trying to find the Atlanta Falcons office.' They
said, `They're closed on Saturdays.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Jefferson called Richardson, and the Snead shuttle was
dispatched. Another physical. Another contract signed. Another news
conference.NOT DONE YET
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are about $1.4 million to $2 million under the
salary cap and have needs on the offensive line, running back,
linebacker, the secondary and, many would say, at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did in free-agency . . . takes a little pressure off
the draft,'' Hill said. ``It's not going to happen like this every
year. You're not always going to get the guys you pinpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson and Ambrose have met their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (Saturday) night, we . . . stayed up all night talking
about it,'' Jefferson said. ``Man, the Atlanta Falcons. I am so
excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambrose isn't exactly bumming, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still got a chance to be at the wedding in Cincinnati,'' he
said. ``We went Saturday night. I just showed up with a little more
money in my pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
