<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLFEA0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    League's two messages
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Eighteen years ago, long before Wayne
Gretzky was gift-wrapped by the Edmonton Oilers and sent to Los
Angeles, a journeyman player gave hockey unforeseen exposure in
Southern California. Paul Mulvey made national news by refusing an
order by then-Kings coach Don Perry _ ``Go out there and don't just
dance.'' Translation: Start a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mulvey nor Perry were long for the NHL. Neither survived
as long as the black eye suffered by the league, which continues to
both embrace violence when it is deemed to be under control and
react with horror when something awful happens, meaning something
that gets hockey on network news.
</P>
<P>
   The contradiction was evident again last week after Boston's
Marty McSorley clubbed Vancouver's Donald Brashear in the head with
his stick. McSorley has received an open-ended suspension and must
seek permission from NHL commissioner Gary Bettman if he wants to
play next season. Brashear has a grade 3 concussion and might not
make it back this season.
</P>
<P>
   What has been overshadowed is that both players _ either
``enforcers'' or ``goons,'' depending on your perspective _ were
put on the ice by their coaches in the final seconds of a game that
had been decided. The league finds no problem with that.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL has made progress in curbing violence. Fighting is down
and more suspensions are handed out for severe penalties,
particularly involving shots to the head. But the league believes
that fighting is part of the game and finds no connection between
two players brawling and such acts as that of McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that violence is violence. If NHL owners really
wanted to end it, the league would hand out automatic ejections for
fighting and severe stick penalties. Owners and coaches would get
stiff fines. The NHL hasn't done it because speed and violence make
a lovely marketing pair. The negative side is the occasional
incident like the one Monday in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want people waving the flag that our sport has
crossed the line,'' league vice president Colin Campbell said. ``It
was an isolated incident. We don't like what happened, and we don't
like that it's on the national news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be grossly unfair to suggest that his conduct is at
all representative of the game, of the other 700 players who play
in the NHL,'' Campbell said. ``We regret that this act occurred and
that it has brought this kind of attention to our game. This is not
how we want hockey portrayed.''
</P>
<P>
   But they can't have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
