<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9457 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-STOCK-TRACKING0227-CO     02-26 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-TRACKING0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firms have upper hand in use of tracking stocks
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The idea of tracking stocks, as a separate kind of
security, makes a lot of sense to companies _ but has run into
drawbacks with investors.
</P>
<P>
   Elegant in concept, the tracking stock is tied to a portion of
the company's business, usually a showy business line that stands
out from the rest of the products or services. The idea is to catch
the eye of investors who might not otherwise pay attention and to
raise capital in greater amounts.
</P>
<P>
   The idea seems especially appropriate for utilities or companies
in basic materials _ companies that do good work day in and out but
normally lack the drama of other companies that are more often in
the news.
</P>
<P>
   That's why BellSouth is inclined toward a version of the tracker
stock, perhaps an issue tied to growing international business
and/or wireless communication, areas that can claim more growth
than most other product lines within the giant company.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific has already issued a tracker stock for its
timber line of business.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea behind the tracker stock is that it should create
some buzz and enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The tracking stocks, which sometimes are given to existing
shareholders or sold separately, are supposed to reflect the happy
developments in the tracked business. This is assisted by issuing
separate revenue and earnings statements reflecting what's going on
in those businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems that have arisen are predictable. Creating the
ideal tracker stock is not unlike picking winners on Wall Street,
or timing the market. It simply isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   How was Georgia-Pacific to know that its nice timber stock would
get upstaged by a nice upswing in paper, of all things.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the market becomes leery of the decision to track one
activity but not others, or investors get confused and decide to
back away from the securities in that company until they figure it
out _ which may take awhile.
</P>
<P>
   What about the proceeds corralled by sale of tracker stocks?
Often they are plowed back into support for the company at large,
not necessarily the glamour activity.
</P>
<P>
   With tracker stocks, there isn't the tidy closed relationship
between capital, investment and management strategies investors are
accustomed to expect in traditional investments or plays.
</P>
<P>
   As one analyst put it, ``Tracker stocks are a good idea for
companies, not so good for investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific has tried to do some extra things to create the
right environment and feedback relationship between the tracked
unit and the investors. As market capitalization grows in Timber
Co., the tracked business line, it will give greater voice to
holders of the tracker stock.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Haldin, a spokesman for Georgia-Pacific, says that the
timber stock, launched in late 1997, has done pretty much what the
company desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has allowed investors to measure timber industry activity
against other timber business, apart from all the other parts of
the timber products business,'' Haldin said, ``and to that extent
it has been a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that is a better measure of the success of the
tracker stock than how it stacks up against other tracking
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though there is some confusion and resistance to tracker
stocks in some quarters, companies are probably going to stick with
the new strategy, at least for a while, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The new stocks do, after all, bring in some new capital. They
are also an additional potential benefit and stock option to be
dangled in front of prized employees or managers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one wonders if the tracking trend does not weaken the
wholesome idea of diversity in a company.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a teacher, for instance, it would be hard to
entertain the idea of removing from your class the most brilliant
students so they could go into a fast track of study, leaving you
with only the plodding students.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of the mix could be diluted.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, however, anything, even a gimmick, might serve a
decent purpose if it helps to focus new attention on companies,
especially the old-line companies that are sometimes pushed out of
the limelight by the glamour players in the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
