<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SOC-WOMEN'S-LEAGUE-NY     02-26 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN'S-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WOMEN'S PRO SOCCER LEAGUE REQUIRES A KICK-START  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Nancy Lieberman-Cline is the president of the Women's Sports
Foundation and general manager and head coach of the Detroit
Shock.)  
 By NANCY LIEBERMAN-CLINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since the U.S. national women's soccer team won the 1999
Women's World Cup, there has been talk of the establishment of a
women's professional soccer league. Lots of talk, and finally some
action.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, John Hendricks, the chairman and chief
executive officer of Discovery Communications, announced plans to
form the Women's United Soccer Association, with play starting in
the spring of 2001. But will his initiative win approval from the
U.S. Soccer Federation, which governs the sport in this country?
There is no guarantee of that.
</P>
<P>
   The men's league, Major League Soccer, also has a business plan
that includes the option of a partnership between MLS and a women's
league. Many people interpret this as an indication that MLS is
seeking to control the development of a women's league to prevent
competition with its sponsorships. Thus, the female players have
not demonstrated much excitement over the MLS marriage proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the success of professional team sports have
depended on four factors:
</P>
<P>
   _ Wealthy individuals who ante up franchise fees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cities that offer arenas and tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   _ An experienced and savvy direct-marketing machine in each
franchise city.
</P>
<P>
   _ A central league office that can deliver a stable, long-term
and lucrative television contract and strategic leadership that
prevents weak franchises from dragging down the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The team sports that do not make it fail from lack of any one of
these factors.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to popular thought, player salaries do not make or
break the model. Negotiations with players actually result in
players receiving a reasonable percent of total revenue, even if
the multimillion-dollar figure for some individuals appears
unreasonable to some fans and observers. Those skyscraper salaries
would not exist if the revenues were not there.
</P>
<P>
   The Hendricks group appears to have only one of the
prerequisites in place: the deep pockets of initial investors. A
minimum of $40 million is to be provided by the initial investors
to finance a minimum of eight teams, plus league administration,
during the first five years of operations. The cast of investors is
impressive: a former chairman of Continental Cablevision, Amos
Hostetter Jr.; the chairman of Cox Enterprises, James Kennedy; the
president of Cox Communications, James Robbins; the president of
Comcast Corp., Brian L. Roberts; the vice president for programming
investments of Comcast Corp., Amy Banse; the chairman and chief
executive officer of Time Warner Cable, Joseph J. Collins; and the
senior vice president for programming of Time Warner Cable, Fred M.
Dressler.
</P>
<P>
   In the plan, each investor will be responsible for staff and
facility resources along with TV and promotional support for the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Herein lie the concerns. A developing franchise needs a
passionate, tireless staff that is focused on one goal: making the
local franchise successful in terms of season ticket sales and
walk-up sales.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing the MLS to start the league might be a crucial error.
You cannot take a staff that is struggling to develop the men's
league and tell its members they need to approach a women's product
with the same effort and enthusiasm. The Women's National
Basketball Association started out with an assumption that the NBA
staff would do the women's league too, but it is moving away from
that. The women's soccer league needs to be built from the grass
roots, and each franchise needs an experienced team devoted to
developing one product.
</P>
<P>
   There is one more ingredient in the success of a team sport or
any professional league that cannot be underestimated: the passion
and business acumen of a single individual who can make all the
pieces come together during the league's initial years. The former
U.S. women's coach Tony DiCicco has been talked about as the
commissioner and the former SFX executive Lee Burke has been
mentioned as assisting in the formation of the Hendricks group
league. The credentials of whoever will lead the central office is
a make or break decision.
</P>
<P>
   It took vision and hard-nosed business skill to get past
critical periods in the NCAA (Walter Byers), the NBA (David Stern),
the NFL (Pete Rozelle) and other successful leagues.
</P>
<P>
   In the current economic climate, strong central administration
is essential. A new league must have an integrated marketing and
advertising strategy and campaign. There has to be centralized
control that will not allow a franchise to fail. There is no time
and no financial buffer to learn from mistakes. Is Burke or DiCicco
the brilliant marketing or management strategist who will fill this
leadership need?
</P>
<P>
   Local television is a nice addition to the national league
package but will not replace a major cable or broadcast carrier
deal. The Hendricks group reportedly expects significant rights
fees for the league television package. That might not be
realistic. Even David Stern had to buy time for the WNBA Chances
are that the Hendricks group will not be able to get any rights
fees for the kind of coverage it wants and needs. The Women's
United Soccer Association may have investors with potential cable
television and promotional reach, but that potential must be
translated into a reality that will benefit all franchise markets.
</P>
<P>
   Does central ownership of a league help, as in the league model
developed by the now-defunct women's American Basketball League and
nicely executed by the WNBA? Definitely; especially at the start-up
stage when consolidation of costs and central management of
promotions results in financial efficiencies. The WNBA had a
particular advantage by having a big-brother pro team system in
place and lots of muscle _ the leverage of the imminent renewal of
the NBA television contract _ to deliver the TV piece of the
puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of naysayers have suggested that there is not a strong
enough market for women's pro soccer and that it needs to have a
significant mass participation base and a successful collegiate
Final Four before launching a pro league. Tell that to the NHL or
the Miami or Dallas NHL franchises. The market is there for women's
soccer. What is needed are the leadership, marketing, investment
and television pieces to exploit it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1652EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
