<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9460 &Cx1f; tad-z
b i BC-LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH-$AD     02-26 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH-$ADV27-1STLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 4th graf, deletes 'soft-spoken ...'; in14th graf, adds
'fired an American' to clarify ...
 &HT;    HEZBOLLAH SHARPENING TACTICS IN LONG WAR WITH ISRAEL
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Nabatiyeh is southeast of
Sidon, in central-southern Lebanon
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Feb. 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABATIYEH, Lebanon _ Hidar Madloum is ready to die in his fight
against Israel, but that's not the only reason for his army's
success.
</P>
<P>
   In 12 years with the Lebanese Hezbollah guerillas, he has
witnessed advances that make the small force a surprisingly tough
adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very beginning, the training was not based on
precision. Now, we see the latest technology,'' Madloum, a
soft-spoken, but intense war veteran said in an interview last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of firing rockets from our shoulders, we can maneuver
them from a distance,'' says Madloum, 28, pantomiming remote
controls with his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Madloum's Hezbollah appears to be on the verge of driving Israel
out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In the rugged mountains of south Lebanon, guerrillas like
Madloum have matched a superior force with self-sacrifice,
adaptability and a keen use of propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   They move low in the valleys, wait in ambush and cull
information from supportive villagers. They watch videotapes of
their attacks to improve their methods and use the same videos to
torment the Israeli public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis are losing a guerrilla war and losing it pretty
clearly,'' said Bard O'Neill, an expert on the Middle East at the
National War College in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has occupied a portion of south Lebanon since 1982. It
took the land to chase out PLO fighters. They left, but Israel
stayed and Hezbollah, the Lebanese Party of God, formed in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis fear that Hezbollah, backed by Syria and Iran,
will attack Israel if allowed to approach the border.
</P>
<P>
   But, opposition to what some call ``Israel's Vietnam'' is
increasing. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak promises to withdraw
the troops this summer.
</P>
<P>
   For many Israelis, it could not happen soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   This month, shortly after Israeli leaders touted months without
a loss, Hezbollah killed seven Israelis in just over a fortnight.
</P>
<P>
   In one attack, Hezbollah apparently fired an American-made TOW
guided missile _ new to its arsenal _ at a slit in a reinforced
Israeli bunker.
</P>
<P>
   In another, they lead Israelis into a classic guerrilla trap.
They injured several with a hidden roadside bomb, then shelled to
kill a medic who responded.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said the Israelis have been slow to grasp that they are
fighting skilled guerrillas, not just ``terrorists.'' Just about
everything, he said, is in Hezbollah's favor _ rough terrain, a
supportive public and the will to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors counter Israel's formidable air force and the
billions of dollars it spends on its army _ including about $2
billion a year from the United States. Israel reportedly has 1,000
to 1,500 troops in southern Lebanon, plus about 2,000 in the local,
Israeli-paid, South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hezbollah's war chest comprises mostly an estimated
$100 million a year from Iran. Some of that goes to a system of
schools and hospitals, and a political party.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated to have 500 to 1,000 full-time fighters and more
part-timers culled from the countryside of rocky, terraced hills
and olive orchards. About 100,000 Lebanese live in the occupied
area.
</P>
<P>
   True, Hezbollah's casualties are higher than Israel's _ about
1,400 compared to Israel's approximately 260 battlefield deaths.
But, Israeli parents worry that their sons might die in vain before
an eventual withdrawal. The guerrillas die readily for their land
and Shiite Muslim religion.
</P>
<P>
   Fighter Madloum took shrapnel in his skull last year. He still
has headaches, but he is back fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Nabatiyeh, a farming town of about 70,000 that sits just
outside the Israeli-occupied area and below two Israeli hilltop
forts, he talks to Cox Newspapers last week. Dressed in a dark
anorak coat and black jeans, Madloum spoke of his pleasure at his
near death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martyrdom, for us, is victory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not disclose his guerrilla specialties, but said his
part-time job as an engineering firm's mapmaker has helped him in
battlefield reconnaissance.
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed that Hezbollah studies America's weaknesses in
Vietnam and the Soviet Union's defeat in Afghanistan. Commanders,
he said, watch Hezbollah battle videotapes to correct mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah is elusive. Fighters wear civilian clothes when not
fighting. They keep few or no fixed camps. Madloum, for instance,
asked that the precise location of this downtown interview not be
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Timur Goksel, senior advisor to the U.N. forces monitoring the
war, says Hezbollah shows a ``natural evolution.'' A process of
trial-and-error costs lives, but keeps pace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Israel began tracking the wires on Hezbollah's
roadside bombs, so Hezbollah began detonating them with radio
signals. Israel intercepted the signals, so Hezbollah scrambled
them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israel's natural strength, air power, is limited by
the conventions of modern war.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Israel launched a massive air and artillery barrage
against civilian targets. It prompted international outrage and
lead to new rules aimed at keeping civilians out of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah is supposed to stay away from civilian areas, too, but
that is hard to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   Near Nabatiyeh, an elderly couple lives about a half-mile away
from a hilltop Israeli outpost _ a fortified mound with lights and
fencing.
</P>
<P>
   They are tired of their home being pocked by Israeli shrapnel
and machine guns, but stay to show their determination. They say
villagers inform Hezbollah when Israelis might head toward the
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are resistance,'' said 65-year-old Samiha Homani
Kallas, ``the men, women, children, houses, animals and trees.''
</P>
<P>
   (Optional end)
</P>
<P>
   And, in case Hezbollah's successes go unnoticed, it uses videos.
The results in Israel are reminiscent of the coverage that hastened
the end of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Ra'ad, a Hezbollah member of the Lebanese parliament,
said Hezbollah announces battlefield victories in hopes that
Israeli military sources will deny them. Then, Hezbollah will
release the video.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have dragged the enemy into a kind of press trap,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity also strengthens Lebanese resolve.
</P>
<P>
   A Beirut exhibition this month featured battle videos. One was
called ``Screaming Israelis,'' showing Israeli troops writhing in
pain after a roadside bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has proven that the Israeli soldier can be killed,'' Ra'ad
said. ``The image of the Israeli army is legendary. But now, if you
ask any child in south Lebanon, he will say he can kill Israeli
troops.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   HEZBOLLAH _ LEBANON'S PARTY OF GOD
</P>
<P>
   Activities: Guerrilla army, school and health network, political
party.
</P>
<P>
   Goal: Immediate aim is to drive Israel from occupied territory
in southern Lebanon. Some say it wants to eliminate Israel
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Leader: Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah.
</P>
<P>
   Formed: 1985, officially.
</P>
<P>
   Ideology: Bases itself on fundamentalist Shiite Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters: Roughly 500-1,000 full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Backers: Syria allows weapons to flow to Hezbollah from Iran,
which aids with up to $100 million a year, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
