<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9461 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FREEDOM-BELL0227-COX     02-26 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-BELL0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let freedom ring on the mountain
 &HT;    By Tinah Saunders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ The granite dome of Stone Mountain isn't
from the center of Stone Mountain Village, but its presence loomed
over Saturday's unveiling of a Freedom Bell dedicated to the memory
of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain is where the Ku Klux Klan reorganized at the
beginning of the 20th century. King used it as a symbol of racism
in his ``I Have A Dream'' speech in 1963, declaring, ``Let freedom
ring from Stone Mountain, Ga.''
</P>
<P>
   The bell did indeed ring Saturday in the town that Mayor Chuck
Burris called ``a symbol of progress and hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Burris, elected in 1997, is Stone Mountain's first
African-American mayor. Its six-member City Council has several
African-American members. And the crowd of about 500 who came to
hear the bell rung for the first time was racially mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stone Mountain got a bad name because of the Klan, but the
town was never a part of that,'' said Hugh Jordan, former chairman
of the state Legislature's Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit
Overview Committee, the precursor to MARTA, the current
metropolitan area transportation system. Jordan was born 79 years
ago in a house 500 yards from site of the ceremony on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The races have always gotten along here, that's why you see so
many blacks on our city council,'' he said. ``(Councilman) Robert
Smith has served on it for 25 or 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Georgia State flag flying overhead, Burris introduced
visiting officials, including the consuls of Nigeria and Barbados,
Attorney General Thurbert Baker and the county's CEO, Liane
Levitan.
</P>
<P>
   Among the speakers was Brenda Cornelius, director of community
affairs for Governor Roy Barnes, who read a message from the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``How far we've come in a city where once the KKK marched with
impunity,'' Barnes wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan reminisced about her first days as an Austrian immigrant
in Georgia, when she was not allowed to ride in the back of a bus
because blacks were relegated to those seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not understand,'' Levitan said. ``Change can be slow in
coming, but it happens for those who refuse to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joseph Lowery, president emeritus of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, also spoke to the crowd,
impressing a visitor from Charlotte who happened upon the ceremony
while his wife was shopping in the stores along Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice ceremony. I got here about the time Rev. Lowery
began speaking and I really enjoyed him,'' Larry Eaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Council members gathered to pull the burgundy velvet drape from
the 1,700-pound bell. Set on a granite slab in the center of the
village and burnished to a golden glow, the bell rang out to cheers
from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Bell was rescued from a church in a Pennsylvania
coal mining town that had to be abandoned because of fires in the
mines below it. It is more than 100 years old and larger by one
inch than the Liberty Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is very significant. It shows that unity is
coming to Stone Mountain and to the entire country. It's long
overdue,'' said Anthony Byrd, who attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Mom Shirley Byrd agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm a part of making history today. It's
wonderful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bell will be tolled annually at noon on King's birthday
holiday, said Burris.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm sure we will think of other occasions to ring it
too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
