<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HORNETS-MASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASON FACING ASSAULT CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
 (With MASON-ARRESTED) 
(nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Running through drills at their
shoot-around Saturday morning, the Charlotte Hornets appeared no
different than any other team on any other day. And perhaps, more
than any other team, they could handle the latest development
without flinching.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets arrived at Continental Airlines Arena before 10
a.m., receiving the news from coach Paul Silas that forward Anthony
Mason was in a Manhattan jail cell, facing assault charges and an
uncertain future. Mason, along with his cousin and three friends,
were arrested outside Perks Bar in Harlem at 4:30 a.m., following a
fight that left three other men hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest in a series of difficult moments for the team,
the most visible of which was the Jan. 12 automobile accident that
claimed the life of forward Bobby Phills.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the season started, Derrick Coleman wrecked his
Range Rover on Oct. 27 in an accident that left his teammate
Eldridge Recasner with a collapsed lung. Coleman was charged with
drunk driving, but was later acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Recasner later was charged with fourth-degree assault at a
Seattle airport ticket counter after his sister and mother were
involved in a car accident and, believing that his sister might not
survive, he snapped at an airport employee.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Hornets' owner, George Shinn, has had his share of
trouble. Shinn was sued on a charge of sexual assault. He was found
not liable in a sordid trial, and two weeks afterward, the woman's
husband committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough,'' Silas said. ``But we've come through all
adversity, so another episode doesn't really bother us that much.
We keep rolling. I expect a lot out of them and they expect a lot
out of themselves and we will not falter. Whatever it takes we're
going to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman could only shake his head at the news. Despite his own
history of troubles, he has endured and has been playing the best
ball of his career. As he bounced his 3-year-old son, Derrick Jr.,
on his lap, Coleman struggled to explain how the team has still
managed a 30-23 record through the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything that we've been through this year, we've
managed to stick together as a team and that's helped all of us
through it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of Mason in particular, Coleman said: ``We're more concerned
about his well-being than anything. We just hope that we can get
him here in time to play the basketball game and he can worry about
that other stuff later on.''
</P>
<P>
   As word of Mason's arrest filtered in, at the Nets' practice
site, Kendall Gill spoke of how an athlete is often placed in
difficult situations. But he said athletes have to be aware of that
hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get angry when I see something like Darryl Strawberry
failing another drug test because I idolized him when I was growing
up,'' Gill said. ``To see him have so many opportunities and keep
doing it after it he gets chance after chance, you can't feel sorry
for the guy anymore if trouble keeps following him. Maybe trouble's
not following him. Maybe he's looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mase's situation, I wasn't there, but you hate to see
somebody keep getting in trouble with the law like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gill admitted that it's sometimes hard to walk away when
confronted with situations as an almost everyday occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful when you go into bars, grocery stores,
even when you walk along the street,'' Gill said. ``You never know
when somebody is going to come up and try to start something with
you, say something smart. We're all human beings. You don't like
anybody to say negative to you. Professional athletes,
entertainers, we're targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've walked away sometimes and I've gotten into a brawl or
two. It happens all the time. That's why you see Shaquille O'Neal
taking a bodyguard with him. You have to guard yourself against it.
It's unfortunate it has to be like that, but that's the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even repeat what people say to you, in the club, on
the street,'' he added. ``Fans may be mad because you missed a shot
or you missed a rebound or they're just plain jealous. A lot of
people think when you make it to the top all your problems
disappear. They actually increase. When you know that you can
better deal with it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
