<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-CLEMENTE-NYT &LR;      02-26 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CLEMENTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAN CLEMENTE'S   QUICK RETURN   LIFTS HARVARD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Life could not have been better for Dan Clemente last
November.
</P>
<P>
   As the starting power forward on the Harvard men's basketball
team, the 6-foot-6-inch Clemente was a steady contributor as the
Crimson started out with a 3-1 record. Harvard was poised to make a
run at the Ivy League title.
</P>
<P>
   But then Clemente began to lose focus, literally. He first
experienced impaired vision in his right eye in early December.
Initially, the problem did not affect his performance as he shot 7
for 11 and was 4 for 6 from 3-point range in scoring 24 points
against Navy on Dec. 4 in an 85-83 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision in my right eye was very blurry,'' Clemente said.
``I did not think it was a major problem; I thought maybe I needed
a new prescription for my contact lenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The blurring persisted, and after a dismal 6-point performance
in a 58-57 loss to Boston University on Dec. 7, Clemente sought
medical attention. ``My optometrist could not figure out what was
causing the blurring, so he referred me to a specialist,'' Clemente
said.
</P>
<P>
   After a consultation with Dr. Jeffrey Heier of the Boston Eye
Institute, Clemente was informed that his retina was detached in
his right eye, severely damaging his central vision. If left
unattended, the eye could go completely blind. Clemente needed
emergency surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Heier said the injury most likely occurred when Clemente took a
hard hit to the head, but Clemente does not recall a specific
incident. ``I get hit hard in the head three times a day during
practice and in the games,'' Clemente said. ``It could have
happened at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemente underwent surgery on Dec. 10, two days after his visit
to the doctor. The healing process was a difficult one, as was the
realization that he might never play basketball again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have spoken to literally 10 doctors all over the
country who said there was no way Dan would be able to play,'' said
Clemente's father, Brian. ``He was very depressed by this, but we
tried to remind him that this is not the end of his life. He was
determined to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Dan Clemente was told he would have to sit out three
to four months before being re-evaluated. Since he had already
played 21 percent of Harvard's schedule, Clemente could not be
designated a redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever really thought there was a chance that I could be
back this season,'' he said. ``I told the coaches that I would be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemente's retina healed nicely. He was cleared to play Feb. 1,
and started practicing the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing Clemente's vulnerability to another eye injury,
Harvard's trainer, Gary Gisler, contacted the Boston Celtics'
trainer, Ed Lacerte, and inquired about a pair of protective
goggles.
</P>
<P>
   In his first game back Feb. 4, a 67-57 victory over Cornell,
Clemente shot 9 for 19 from the floor (4 of 7 from 3-point range),
scoring 24 points. In the five games since, he has averaged 15
points a game on 44 percent shooting for the Crimson (10-14 over
all and 5-6 in the Ivy League). Going into Friday night's loss to
Princeton, Clemente, who missed 11 games with the injury, was
leading the league in scoring (19.1 points a game) even though he
had not played enough games to qualify for the scoring title.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente's coach, Frank Sullivan, said: ``It is lucky for a
coach to have his best players as the hardest workers. And he
definitely personifies that. When he was injured, Dan did whatever
possible to keep in good condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan admitted that he is concerned about the possibility of
Clemente reinjuring his retina, but reassurances from doctors and
the protective goggles have eased his worries.
</P>
<P>
   The eye injury is not the first time in his Crimson career that
Clemente has shown resilience. Before last season, as a sophomore,
Clemente experienced chronic ankle pain. After talking to the
team's trainers, the consensus was that he did not need surgery. He
could play through the pain without causing permanent damage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, however, wanted to hold Clemente out of the opener
last season against Boston College to give him more time to heal.
But Clemente finally persuaded Sullivan to put him in down the
stretch. In the final four minutes, he made two 3-pointers to spark
the Crimson to a 62-61 victory. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
