<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SFX-SPORTS-2TAKES-NYT     02-26 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SFX-SPORTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SFX IS TAKING STOCK OF SPORTS COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   You are SFX Entertainment, and you are dominating the world of
live entertainment. In three years, you have bought your way into
concert tours, touring Broadway shows and family entertainment. You
have shaken up an industry of small independent firms, consolidated
them and recast them as a behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   What do you do next? Which other fragmented industry will accept
your cash, your stock and your covetous appetite for growth?
</P>
<P>
   Sports.
</P>
<P>
   You snap up agencies that represent 16 percent of all major
league baseball players and 22 percent of all NBA players. You go
into business with Michael Jordan by acquiring the agent David
Falk's firm and wrest Andre Agassi away from his agents at the
International Management Group.
</P>
<P>
   You send the U.S. national women's soccer team on tour after it
wins the 1999 World Cup, and you offer to help finance a new arena
for the New York Islanders. You negotiate Kobe Bryant's purchase of
50 percent of Olimpia Milano, an Italian basketball team, and you
sign Florida State's Peter Warrick, who will be a top pick in the
NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   You expand into professional figure skating championships, the
Internet, monster truck events, stadium and arena naming rights,
player endorsements, corporate sponsorships, film and television
production and financial management.
</P>
<P>
   You are big and brash. You have financed a broad swath of
entertainment and sports acquisitions with $2.2 billion in stock,
loans and debt. You have created a sports group that is a small but
high-profile part of the company, which generated $1.2 billion in
revenues through the first nine months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And you adopt a vision that accommodates your broad ambitions:
Sports and entertainment intersect like the loops of a cat's
cradle, where, with a critical mass of athletic humanity, you can
strike more deals generating more cash for the bottom line and
create events in which players can own equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're asked, `Who's your competition?' _ it's everyone
and no one,'' said Bill Allard, president of SFX Sports Group. ``In
each of our areas, we have competition, but the totality of it,
with what we offer sports- and entertainment-wise, nobody can
provide the kind of value we can.''
</P>
<P>
   SFX's rapid growth signifies the frenzy to combine product and
distribution in a global communications market increasingly
dominated by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything at SFX is, in theory, designed to interact in
the service of athletes, spectators, sponsors and corporate
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate America is quite interested in one-stop shopping,''
said Dean Bonham, a sports marketer in Denver, ``to be able to go
to one place for an event, an athlete, an ad placement and a
sponsorship.''
</P>
<P>
   That scope attracted Agassi to SFX. He was unhappy with IMG for
not exploiting his personality and feats, especially after he won
the French Open in June. ``We did everything Andre wanted us to
do,'' said Bob Kain, executive vice president of IMG. ``But he said
it was time for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi knew SFX through tournaments run by ProServ, which became
part of SFX last year when SFX acquired the Marquee Group,
ProServ's owner since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Blumberg, president of the SFX Sports talent division,
called Perry Rogers, Agassi's lawyer, last November. ``Would you
listen to what we're doing?'' Blumberg asked.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi jumped to SFX soon after, believing that its two-pronged
assault on sports and entertainment would benefit him more than
IMG, which had been the paradigm of broad-based sports marketing
for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a meeting with SFX with Co. A may result in Deal
B,'' Rogers said. It is unlikely that Agassi wants to be a rock
singer or a Broadway star, but Rogers said Agassi was particularly
interested in SFX's plans for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Had SFX not existed, Rogers said, IMG would still have Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's defection shocked IMG. There has been speculation that
one of SFX's enticements to Agassi was stock worth at least $10
million, which SFX will not confirm or deny. Mark McCormack, IMG's
chairman, blasted SFX in The Sports Business Journal, a trade
newspaper, as a ``stock play,'' accused it of overpaying ``for
everything they have bought,'' and predicted it will sell out a
quick score.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, trading in SFX shares on the New York Stock Exchange
was halted briefly after a report that CBS wanted to buy into the
company. CBS denied it, but SFX stock closed up by $3.312 to
$35.125 a share.
</P>
<P>
   SFX Entertainment began to carry out its sports strategy in
1998, more than a year after being spun off from SFX Broadcasting
and beginning its entertainment-business buying spree. Robert F.X.
Sillerman, SFX's executive chairman, knew about the sports business
_ he co-founded and helped finance Marquee in 1995 with Bob
Gutkowski, a former chairman of Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day we spun off from SFX, we had no conscious plan to move
into sports,'' said Mike Ferrel, president of SFX Entertainment.
``But as we aggregated our position in live entertainment, Goldman,
Sachs said they represented David Falk and would we talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   SFX paid Falk, whose clients include Jordan, Patrick Ewing and
Alonzo Mourning, $118 million in cash and stock plus incentives
worth $15 million. The price was rich but gave SFX instant access
to premier athletes, steady cash flow (except during last season's
NBA lockout) and the cachet of adding Air Jordan to the corporate
quiver.
</P>
<P>
   More purchases followed, focusing on agencies strong in baseball
(Hendricks Management and Speakers of Sport), and one with a dual
focus on baseball and basketball (Tellem &AMP; Associates). Marquee was
bought for $115.2 million in stock and assumed debt last year,
which led to Gutkowski's exit after a failed struggle against Falk
to run the SFX Sports Group. Falk is the chairman of the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've acquired all we need in basketball and baseball,''
Allard said. ``We're the best in the business.'' Football and
hockey agencies are on deck.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been down the road pretty far on something,'' said Tom
Reich, a prominent baseball and hockey agent, who would not
identify his suitors. ``We're re-evaluating the landscape; we're
uncommitted. But it's clear that most people are going to have to
have an affiliation going forward. It's not a direction that will
be reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   SFX is not alone in its sports strategy. Assante Corp., a
Winnipeg-based money management company, paid $120 million in cash
and stock for Steinberg, Moorad &AMP; Dunn, which represents Troy
Aikman and Steve Young, then bought Eugene Parker's
football-oriented agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merging to maximize your clout with the players you bring to
the table is a strong force in this business,'' Parker said. He
said Assante preserved his independence but that an SFX acquisition
would have ``felt like a forced fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Octagon, a division of Interpublic Group of Cos., owns a raft of
agencies, including the former Advantage International. ``We all
have a different slant to what we do,'' Frank Craighill, Octagon's
president, said. ``The world's big enough for all of us. To be
honest, I don't think SFX will control the world.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, SFX has not bought out Ralph Cindrich, a top football
agent. He represents 60 active players and likes his independence.
But he knows it will be difficult to compete against corporations
that can offer stock, cars, lines of credit and signing bonuses to
recruit clients. ``I don't view being acquired as inevitable,'' he
said, ``but almost everyone will listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy and Alan Hendricks sold their baseball-based agency to SFX
last June for $15.7 million. Randy Hendricks said he did not sell
to move into easy retirement. ``We did well with a model that we
had for 30 years _ a boutique agency _ but to do the best job we
can, we were better off with SFX,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrel and Allard know they cannot dominate sports in the same
manner as they do live entertainment. If you are a rock star, band
or musical, it is hard to traverse the country without running into
SFX.
</P>
<P>
   With league salary structures and other limitations, SFX is
unlikely to negotiate with team general managers with any greater
leverage than its agents had when they were independent. Falk,
Hendricks or Arn Tellem are unlikely to demand that a team sign one
player in order to talk to a better one, because they are in the
SFX family. But SFX has yet to say whether Falk will recuse himself
from negotiating player contracts with Jordan, the president of
basketball operations for the Washington Wizards, because Jordan
still has marketing deals handled by SFX.
</P>
<P>
   But one agent, who asked to remain anonymous, said he wondered
if SFX's agglomeration of agencies would diminish union solidarity
in the event of a strike or labor tactics that might reduce profits
to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who thinks agents would jeopardize the best interests
of their clients,'' Allard said, ``doesn't know these agents very
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
