<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SETON-VILLANOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST LOSS HAS SETON HALL FEARING NCAA REJECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLANOVA, Pa. _ Instead of surging toward its first NCAA
tournament berth in six years, Seton Hall is stumbling at the
finish line.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates' case for an at-large bid lost more luster Saturday
at Villanova. Seton Hall, buried by a 17-1 Wildcat run in the first
half, lost, 87-74, for its third defeat in four games. Its lone
victory came last Wednesday against a Minnesota team that had lost
two starters the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall fell to 19-7 overall and 10-5 in the Big East. In the
last 10 years, two Big East teams with 19 victories have been
rejected by the selection committee. Both finished poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Villanova, clinging to its NCAA hopes, improved to 17-7 and 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closer now than we were this morning,'' said coach Steve
Lappas of his team, which outshot Seton Hall, 48 percent to 43
percent, and outrebounded the Pirates by 44-36.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates close out the regular season at Madison Square
Garden against St. John's on Tuesday. Before Saturday, Seton Hall
was one of four teams vying for the top three spots in the Big East
standing and a first-round bye in the conference tournament. Just
one and one-half games separated Syracuse, St. John's, Miami and
Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a slump-busting 31 points from Darius Lane, the Pirates
turned in their fourth straight lackluster performance. Villanova
stretched a 47-39 halftime lead into a 14-point margin on several
occasions in the second half. The Pirates crept in for three
straight layups to trim the lead to 73-65 late in the second half,
but the Wildcats replied with 4 unanswered points and kept the
margin at 12 with under three minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall pulled within 8 again with 1 minute 30 seconds left,
but a Malik Allen dunk followed by two Gary Buchanan free throws
sealed the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Allen and Buchanan scored 17 points apiece, and Brian Lynch
added 16 for the Wildcats. For Seton Hall, Shaheen Holloway
contributed 12 points, followed by Rimas Kaukenas with 11 and Ty
Shine with 8.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, who had shot only 32 percent in his last three games, came
out on target Saturday. He scored 17 points in the first 10
minutes, and his driving layup put the Pirates up by 30-21.
</P>
<P>
   With Samuel Dalembert intimidating the Wildcats' leading scorer,
Allen, inside, Seton Hall appeared to be on its way. But when coach
Tommy Amaker began mixing and matching lineups because of fatigue,
the Pirates were victimized again by a huge 'Nova run.
</P>
<P>
   Villanova outscored Seton Hall, 17-1, to burst to a 40-33 lead.
The Pirates stumbled through eight minutes without a field goal.
Lane broke the spell with a putback, but Villanova answered with a
7-2 surge capped by Lynch's 3-pointer. Villanova led, 47-39, at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Lane made eight of 12 field-goal attempts on mostly bombs, but
then the Wildcats paid more attention to him. And with lineups that
at times did not include the starters Holloway, Kaukenas or
Dalembert, Villanova's job was made easier.
</P>
<P>
   Allen made the most of Dalembert's seven-minute absence, scoring
all 8 of his first-half points without the freshman center guarding
him.
</P>
<P>
   Dalembert had recorded double figures in points and rebounds in
his last two games, but he seemed to get lost in the offensive
scheme when Lane took over.
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall could not make headway early in the second half.
Jermaine Medley's 3-pointer gave Villanova a 56-44 lead with a
little more than 16 minutes left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
