<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-MIDEAST-PEACE-ASSES     02-26 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MIDEAST-PEACE-ASSESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: AN ARAB TOWN SYMBOLIZES CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Adds art note) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABU DIS, West Bank _ The Israeli-Palestinian peace effort, which
U.S. envoys were busy trying to revive last week, is deadlocked
over the fate of this unprepossessing Arab town on the eastern
outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing this dusty hillside suburb to become a monthlong
stumbling block bodes ill for the conclusion of a peace deal by
mid-September, and hints at the skepticism of both Israelis and
Palestinians about finding a way to divide the disputed territory
that is at the heart of the bargain. If they were more confident,
it is doubtful that they would have fought to a bitter draw over a
town that is far from the most intractable issue dividing them.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Dis has become important partly by accident, as each side
waits for Hafez Assad, the Syrian president. Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks were adversely affected by the revival of talks between
the Israelis and Syrians in December. Now that Israeli-Syrian talks
are suspended but still may be resuscitated, the Israelis and the
Palestinians are in something of a holding pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over Abu Dis has bought them some time. But it has
also turned Abu Dis, which was supposed to be a symbol of
compromise, into a symbol of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate also illustrates how Ehud Barak, the Israeli prime
minister, and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, are both now
reluctant to teach their people to swallow the compromises that
would be inevitable under a final peace plan. And they are both
hesitant to make concessions now that would upset their domestic
critics _ as if they expect it to get easier later, when a final
deal is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike nearby villages, Abu Dis was not annexed by Israel as it
expanded Jerusalem. As a West Bank town, it existed under full
Israeli control from 1967 to 1996, when the Palestinians gained
partial control as one of the steps toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   The 22,000 residents of Abu Dis have a Palestinian governor and
civil administration and see little evidence of an Israeli
presence. But the Israelis retain security control of the town,
which means they have the right to enter for the purpose of
preventing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In an unofficial Israeli-Palestinian plan drafted four years
ago, Abu Dis, with its hillside view of the Mount of Olives and the
Dome of the Rock, was proposed as an alternate capital of the
future Palestinian state. Together with other Palestinian towns
outside Jerusalem, it would be packaged as a kind of alternative to
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   A fancy office building under construction here is widely
believed to be a potential future home for the Palestinian
parliament-to-be. But Arafat does not publicly accept the idea of
Abu Dis as the Palestinian capital, since that would imply giving
up the fight on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   If such a compromise is on the horizon, Palestinians have not
been prepared for it by their leader, and it would come as a shock.
Even the town's residents say that no one could ever mistake Abu
Dis for the real thing _ Jerusalem _ which is called Al-Quds in
Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arafat asked that the Israelis hand over full control of
Abu Dis, and other villages, in the transfer of West Bank land that
was supposed to take place on Jan. 20. As a gesture from the
Israelis and a tangible gain to show his people, he wanted a
populated Arab town as close to disputed Jerusalem as possible. But
Barak refused, and continued to refuse even as his refusal caused a
total breakdown in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ross, the American Middle East peace envoy, was shuttling
last week between Israelis and Palestinians, trying to find a
formula to break the deadlock. Palestinian officials said on Friday
that they would tell him by Sunday where they stand.
</P>
<P>
   But if Abu Dis remains a condition, it will be difficult to end
the stalemate. Barak has made such a public point of his refusal to
concede it that it would be difficult for him to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Barak objects to turning over Abu Dis, because he does not want
to decide the fate of the greater Jerusalem area in a piecemeal
fashion, but rather to negotiate it all at once. He also does not
want to relinquish territory adjacent to Jerusalem too soon _ given
the possibility that the negotiations could disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   Barak does not talk much to the Israeli public about his
reasoning. And into this vacuum the right wing has come charging.
They are trying to equate the concession of Abu Dis with the
concession of Jerusalem itself, and to raise concerns about Barak's
rumored willingness to eventually transfer civil administration of
some Arab neighborhoods in Jerusalem to the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Barak's cabinet have urged him to reconsider
and to transfer Abu Dis or another village near Jerusalem to full
Palestinian control. Abu Dis will eventually be transferred, they
say. Why wait, they ask, if this is so important to Arafat? Some
have said Barak is humiliating the Palestinians and making it
harder for Arafat to back down, and even to accept a promise that
Abu Dis will be delivered in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian and Israeli experts believe that Arafat, with his
faith in Barak wavering, is now pushing hard to obtain whatever
land he can, especially the areas close to Jerusalem. Then, if
negotiations break down or never resume, he will declare what he
possesses to be a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Dis gained a special status in the Palestinian world when
Ahmed Qurei, now the speaker of the Palestinian legislature,
returned here from exile in 1994. It was his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   When Shimon Peres, the former Israeli prime minister, gave the
Palestinians partial control over Abu Dis two years later, some saw
it as a personal gesture to Qurei, who is known as Abu Ala. They
had both negotiated the Oslo interim peace agreement that laid the
groundwork for the final peace now being sought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
