<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCHOOL-INCIDENT-COLUM     02-26 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-INCIDENT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BOY FUMES, AND SUDDENLY, HE'S CAUGHT IN THE CRUCIBLE OF
COLUMBINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo.)  By   MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORANGETOWN, N.Y. _ The incident at Cottage Lane School began
with the private seething of a 10-year-old boy. His teacher had
kept the class inside at recess to punish students for talking, and
he was mad.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Misha Spivack, opened his ``Personal Response
Journal,'' where students record their thoughts, and described his
fifth-grade teacher with an expletive for buttocks. After the
teacher, Lawanda Lane, read it last month, she told school
officials, who arranged with Misha's parents for him to take the
next day off and then switch teachers.
</P>
<P>
   With Misha out, Lane discussed the matter with the class _ to
calm students, school officials say; to get dirt on Misha, his
parents say. After that, rumors spread that Misha had pipe bomb
recipes from the Internet and had talked of bringing a gun to
school. Worried parents called the teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a post-Columbine frenzy was under way, turning
educators into investigators and parents into defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, who did not return telephone calls, alerted the police. A
detective visited the Spivacks and found that whatever Misha might
have claimed, the family had neither a gun nor a computer, much
less Internet access. When Misha got to school that morning, he was
the talk of Cottage Lane. Then a student spotted the knife.
</P>
<P>
   It was a souvenir from a camping trip that Misha said he had
worn for some time on a key chain attached to his belt. It has a
nail file, little scissors and a 1 1-2 inch blade. The student told
a teacher. Misha was suspended pending a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't tolerate knives in school,'' said Eileen K. Gress,
superintendent of the South Orangetown Central School District.
</P>
<P>
   Worry swept this southeastern Rockland County community, where
families flock in pursuit of good schools. The principal,
superintendent and school board members all got calls. At the high
school, students asked Anton Spivack, 14, whether his little
brother had stabbed someone.
</P>
<P>
   At the disciplinary hearing, Larry Spivack acknowledged that his
son had the knife and also that he had taken Misha to school once
during his suspension _ so he could tell classmates he was not a
threat. The featured witness, a fifth grader, said Misha told him
he ``didn't like'' their teacher ``and he wanted to hurt her.'' A
transcript shows the boy testified that Misha said ``he might bring
a gun to school'' and that ``he said this school should be
Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   Spivack rested his case with a line from ``The Crucible'':
``I'll tell you what's walking Salem: vengeance is walking Salem.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Misha, whose report cards show
above-average grades, didn't deny talking tough. ``I probably did
say that,'' he said. ``But I don't think I was so specific. I
wouldn't say pipe bomb because I don't even know what a pipe bomb
is.'' He contends many classmates say things like: ``God, I think
this school sucks. I wish we could blow it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gress suspended Misha for a total of eight days. In a letter to
parents, Gress said that despite the pocketknife and ``language
which alarmed'' some people, ``there was never any harm intended to
the students, staff or the school.''
</P>
<P>
   His suspension over, Misha now rides to and from school alone in
a van, not on a school bus. An aide has been with him much of the
time. For a while, he said, he was not allowed in regular student
bathrooms. Gress said she wanted to ``provide support'' in the
transition, emphasizing that ``the incident has been hard on every
child in the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Rise Spivack did not condone her son's language, but defended
his right to an opinion, particularly in a journal he expected
would be private. Gress said school violence nationwide had
heightened the ``responsibility to be vigilant,'' but insisted that
a penknife would always trigger a serious response. ``The burden is
to not overreact,'' Gress said.
</P>
<P>
   At least on that point the Spivacks agree. The couple _ he is a
musician, she is a dancer _ moved here for clean air, open space
and good schools. But they said the commute was getting to them,
and Misha's experience was the last straw. They're moving back to
New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
