<SLUG> BC-BBO-INSIDEBASEBALL0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baylor vs. Sosa: first salvo for manager inside baseball
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Sammy Sosa finally gets on the field today.
Don't think that doesn't disappoint the new boss of the Chicago
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Don Baylor fired his first warning shot as new manager of Cubs
after Sosa postponed his arrival in Mesa, Ariz., because of a case
of flu and a sudden flight home to the Dominican Republic. The rest
of his position players have been working out for eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big deal,'' Baylor said. ``I imagine a lot of guys in
that (locker) room probably care. You don't want to put one guy
before the team. That's not going to happen. I know one thing for
sure. This team lost 95 games last year. We have to change that
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of people are watching Baylor this spring, after he left
his Atlanta hitting coach job for the resuscitation project that is
Chicago. For years, the Cubs have been seen as a fun, if not
frustrating team to play on, where Wrigley Field and rabid fans
make for a comfortable setting for yearly underachievement.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's first priority has been to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bases are still the same, pitching mound is the same, but we
have to change an attitude,'' Baylor said. ``This is not a spring
training where you take bats and balls and throw 'em out and let
'em do things.''
</P>
<P>
   Challenging Sosa straight off is an interesting choice. Baylor
had just designated the right fielder, along with reliever Rick
Aguilera, first baseman Mark Grace and right-hander Kevin Tapani,
as unofficial team captains.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has customarily been a late spring arrival and played in
all 162 games last year. But Baylor is demanding the 1998 MVP make
up the defensive drills he missed, particularly since the team will
start newcomer Damon Buford in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to stay after school,'' Baylor said. ``He
has to find time to get it all in. The defensive end, I don't care
when you report, it still goes on. He will have to do the work
eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa will also find a new set of team rules, for Baylor has
tightened up on what was allowed under former manager Jim
Riggleman. A sampling: no caps will be worn backwards; no cut-offs
or gym shorts allowed; all players will stand on the top step for
the national anthem; and no scruffy beards or unkempt goatees. No
sooner were the rules taped to the clubhouse wall than Aguilera
trimmed his trademark beard into a trim goatee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club is very visible and appearance has a lot to do with
things,'' Baylor said. ``To me, it's part of attitude. Look
professional. Look like you're a major-league player, not a rock
star.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome home, Mr. Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   THE ART OF THE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   If the New York Mets are serious about dealing left-handed
reliever Dennis Cook, Texas is already serious about acquiring him.
The Rangers are concerned lefty Scott Venafro, who has yet to throw
his spring, may have a career-threatening circulation problem in
his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has renewed talks with Anaheim for center fielder Jim
Edmonds. Angels general manager Bill Stoneman seems to willing to
listen, having just been turned down by Colorado when he offered
Edmonds for a starting pitcher. The Mariners are willing to deal
newcomer Brett Tomko or left-hander John Halama.
</P>
<P>
   CALL IT A CAREER
</P>
<P>
   New Cardinals reliever Scott Radinsky, bouncing back from elbow
surgery, realizes his second career as guitarist in his alternative
rock band Pulley may be drawing to an end. He is 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can jump around and scream at 15-year-old girls only so
long,'' Radinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   WRY, FUNNY VALENTINE
</P>
<P>
   If the New York Mets' October run diminished the pressure on
manager Bobby Valentine, someone forgot to tell Fred Wilpon. The
club's CEO says he has no intention of negotiating a new contract
for Valentine until season's end, when his current deal expires.
This is the team's response to Valentine's 273 wins since 1997 and
the club's finishing two games short of the 1999 World Series?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have the answer for why he said that?'' Valentine
asked. ``If I thought about it, and didn't have the answer, then I
guess I'd scratch my head. If I got an answer, I wouldn't scratch
my head.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, worried about Todd Hundley's stalled career (.207,
major-league 16 errors for catchers last season), quietly
negotiated a $500,000 buyout of his option for 2001, which could
make him a free agent after this season.... San Francisco's options
at second base for the injured Jeff Kent (strained rib muscle) are
reserve Ramon Martinez, Wilson Delgado (a natural shortstop),
prospect Jay Martinez, Toronto reject Felipe Crespo, or moving Bill
Mueller from third base. The downside: no one knows how long Kent
will be out.... Cincinnati's relaxing of its player jewelry rule
doesn't do much for catcher Eddie Taubensee. ``I'm not going to
wear one, even though my wife has some nice ones in her jewelry
box,'' he said. ``It would be hard for pitchers to take a catcher
seriously when he is wearing an earring.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia took another step toward moving left fielder Ron
Gant when the club decided to let rookie Pat Burrell, the No. 1
overall pick of the 1998 draft, start in Gant's position all
spring. ``I've been traded before,'' said Gant, whom the club tried
to move over the winter. ``I know what it's like. I know baseball
is a business and sometimes teams go on youth movements. So, if
they trade me, I understand the situation. But it would be their
loss.''... The new bidder for the Kansas City Royals is an
Atlantan: Facundo Bacardi, the wine and rum heir, is the third
party to show interest in the club, promising to keep the Royals in
Kansas City. Born in Chicago, raised in Florida, Bacardi had never
visited Kauffman Stadium until last week.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked Boston's Jimy Williams if he had caught
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra's guest appearance on ``Two Guys and a
Girl,'' the manager said he missed it and asked, ``He played the
guy, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
