<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-JOSPIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST BANK STUDENTS THROW STONES AT FRENCH LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Angry Palestinian students pitched stones at French
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin on Saturday and pummeled his car with
rocks as he was ending a visit with Palestinian intellectuals at
the leading university in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The students at Bir Zeit University outside Ramallah were
protesting remarks that Jospin made last week during a visit to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin had condemned as ``terrorist acts'' the attacks by
Hezbollah _ or Party of God _ guerrillas on Israeli soldiers in an
Israeli-occupied zone in southern Lebanon. His remarks immediately
raised a fury in the Arab world. On Saturday the Syrian government
summoned France's ambassador to protest the remarks and to clarify
Jospin's position, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must protest because Hezbollah is a resistance movement,
not a terrorist movement,'' said Ziad, a demonstrator who would not
give his last name. ``It's not only a Lebanese matter. It's an Arab
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The violence greatly embarrassed the academic leaders of Bir
Zeit, whose new law school was financed by the French government.
And it angered Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, who was
playing host to Jospin and had lent the French leader his silver
Mercedes, which was dented by the stones.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin was struck by at least one stone and received a small
scratch on the head, despite the Palestinian security officials,
who formed a human shield and held a plastic bullet guard above his
head. After the incident, Jospin continued to Gaza as planned and
dismissed the demonstrators as a small, unruly group.
</P>
<P>
   But Palestinians saw the attack as an outburst of frustration.
Students at Bir Zeit, expressing a deep-seated feeling in their
communities, said they believed that the peace effort was going
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   After apologizing to Jospin, the university announced that it
was shutting down for three days. Palestinian police arrested at
least 15 students who had participated in the melee, and senior
Palestinian security officials opened an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   When Jospin arrived, students began yelling in French, ``Barak
terrorist, Jospin accomplice.'' Ehud Barak is the prime minister of
Israel, who has been severely criticized in the Arab world for
bombing Lebanese power stations in response to attacks by Hezbollah
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The protests escalated, and Jospin was harangued throughout his
visit, despite his attempts to proclaim France a friend of Lebanon
and a critic of the Israeli zone.
</P>
<P>
   As he was leaving, the demonstrators threw leaflets, then small
stones, then larger ones. Stones also flew at Nabil Shaath, a
senior Palestinian official who accompanied Jospin. The students
followed their car, kicking it and pelting it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
