A9478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-CHUCKSMITH0227-CO     02-26 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHUCKSMITH0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran Falcons ends let go easily
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_ One of the basic laws of physics says that for every
action there is an equal and opposite reaction.
</P>
<P>
   For the Falcons, it means that for Ashley Ambrose and Shawn
Jefferson there are Chuck Smith and Lester Archambeau.
</P>
<P>
   The two longtime Atlanta defensive ends became unrestricted free
agents on Feb. 11. Now, Smith's a Panther and Archambeau's a
Bronco.
</P>
<P>
   For all the energy the Falcons used in pursuing Ambrose and
Jefferson, they expended virtually none in pursuit of Smith, 30, or
Archambeau, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Smith declined interview requests for this article, but he said
last week on WQXI-AM, ``(The Falcons) never tried.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Harold Richardson began trying last summer to
extend the contracts of Archambeau, center Robbie Tobeck, wide
receiver Terance Mathis and fullback Bob Christian, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis and Christian worked out extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with Archambeau ended in October, shortly after the
player's age became an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The team had a few brief conversations with Smith's agent but no
contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   Why? ``Because they would never give us a figure of what they
were looking at,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``You had to expect they
were thinking a huge number.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith might have considered himself worthy of a $9 million
signing bonus like the Colts gave defensive end Chad Bratzke a year
ago, or the five-year, $30 million contract and $6 million signing
bonus Chidi Ahonotu got with Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Harold, `Here's where (the bidding) is going to be. Are
you going to be in the ball game?''' Smith's agent, Jimmy Sexton,
said. ``He said, `Let me think about it. I don't think so.'''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing precluded the Falcons from making an offer to Smith
if they were interested in having back the second-leading sacker in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   There was a chance to do a deal. After defensive tackle Travis
Hall signed a seven-year, $51.5 million extension the day before
the season opener, the agents for Smith and Archambeau called
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Hall had three years left; Archambeau and Smith one each. So,
why extend Hall first?
</P>
<P>
   Richardson told Sexton that he would give the same deal, which
included a $5.1 million signing bonus, to Smith that very day.
</P>
<P>
   As the free agency approached, re-signing Smith was not as big a
priority as signing Ambrose, or probably Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our only chance would have been if the market came back to a
range we were talking about,'' Reeves said. ``But if we waited, we
might not have been able to sign Ashley and Shawn.
</P>
<P>
   Even after signing Ambrose and Jefferson on Feb. 12, the Falcons
had enough cap room to match the Carolina offer that Smith's agent
called in to Richardson on Feb. 16. The Falcons declined to match.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 18, they agreed to a four-year, $10 million contract
with Saints free-agent defensive end Brady Smith, 26, who got a
$2.5 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last week, Archambeau signed a seven-year, $17.5 million
contract with Denver, including a $2.5 million signing bonus. The
last offer made by the Falcons in October was better.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that Archambeau's stats dropped this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, age can work against you,'' Archambeau's agent,
Alan Herman, said. ``I don't think you can look back with regret.
And I don't feel any hostility.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith might.
</P>
<P>
   ``As... we started putting the deal together, he started looking
at things that were important beyond money,'' Sexton said. ``I
think, in the end, the fact he'll get to play against Atlanta twice
a year was important.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
