u i BC-RUSSIA-JOURNALIST-NYT     02-26 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JOURNALIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNALIST ATTACKS RUSSIA AFTER BEING REARRESTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Radio Liberty journalist Andrei Babitsky,
rearrested Friday after surfacing from more than a month's
detention in Chechnya, has told his colleagues at the American
radio network that Russian officials violated the agreement under
which he voluntarily agreed to be exchanged for Russian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he was coerced into the roadside swap Feb. 2 under
protest, a colleague said Saturday. Babitsky, a Russian national
whose radio reports on civilian suffering and military brutality in
the war in Chechnya inflamed the Russian authorities, has been
detained since Jan. 16 in a case that has drawn international
attention over the manner in which Russian security services seized
a war correspondent and traded him into captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky surfaced Friday in Makhachkala, the capital of
Dagestan, which adjoins Chechnya, and was arrested on a charge of
carrying a false passport, a charge that is sure to further
complicate the legal proceedings against him.
</P>
<P>
   While Babitsky was in detention, one of his colleagues at Radio
Liberty, Oleg Kusov, was able to debrief him over several hours.
Kusov said Saturday that Babitsky was coerced into the exchange
after Russian officials reneged on their pledge to carry it out in
a manner that would place Babitsky in the hands of a Chechen field
commander, Turpal Ali Atgeriev, who was known to Babitsky.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television on Saturday night broadcast part of the
police interrogation of Babitsky, in which he said he had been
promised that Atgeriev ``guaranteed my freedom after the
exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Babitsky was escorted to the place where the exchange
was to take place, the masked man who approached from the Chechen
side was clearly not Atgeriev, and Babitsky tried to call off the
exchange. ``He refused to be exchanged, as he told me,'' Kusov
said, ``but his words could not change anything, and the man in the
mask rudely took him by his arm and took him to the car.''
</P>
<P>
   The swap engineered by Russia's Federal Security Service was
described by Russian officials as ``voluntary.'' Babitsky's account
will probably further enrage Russian journalists, many of whom have
taken up his cause because they see their own fate threatened by
the pre-emptory and authoritarian manner in which a journalist
unpopular with the Kremlin has been singled out for harsh
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   After being held in a ``dark room'' in an unidentified Chechen
village for several weeks, Babitsky is apparently in good health,
his colleague said. ``He was locked in a small room,'' Kusov said.
``Food was scarce and he had no chance to get any information. He
did not know these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky apparently was traveling with a false Azerbaijani
passport, bearing his photograph but the name of Ali Musayev. He
used the passport to register at the hotel in Makhachkala after
being delivered to the Dagestani capital by masked men who then
released him there. Kusov said Saturday that Babitsky ``knew he had
this passport on him; there was his picture in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The police in Dagestan, a Russian republic, are awaiting
instructions from Moscow on the matter. Asked during his police
interrogation why he was carrying the false passport, Babitsky
replied, ``I had no other document'' and ``I was afraid to disclose
my whereabouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio Liberty officials said they would travel to Dagestan on
Monday seeking Babitsky's release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
