<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-U.S.-MARATHON-NYT     02-26 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-U.S.-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG SHOT WINS PLACE ON U.S. OLYMPIC TEAM
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ She moved from the anonymity of the pack into
sudden contention in Saturday's Olympic marathon trials, surging
into third place, second, then first after 20 miles, and finally,
all the runners with faster qualifying times and bigger reputations
were behind her. At that moment no one was more surprised to be
ahead than the leader herself, Dr. Christine Clark.
</P>
<P>
   There could not have been a more unlikely victor. Clark, who is
37, finished 76th at the 1996 Olympic trials on the same course. A
pathologist and mother of two, she runs only 70 miles a week, 30 or
40 fewer than the average. And she does two-thirds of her training
on a treadmill in the winter, considering that her home is
Anchorage, and no one has yet discovered a way to put snow chains
on running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature rose above 80 degrees on the rolling 26.2-mile
course, which might have melted a runner not conditioned to such
wilting heat. Instead, Clark shaved more than seven minutes off her
previous best time to win the trials in 2 hours 33 minutes 31
seconds. Because that was a half-minute slower than the Olympic
``A'' qualifying standard, only Clark will represent the American
women at the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in my wildest dreams did I think that I'd be here,''
said Clark, who had only the 22nd fastest qualifying time. ``I
think this gives a lot of women hope that they can be in their 30s
and have a career and kids and do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to Kristy Johnston of Shepherdstown, W.Va.,
one of the favorites, in 2:35:36. She had qualified for Saturday's
race in 2:32:34, under the Olympic standard, but the U.S. track and
field federation decided last December that only runners who won
the trials or finished under 2:33 Saturday would be eligible for
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston called the process unfair, but Craig Masback, the chief
executive officer of USA Track and Field, said that the most
equitable system was to let the athletes decide the Olympic team in
the same race, on the same course, under the same conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing third was Anne Marie Lauck (2:36:05) of Hampton, N.J.,
who made a gutsy move near Mile 4, looking over her shoulder,
finding that no one wanted to work with her and just taking off.
Lauck apparently made her move with the 2:33 requirement in mind.
She reached the halfway mark in 1:15:28 with a 33-second lead over
Kim Pawelek and a 60-second advantage over a pack of runners that
included Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so tough, I thought she was gone for the duration,''
Clark said of Lauck, who finished 10th at the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   But she was not gone. Lauck runs with the pounding stride of a
track runner, and her legs seemed to grow heavy as she put in three
consecutive miles at a pace above six minutes. Pawelek began to
have trouble with her feet in the heat and faded to seventh in
2:39:16. Clark caught her just after Mile 16 and pulled even with
Lauck at Mile 20. Then Clark tossed in a 5:42 mile on a downhill
portion and was alone in front. She kept the lead on a series of
hills and ended any suspense by running Mile 23 in 5:39.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to run my race, keep a steady pace,'' Clark said.
``I don't have tremendous leg speed. I can't run one mile at 5:10,
so where am I going to get a surge? People kept coming back to me.
It so far surpassed my expectations, it's a little hard to
describe. I wanted to make the top 20. If I had a great day I
thought I could make the top 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauck was so drained that she collapsed at the finish line. Joan
Benoit Samuelson, the 1984 Olympic champion, finished ninth in
2:39:59. But Clark maintained her long, fluid stride throughout the
race and won by more than two minutes. Of eight or nine marathons
that she has run, this was her first significant victory. She was a
high school cross-country champion in Billings, Mont., but ran
sporadically from 1983 through 1993, while she completed medical
school and her residency.
</P>
<P>
   She works 25 to 30 hours a week at Providence Medical Center in
Anchorage, where her husband, John, is a pulmonary physician in the
intensive care unit. On days that she works, Clark arises at 6 a.m.
to train on her treadmill with tempo runs of five or six miles at a
5:30 pace, or with a 15-mile run at a 5:50 pace. Time for running
must be slotted between time for her patients and her sons,
Matthew, 9, and Danny 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply don't have any more time to do more miles,'' Clark
said. ``I don't see the purpose of that for myself. Less is more.''
</P>
<P>
   She has always dreamed of the Olympics, but it always seemed a
distant dream. Now that it has come true, Clark said the feeling
was unfathomable. She is not expected to contend for a medal in
Sydney. Her time Saturday was 13 minutes, or more than two miles,
off the world record. Then again, Clark has shaved 11 minutes from
her personal best in her last two marathons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have more minutes to shave off,'' she said. ``I
don't think I've reached my peak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
