<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-SPY-NYT     02-26 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-SPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDER TO LEAVE U.S.  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Fla, Md., Cuba, Switzerland)  DEFIANT, CUBAN DIPLOMAT DEFIES By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Cuban diplomat ordered expelled last week by
the United States on spying charges gave up his diplomatic immunity
Saturday and challenged U.S. officials to arrest him so that he
could prove his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat, Jose Imperatori, said through his lawyer that he
would not leave the United States by Saturday afternoon, the
deadline he had been given. His lawyer, Kurt L. Schmoke, a former
mayor of Baltimore, said he would begin a hunger strike ``in order
to clear his name.''
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori was identified by the Cuban interests section, which
represents the Cuban government in the United States, as the
diplomat who was identified as having been in contact with the U.S.
immigration official who was charged last week with spying.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has insisted that Imperatori did nothing wrong and met with
the official on routine business.
</P>
<P>
   Schmoke said at Imperatori's apartment that American authorities
had told him Imperatori would be taken into custody and flown out
of the country Saturday night. He added that Imperatori would not
resist and would cooperate with any investigation, and that even if
he were deported, he would be willing to return to the United
States to testify in the spy case. The State Department did not
respond immediately to requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary confrontation, breaking the normal standards
of diplomatic conduct and forgoing the routine tit-for-tat
expulsions that are the norm when diplomats are entangled in
charges of espionage, comes at a time when the United States and
Cuba are also embroiled in a dispute over whether to return a Cuban
boy to his father in Cuba or allow him to stay with relatives in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Cuban interests section, Fernando Remirez de
Estenoz, said at a news conference at the diplomatic mission here
Saturday that the arrest of the American immigration official and
the move to expel Imperatori were connected to the custody battle
over the boy, Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest and expulsion order, Remirez said, took place just
days before a court case concerning the boy, although the United
States contends that the charges involving Imperatori and the
American official ``went on for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The immigration agent, Mariano M. Faget, is a senior official in
the Miami office of the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
Remirez said that the accusations made against both Imperatori and
Faget were false.
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori said in a letter to the head of the mission:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Comrade Remirez,
</P>
<P>
   ``I am addressing you to submit my resignation, as of this
moment, to my position and functions in our beloved interests
section and to the prerogatives therein. I have decided to stay in
America, assuming all the necessary risks and consequences, to
struggle against the slanders that hurt my honor, and that of the
interests section in Washington and my own homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement read by Felix Wilson Hernandez, the deputy chief
of the diplomatic mission, Imperatori said: ``I have become the
victim of a major slander. I have been wrongly accused of doing
intelligence work in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that one factor compelling him to waive his diplomatic
immunity and stay in the United States was his wish to disprove the
accusations against Faget.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government had issued an expulsion order for Imperatori
last Saturday, giving him until 1:30 p.m. this Saturday to leave
the country or face arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Although he could have avoided arrest by staying inside the
interest section, an embassy in all but name that operates under
the auspices of the Swiss Embassy in Washington, he chose instead
to spend the day at his apartment in suburban Bethesda, Md., where
it would be easy to arrest him. Schmoke pointedly gave out the
street address and apartment number at a televised news conference
Saturday .
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori was first accused of espionage after the FBI arrested
Faget and charged him with espionage on Feb. 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-REPUBS-ART-NYT &LR;      02-26 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REPUBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE'S REPUBLICAN PARTY CHAIRMAN IS CALM IN THE
CROSSFIRE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It is not insignificant that William D. Powers,
the feared and powerful chairman of the New York state Republican
Party, was one of only 87 marines stationed in Cuba on the day the
Cuban missile crisis broke out. And although reinforcements arrived
within hours, Powers said, he spent much of the next few days in a
foxhole awaiting nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty good odds, though,'' said Powers, 58, in his coolest
hey-no-problem voice. ``Eighty-seven marines can create a lot of
havoc.''
</P>
<P>
   Which immediately brings him to the present task: facing down
the New York presidential primary, a potential humiliation for a
state Republican Party that embraced Gov. George W. Bush and then
fought, to ridicule and ultimate failure, to keep the surging Sen.
John McCain off the ballot. Now, with less than two weeks to go
before the March 7 vote, Powers, along with Gov. George Pataki, is
under enormous pressure to deliver the state for Bush _ not only to
avoid the embarrassment of defeat, but also to help ensure that
there is a Bush administration so that New York Republicans can
count on appointments and influence in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Powers has to keep up the pressure on his
stubborn U.S. Senate candidate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, to campaign
more upstate. On his flank he is deflecting sniper fire from an
ambitious party guerrilla, Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island, who
continues to insist to disbelief that he may challenge Giuliani in
a Republican primary. Powers is also trying to hold down the
fighting on another front within his own party, notably between
Pataki and the state Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, who,
when asked how he was getting along with Governor Pataki,
responded, ``Governor who?''
</P>
<P>
   Not least, there is the tension between Giuliani and Pataki,
plus the complications of Powers' own relationship with each man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks I have problems,'' Powers said one afternoon
last week in his Albany foxhole, a historic four-story brownstone
near the Capitol that serves as the state party headquarters. ``I
really don't have any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask him.
</P>
<P>
   On Bush's appearance at Bob Jones University, for example, and
whether its Christian conservatism and anti-Catholic leanings will
alienate the large numbers of Catholics in New York, Powers was
sanguine. ``I would suppose from a PR point of view that maybe it
wasn't the best thing,'' he said. But, ``I know George W. Bush, I
spent quite of bit of time with him. I don't believe that there's
any bias, I think he's a good man, and I don't believe that voters
are going to hold that against him.''
</P>
<P>
   On his fight to keep McCain off the ballot, which critics
compared to Soviet politics, Powers was without remorse. ``He came
into New York, didn't go through the petition process, got people,
and sued us,'' Powers said. ``So I'm on the defensive the minute he
walks in. So which cheek do you want me to kiss him on? The party
is being attacked. What am I going to do? Lay down, or roll over?''
</P>
<P>
   On Giuliani's campaign, and the anxieties of Republican county
chairmen that the mayor has been AWOL upstate, Powers was relaxed.
``We've not had a problem moving him around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And on his own relationship with Giuliani, the man who in 1994
endorsed Powers' arch-enemy, Gov. Mario Cuomo, a Democrat, Powers
was straightforward. ``You and I can pick something to fight about
all day. We're going to get tired of doing that,'' he said, adding,
``So you're better off putting that behind and saying, `We don't
agree, we didn't agree, and we didn't do very well on that.' And
that's kind of, maybe, how Rudy and I get along.''
</P>
<P>
   During the ballot fight, Powers was largely invisible, but in
the last week has begun to endure interviews in the interest of
promoting the idea that the state Republican Party is not imploding
and that his political organization can handle the challenge of
McCain. ``I don't like to do this stuff,'' Powers said, noting that
in the old days he was so desirous of press attention that he once
held a news conference accusing Cuomo of stealing his car. But
after the party defeated Cuomo, Powers said, ``I didn't think that
was my job anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Today his main job is to make sure that his 62 county chairmen
line up enough bodies to get out the Republican vote, work the
phone banks and blanket the state with leaflets. ``You want to win,
or you want to lose?'' Powers said. ``There's no second place in
our business.''
</P>
<P>
   His supporters say that nobody is better at winning than Powers,
a former aide to Sen. Alfonse D'Amato who took over the state party
after it had been left for dead in the 1990 election, when the
Republican candidate for governor, Pierre Rinfret, finished a far
second to Cuomo and left the party more than $2 million in debt.
Rep. John Sweeney, a Republican from Albany, remembers that on the
day in 1991 that Powers assumed his duties, among the well-wishers
at the hotel ceremony was a man with a subpoena, who very
unceremoniously thrust it into Powers' hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party was so in debt, the creditors were beginning to
seize property,'' Sweeney said. ``It was a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next decade, Powers and his patron, D'Amato, built the
party from the ground up as they assembled one of the most
prodigious political fund-raising machines in the country. Powers
began to be compared to an old-style Tammany Hall political boss
and played a big role in promoting the gubernatorial candidacy of
an obscure former mayor of Peekskill, Pataki, who upon election in
1994 became Powers' biggest success story. Of course, Powers lost
races, too, including the 1998 re-election campaign of D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   And now, should McCain win?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about that,'' Powers insisted. ``That's
negative. I think about what I have to do to win.'' For years, he
said, he kept a picture of Cuomo in his office. ``And everybody
thought I was crazy,'' Powers said. ``Hung right there.'' And they
said, ```How in the world can you have a picture of Mario Cuomo up
there?' I said, `Because I think about what it takes to beat him
all the time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Powers said he had not yet festooned his mantle with a picture
of the first lady.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NEWFAMILY0227-COX     02-26 1810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWFAMILY0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changing families, wavering political loyalties
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROTWOOD, Ohio _ Traditional politics is losing its hold on
American families.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Melson family of Trotwood.
</P>
<P>
   Sam, 51, is a Democrat, his wife, Connie Lucas-Melson, 48, a
Republican. They have a blended family, with nine children ranging
in age from 15 to 31 and in politics from Democrat to Republican to
those who don't know what they are.
</P>
<P>
   Sam has three kids from past relationships. Connie's first
marriage produced four children _ two from childbirth, one by
adoption and one is a foster son. The couple, who married in 1996,
is now raising two teen-age foster sons. But when they talk about
any of their children, they only use the words son or daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't the typical family in terms of what society portrays
as family, but we promote love, education and self respect, things
that too many families are missing,'' Lucas-Melson said.
</P>
<P>
   America is full of families like the Melsons. Families are less
traditional and less predictable politically. No longer can
Democrats assume if you're a minority you're a Democrat. Soccer
moms, the great symbol of the last presidential election, are part
of the expanding middle that determines who wins and who loses.
Fewer young people look to mom and dad when deciding how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this new politics it doesn't matter where you come from or
what you were before, it's what you want to get now,'' Lucas-Melson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Political loyalties still have a hold on many families.
Fifty-six percent of Miami Valley residents said they are
registered in the same political party as their parents, according
to a Dayton Daily News poll. But, nearly a third _ 29 percent _
said they were not, and 15 percent said they didn't know or didn't
answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American family is really changing in fairly dramatic
ways,'' said John Green, a political scientist at the University of
Akron. ``People are marrying late. A lot of people don't get
married. People are living longer. Divorce is very high. I'm not
sure we quite understand where it's heading.''
</P>
<P>
   This much seems certain: Changing family dynamics present
difficult _ and expensive _ challenges for political parties and
their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just run candidates out there and say `vote for them
because he or she is a Democrat,' it doesn't work that way
anymore,'' said Dennis Lieberman, chairman of the Montgomery County
Democratic party. ``Families and their children are constantly
changing, as parties we have to prove ourselves in every election.
You can't dictate or rule by fear anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Melson is one of those Democrats who doesn't like being taken
for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hollywood would find it difficult creating a black American
Democrat that could match Melson's life.
</P>
<P>
   He picked cotton with his grandma on a Georgia plantation.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, he was plucked from rioting streets by a
well-known Dayton civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   A Vietnam soldier thrust into combat, he hated the war and the
Republican president who wouldn't send him home.
</P>
<P>
   A former union boss and prison counselor, Melson has never voted
for a Republican presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If Vice President Al Gore or any other Democrat could take for
granted at least one vote in November, you would expect it to come
from Melson.
</P>
<P>
   But traditional politics now mean little to Melson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've become more radical in my voting over the last few years.
I just don't give my vote to the Democrats any more because they
are on the ticket or because I'm black,'' Melson said. ``Hell, I
might even vote for McCain. In my eyes I don't see a whole a lot of
difference between the Democrats and Republicans anymore. But I
promise you that I'm gonna make them work for my vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News poll, conducted from January 5-9, underscored
some of the challenges facing both political parties in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how interested they'd be in politics if there wasn't
a political system with two dominant parties, 84 percent said
they'd be just as interested or more interested, the poll found.
Only 13 percent said they would be less interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Republican and I will always have some sense of loyalty
toward the party,'' said Mike Kitchen, a 38-year-old father of
three who participated in the Daily News poll. ``But like most
people, a big part of my vote is based on the issues that affect me
and my family. For me, it's tax relief, education and family
values. Whoever rates best in those areas gets my vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The Melsons are not the Waltons or even the Cosby family.
</P>
<P>
   When Connie Lucas-Melson was raised in West Dayton in the early
1960s, her politics were already decided _ or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother preached that blacks and working people supported
Democrats. Republicans were only rich and white.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking changed for Connie as a 12-year-old school girl
when she played the role of a Republican as part of a civics
project. Her seventh-grade teacher took her class to a downtown
campaign rally held by Democrat Lyndon B. Johnson, who was
supported by the local black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I decided right then to become a
Republican. I thought if the Republicans are so bad, then they need
more black people in the party to make a change,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to support the ``white party'' wasn't popular with
her black friends as a teen-ager. They questioned her loyalty to
Dr. Martin Luther King and the on-going civil rights movement. They
challenged her to stay black. She challenged them to think for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always wanted me to separate my blackness from my
politics and I won't do that for anybody,'' said Lucas-Melson,
whose living room resembles a memorial to Dr. King, Malcolm X and
her African-American heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas-Melson's political ambitions in the Republican party have
moved far beyond her seventh-grade civics project. In the mid-1970s
she helped recruit blacks to the Montgomery County Republican Party
as a member of the Young Republican West group and helped run
campaigns for black candidates. In the 1980s she was the 2nd vice
president of the Ohio Republican council. And most recently she
served eight years as the 2nd vice president on the Montgomery
County Republican Party's executive board.
</P>
<P>
   But Lucas-Melson's political involvement has now taken a back
seat to her marriage and her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love politics, but it's a lot tougher for families to stay
involved with everything else going on in your life,'' she said.
Still, in a time when 30 million people are glued to a single game
show and worrying about how many lifelines someone has left, the
Melsons find time to talk and debate politics.
</P>
<P>
   They talk about education, Clinton, gun control, and other
issues, but the conversation often centers on racism and why the
world still seems so black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Melson doesn't understand why a baseball player would
publicly degrade blacks, gays, and just about anyone who isn't a
white male. Why the Ku Klux Klan gets so much attention from the
media. Or how in the late 1990s three guys in Texas could tie a
black man to a pick-up truck and drag him to his death.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Melson was recruited by C.J. McLin Jr., a
legendary Ohio politician from Dayton, to lead a local youth patrol
that would help prevent street riots during the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Melson said McLin and Art Thomas, his other mentor, a Dayton
civil rights leader in the 1960s who went on to become president of
Central State University, bombarded him with messages of unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope 30 years ago was that all the hating would stop.
Politics hasn't helped bring people together because everyone has
to be labeled something like white conservative, black liberal and
so on,'' Melson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there's the young people who are oblivious to what's
going on in the world. We had the war, the civil rights movement,
Watergate and all that stuff that had the country wrapped for
politics. What do today's kids care about?''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Sam and Connie's sons have the answer to their dad's
question.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mitchell and Lukinte Lucas admit that their world revolves
around their careers, bodies, bigger bank accounts or a new car.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, 27, is a graduate of the prestigious Pennsylvania
University Wharton School of Business with a degree in economics
and already has an annual income of $67,000. He works as an account
executive for an advertising and printing company in Evansville,
Ind., and spends several weeks a year traveling around the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell uses the Internet every day to keep track of
technology, business and Wall Street, but politics isn't part of
his daily browsing. He drives an SUV, but says his next car will be
a Cadillac. When he's not on-line or working, he can be found in
the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the economy doing well? Yes it is, and I'm doing well, so
that's pretty much what I need to know about politics right now,''
Mitchell Lucas said. ``That's the main reason I don't want to go
back to school or even think about having children right now,
because there's a lot of money to be made in this economy. The bulk
of my time is spent on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is a registered Republican, but admits that he voted
for President Clinton because of the thriving economy. He plans to
vote in November and the candidate promising the biggest tax cuts
will likely get his vote.
</P>
<P>
   While money and career are driving his current life, Mitchell
believes politics and marriage will eventually become higher
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to come back home some day and become mayor of
Dayton,'' he said. ``My mom was so into politics when we were
growing up, but my brothers and I never really talked about it. I
couldn't even tell you if they are Democrats or Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's brother Lukinte isn't sure whether he's a registered
Independent, Democrat or Republican, but it really doesn't matter
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always vote, you have too, that's something I learned
from my mom, but nothing about politics seems real,'' Lukinte said.
</P>
<P>
   Lukinte, 22, lives in Atlanta and spends most of his time trying
to launch a music career. He is a Rap and R&AMP;B performer and also
owns a small company that promotes concerts in Atlanta-area clubs.
When he's not rapping, he's listening to rappers like DMX and JZ.
</P>
<P>
   He watches the news and believes Gore will take on Texas Gov.
George W. Bush for the presidency in November. But he has never
heard of John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're trying to take care of your own life,'' he said,
``it's hard to keep up with everything going on in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
