<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9489 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-OLDFAMILY0227-COX     02-26 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDFAMILY0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Different generations, different politics
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEBANON, Ohio _ He was born during World War I, walks with steel
knees and survived open heart surgery with six bypasses. Kitchen
towels wrapped around his boots keep him from slipping as he walks
a visitor up a snow-covered hill on his 215-acre farm, proudly
pointing out the creek that runs through the property, the
farmhouse built before the Civil War and the gazebo constructed
with family labor.
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching the top of the hill, William Henry Otto
Baudendistel pledges his allegiance to God, family, farming and
Republicans _ not necessarily in that order. In between breaths he
grumbles about the ``good men'' disappearing from politics.
Coolidge, Ike, Reagan, Bush _ these were presidents that embodied
character, he says.
</P>
<P>
   And then the visitor leaks the family secret: His son Tom and
his grandson Tommy voted for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They voted for who? That ... Clinton? My God, I thought I
taught them better than that,'' he says with no trace of a grin.
</P>
<P>
   The Baudendistels, like many American families, pass on their
homes, recipes and heirlooms from generation to generation, but not
their politics.
</P>
<P>
   Children aren't looking toward mom and dad anymore to tell them
how to vote. And in some families, children don't even tell mom and
dad how they vote. Families are more diverse, more politically
independent, more complex.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of the family have become the politics of America.
</P>
<P>
   The Baudendistels are a family drenched in tradition and
history. They are farmers, Catholics and craftsmen. Their holiday
reunions resemble a small town festival.
</P>
<P>
   But their political views don't match their personal bonds.
</P>
<P>
   William and his wife Margaret are hard-line conservatives. Tom
and his wife Sandy are Democrats, but don't consider themselves
liberals. Tommy and wife Lyn are Republicans, but consider
themselves moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have dirt in our blood from my grandfather, but we didn't
get his politics,'' Tommy said. ``I respect my father and
grandfather, but I decided to support a candidate or party based on
my own life and beliefs, not theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   TRADITION, HISTORY AND FAMILY VALUES
</P>
<P>
   William Baudendistel, 85, says he was Republican, before he
really knew what it meant to be a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid you didn't wait around for hand-outs from the
government or anyone else, you got your butt out there and hunted
for work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Depression was pummeling his family's income and
William wasn't earning any money sitting in a school house. So he
quit school at the age of 14 and got his big break a few years
later when a roofing company agreed to pay him 30 cents a day to
make shingles.
</P>
<P>
   He married his sweetheart Margaret and went to work on a dairy
farm.
</P>
<P>
   But to get his own farm William borrowed $13,000 in 1946 _
$10,000 from his father-in-law, $2,000 from his sister-in-law and
$1,000 from the guy who bought his milk. The $13,000 included 126
acres and a farm house. They later added 90 more acres for
$120,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put everything we had and everything we didn't have into
the farm and this old house,'' said Margaret, 82. ``We raised it
all here. Seven kids, hundreds of cows, corn, wheat and more
memories than my walls can keep track of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baudendistels, who have been married 63 years, estimate the
farm's value at about $10 million, but have never considered
putting up a 'For Sale' sign. William stopped milking cows a few
years ago and now rents portions of the farm for other families to
work.
</P>
<P>
   William and Margaret spend much of their time keeping up with 17
grandchildren and 11 great grandchildren. Traditional Catholic
family values mean everything to the couple. ``A lot of these
politicians come at you with this idea or this plan, but that stuff
means nothing if his character smells like the cow pasture,''
William said. ``I learned my lesson on Democrats with (John F.)
Kennedy. I really liked him and then he started all that womanizing
and carrying on.''
</P>
<P>
   William is supporting George W. Bush over John McCain because he
sees him as a true conservative. He likes McCain's military record
but doesn't like his one-time reputation as a playboy. He likes
Bush's dedication to cutting taxes and government spending, and
thinks he mirrors his father's commitment to family values.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to think anymore. The country votes out
George Bush, a great man of character devoted to his family, after
one term, and then we keep the disgrace we have in the White House
now for eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   FROM REPUBLICAN NEST TO KENNEDY
</P>
<P>
   Once he graduated from high school and left the family farm, it
didn't take Tom Baudendistel long to become what his father didn't
like. Tom traded his farm chores for a union card and went to work
at the General Motors Corp. factory on Home Avenue in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of United Rubber Workers Local 817, which has
since been molded into the United Steel Workers of America. Tom
worked in the plant for 14 years before his dad finally set foot in
the factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad didn't want to know much about the plant or what I did, he
hates unions and I was a union guy,'' said Tom, who retired from
GM's Delphi Chassis plant after 30 years. ``I think my dad, like a
lot of people, resented how much GM was paying us back then. It was
a lot more than he could pay people to work on the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom was also a Democrat. As a teen he was captured by the glow
of President John F. Kennedy and vividly remembers Kennedy's 1961
inaugural speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asking what I could do for my country after I heard that
speech,'' he said. ``The country believed in him and that both
(inspired) and scared a lot of people. For me it was like a member
of my family died the day he got shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom, now 56, has been married to his high school sweetheart,
Sandy, for 35 years. They have two grown sons, Tommy and David.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy, 55, also worked full-time most of her life and together
with Tom helped put their sons through college. Then, in 1993, a
week before Tommy and Lyn's wedding, Sandy learned she had breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Except for her husband, she didn't tell family members about her
illness until after her son's honeymoon. She used radiation
treatment to eventually beat the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics don't mean a whole lot during a time like that,'' Tom
said.
</P>
<P>
   The scare not only shook the family but changed the family's
political priorities, putting health care issues on the front
burner.
</P>
<P>
   Lifelong Democrats, Tom and Sandy now say they are undecided on
their choices for president, and Tom says he may even vote for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that will get me back in my dad's will,'' Tom said with
a smile.
</P>
<P>
   CONCENTRATION ON ISSUES, NOT POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Baudendistel didn't inherit his dad's blue collar.
</P>
<P>
   He was the preppy fraternity brother at the University of Dayton
who earned both a bachelor's and master's degree in mechanical
engineering and is working on his Ph.D. He helped local Republicans
put up yard signs for their campaigns, loved Ronald Reagan and
enjoys debating politics with his Republican friends.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, he now earns over $60,000 a year working as a design
engineer for Delphi Automotive's chassis division in Dayton. He has
become a moderate Republican and is hoping McCain becomes the next
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad and I are very different people, we vote don't vote the
same way and believe in different things, but so what? We still
love and respect each other,'' Tommy said. ``My grandfather grew up
during the Depression, my dad was a teen-ager during the '60s and I
was raised in the '80s. Of course, our politics is going to be
different.''
</P>
<P>
   But politics is hardly the top priority for Tommy and his wife
Lyn. The couple have been married for six years and are raising two
young daughters. Lyn works part-time and they are slowly restoring
and renovating a Baudendistel family farm house in Farmersville.
</P>
<P>
   They hire a baby sitter on Monday evenings, but instead of
dinner and a movie, the couple can be found in their basement
installing insulation or in an upstairs hallway blowing out walls.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have time to study Al Gore's health care plan or
ponder whether George W. Bush would make a good commander and chief
for the military.
</P>
<P>
   Their votes hinge more on issues than politics. Lyn wants a
president who is firmly pro-choice and will fight for equal rights
for women. Tommy wants a ``true education president'' who will work
to fix public schools and at the same time supports a voucher
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get older, become a parent, your views of politics and
what's really important tend to change,'' Lyn said. ``Our
generation has it easy. We are so lucky that we only have to worry
about ourselves. I don't think people today care as much as they
used to because they really haven't had to sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
