<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Texas routs Texas A&AMP;M, awaits Kansas 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Texas took a break from the Big 12 championship war
long enough to record what has become an automatic victory in the
once-and-perhaps-future competitive series with Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a career-high 20 points from forward Chris Owens and a
smothering defensive performance from guard Will Clay on flashy
Aggies rookie Bernard King, the No. 14 Longhorns disposed of A&AMP;M
yesterday, 85-58.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, that's 14 in a row over the Aggies (7-18, 3-11)
and 23 of the past 25. Texas (20-7) hit the 20-victory mark for the
first time since 1996. The Longhorns bumped their Big 12 record to
11-3, helped wipe away the memory of] Tuesday's loss at Iowa State
and turned their focus toward tomorrow night's visit by No. 23
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iowa State game has been made in some reports like it was
the end of our season,'' said Chris Mihm, who, with 21 points and
10 rebounds, recorded a conference-leading 17th double-double. ``It
was definitely a big loss, but we're not going to lose our
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a day off to settle things, two great practices and we
totally put it behind us. We gave great effort and had a lot of fun
today. This was what we needed. We played hard and controlled the
game from start to finish. We play like we did today and we'll be
in good shape Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens had eight rebounds in addition to his 20 points against
the Aggies, who were missing center Aaron Jack. He fainted from
apparent dehydration in the dressing room at halftime of
Wednesday's game at Kansas State. While Owens and Mihm were
dominating inside yesterday, Clay put the clamps on King.
</P>
<P>
   King carried a 17-point average into the game, but had averaged
25 points in his past four games, connecting on 17 of 40 3-point
shots. He finished with 13 points yesterday on 5-for-20 shooting,
including 3-for-9 from beyond the arc. But he scored just eight
points against Clay, whose 16 points were one shy of his season
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a challenge guarding Bernard,'' said Clay, who started
in place of slumping guard Lawrence Williams. ``It's my job to
bring energy to this team and guard the other team's best
\Rperimeter\S player. Bernard is a great player and I took it as a
challenge. I just tried to play hard and bring energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow's game looms large for the Longhorns for seeding
purposes, both for the Big 12 and NCAA tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game this time of year is important,'' said UT coach
Rick Barnes, whose team led by as much as 36 (79-43). ``Today's
game was important. They're all big because at this time of the
year you're dealing with mental makeup, the momentum you want to
get going and you've got to play good hard basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've responded well this season after losses. I liked the way
we worked the game today. Not to take anything away from Iowa
State, but we got away from our plan up there. Today we stayed with
what we needed to do. We know Kansas is a young team, but they're
very talented and they've played a great schedule like we have.
They've been battle-tested, and we've got to be ready to lay it out
there on Monday.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
