<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-NOTREDAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT WOMEN TOPPLE IRISH FOR TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Since joining the Big East in 1995, the Notre
Dame women's basketball team had beaten every team in the
conference except one: Connecticut. And if the Fighting Irish were
to do it, Saturday seemed the opportune time.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Notre Dame had won 20 straight games _ the longest
winning streak in Division I _ and was ranked fifth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In the 6-foot-5-inch junior center Ruth Riley and the freshman
point guard Alicia Ratay, the Irish had two of the best players in
the Big East and, indeed, in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Notre Dame saved its worst game of the season for a showdown
confrontation with top-ranked Connecticut in a game that was to
decide the Big East championship.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing from the start, and with Riley held to only one field
goal before fouling out with just under five minutes left, the
Irish lost their 11th straight game to UConn, 77-59, before a
capacity crowd of 16,294 at the Hartford Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen turnovers, including six by Riley, who came into the
game averaging 16.5 points but scored only four, hurt the Fighting
Irish (24-3 overall and 15-1 in the Big East).
</P>
<P>
   So did seven blocked shots by Connecticut (26-1, 15-0), four of
them by center Kelly Schumacher, who, surprisingly, outscored
(eight points to four) and outrebounded Riley, a potential
all-American and Big East player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing by as many as 16 points in the second half, Notre
Dame drew within six points at 58-52 with 4 minutes and 45 seconds
left in the game on Niele Ivey's fourth 3-pointer and two free
throws by Ratay, who, like Ivey, finished with 17 points, a total
matched by Connecticut's Shea Ralph.
</P>
<P>
   But then UConn went on an 11-2 run keyed by three baskets by
point guard Sue Bird, who wound up with 14 points on 6-of-9
shooting, which effectively put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, in Connecticut's second-to-last regular-season
game, gave the Huskies their seventh consecutive Big East title and
guaranteed them the top-seeded spot in the Big East tournament,
which begins March 4 at Storrs, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, hitting its first three shots, spurted to an 8-0
lead at the start on layups by Ralph _ the second off a
behind-the-back pass by Bird _ and Swin Cash and a follow by
Schumacher off a missed jumper by Svetlana Abrosimova.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three minutes elapsed before Notre Dame scored on point
guard Ivey's first of two 3-pointers in the half. Then, two free
throws by Riley narrowed UConn's margin to 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   But that was as close as the Irish got in the half, and the two
free throws were the only points scored by Riley, who came into the
game averaging 16.5 points. Adding to that, Notre Dame's
second-leading scorer, Ratay, managed only one field goal in the
half. The freshman, who entered the game averaging 15.6 points a
game, hit a 3-pointer with just under five minutes left before
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Ratay's 3-pointer, followed by Ivey's second, trimmed the
Huskies' lead to 22-15 with 4:13 left in the half. But then UConn
finished with an 11-4 run to take a 33-19 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the sloppily-played half, marked by 13 Notre Dame turnovers,
four of them by Riley, the Irish made only seven of 25 shots for 28
percent, while UConn connected on 13 of 29 for 44.8 percent, with
Ralph leading the way with 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   With Riley getting off only two shots in the half, Notre Dame
managed only four points in the paint over the first 20 minutes
while the Huskies tallied 22, including four by Schumacher, who
also had five rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
