<SLUG> BC-GORE-TV-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GOES INTO THIN AIR IN NEW TV SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might be called ``Al's Excellent Adventure.'' Last summer,
Vice President Al Gore and his son, Albert Jr., climbed to the top
of 14,000-foot Mount Rainier in Washington. In this new 30-second
spot that began running Saturday, Jim Frush, the president of the
American Alpine Club and the climber who led the expedition,
recounts the experience.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Century Media Group
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: Shots of Frush, alternating with pictures of Gore
and company, in full climbing gear, on the snow-covered mountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: Frush: Before I guided Al Gore and his son to the summit
of Mount Rainier, I knew him primarily for his environmental
positions, not as a person. But you get to know somebody in the
mountains: how they react to pressure, how they handle adversity.
And we had a very tough climb. Terrible conditions. A lot of people
turned back, but Al, he didn't want to quit. He wanted to try to
get to the top. And we made it, safely. Strength of character,
perseverance, grace under pressure _ these are qualities you look
for in a mountaineer; they're even better in a president.
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: As in any situation in which one sits through the
slides from someone else's vacation, the pictures say it all.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: In taking up one of the hardiest of ``in'' pastimes,
give Gore an A for trend-spotting. The sight of Gore trudging into
thin air is intended, of course, to establish his rugged, outdoorsy
credentials, at a time when he is seeking to solidify his image as
a protector of the nation's natural resources _ an image that
environmentalists say he deserves. The spot expresses a
vigorousness that is missing in most political commercials, and
certainly provides a vivid contrast to the many television
advertisements that feature his opponent, Bill Bradley, looking a
little tired as he sits in a chair and talks about his philosophy.
As with many of Gore's attempts to seem a regular guy, though, the
script might appear to some viewers to lay it on a bit thick,
especially when Frush gives the impression that getting to one kind
of summit makes one more suitable to capture another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1830EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BIKE-PANTANI-NYT &LR;      02-26 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-PANTANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A FALL, PANTANI GETS BACK ON THE BIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Over eight months after he was stripped of certain
victory in the Giro d'Italia, the world's second-ranked bicycle
race, a troubled Marco Pantani has finally come out of seclusion
and returned to competition.
</P>
<P>
   Other Italians say that Pantani, 30, the winner of both the Giro
and the Tour de France in 1998, remains despondent. In remarks
before he briefly started racing in the Tour of Valencia last week,
he did little to contradict that judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worrying about my return,'' he began, jauntily enough,
at a news conference in Spain. ``I'm not afraid. I've never been
afraid,'' and here he changed tone, ``even if recently I've felt
very isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to news reports, he dealt with a question about
whether he had contemplated retirement after he was ousted from the
Giro because the red cells in his blood exceeded the maximum
permitted level, an indication of drug use. A second test of the
hematocrit, or red-corpuscle count, in his blood sample confirmed
the finding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that I thought about it,'' he said of retirement.
``I had my doubts. But in the end, I couldn't do anything but
return to bicycle racing. I don't know how to do anything else but
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he cut short his return, failing to appear at the
start of the race's third daily stage on Thursday. His next
scheduled appearance is in the Clasica de Almeria in Spain on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   His fall from grace has been cataclysmic. The 5-foot-7-inch,
132-pound Pantani is the sport's swiftest and most explosive
climber. That power had put him in the pink jersey of the Giro's
leader with two days left in the three-week race when he failed the
blood test last June 5.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he was arguably the most popular person in Italy _
il campionissimo, the champion of champions, as he was called after
he won the Giro and the Tour in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   After his ouster, Pantani, who rides for the Mercatone Uno team
in Italy with a shaved head covered by a bandanna, a ring in his
left ear and the nickname of the Pirate, went from the life of a
hero to one of a recluse.
</P>
<P>
   Until he showed up in Valencia, Spain, he had not raced since
his disgrace. Last July, he refused to ride in the Tour de France,
in which he was the defending champion, saying that the course did
not please him and that he was in no mood to compete. Then in
October he skipped the world championships in Verona, Italy, that
were not far from his home and were over a course that was ideal
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the presentation in Rome of the course for this year's
Giro drew him out of seclusion last fall. Pleading a cold, he
stayed away, and his name was barely mentioned during the ceremony.
The reason is that he continues to be investigated by Italian court
officials who are looking into the use of illegal
performance-enhancing drugs in sports.
</P>
<P>
   What Pantani failed is technically not a drug test. Introduced
in 1997 ostensibly to safeguard riders' health, the test hints at
the use of the synthetic hormone EPO, which bolsters red blood
cells and thus the amount of oxygen that is carried to muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani's troubles did not end with the Giro ouster.
Investigators next focused on his hospital records from an incident
four years earlier. Pantani had to learn to walk again after he was
hit by a car during the Milan-Turin race late in 1995. His left leg
was fractured and he was on crutches for the rest of that season
and most of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The records showed that Pantani's red-corpuscle count at the
time was 60.1 percent, far above the 50 percent limit. When an
Italian prosecutor summoned him in November for questioning,
Pantani invoked his right to silence. He has been placed under
formal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a panel of experts appointed by the prosecutor to
examine Pantani's blood sample in the 1999 Giro dismissed his
explanation that his elevated hematocrit level there was the result
of dehydration or natural causes. Instead, the experts ruled that
he could have been using EPO.
</P>
<P>
   While he was still riding in the Tour of Valencia, which ended
Saturday, Pantani refused to comment on the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just passed through a very negative period,'' he said
earlier in Spain. ``But I've learned a lot these last few months.
I'm here to race, because I want to race. I feel relieved now
because the most important thing is simply to be back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
