<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-EXPO-ART-NYT     02-26 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-EXPO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS COLUMN: SOMETHING FOR EVERYONE AT OUTDOOR EXPO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUFFERN, N.Y. _ Now in its 23rd year, the World Fishing and
Outdoor Exposition will return to the Rockland Community College
Fieldhouse on Thursday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The largest, most comprehensive and most durable affair of its
kind in the New York, New Jersey and Connecticut area, the show
focuses on fishing, hunting and outdoor equipment, much of which
can be bought at special show discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Expo, as it is known, has also for a long time included special
exhibits of live birds and animals. This year the New York Raptor
Project will have a number of live wild birds of prey on hand,
including eagles, falcons, hawks and owls.
</P>
<P>
   A newcomer to the show will be Brody, a 1,200-pound, 4-year-old
Kodiak brown bear. Brody's present home is in Indiana, where he
lives with his owner and trainer, Jeff Watson. According to the
Expo's manager, Paul Fuller, Brody has quite a few entertainment
credits on his resume, including a television appearance on
``Walker, Texas Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having a chance to ogle, and perhaps even fondle,
the latest fishing, hunting, boating and camping equipment,
showgoers can talk with guides, outfitters, charter-boat skippers,
lodge and resort operators from the United States and Canada. It is
an excellent opportunity to arrange an outdoors adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Expo's seminar series, generally devoted to
fishing and casting instruction, hunting and the habits of such
creatures as deer and wild turkeys, have been well attended. They
take place every day and are open to all ticket-holders at no extra
charge. Schedules are handed out at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Hite, a professional black bass tournament angler and
winner of the 1999 Bass Masters Classic, will conduct three
seminars, two on Saturday and one next Sunday. Additional insights
into how experts catch black bass will be provided in other
seminars, two on Thursday and two on Friday by the ``Hawg Trough
Team.'' Doug Hannon, who calls himself The Bass Professor, will
dispense more black bass lore over the weekend with presentations
titled ``Understanding Bass Behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a fly-casting demonstration and lecture by Frank
Angelo each day. Also scheduled for a seminar session each day is
Peter Fiduccia, an author and well-known expert on the habits of
whitetail deer. Hunters might also wish to attend one of Kevin
Kreh's whitetail deer seminars as well as one of those presided
over by Craig Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   The Kreh seminars will include insights into ``the Rompola Buck
Story.'' This story, which has been given considerable attention in
hunting publications and newspapers, involves a whitetail buck with
a huge set of antlers that was killed with bow and arrow by Mitch
Rompola in his native Michigan in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rompola has said that the buck exceeds the present Boone and
Crockett Club record for a typical whitetail rack, held by Milo
Hanson, a Saskatchewan farmer, who shot the animal on his own land
in November 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Boone and Crockett Club founded in 1887 by President
Theodore Roosevelt and others to promote conservation of big game
animals and their habitat, began in 1932 to keep trophy records of
animals taken in North America. Scoring involves meticulous
measurements of the antlers, including the circumference of the
main beams and their spread, the length of the points and the
symmetry of the antlers.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Rompola has not applied for Boone and Crockett
recognition. Kreh, a friend of Rompola, will presumably elaborate
on this decision.
</P>
<P>
   Other seminars include black powder deer hunting by Dave Ehrig;
trophy striped bass fishing with Bob Rochetta; offshore fishing
with Capt. Matt Muzlay; and ``Finding Fish Wherever You Go'' by
Mike Laptew, who is, among other things, a superb underwater
photographer. Manny Luftglass has a seminar on fishing New Jersey's
Lake Hopatcong and another on fishing the tidal portions of that
state's rivers and its bays.
</P>
<P>
   New to the show this year are six dioramas _ provided by Halley
Caller Wildlife Calls _ of all the subspecies of North American
wild turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   The show also has two angling competitions. On Sunday there will
be a casting contest, with prizes awarded, for youngsters,
sponsored by the Westchester Rod and Reel Bassmasters, and every
day of the show those so inclined may take part in a simulated big
game fishing tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Rod bent and line peeling off the reel, contestants will respond
as well as they can while a computerized scoring machine measures
how well they fight the big game fish that is cavorting before them
on a television screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
