<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FOSTER-FELONS-2TAKES-     02-26 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTER-FELONS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM FOR LAW BARRING FOSTER PARENTS WITH FELONIES IN PAST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Under a far-reaching new federal law designed to
protect children's safety, New York state officials for the first
time are conducting criminal background checks on all current and
prospective foster and adoptive parents.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, children's advocates and some government officials
contend, youngsters are being removed from otherwise stable foster
homes without regard to their parents' fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Two State Family Court judges have declared the state's
interpretation of the federal law unconstitutional, allowing a
woman with a 21-year-old manslaughter conviction and a man
convicted of robbery more than 15 years ago to retain custody of
their foster children. The state attorney general, whose office is
authorized to defend the statute, has appealed neither ruling.
Several similar cases are pending statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, children from 44 foster homes in the city have been
taken away in the last several months, according to the
Administration for Children's Services, and children from at least
another 65 foster parents are about to be.
</P>
<P>
   The new law calls for what some people in child welfare circles
say should have been required long ago in New York. Until the
federal Adoption and Safe Families Act took effect a year ago, New
York was one of the few states where foster care agencies were
legally barred from conducting criminal background checks on foster
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a radical shift, all current and prospective foster and
adoptive parents are fingerprinted. If found to have been convicted
of any one of a list of felonies considered violent, from attempted
robbery to murder, they are automatically disqualified. Their
foster children must be removed.
</P>
<P>
   Implementation of that mandatory provision has unleashed an
intense and sensitive debate over whether a convicted felon can be
a capable guardian. Lawyers for foster parents have argued that the
provision violates their right to due process, making it the first
piece of the far-reaching new law to be widely challenged.
</P>
<P>
   The issue seems to have made strange bedfellows. Gov. George
Pataki said last week that he planned to introduce a bill to give
judges or local social service officials flexibility to decide
whether someone convicted of a felony should retain custody of a
foster child. The Office of Court Administration, a state agency in
charge of the courts, has proposed allowing greater judicial
discretion in the matter. Even the Giuliani administration, hardly
known for being soft on crime, is drafting similar revisions.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Nicholas Scoppetta, the city's child
welfare commissioner, was careful to note his support for the
mandatory checks. But, he said, those presumed to be unfit parents
because of their criminal convictions should have a chance to prove
otherwise. ``In general, it's a very positive thing to do these
checks,'' he said. ``I just want to allow for exceptions to the
rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the law took effect, lawyers for foster parents and
children have sought to declare it unconstitutional, often with the
backing of the very agencies that are required to remove the
children. The Legal Aid Society's Juvenile Rights Division is
seeking to file a class-action suit in State Supreme Court in
Manhattan on the question, although a judge has yet to certify it
as a class action.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates contend that to remove a child automatically,
without regard to how long ago the foster parent was convicted or
how well he or she has since cared for the child, can do more harm
than good. In many instances, they say, the convictions are old,
and the foster parents have proved to be able caretakers, providing
stable homes to children whose ties to their biological parents
were severed long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Adoption and Safe Families Act went into effect last
February, New York has fingerprinted nearly 54,000 current and
aspiring foster and adoptive parents, as well as all adults in
their households, according to figures from the state Department of
Social Services. So far, 316 have been found to have convictions
that disqualify them.
</P>
<P>
   Another 3,770 have been convicted of discretionary crimes _
meaning foster care agencies can remove the children if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Because of court challenges, the removals of dozens of children
have been temporarily blocked, pending final decisions by Family
and Supreme Court judges statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is the case of a 10-year-old girl in Brooklyn. Under
the new law she must be removed from the custody of her foster
parent, an aunt she calls ``Mommy'' who has cared for her for half
her life. A lawyer representing the foster mother painted a bleak
picture: taken as a toddler from her biological parents because of
drugs and domestic violence, the girl lived with a grandmother for
three years. When she died, the girl landed at her aunt's.
</P>
<P>
   In January, came the prospect of another shuffle. The foster
parent, whose lawyer declined to identify her, had been convicted
of two attempted robberies, 10 and 11 years ago. After a required
safety check, the foster agency in charge of her case recently
concluded that the child was not at risk, according to the foster
mother's lawyer, Lauren Shapiro, director of the Family Law Unit at
South Brooklyn Legal Services.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the woman was told, the child would have to be removed.
At the request of the child's lawyer, a Family Court judge in
Brooklyn has issued a temporary reprieve, pending a final ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Jacobs, a lawyer with the Legal Action Center, pointed to
the case of two boys who hopscotched through foster homes and group
homes before landing with a foster father in the Bronx two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The man, whose name Jacobs declined to reveal, had been
convicted of attempted robbery in 1966. So the boys, he was
notified last fall, would have to be removed, notwithstanding the
favorable assessments of his care by the foster agency in charge of
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' guardians, Jacobs said, plan to go to court to block
their removal. Once they do, Ms. Jacobs will argue that the
mandatory removal provision is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   So far, two Family Court judges, Philip C. Segal in Brooklyn and
George J. Pulver Jr. in upstate Greene County, have agreed,
declaring that the mandatory removal provision denies due process.
</P>
<P>
   In the Brooklyn case, Segal has allowed the woman convicted of
manslaughter _ named in court papers as Gwendolyn Grant _ to adopt
four nieces. ``Irrebuttable statutory presumptions created by the
Adoption and Safe Families Act (ASFA) violated state and federal
constitutional due process requirements,'' his September decision
concluded.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In Greene County, Pulver ruled that an old criminal conviction
should not automatically disqualify a man, whom he called Richard
C. Benson, using a pseudonym, from continuing to serve as a foster
father to three young brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, whose ties to their biological parents were severed by
the courts, have been with Benson and his wife, Alicia, for more
than two years. But when the couple sought to adopt the children,
identified in court papers as Corey, Steven and John, they were
told they could not. Benson had been convicted of armed robbery in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   The man's criminal record was no secret to the foster care
agency that handled his case, according to the parents' lawyer,
Joseph Stanzione. The couple was well known in their community as
able caretakers, he said, so much so that social service officials
living nearby sometimes entrusted them to baby-sit their own
children. In court, they testified on the couple's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The foster parents ultimately prevailed. ``It is absolutely
clear to this court that Richard has fully rehabilitated himself
from his long-ago life of crime and is a positive role model,''
Pulver wrote in his decision. ``It is equally clear that
petitioners are the best thing that ever happened to Corey, Steven
and John and that it is in the children's best interests to become
petitioners' legal sons through adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   The adoption proceedings are continuing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
