<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GA-RACE _ The most exciting GOP presidential campaign in a
generation is missing two important elements in Georgia _ the
leading candidates. Neither Texas Gov. George W. Bush nor Sen. John
McCain has spent much time in the state, and on Friday McCain
canceled an appearance in Atlanta that had been planned for Monday.
It was his only planned stop in Georgia before the March 7 primary.
(Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NOTAGAIN _ As Rep. Bob Barr puffed away on a cigar at a
congressional retreat last month, he heard something peculiar
coming from some fellow Republicans: worrying about Gov. George W.
Bush's candidacy. Suddenly, the man they had anointed to lead the
party to the White House was not such a sure bet. Instead, Sen.
John McCain (R-Ariz.) seemed like the man to watch, having just won
the New Hampshire primary. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OLDFAMILY _ He was born during World War I, walks with steel
knees and survived open heart surgery with six bypasses. Kitchen
towels wrapped around his boots keep him from slipping as he walks
a visitor up a snow-covered hill on his 215-acre farm, proudly
pointing out the creek that runs through the property, the
farmhouse built before the Civil War and the gazebo constructed
with family labor. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NEW FAMILY _ Traditional politics is losing its hold on American
families. Take the Melson family of Trotwood. Sam, 51, is a
Democrat, his wife, Connie Lucas-Melson, 48, a Republican. They
have a blended family, with nine children ranging in age from 15 to
31 and in politics from Democrat to Republican to those who don't
know what they are. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-HISPANICS _ NEW YORK _ As voting nears in the four
biggest states, Vice President Al Gore appears to have a major
advantage in Hispanic support, a significant bloc in California,
New York, Texas and Florida. Why he's ahead and why it matters.
(Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-DATA _ For a map or list, the 10 states with the
largest Hispanic voting-age populations.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both items MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-GEORGIA _ WASHINGTON _ In an indication of Vice
President Al Gore's dominance in the South, Bill Bradley is not
even contesting the March 7 Democratic primary there. The big
question seems to be whether Democratic voters will cross over to
the state's open GOP primary, as they did in Michigan. (Shepard,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-NOTES _ Mark Sherman's political notes. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TAXES _ WASHINGTON _ When the National Association of
Governors opens its annual meeting Sunday, topic A will be what to
do about taxing sales on goods sold over the Internet. Most
governors fear that the growth of e-commerce will rob them of the
money to hire cops and firefighers or build roads. At the same
time, governors desperately want to appear friendly to tech
companies so they can attract New Economy jobs. Their dilemma
deepens as sales boom in cyberspace and complaints increase on Main
Street about the unfairness of a tax-free Internet. (Geewax, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-QANDA _ WASHINGTON _ Q and A on how sales taxes work on
the Internet under current law. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-OPTIONS _ Congress already has several options on the
table. This chart will show what the bills are, what the status is,
and the most likely outcomes. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLITICS _ WASHINGTON _ As it decides what to do about
taxing Internet sales, Congress will be closely following how the
issue plays in the presidential campaign. Already, the topic has
emerged as a major point of dispute between the Republican
front-runners, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain of
Arizona. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PLAYERS _ Who in Congress is fighting hardest to block
or to impose Internet taxes? (Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TIMELINE _ Key dates in the issue leading up to October
2001. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: All stories MOVED Tuesday in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet FOCUS page for the week. The layout is
available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOCUS 0227: TARGETING ONLINE SALES -- The Internet sales
tax debate is embroiled by a cross-current of competing interests.
(Geewax, Cox News Service). Art includes one 4-column color
illustration.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TAXES BOX -- A box describing the relationship between
states and sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INTERNET TAXES Q&AMP;A -- Some answers to frequently asked
questions about Internet taxes. (Geewax, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TAX PROPOSALS -- Here are some ideas regarding the
taxation of the sale of goods and services over the Internet.
(Geewax, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MACKAY _ WASHINGTON _ Former Florida Gov. Buddy MacKay has been
the president's special envoy to the Americas for the past year.
Now MacKay is turning his attention on Congress as he lobbies for
passage of the Caribbean Basin Initiative expansion and for an aid
package to Colombia. (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-GOALS _ WASHINGTON _ Most of today's efforts to
improve K-12 education require data to measure how well students,
teachers, principals and districts are doing. On Saturday,
governors and other state and federal officials on the influential
and bipartisan National Education Goals Panel finish two days of
hearings and planning on how to overcome the reluctance in many
states to provide more accurate and more timely data on everything
from test scores to dropout rates. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SHELTERS _ WASHINGTON _ The plight of millions left homeless by
natural disasters was the focus of some of the nation's brightest
high school students this week. Teams from 18 cities competed to
design the best temporary disaster shelter as part of the annual
National Engineering Design Challenge. What they came up with.
(Turay, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton pushes for gun
control legislation this year, his priorities include requiring
child safety locks for handguns, banning the importation of large
capacity ammunition clips, barring violent juveniles from owning
guns for life and closing what he calls ``the gun show loophole''
for sales. We ask local lawmakers which provisions they might
support and which are out of the question. (Moscoso and Livingston,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Separate versions will move for East Texas papers, Waco and
Eastern North Carolina papers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-FUNDS _ A list of local lawmakers who receive money from
the NRA and gun control groups, as well as a list of those who own
guns. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-INTERNET _ WASHINGTON _ The National Rifle Association,
long known for its formidable lobbying in Congress, has developed
an equally impressive Internet site. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM-BELL _ STONE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ Taking their cue from MLK's
``I have a dream'' speech, in which he called for freedom to ring
``from Stone Mountain, Ga.,'' Stone Mountain officials will hold a
ceremony Saturday in which Chuck Burris, the first black mayor of a
city that, at the time of King's speech, was home of the KKK, will
ring a newly installed Freedom Bell. The 1700-pound bell will be
rung at11 a.m. EST in the middle of Main Street in Stone Mountain
Village. (Saunders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH PHOTO.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-HEZBOLLAH _ BEIRUT, Lebanon _ How can a guerrilla
movement with 500 full-time fighters and a couple of thousand
part-timers consistently rack up battlefield successes against the
Israeli army? Hezbollah can do it because it is fighting on its own
turf, with grass roots support and cunning adaptability. A military
expert at the National War College in Washington says Hezbollah is
one of the world's best guerrilla armies. Meanwhile, Israel, like
the U.S. in Vietnam, still doesn't seem to have the hang of
guerrilla warfare. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECTION _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Who exactly is the
man considered the favorite in the Russian elections? He has
declared the election is about morals and character, but he is
secretive and close-mouthed about his own history. He won't talk to
the press, so what do school friends, former bosses and neighbors
say about his personality? Where did he used to live and study?
What characteristics have struck such a resounding chord in the
Russian electorate? (Coker, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   STOCK-TRACKING _ Tracking stocks, whose values are tied to the
performance of designated segments of corporate operations, are
gaining popularity and are now being used or contemplated by
familiar names like General Motors and AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom, and
local companies like BellSouth. Trackers give companies a chance to
highlight product lines or services that stand out from the rest of
the company wares, and also create a new currency useful in
acquisitions. But do the stocks serve a real purpose, and what are
investors to make of them? Do they detract from the the older
company shares? We discuss tracker basics, and also provide some
outlook. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   This budget moves daily through the week, then on Saturday at 2
p.m. and 6 p.m. EST and afterwards as necessary based on news
developments. If stories will move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be
given. All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted.
</P>
