who died recently at age 77, was the late Pete Rozelle's executive
assistant, but in and outside the National Football League
headquarters, she was much more. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- OUTDOORS-COLUMN-B&AMP;W -- Brody
the Kodiak bear makes his debut at the outdoor exposition in
Suffern, N.Y., this week. The largest, most comprehensive and most
durable affair of its kind in the New York, New Jersey and
Connecticut area, the show focuses on fishing, hunting and outdoor
sports equipment, much of which can be purchased at special show
discounts. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- BKN-NOTEBOOK -- The Toronto
Raptors' Vince Carter detonated for 33 points, 9 rebounds and 9
assists Wednesday night against the Knicks in Madison Square
Garden. Of his growing celebrity, he says: ``It's crazy sometimes,
but as much stuff as I do, I always put basketball first and
foremost. I understand I am where I am because of the game.'' (G.
Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Feb. 26, 2000 --
BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN -- The Lakers' Kobe Bryant makes quick steals,
pogo-stick jump shots, electric drives and jams of rebounds from
far above the basket. He is fourth on the Lakers in assists and
tied for fourth in rebounds. (G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- CONN-BLOTTER -- While Ben
Keating waits his turn in the Madison Gourmet Beanery in Madison,
Conn., Cory Williams signs a petition asking town selectmen to
suppress the police report in the twice-weekly Shore Line Times,
which is edited by Elizabeth Young, right, shown in her Guilford,
Conn., office. The police blotter provides the name, age, address
and alleged offense of everyone arrested in Madison and Guilford in
the previous week. (George Ruhe/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- NY-REPUBS -- Republican
Party infighting does not faze William D. Powers, the New York
State GOP chairman. He has helped build a successful fund-raising
machine. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- HARLEM-STARTUP -- Adam
Kidron, center, a founder of Urban Box Office Network, with Tyrone
Thomas, left, chief technology officer, and Ney Pimentel, chief
executive of Latinaflava.net, a division. The year-old start-up
already employs 250 people at offices in Chelsea; later this year,
it will become the first Silicon Alley company to set up
headquarters in Harlem, bringing badly needed high-technology jobs
to the neighborhood. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MIDDLETOWN, Conn. -- Feb. 26, 2000 --
WESLEYAN-ADMISSIONS -- Raphael Figueroa, 35, an admissions officer
for Wesleyan University in Middletown, Conn., and some of the
stacks of applications he has been evaluating. As he spends long
days at his home in Connecticut poring over the files, he reminds
himself, ``I don't have the ability to bring them all to
Wesleyan.'' (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- MCCAIN-BACKGROUND-2-B&AMP;W
-- As the Navy's liaison to the Senate, John McCain visited with
Sen. John W. Warner at a reception around 1980, the year he married
Cindy Hensley, left. McCain's best-selling autobiography ends with
his release from Vietnam prisons, omitting everything afterward,
and McCain and Cindy both declined to be interviewed about that
period. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- MCCAIN-BACKGROUND-1-B&AMP;W
-- John McCain was welcomed home by President Richard M. Nixon in
1973 after his release from a prisoner of war camp in Vietnam. The
past is central to McCain's campaign, yet paradoxically his most
remarkable metamorphosis, from a battered ex-pilot on crutches to a
new congressman, is among the least-known chapters of his storybook
life. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- HOWDY-DISPUTE-B&AMP;W -- Velma
Dawson with the original Howdy Doody on the day in 1948 that Howdy
left Hollywood for stardom in New York. Howdy has been locked in a
trunk in a bank vault in New London, Conn., for the last year, and
it may take a judge's order to get him out. Yes, boys and girls,
it's a lawsuit and custody battle over the actual Howdy Doody
marionette used on the show, which ran for 2,543 episodes from 1947
to 1960. In short, the eBay artifact of all time. (The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 26, 2000 --
KOSOVO-DISCORD-3 -- Albanian children watch the construction
Friday, by French soldiers, of a footbridge across the Ibar River.
The bridge is designed to allow Albanians to return to their homes
in the northern part of the city without having to cross the main
bridge, watched by Serbs. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 26, 2000 --
KOSOVO-DISCORD-2 -- American soldiers searching the Albanian area
of northern Mitrovica - largely a Serbian enclave - on Friday.
Under intense pressure from NATO capitals shocked at the violence
here and keenly aware that it symbolizes the West's failure so far
to bring any real measure of security, justice or freedom of
movement to minorities in Kosovo, the province's international
authorities have hastily drawn up a plan intended to improve the
town's precarious state. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- Feb. 26, 2000 --
KOSOVO-DISCORD-1 -- British troops standing guard as Albanians
protest against the Serbs in Mitrovica. The authorities are trying
to devise a plan to defuse the tension between the two groups,
which has escalated into violence and has resulted in Albanians
being driven from their homes in the Serbian sector. (Andrew
Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- OBIT-CLINE-B&AMP;W -- Carroll B.
Cline, a lighting designer whose clients included the Santa Fe
Opera Theater in New Mexico, the Norman Rockwell Museum in
Stockbridge, Mass., and the lobby of 1251 Avenue of the Americas,
died Thursday at his home on the Upper West Side in Manhattan. He
was 72. The cause was cancer, said his wife, Katherine D. Cline.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- NYPD-DIALLO-4 -- A neighbor
Saturday visits the spot where Amadou Diallo died a little more
than a year ago, the vestibule of his apartment building on Wheeler
Avenue in the Bronx. The Diallo family, dismayed by the Friday
verdict acquitting four New York City officers in the shooting
death of Diallo, is expected to file a multimillion-dollar lawsuit
against the city. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- NYPD-DIALLO-3 -- After the
verdict Friday acquitting four New York City officers in the
shooting death of Amadou Diallo, people reacted with calm, sadness
and, in many quarters, like at the Rev. Al Sharpton's rally
Saturday in Harlem, a determination that Diallo's death would not
be in vain. The Diallo family, dismayed by the Friday verdict, is
expected to file a multimillion-dollar lawsuit against the city.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- NYPD-DIALLO-2 -- Kadiatou
Diallo, Amadou Diallo's mother, thanks the crowd attending the Rev.
Al Sharpton's rally in Harlem on Saturday. The Diallo family,
dismayed by the Friday verdict acquitting four New York City
officers in the shooting death of Amadou Diallo, is expected to
file a multimillion-dollar lawsuit against the city. (Suzanne
DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Feb. 26, 2000 -- NYPD-DIALLO-1 -- The verdict
Friday in the Amadou Diallo case has sparked an intense reaction.
The morning after four New York City officers were acquitted in the
shooting death of Diallo, people have been visiting the Wheeler
Avenue vestibule in the Bronx, where he died after being shot 19
times a little more than a year ago. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York
Times)
</P>
