<SLUG> BC-NJ-CASINO-MERGER-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK OF MERGER RAISES NEW CONCERN FOR ATLANTIC CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been more than four years since the Las Vegas casino
magnate Stephen Wynn announced plans to build a $2 billion hotel
and gambling complex on a landfill in the marina district of
Atlantic City, N.J., and almost as long since MGM Grand said it
would build a $700 million resort at the northern end of the
Boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials were so eager to get Wynn to bring badly
needed hotel rooms and Las Vegas-style glamour to Atlantic City
that they agreed to his demand for a new $330 million roadway and
tunnel to whisk visitors from the Atlantic City Expressway to the
western side of the city. That tunnel, known as the Brigantine
Connector, is on schedule and expected to open in May 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But neither company has yet broken ground. Both Wynn's Mirage
Resorts and MGM Grand have been stymied by legal and political
complications. And a bid a few days ago by MGM Grand for Mirage has
suddenly left Atlantic City officials fearing further delays and
the potential for serious business stagnation: With hotel occupancy
near capacity, Atlantic City needs to add rooms fast to stop losing
business.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, MGM Grand made an unsolicited $3.3 billion offer
to buy Mirage. Two other major casino companies, Park Place
Entertainment Co. and Harrah's Entertainment Co., then said they
were considering making their own offers for Wynn's empire, which
is perceived as vulnerable because its lavish new resorts in Las
Vegas and Biloxi, Miss., have failed to meet financial
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Toscano, the senior policy adviser to Mayor James Whelan,
said Atlantic City feared that a battle between Mirage and other
casino operators would lead to further delays in the Atlantic City
projects, just at the moment when the impasse appeared to be
ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Takeover struggles have a tendency to freeze both the
companies involved,'' Toscano said, ``and this is not a good time
for that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirage officials would not talk about what impact the proposed
merger might have on its Atlantic City project. ``All of the
activity in Atlantic City is moving forward as planned,'' Alan M.
Feldman, a Mirage spokesman, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   James J. Murren, the president and chief financial officer of
MGM Grand, said it was ``extraordinarily premature'' to speculate
about what would happen in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   If MGM Grand does acquire Mirage _ and no one can say whether it
will _ the Atlantic City plans are likely to merge as well,
resulting in one new resort instead of two, according to several
analysts. The new hotel is likely to be located on the larger
170-acre marina site rather than on the 30-acre Boardwalk parcel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is desirable because it's such wide open land,'' said David
W. Anders, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston. ``You could
develop the property exactly as you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss _ or postponement _ of one of the resorts would be a
disappointment for Atlantic City, where hotel occupancy rates
exceed 90 percent. Thanks to the expansion of several existing
hotels, the city has nearly 12,000 hotel rooms. But Atlantic City
could fill twice that many, despite increasing competition from
casinos in Connecticut, said Jason Ader, an analyst with Bear
Stearns &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The room shortage makes it difficult to attract package tours
and scheduled flights by major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The construction delays have also placed a financial burden on
the city, which is heavily dependent on the casinos for tax
revenues. The city's tax base took a hit recently when the aging
Trump World's Fair Casino closed. Last month, Whelan said he was
``out of smoke and mirrors'' and proposed a 3.7-cent increase in
the property-tax rate, the first since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although about 48,000 people are employed in Atlantic City's
casino industry, the city needs the jobs that the new resorts would
add. The unemployment rate in 1998, the last year for which figures
are available, was 13.4 percent, more than twice the rate for the
state as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer this drags out, the more frustrated people
become,'' Toscano said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mirage is also a partner in The Borgata, a $750 million casino
resort planned at the marina by Boyd Gaming Corp., which operates
the Stardust Resort Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas. Boyd still
intends to break ground this summer, said Rob Stillwell, a company
spokesman. Designed to resemble an Italian village, the resort
would be next to the new Mirage complex.
</P>
<P>
   Long before MGM Grand made its takeover move, the Mirage project
had encountered a series of hurdles. Donald Trump, a longtime
rival, tried to block it through litigation, saying Wynn had been
given preferential treatment because he did not have to pay for the
land. (Mirage did have to pay to clean the former landfill,
however, and it is contributing one-third of the cost of the
tunnel, with the state subsidizing the rest.)
</P>
<P>
   A protracted legal fight was also waged by residents who said
the tunnel would destroy their middle-class neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Toscano said Mirage contributed to the delays by revising its
design plans twice. On Wednesday, however, in what Toscano
described as ``the first major step,'' the company is scheduled to
appear before the city planning board to seek approval for roads
proposed at the marina.
</P>
<P>
   MGM Grand also faced obstacles in assembling its Boardwalk
parcel, but Toscano and Murren said that the last holdout among the
property owners was on the verge of making a deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
