<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GA-RACE0227-COX     02-26 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-RACE0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia voters eager to see action _ and candidates
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most exciting GOP presidential campaign in a
generation is missing two important elements in Georgia _ the
leading candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Texas Gov. George W. Bush nor Sen. John McCain has spent
much time in the state, and on Friday McCain canceled an appearance
in Atlanta that had been planned for Monday. It was his only
planned stop in Georgia before the March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk of a Georgia visit by Bush before the balloting,
but no date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched among the giants of the electoral process, Georgia
has been relegated to almost an afterthought. The state offers
fewer than 10 percent of the delegates who are up for grabs March
7. Not only are California, New York and Ohio voting the same day,
but a cluster of New England primaries, where McCain appears
strong, also diminish Georgia's importance.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the national race has been growing in Georgia since
McCain's victory in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get it in my law office, at the barbershop, walking around
on the square,'' said Chuck Clay, chairman of Georgia's Republican
Party. ``The only candidate being talked about in a real positive
way is McCain. He has the enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   But the McCain buzz may not translate into enough support to
defeat Bush in Georgia, Clay said _ and other Republicans who also
are neutral in the GOP race agreed.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has a skeletal organization in Georgia, with a brand-new
headquarters. More than 2,000 people have signed on as volunteers,
most of them since McCain won the New Hampshire primary Feb. 1,
said John Sours, McCain's Georgia chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign may have been shaken by Bush's loss to McCain
in the Michigan primary last week. But the Texas governor retains
significant advantages over McCain in this state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is expected in Atlanta sometime before the primary,
has a well-developed statewide organization that is geared toward
turning out traditional Republican voters on primary day. The
campaign has volunteers making phone calls in 40 counties. Campaign
workers distributed 120,000 pieces of literature last weekend
alone, said Eric Tanenblatt, manager of the Bush campaign in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of Georgia's elected Republicans are supporting Bush,
although the same edge existed in Michigan and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The spillover from the South Carolina primary campaign also may
work in Bush's favor. Voters in the Augusta and Savannah areas saw
and heard his ads. ``The best thing for the Georgia Bush campaign
is to have South Carolina produce a clear victory, which it did,''
said Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.), Bush's top supporter in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   In South Georgia, Coverdell said he would remind farmers that
McCain voted against sending them disaster relief in the name of
fighting wasteful spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's successful appeal to social conservative voters in South
Carolina also should work in parts of the state, although perhaps
not in the vote-rich metro area.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and McCain are similarly opposed to abortion rights,
McCain sent a disturbing signal to social conservatives when he
said his family would decide whether to end his teenage daughter's
hypothetical pregnancy, said Rusty Paul, the former Georgia GOP
chairman and aide to Steve Forbes' former presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was sent, but it was received, this
dichotomy between what he would want to apply to everybody else and
his family,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Sours argued that tailoring a campaign to attract social
conservatives would not work as well in Georgia as in South
Carolina. ``South Carolina does not have an Atlanta, such a large
concentration of voters who are independent minded, conservative on
some issues, moderate on others,'' Sours said.
</P>
<P>
   Another potentially important factor is that the Democratic
presidential candidates also will be competing in Georgia on March
7. Democrats and independent voters crossed over in large numbers
in the primaries in Michigan and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Paul, who is not supporting either Bush or McCain, said that
Democratic leaders who back Vice President Al Gore in Georgia will
work hard to produce a large turnout for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gov.) Roy Barnes is under pressure to turn out Democrats for
Gore in the first Southern state for the Democrats,'' Paul said.
``That probably hurts McCain some.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain forces are banking on Gore's overwhelming lead in the
polls and Bill Bradley's failure to mount a serious campaign in
Georgia to persuade some Democrats and independents to vote where
the action is _ or at least appears to be.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has played an important role in one or the other party's
nominating process for the better part of 20 years. In 1984, the
state gave Walter Mondale a win that stopped Gary Hart's momentum.
Four years later, Jesse Jackson claimed a victory that prevented
Gore from sweeping his home region. The beneficiary was the
eventual Democratic nominee, Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1992, Gov. Zell Miller convinced lawmakers to hold the
primary a week earlier in March. The change made Georgia Bill
Clinton's first stop after New Hampshire, and Clinton's resounding
win propelled him to the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, President Bush won almost two thirds of
the vote against Pat Buchanan's insurgent campaign in 1992. Four
years later, Georgia again helped seal Buchanan's fate, this time
voting strongly for Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing those campaigns had in common was candidates who
spent time in the state and, more significantly, bombarded
television viewers with political ads.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the calendar forced the candidates to campaign
elsewhere, the ads were a near-constant reminder of the importance
they attached to the state. This year McCain plans no television
ads in Georgia, political director John Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   As long as McCain is relatively quiescent, Bush has no need to
ratchet up his campaign, said Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster who
is not affiliated with either campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign doesn't look like much here and probably won't
unless McCain gets a lot more going,'' Ayres said. ``But if you
haven't built a foundation up to this point, I don't know that you
have time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
