<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-U.S.-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-SAUDI MEETING ON OIL TAKES A STEP FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia _ The U.S. effort to secure lower oil
prices took an important step forward Saturday when senior Saudi
and U.S. oil ministers agreed that there could be a better balance
between oil supplies and demand.
</P>
<P>
   The carefully worded statement issued here Saturday night by the
Saudi oil minister, Ali al-Naimi, and Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson did not state that boosting production would help end
that imbalance or stabilize oil prices, which at over $30 a barrel
have hit their highest level in nine years. Nor did it commit Saudi
Arabia to producing more oil.
</P>
<P>
   But it did show, according to oil experts and diplomats here,
that both Saudi and U.S. officials are concerned that the soaring
oil prices caused by production quotas imposed last year are now
creating speculation and shortages that jeopardized world economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, Saudi Arabia vowed that it would continue to
``review the oil supply and demand levels to ensure market
stability, prevent oil price volatility and avoid harming the world
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Naimi had stressed in his talks with Richardson
that the decision to pump more oil could be made only by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, which is scheduled
to meet in Vienna, Austria, at the end of March to review
production cuts that it adopted a year ago after the price of oil
fell below $10 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   But several oil experts and diplomats interpreted this statement
to mean that Saudi and U.S. oil officials had similar
interpretations of oil market pressures and that the Saudis would
try to persuade other OPEC members that some production increases
were warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's trip also suggests that a consensus is emerging
among key OPEC states that the production cuts, which Saudi Arabia
urged other members to adopt last March, may have outlived their
usefulness. Oil prices have almost doubled since OPEC decided last
year to reduce daily production by 4.3 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Whether OPEC should pump more oil and at what pace will also be
discussed in London on Thursday at a meeting of oil ministers from
Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico. Before that, officials said,
Richardson will meet with Venezuela's oil minister. The OPEC
members, together with nonmembers Mexico and Norway, produce about
a third of the world's supply of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi officials said no announcement would be made before the
OPEC meeting. But privately, several Saudi officials said they
believed that an increase of more than a million barrels a day
could be justified.
</P>
<P>
   Yet differences persist over tactics and pricing strategy, not
only among OPEC members but within Saudi Arabia's ruling family.
While Saudi oil officials seemed impressed by U.S. data showing
that oil inventories in the United States have fallen to the lowest
point in 20 years and that the world is consuming 75 million
barrels of oil a day and producing only 73 million, a senior Saudi
official wondered whether there was what he called a ``false sense
of crisis'' spurred by a media frenzy over rising prices and
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reserves are meant to go down, especially during a harsh
winter,'' Prince Saud al-Faysal bin Abd al-Aziz, the foreign
minister, said in an interview. ``That's what reserves are for,
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Saudi oil officials are concerned that rising prices for major
consumers risk jeopardizing the economic growth upon which future
oil sales depend. At the same time, they emphasized the need for
building consensus in OPEC. Any suggestion that the kingdom was
responding to U.S. pressure would complicate that task, one
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration is said to be preparing measures to
address shortages, Richardson reiterated on Saturday that oil from
the strategic reserve should be used only to respond to a national
emergency, not to affect price levels.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the discussions here, Richardson said, ``This has
been a very successful trip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
