<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9510 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BB0-GALLOWAY-GRIFFEY-     02-26 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-GALLOWAY-GRIFFEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUNIOR ADDS POP, BUT LEAVES REDS SHORT-ARMED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Thirty miles due north on the interstate,
baseball's biggest story of the spring unfolds daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live'' from Sarasota, it's the Junior Griffey Show, starring
Junior himself, and co-starring Jim Bowden as the master thief who
stole Junior from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's version of Hollywood has now moved to Cincinnati,
with a temporary training camp stop in Sarasota. Fast-forward the
fantasy script to October, and Griffey will be leading the Reds
into the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's fine. Except here in the swampland of Charlotte
County, also known as the Hooterville of spring camps, there is a
somewhat bemused reaction to the hoopla surrounding the Reds and
Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Respect among the Rangers for Junior is immense, based on 11
seasons of facing him in divisional competition. But as one voice
said here Friday, ``Tell me again _ who do the Reds have for
pitchers?''
</P>
<P>
   Junior or no Junior, it always comes back to that, right? It
certainly did in Seattle, when once the Mariners lost Randy
Johnson, they surrendered AL West supremacy to the Rangers. Griffey
was still there, and so was Alex Rodriguez, along with a batting
order that could equal the Rangers' firepower. But the turning
point in the division was the departure of Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with what's going on in Sarasota with Griffey, the
Rangers work out here daily in relative seclusion. A few fans show
up, and an alligator or two might wander by. Baseball-wise,
however, there is a comparison between this spring's Reds and the
Rangers of forever.
</P>
<P>
   See if you've heard this before:
</P>
<P>
   A pitching staff with two marginal starters _ Denny Neagle and
Pete Harnisch _ and total question marks in the other three
rotation spots. A bullpen that overachieved last season, and was
also overworked, and may be facing that same load of innings again.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Reds, who added Dante Bichette's bat, along with
Griffey, meaning the lineup is packed with muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds of this season are exactly where the Rangers had always
been, and don't want to be anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Less pop, more pitching. Around here, that's the new plan for
2000 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the expectations to be high, and I feel they deserve to
be high,'' said Dick Bosman, the pitching coach who is normally
scrambling in spring training to fill staff holes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have lost an 18-game winner (Aaron Sele) and a
13-game winner (Mike Morgan) from last season's rotation. Plus, the
main pitching acquisition of the off-season, Justin Thompson, is
only doing long-toss in spring training while rehabbing from
shoulder surgery. Thompson may not be ready for the rotation until
May.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnny Oates, not a manager who normally backs himself into
a verbal corner, still says ``this is the best and deepest staff
since I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   While adding free-agent returnees Kenny Rogers and Darren Oliver
in the off-season didn't exactly cause an Arlington box-office
stampede by the fans, Oates and Bosman were elated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of this job is to think maybe I can point out one
little thing, or change one little thing, and suddenly that pitcher
is improved,'' Bosman said. ``Guys like Rogers and Oliver are
veterans who have thrown a lot of quality innings in the majors.
And they have the kind of arms that can throw a lot more. I love
the kids, but now we've got seasoned pros one-through-five in the
rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers left here last spring with Sele and Rick Helling as
the established starters, but after that it was up to a relic like
Morgan or a soft-tosser like John Burkett to fill in. That's all
the Rangers had. Even worse, Mark Clark, expected to be the No. 3
man in the rotation, was an immediate bust and contributed nothing
last season.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Bosman will have lefties Rogers and Oliver, in
addition to Thompson when he's ready. That's three southpaws
compared with none last season. Rick Helling will be the No. 1
starter out of camp, and he's expected to improve off a subpar 1999
(14-11, 4.84 ERA), while Esteban Loaiza is the fifth starter. He
was 8-4 with a 3.83 ERA as a starter after the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   The depth allows another lefty, Matt Perisho, to replace
Thompson in the early rotation, although Clark is still a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just say I'm excited by what I think we have, and leave
it at that,'' said Bosman.
</P>
<P>
   His overworked bullpen carried the staff last season, ``but
we've now got some innings-crunchers in the rotation,'' Bosman
added. Plus, the bullpen has added young Francisco Cordero, an
exciting prospect with a large arm.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in years, the Rangers talk pitching as the
team strength. Against all the noise about Junior that's coming out
of Sarasota, it's no more than a whisper in the swamps.
</P>
<P>
   The answer from here, however, is: been there many times and
don't want to go back.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
