<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HARLEM-STARTUP-ART-79     02-26 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEM-STARTUP-ART-795&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HARLEM, AN INTERNET COMPANY FOR THE INNER CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the co-producer of ``New Jack City,'' a 1991 film
starring Wesley Snipes as a Harlem drug lord, George Jackson
introduced a mass audience to the sounds and sensibilities of
inner-city streets.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, after a string of other movies and a brief stint
as president of Motown Records, Jackson embarked on a third career.
He developed ambitious plans for reaching the expanding market for
hip-hop and Latino culture through a network of World Wide Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   With two close friends, he founded Urban Box Office Network, a
year-old company that already employs 250 people at ramshackle
offices in Chelsea. Later this year, it will become the first
Silicon Alley company to set up headquarters in Harlem, bringing
badly needed high-technology jobs to the neighborhood where Jackson
grew up.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be no homecoming. On Feb. 10, less than three
weeks before the scheduled start of the company's first major Web
site, Jackson died of a stroke. He was 42.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Jackson, a 300-pound Harvard-educated bear of a man
who was affectionately known as Papa, has devastated his young
staff and left a void that his partners _ Adam Kidron, a long-time
British music industry producer, and Frank Cooper, the former vice
president for business affairs at Def Jam Recordings _ are
struggling to fill. But they say they are not deferring any of
their plans. And their backers maintain that Jackson left behind a
company in good enough shape to withstand his loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the investors feel confident that the leadership and the
depth is there to take it forward and make it a successful media
company,'' said Kathryn Wylde, the president of the New York City
Investment Fund, a private company that tries to stimulate job
growth. The fund has given Urban Box Office $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company also expects the Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone _
a federal, state and city program designed to foster economic
development in Harlem _ to grant it a $4 million loan for
renovating an industrial building at 126th Street and Amsterdam
Avenue. And the company will receive tax breaks for hiring
neighborhood residents, who make up one-fifth of its current work
force, said Terry C. Lane, the president of the Empowerment Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said he hoped that Urban Box Office would inspire other
Internet companies to move to Harlem. He said he had been talking
to two dozen other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its Harlem location, the new venture will not be aimed
exclusively at African-Americans and other minority groups, Kidron
said. He defined the target audience as young people with an
``urban mind-set.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Smikle, the president of Target Market News, a Chicago-based
company that monitors African-American media and marketing, says
that although African-Americans have been slower than other groups
to embrace the Internet, they are catching up fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of sites trying to go specifically after the
younger portion of this audience,'' Smikle said. ``That's a field
that could get pretty crowded quickly.'' But he said no one else
had matched Urban Box Office in scale.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of creating a Web portal for urban music, entertainment
and information did not originate with Jackson. But his friends and
business associates say that his ebullient and forceful personality
got the project off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It was a role that Jackson was used to. ``He was the type of guy
who would take iconoclastic people and create a family,'' said Doug
McHenry, his film-producing partner. ``He would be the glue and
help them formulate the vision and make it practical.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was the drawing card for Flatiron Partners, a venture
capital company specializing in the Internet that has invested $16
million in the online network. Jerry Colonna, the managing partner,
said, ``I'd be lying if I didn't say that within 10 minutes of
meeting George, I knew I wanted to fund this project.''
</P>
<P>
   Colonna said he was impressed by the breadth of the company's
goals. In addition to serving as a distribution system, Urban Box
Office will offer original content, including situation comedies,
dramatic series, talk shows and animation. Other sites will offer
hip-hop blended with Latin rhythms and what Kidron called ``the
full range of e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   As Colonna said, ``As a venture capital company, you want to
back entrepreneurs who think big, not people who say, `I want to
get bought out by Yahoo.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Web sites are being rolled out one by one, and company
officials say the network itself will not go online until a
critical mass has been reached. The most elaborate one so far _
www.indieplanet.com, which is intended to showcase independent
musicians, artists and writers _ will make its debut on Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The online network was actually the brainchild of Kidron, who
produced albums for the Sex Pistols rock band in the 1970s. Kidron,
40, said he initially hoped to create a cable channel but was
unable to secure an outlet in New York.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to a public library in Yonkers, Kidron said, he
began to understand the changes the Internet had wrought. As a
group of teen-agers logged onto the Internet to listen to music, he
noticed that they relished being able to flit from site to site.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was more important than the quality,'' Kidron said, ``was
that the kids could go on the Web and they could choose what they
were going to program. That was the defining moment in building
Urban Box Office and why it is structured the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kidron was developing his idea, Jackson was coming off a
frustrating year. He had moved to New York in 1997 to try to rescue
Motown, a legendary record label founded in Detroit that had been
run into the ground. Since he was a neophyte in the music business,
his arrival was greeted with skepticism. But Danny Goldberg, the
former chairman of Polygram's Mercury Group, which then owned
Motown, said he had hired Jackson to run the label for other
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had tremendous executive and leadership qualities that are
extremely hard to find,'' Goldberg said. ``The things he didn't
know he could learn.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jackson acknowledged, the Motown job was a struggle.
``There's tremendous pressure on me, nothing but pressure,''
Jackson told The Boston Herald a few months after he took the job.
Before he had a chance to prove himself, however, Polygram was sold
to Seagram Co. and he was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   When he teamed up with Kidron, Jackson was initially reluctant
to base the new company in Harlem. ``He didn't want to go there and
have us be this isolated thing of privilege in this place of
enormous destitution and lack of opportunity,'' Kidron said. But
eventually Jackson came to see the advantages of locating in a
world-famous neighborhood with deep cultural roots, his friend
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kidron does, too. ``Harlem,'' he said, ``is this amazing urban
brand that has fallen into decay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
