<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9513 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-NOTAGAIN0227-COX     02-26 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTAGAIN0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia comrades stick with Bush as primary nears
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Rep. Bob Barr puffed away on a cigar at a
congressional retreat last month, he heard something rather
peculiar coming from some of his fellow Republicans: worrying about
Gov. George W. Bush's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the man they had anointed to lead the party to the
White House was not such a sure bet. Instead, Sen. John McCain
(R-Ariz.) seemed like the man to watch, having just won the New
Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, an early backer of Steve Forbes for president, stood on
the outside of the conversation, surprised at the level of concern
over Bush's prospects. ``They were a bunch of nervous Nellies
running around talking about what they should do,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   And that was before McCain swept the Michigan and Arizona
primaries last week, creating the specter of a hotly contested
Republican primary battle.
</P>
<P>
   The worry that Barr heard isn't shared by his fellow Georgia
Republicans in Congress _ at least not on the surface. Seven of the
nine back Bush. And they don't seem say they are not swayed by
McCain's bid.
</P>
<P>
   GRAMM WAS THEIR MAN
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, every one of them all but one of them endorsed
Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas) for the Oval Office, save one. Rep.
Nathan Deal was too busy defending his own seat to worry about the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   So, have Georgia's congressional Republicans bet on the wrong
horse again?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell offers an unequivocal ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go for the person you want to win, the person you
believe is the best for the job,'' he said. ``I have never believed
in sitting around and waiting to see who is most likely to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, Bush's point man on Capitol Hill, has a long history
with the Bush family. He was an early supporter of supported Bush's
father for president back in 1980, when he had about 1 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell said 44 of the 55 GOP senators Senate's 55 Republicans
back the Texas governor and that his `` Coverdell said. ``Bush's
support among Republicans is increasing. It's getting bigger and
bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   As for McCain, he said Republicans see him as a ``spokesperson
for the Democrats.'' That's why there are so many cross-over votes
for him, Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Kingston, who has not endorsed a candidate, said
backing Gramm so early the last time taught him a valuable lesson:
Sometimes the Lone Star candidate isn't always a shining star.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston thinks McCain's challenge to Bush has actually been
good for the GOP. ``We all quietly appreciate what McCain is doing
because if (Bush) can't get past McCain, he won't get past
(Democrats Al) Gore or (Bill) Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly invigorated the race and drawn attention, he
said. to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching the Democratic primary race is like watching two life
insurance salesmen argue about which annuity is the best,''
Kingston said. ``It's absurd that they are arguing about who is
more liberal. That's sort of like Frank Zappa and Jerry Garcia
arguing about who is the hippest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder hasn't wavered from the Bush camp, either,
mainly because he likes the way Bush cut taxes and improved schools
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's predictable,'' Linder said. ``If an issue comes up, I
know where he'll be. I can't say the same about John McCain. He's
unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charlie Norwood was among the first in the delegation to
jump on the Bush bandwagon. He's convinced that McCain has gotten
where he's gotten on the backs of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something that they see in McCain that's liberal,''
Norwood said. The media, he said, has hyped McCain because they
don't want to write about a ``boring Republican primary.''''What
would they be talking about if Bush were a shoe in?'' Norwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's victory in South Carolina shows he can be a serious
candidate, Deal said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, plenty of people respect McCain for being a maverick,
``but most traditional Republicans are overwhelmingly Bush
people,'' Deal said. If the race goes to the convention, it would
force Bush to spend lots of money and detract from his being able
to help lawmakers in congressional races, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the good part of it is it generates a lot of interest,''
Deal said. ``I think McCain is doing what our system allows people
to do: run and put their best effort forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Johnny Isakson agrees that McCain generates interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to think what's going on in this hotly contested
primary is there are more pluses than minuses,'' he said. ``The
media have gone from writing every day about Gore and Bradley to
writing about Bush and McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   And that means voters are getting engaged in GOP politics.
</P>
<P>
   `IT'S THE RECORD, STUPID'
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Saxby Chambliss stood with his fellow Georgians and said he
doesn't regret his early endorsement of Gramm in 1996. endorsed
Gramm when he announced four years ago and He doesn't regret that
decision. Nor does he regret backing Bush early on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the wrong horse with Gramm,'' he said. ``It was the
right thing to do. We think we've done the right thing this time in
supporting Bush so early on.''
</P>
<P>
   As for McCain, Chambliss turned philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you'd like for your guy to breeze through without any
problems,'' he said. ``But what primaries do is make better
candidates out of you. He's going to be fine in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The slogan, ``It's the economy, stupid,'' helped Bill Clinton
win the presidency in 1992. Rep. Mac Collins hopes this time voters
will see that, ``It's the record, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   All week long, Collins has soothed concerned Bush voters in Pike
County by merely laying out his record as governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big difference between the two,'' Collins said of
Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's list of reforms in Texas include tort reform, tax relief,
welfare, education and managed care, he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's list? A bill to regulate tobacco companies and one to
overhaul campaign financing, Collins said. Both were major pieces
of legislation, and both failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a president who knows how to work with a legislative
body,'' he said. ``I think once people start looking at the record,
they will see that Bush is the right choice.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
