<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-RESPERT0227-COX     02-26 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RESPERT0227-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   His countdown on hold
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Tierney
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What really gnaws at Jason Respert is that he already
had given the gate to the Gators. The premier offensive-line
prospect in the Southeast had whited-out Florida on his roster of
candidate universities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in this mutual exploitation society that defines
recruiting, Respert took a freebie trip to Gainesville that,
worst-case scenario, could cost him his freedom. Four days before
Tennessee would roll out the orange carpet for him, he was jailed
for alleged attempted sexual battery and burglary of a residence.
</P>
<P>
   In the football universe, his current residence is limbo. The
Volunteers have placed his scholarship in deep freeze. They do not
dare tender it unless and until his litigation is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, he lingers in purgatory. Prosecutors still are winding
up interviews with witnesses to determine what to do in the case.
Respert is free on $50,000 bond.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from proclaiming his innocence, Respert volunteers no
details on the Gainesville soiree that apparently brought him to a
tavern patronized by Gator players and dead-ended during the wee
hours in an apartment occupied by several young women.
</P>
<P>
   He did offer this: ``Like my mama always says, `The world isn't
fair.'''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Respert would cringe at being labeled a mama's boy.
Wouldn't any 18-year-old, especially one whose rock-solid 6-foot-4,
300-pound body fills a doorway? But he might not deny it, either.
</P>
<P>
   Home for June Respert was College Park near Atlanta's Hartsfield
International Airport when she divorced in 1988 and headed south
with her three children. Seeking a fresh start in a locale within
reach of Jason's father, who since died, and her parents in
Montezuma, she dropped anchor in Warner-Robins.
</P>
<P>
   In no time, Jason was a typical W-R kid. Which is to say, he
played football.
</P>
<P>
   His heritage? Not so typical. Jason was borne of an interracial
marriage. It confused and hurt when classmates called him ``Oreo.''
Once, he angrily asked June, ``Mama, why did you have to have me by
a black guy?''
</P>
<P>
   June bit her lip and drummed a message into him: Be proud, not
ashamed. At the same time, she grew concerned that those who
frowned on her former marriage were watching this youngster with
mixed blood, ready to pounce on any misstep. So she did not spare
the rod in his upbringing. Asked how she administered the
tail-whippings, Jason whispered outside of her earshot, ``With the
first thing she could grab.''
</P>
<P>
   The spankings were leavened by positive maxims. ``You can have
both worlds,'' she eventually told him. ``You can date and fall in
love with anyone you choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Football brought respect, never more so than after Respert tore
the left anterior cruciate ligament in spring practice before his
sophomore season at Northside High. Standard rehab for such a
debilitating injury at his age requires as long as a year. His was
completed by four months, which astounded Dr. James Andrews of
Birmingham, the noted surgeon who repairs football-damaged knees of
all shapes and status, from high school backups to Pro Bowlers.
</P>
<P>
   With his balletic footwork, brute strength, mean streak and
college-eligible grades, Respert was sniffed out by the A-list of
college coaching. B. Bowden and Spurrier, Fulmer and Donnan. He
whittled his wish list to five, matching the NCAA's maximum
allowable recruiting visits.
</P>
<P>
   The first, to Michigan, was a dud. Georgia bowled him over with
the name-on-the-jersey scheme, and he obliged with an oral,
non-binding commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flattered there,'' he said. ``It was the home-state
school. I liked coach (Doug) Marrone,'' the offensive line
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, Respert felt like TV's millionaire bride as doubts
crept in. In retrospect, he said, Georgia pressued him because, as
the linchpin of its class, he would lure other prospects to tag
along.
</P>
<P>
   Next on his itinerary: Knoxville. Respert thought about begging
off and advised Phil Fulmer about the pledge to UGA. Fulmer urged
him to visit nonetheless. ``Then if Georgia's still the place for
you,'' the coach said, ``go there.''
</P>
<P>
   In Big Orange country, Respert was taken by the Tennessee River,
the notion of playing before crowds exceeding 100,000 and,
especially, the paternal approach of Fulmer. ``About 85 percent of
the time, Coach talked about non-football stuff,'' he said. ``He
was just like part of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Tennessee it was. Respert canceled scheduled inspections of
Florida State and Florida. But, on the final weekend before signing
day, Gainesville was back on _ in defiance of advice from his high
school coach to treat these as business trips.
</P>
<P>
   Respert saw it differently. He wanted to escort his twin sister,
Jennifer, who had yet to accompany him on the college tour, and
repay the efforts of UF line coach Jimmy Ray Stephens. Bottom line,
though: ``I wanted a Florida vacation. (A teammate) told me,
'They're gonna pay for it. Why not go?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer's job duties forced her to cancel. His stepfather
became ill. Respert told June, who came along, ``Mom, we don't have
to go.'' On the drive down, they shooed away second-guesses.
</P>
<P>
   It is standard procedure for recruits to get chaperoned around
campus by college players. Too often, they detour into forbidden
territory. ``If the NCAA knew what was going on at some of these
schools ...,'' June said.
</P>
<P>
   Respert apparently had parted ways with his escort when,
according to Gainesville police, he hooked up with fellow recruit
Tre Orr of Lake City, Fla., and Gator sophomore Alex Brown at a
bar, the Purple Porpoise. June was staying at a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Police maintain that the players obtained telephone numbers of
two women at 2 a.m., called them an hour later and showed up at
their apartment. Brown and the other recruit paired off with the
two women, and Respert allegedly entered the bedroom of a third
resident, asleep and ill. Respert is accused of lifting the woman's
pajama top and putting his hand down her pants.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, he was taken into custody at Florida Field. The
last 28 hours or so of his recruiting experience were spent in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cervone, chief assistant prosecutor, said his office might
determine this week whether to pursue the existing charges, file
reduced ones or dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take it seriously,'' Cervone said, ``but we don't file
charges just on the basis of a police report.''
</P>
<P>
   He indicated that polygraph tests arranged independently by the
Resperts are not admissible and would have no bearing on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   Resperts were barely home when Florida announced it no longer
would recruit him, a token gesture, given his dissipated interest
in the school. Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley caucused
with coach Jim Donnan and declared that they, too, were pulling out
of the Respert sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs assumed that they remained in the running; indeed,
Respert had just told The Atlanta Journal-Constitution that UGA and
Tennessee were running neck-and-neck.
</P>
<P>
   But his heart was speaking louder than his muddled mind. And it
was screaming Rocky Top.
</P>
<P>
   So did his wardrobe. On a junket to Maui for high school
All-America players, Respert was spotted in Tennessee orange.
</P>
<P>
   Respert views the reaction of the schools involved as validation
of his leanings. The Bulldogs, he said, ``are saving face, trying
to do what's best for Georgia. But that was humiliating to me.''
</P>
<P>
   That Tennessee has maintained contact ``means a lot to me,'' he
added. ``One thing I'm happy about is that I went through a
situation like this to find out who's gonna stick with me.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few weeks of too many tears and not enough sleep,
Respert has settled into a holding pattern. Friends and family
organized a defense fund for lawyers' fees. Acquaintances are asked
to contact the prosecutor's office to volunteer as character
witnesses. The mayor is being urged to designate a Jason Respert
Signing Day _ if that day comes.
</P>
<P>
   Respert's calendar, loaded for so many years with school
activities, is blank. School-board policy forbids students in his
legal situation from engaging in extracurriculars. That means no
basketball, no shot put and discus. No Mr. Northside contest, an
honor awarded to a lone graduating senior. Possibly no
Florida-Georgia all-star game.
</P>
<P>
   To a teen who says his worst trouble until now was a speeding
ticket for driving 60 in a 45-mph zone, Respert shudders at what
might transpire. ``I'm confident in my innocence,'' he said. ``I'm
scared that my life is in the hands of someone who doesn't know the
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Respert's favorite TV shows does not register in the
Nielsen ratings. ``Ever since I was little, I watched 'Countdown To
Signing Day,' `` he said of the updates on football recruiting. ``I
was waiting for my chance to be on _ counting the days to when I
sign.''
</P>
<P>
   The count is on hold. To be young is to have 20-200 vision,
unable to see clearly beyond tomorrow. And Respert cannot tell you
what the rest of his senior year, which should be the apex of his
life to date, will bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of just the best year,'' he decided, ``it's gonna be
the best teaching tool I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
