<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING OUT FREE-AGENT LANDSCAPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Double-trouble agent David Falk doesn't mind
taking an interview to the next level ... pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Julius Caesar said after he crossed the Rubicon, `The die
is cast,' '' Falk sang about 45 minutes after he'd been crossed by
the Clippers in Thursday's trade-deadline, snake-eyes roll to
liberate Maurice Taylor from L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Falk had just attempted - and failed - to sell the Clips on
Knicks forward John Wallace after an attractive deal that would
have landed Othella Harrington from Vancouver fell through (blame
the Grizzlies). This Rubicon speech was designed to inform the
planet there is no turning back on his promise that Taylor will
never ever re-sign with the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's practice, Taylor fudged a bit on the party line,
admitting that returning isn't an impossibility, although ``this is
as close as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   So does his agent still believe ``Mo'' - who now openly
campaigns for future employment in Orlando is worth a maximum
contract (about $67.5 million over six seasons) prescribed by NBA
law?
</P>
<P>
   ``Categorically, you can take that to the bank,'' Falk said,
although the last few words were tough to make out over the
stomping of his cloven hoof.
</P>
<P>
   Before we bother the neighborhood teller, let's examine this
summer's free-agent landscape. With only 154 days before the Class
of 2000 honor roll can strike it rich, we're certain to really nail
things down today.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the top dogs - by far - are San Antonio's incomparable Tim
Duncan and Grant Hill of Detroit. The top salary cap dogs - by far
- are the Chicago Bulls and Orlando Magic. By economic design, both
teams stink, although first-year coach Doc Rivers gives the Magic
an aroma of hope. Both teams have enough cap room to offer max
contracts to both players.
</P>
<P>
   Both players share the same agent (Lon Babby), are decent
friends and together would transform either team into a contender.
But, according to most league watchdogs, if they don't team up,
Hill and Duncan are likely to remain where they are.
</P>
<P>
   Next in line on free-agent row is Tracy McGrady of the Toronto
Raptors. McGrady, who only averages 28 minutes per game, will be
paid on spec, but his lab-freak skills dictate he'll receive top
dollar. Recently, the Raptors have backed off their initial
approach of alleged fiscal responsibility and plan to play ball.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to McGrady's future may be teammate and cousin Vince
Carter, who can become a free agent after the 2001 season. If
Carter is planning to ditch the hockey-huggin' Toronto area,
McGrady will do so a year earlier. McGrady is building a home in
Orlando (he grew up in Florida), but insists this is not an
etched-in-stone clue about his future.
</P>
<P>
   On McGrady's heels is Charlotte shooting guard Eddie Jones.
According to one of the Hornets' limited partners, ownership will
offer Jones a max deal. But one league source has indicated that
majority owner George Shinn has issued a thumb-down on the prospect
of paying Eddie about $70 million over six seasons (that's the
ballpark rate for keeping your own hotshot).
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to Taylor and Motown crony Jalen Rose, the
free-agent-in-training Indiana Pacer, who - like Mo - dumped agent
Norm Nixon in favor of Falk last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing on the same team as Jalen is very important to me,''
said Taylor, who did admit he would have signed a long-term deal
with the Knicks, had that trade gone through. But, according to a
league source, the Knicks were prepared to offer Taylor a contract
a notch or two below the maximum rate. Since they already are
committed to $70 million in team payroll for next season - about
$15 million more than the limit that would kick in the league's new
luxury tax - the source sounds credible.
</P>
<P>
   A stoolie close to the Orlando scene said that while Rivers is a
big Taylor fan, the team's money handlers don't think Mo's heroic
enough for mad max money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Falk keeps rolling the dice, expecting to hit seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three of the top six free agents,'' he said, allowing
`we' to include McGrady, whose agent - L.A.-based Arn Tellem - sold
his business to the same outfit (SFX) that made Falk ridiculously
wealthy by purchasing his. ``The other three are going to stay
where they are.'' We assume he's referring to Hill, Duncan and
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Under Falkland logic, the Bulls and Magic will be forced to dump
their considerable loot on the SFX crew.
</P>
<P>
   For Taylor at least, Chicago may be a longshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a four,'' Bulls GM Jerry Krause said of the Clipper's
power forward job description, ``and we have a player at that
position we like (Elton Brand).''
</P>
<P>
   Krause is setting his cap for Duncan and Hill, with McGrady in
the wings to catch the Bulls if they falter on either or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough room under the cap now to sign two full-boat
free agents,'' he said after unloading Toni Kukoc on the 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Full boat'' is how Krause defines a player worthy of big
money.
</P>
<P>
   But we still don't know if a full boat is required when crossing
the Rubicon.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   According to league sources, one member of the Grizzlies'
ownership group sought the advice of a league insider before
telling GM Stu Jackson that any trade involving Harrington and
Wallace would not be sanctioned. The insider is former Pistons
assistant coach Dick Versace, who reportedly may replace Jackson.
... Fresno State's Courtney Alexander leads the nation in scoring
and is the top offensive two-guard prospect in this summer's draft.
``But he may be the worst defensive player I've ever seen,'' said
one NBA general manager. ... Cincinnati power forward Kenyon
Martin, for now, appears to be the runaway answer to what had been
a puzzling question a few weeks ago. The question: If the NBA Draft
was scheduled for today, who would be the first player taken? ``You
know what you're getting with that guy,'' said one scout, who raves
about the 6-foot-8 greyhound's intensity and athletic chops. ...
There was plenty of fiction hacked up by NBA writers last week, but
the weakest was the thin-air report of a deal that would send
Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo to the Suns, who would have kept Jason
Kidd, Penny Hardaway and Cliff Robinson. ``Of the 15 teams in the
Eastern Conference,'' said one general manager, ``11 of those teams
start centers that are 6-10 or shorter. Trading Mutombo (who's 7-2)
would be insane.'' ... More fiction: Miami's Voshon Lenard or San
Antonio's Avery Johnson to the Clippers for free-agent bait Derek
Anderson? All three teams involved laughed off those two ``deals.''
... Joe Safety, the Clippers' VP of communications, must have spent
a great deal of his youth spying on cartoons. Upon hearing Falk's
Rubicon reference, Safety said, ``The die is cast? I thought Mr.
Peabody said that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
