u w BC-COX-EDUCATION-GOALS-0     02-26 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-EDUCATION-GOALS-0227R </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEDERAL TRACKING OF STATE EDUCATION TRENDS CRITICIZED
 &HT;    Resending for all needing
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government spends too little and takes
too long when it measures the progress of states in improving their
schools, the National Education Goals Panel declared Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We somehow have to demand the money to get the job done
speedily,'' said Republican Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, as he
succeeded Democratic Gov. Paul Patton of Kentucky as the panel's
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Congress set up the influential, bipartisan panel a decade ago
to monitor the effects of school reforms. It is composed of eight
governors, four members of Congress, four state legislators and two
presidential members.
</P>
<P>
   Only one-third of the statistics used by the panel to track
national and state-level trends are collected annually. Others are
collected every two, four or 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases, it's truly ridiculous,'' Patton said. ``The
latest (state-level) data on adult literacy is from 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal agencies and nonprofit research groups that supply
the statistics still collect a lot of data on paper, rather than in
computerized form. Entering, editing and analyzing the numbers can
delay publication for another two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the states who are in charge of changing things can't
use three-year-old data, much less 12-year-old data,'' said
Democratic Gov. Jim Hunt of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses spend a lot to keep track of how they and their
competitors are doing,'' Hunt said. ``In educating our children,
our future workforce, we should do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Some states and school districts are resisting efforts to get
them to cooperate in collecting uniform data more swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   State resistance would fade if the federal government were to
pick up more of the cost, Thompson said. ``Money has a strange way
of encouraging people to do things,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Some local educators avoid national tests because they want to
concentrate on ``high stakes'' state tests that directly affect
funding for schools and teachers and promotion chances for
students.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Musick of Atlanta, who chairs the National Assessment
Governing Board, said two states refused to take part in this
year's national math and science tests for students in the fourth
and eighth grades. He said seven other states backed out and some
of the remaining 41 have had a hard time finding enough schools to
agree to conduct the tests.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage states to take part in the national tests,
President Clinton's budget proposes a $5 million bonus pool to be
shared among states whose students show progress on their latest
national tests in math, science, reading or writing.
</P>
<P>
   Praising Clinton's plan as ``bonuses for performance and
quality,'' Thompson said, ``Business has been doing that for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel voted to:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Vigorously support increased funding'' for speedier
collection and publication of data that allows comparisons of the
performance of states, districts, schools, teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   _ Convene a meeting this summer of national groups of business,
education and government leaders to decide how to cooperate on the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ Form a task force headed by former Maine Gov. John ``Jock''
McKernan to recommend new ways to measure and report on educational
trends.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
