<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proving time for Chen
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ No more red carpet, no more rave reviews.
Bruce Chen has to roll up his sleeves and do some serious work to
win the Braves' fifth starter spot this year.
</P>
<P>
   With Steve Avery recently signed and Terry Mulholland another
viable option, Chen has the inside track but not much more. But
both he and the Braves say they're starting over fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always start with a clean slate,'' pitching coach Leo
Mazzone said. ``You don't think of last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The fifth starter's job was Chen's to claim last year, but after
his shaky spring Odalis Perez emerged with it and Chen was off to
AAA Richmond. Once John Smoltz's elbow problems started flaring up
again and Perez was lost for the season to an elbow injury, Chen
got several more opportunities. But he failed each time and became
one of the last pitchers out of the bullpen. He was left off the
postseason roster.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old left-hander will have to show the Braves he has
come a long way from his rookie season. He pitched in 16 games for
Atlanta, seven of them starts, and went 2-2 with a 5.47 ERA. He
gave up an eye-popping 11 home runs in 51 innings, walked 27
batters and allowed 38 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally he would exhibit the precision he was known for in
the minors, but in the end it was his control that failed him.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's shining moment came in Philadelphia when he pitched the
second game of a doubleheader in July and allowed one unearned run
in a 3-1 win. But his next turn he was back to getting slapped
around, allowing six runs in 4 1/3 innings against the Brewers.
That would be his last start before the second-to-last game of the
season, when the Braves had long since clinched the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year made me a more mature pitcher, a more confident
pitcher,'' Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   Stop. Rewind. Confident?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, Chen said, and this was his explanation: ``It's like
taking the SAT. The first time you take the SAT, you do bad. You
know the next time you take it you're going to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last year I know a lot more about myself _ what pitches
work for me, how I react to different situations, what I can do to
overcome them,'' Chen said.
</P>
<P>
   Chen chose to play winter ball in Venezuela this offseason
instead of going back to Georgia Tech, where he's pursuing an
engineering degree. The results weren't great _ he went 0-4 with a
5.68 ERA in six games, allowing 48 hits in 31 2/3 innings. But the
work was important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thrown only 20 innings in the last six months,'' Chen
said. ``I wanted to get my control back, to improve my change-up
and get a more consistent curveball. ... (Last year) I lost my
focus, one batter or one inning. I just want to be consistent. It
shouldn't take me three or four runs to realize I'm off target.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have always raved about Chen's repertoire of pitches
and have done more of the same this spring. But the true test will
come when exhibition games start later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about working ahead in the count,'' Mazzone said. ``And
if you do get behind, don't sacrifice stuff to get strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
