<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9526 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     02-26 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADING DEADLINE PRODUCES LITTLE ACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Has the trade deadline passed yet? Or does it just
seem like the NBA took the week off during what is usually the
busiest time of the season?
</P>
<P>
   There was only one deal Tuesday, and it's barely worth
mentioning (the Hawks shipped guard Anthony Johnson to the Magic
for a second-round draft pick).
</P>
<P>
   That flies in the face of history. In the past 10 years, there
were 30 trades involving 82 players on the day of the trading
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened?
</P>
<P>
   A lot of it has to do with a complicated issue called the luxury
tax, which goes into effect next season. If player salaries exceed
55 percent o f the league's Basketball Related Income (BRI), the
players must return 10 percent of their salaries into an escrow
fund.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bother any owners.
</P>
<P>
   But if the salaries surpass 61 percent of the BRI, teams must
match the excess amount with their own payments into the escrow
fund.
</P>
<P>
   That bothers owners.
</P>
<P>
   So any team that traded for an overpriced star (like Cleveland's
Shawn Kemp) would only be boosting the amount it might be expected
to contribute towards the escrow fund.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, this is the NBA, so some esoteric issue like luxury
taxes can't be the only reason there were no trades. There were
plenty of potential deals out there that just didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone expected the Clippers to deal Maurice Taylor, because
getting something in return for the free agent is better than
nothing, but once again logic took a back seat to stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   And the Heat called nearly every team in the league, desperate
for backcourt help. One potential deal involved Clippers guard
Derek Anderson for Voshon Lenard. But in the end, they accomplished
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The real reason no deals took place is that the teams were
reluctant to take on the burdensome contracts of the Kemps and
Dikembe Mutombo's oft he world, or else tried to swindle other
teams by offering little in return: Like Lenard for Atlanta's J.R.
Rider.
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to a deadly silent deadline, and should mean
that the free-agent period will be extremely active, as teams saved
their salary-cap money to sign players this summer.
</P>
<P>
   All is not forgiven: Hornets guard Eldridge Recasner was act
ivated this week, after missing most of the season with a broken
shoulder, collapsed lung and other internal injuries suffered in an
automobile accident on Oct. 27. Recasner was a passenger in a car
driven by Hornets forward Derrick Coleman, who turned in front of
an oncoming truck to cause the collision.
</P>
<P>
   Recasner is still upset with Coleman over the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows what happened,'' Recasner said. ``It doesn't
matter what the courts said, I don't think. Everybody knows what
the deal was. I don't want to make a big deal out of it because
it's in the past, but it's nothing I've forgotten about, believe
me. I don't want to make a big issue out of it, but I'll never
forget that. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman was acquitted of DWI charges after the accident, but
Recasner is upset that Coleman waited more than a week to call and
see if he was OK .
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into time frames, but whatever length of
time it was, it wasn't satisfactory to me,'' Recasner said. ``If I
did that to somebody, I would want to be there to see how they were
doing, and I didn' t feel that was the case. So nine days or
whatever it was, there's no excuse for that to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman has said he plans to talk to Recasner, but Recasner said
it is too late to patch up any differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much time has passed, so I just want to move on,''
Recasner said.
</P>
<P>
   The bus stops here: The funniest scene of the week had to be in
Minneapolis, where Clippers forward Maurice Taylor refused to get
off the team bus when it arrived at the Target Center, because he
was upset that the team had not traded him.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was so upset a trade to the New York Knicks fell through
that he initially refused to get off the team bus when it arrived
at Target Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frustrated,'' Taylor said. ``They had a chance to get a
couple of first-round picks . . . evidently they chose not to, and
again that shows you what type of organization they are. If they're
going to risk losing free agents on their team that have some type
of value to them for nothing . . . that's just the story of the
Clippers. That's what they do every year. They have free agents,
and they lose them for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brew town blues: Warriors forward Jason Caffey tried to kill a
potential trade to Milwaukee this week by ripping the city. Caffey
said Milwaukee was ``terrible'' and that Bucks coach George Karl
``knows ( Milwaukee's) messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade, which would have sent Caffey and Adonal Foyle to the
Bucks for Robert Traylor, J.R. Reid and a first-round draft pick,
never materialized. But Karl felt it necessary to defend the city's
honor anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who live their lifestyles on judgments of cities,
to me that's kind of a low judgment of your intelligence,'' Karl
said. ``A guy on a losing team that's struggled for years, for him
to say that . . . it (ticks) me off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Caffey still wasn't backing down after being told of Karl's
comments. ``If I'm dealt at the end of the season,'' he said,
``that's obviously my destiny. As long as it's not that place
(Milwaukee).''
</P>
<P>
   On second thought: Two weeks ago, the Celtics traded Danny
Fortson to Toronto, before the Celtics killed the deal after Rick
Pitino was savaged by the Beantown media.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Pitino is now claiming the Celtics want to re-sign
Fortson, who is a free-agent after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably a bad gamble, but I'm going to make it. We'll
see if I can sign him,'' Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   The flip-flop is only the latest example of why players can't
stand Pitino.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
