<HEADLINE>
MASS. GOVERNOR STUMPS FOR BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ With his candidate trailing badly in
statewide polls, Governor Paul Cellucci set off on a bus tour
across the state Saturday, promising a ``massive'' get-out-the-vote
effort for George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But during Cellucci's few minutes in front of City Hall, where
he was kissing babies and touting the Texas governor's bid for the
Republican nomination, a crowd of only about 100 Bush supporters
braved the cold drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the rally, Cellucci acknowledged polls
showing Bush trailing his main opponent, John McCain, by nearly 2
to 1 in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have our work cut out for us,'' he said. Avoiding
a comparison to Michigan Governor John Engler, who endorsed Bush
but couldn't deliver the election, Cellucci said: ``As you know, we
have a very narrow Republican base here.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's road tour Saturday also ferried him and scores of
sign-toting Bush backers to Haverhill, Lowell, and Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Texas governor's devotees in Worcester described
Bush as an inclusive candidate whose calls for deep tax cuts
awakened fond memories of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Toussaint, a 53-year-old Haitian immigrant, said it
didn't bother him that Bush addressed Bob Jones University in South
Carolina, which bans interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush should do whatever he has to do to consolidate his
base,'' Toussaint said. ``He doesn't have to change every group he
speaks to.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he agrees with most of Bush's conservative views, the
real reason he attended Saturday's rally was because of Cellucci.
``I trust Paul Cellucci, and that's why I will vote for Bush,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Petitti, a 68-year-old developer, said he'll vote for
Bush, even if he has to ``drop a notch or two in arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   While there has been a steady stream of Bush supporters
trickling into McCain's camp, Cellucci reaffirmed his commitment to
Bush and observed the oddity of an increasing number of Democrats
voting for McCain, a self-described social conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``My decision to endorse Bush is rock solid,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
