u a BC-DIALLO-POLICE-BOS &LR;      02-26 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-POLICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER VERDICTS, SEEKING ANSWERS IN NYPD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now that the four officers who killed Amadou Diallo
have been found not guilty of any crime, the focus is shifting to
what many call the ``unindicted codefendant'' _ the New York Police
Department itself.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdicts on Friday, many community leaders, street
protesters, and Democratic politicians began to pose the questions
first raised when the shooting took place a year ago:
</P>
<P>
   Is there something about the training methods, the hiring
practices, or the social culture of the department that drove these
four white plainclothes officers, all members of the elite Street
Crime Unit, to fire 41 bullets at a short, slight West African
immigrant as he stood unarmed in the vestibule of his Bronx
apartment building?
</P>
<P>
   The officers said, and the jury apparently believed, that they
thought Diallo was pulling a pistol from his pocket _ not, as it
turned out, a wallet. Still, the question has buzzed for a year:
Why should suspicion trigger 41 bullets?
</P>
<P>
   And how much of what happened that night reflected a word that
has loomed over every discussion of this shooting, but went
unmentioned during the trial _ race?
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to some impressions, shootings by this city's
40,000-member police force are rare and getting rarer. Police fired
their weapons 155 times last year, killing 11 people, according to
department statistics. This was down from 249 shootings, killing
19, the year before, which was down from 317, killing 31, the year
before that. Going back further, police killed 41 civilians in
1990, and averaged 63 killings a year in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   However, in recent years, New York police have assumed a more
aggressive presence, especially in black neighborhoods. In some
respects, this has been welcome, as crime has fallen most sharply
in those areas. But it has also aggravated racial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly true of the Street Crime Unit, a force of
380 officers with the mandate of ridding the city of guns. They
roam the city unshackled by the boundaries of precincts. Until
recently, their motto was ``We Own the Street,'' and they wore
T-shirts quoting Hemingway on hunting humans: ``Those who have
hunted armed men long enough, and liked it, never really care for
anything else thereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   They are told to be aggressive. Unofficially, they get monthly
gun-nabbing quotas. And they follow their directives with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and 1998, according to a study by the state attorney
general, they stopped and frisked 45,000 people. This resulted in
9,000 arrests involving gun possession.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, that meant a lot fewer guns on the street. On
the other, it meant 36,000 innocent people had been frisked.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the frisking officers were white. Almost all the
frisked citizens were black. The officers were seen as an
occupation force.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had no business sending four white police to patrol a
black neighborhood that night,'' the Rev. Betty Neal, a black
minister who often counsels police and has close relations with
Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir,
said of the night Diallo was shot.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Diallo shooting, 80 percent of Street Crime
Unit officers were white, 16 percent were Hispanic, and 3 percent
were black. Afterward, Safir opened up 50 slots for minority
officers. Now, 64 percent of the unit's officers are white, 19
percent are Hispanic, and 16 percent are black.
</P>
<P>
   One concern is that the unit's racial composition, still far
whiter than the neighborhoods it patrols, affects not only the
residents but also the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Julian, who was the department's personnel commissioner
during William J. Bratton's tenure as police chief, said of the
officers who shot Diallo, ``They were overwhelmed by fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else, Julian said, could explain their having fired so
many bullets. Two officers, Sean Carroll and Edward McMellon, who
stood closest to Diallo, unloaded their 9mm pistols, each
containing 16 bullets. (The other two, Kenneth Boss and Richard
Murphy, fired five and four bullets, respectively.)
</P>
<P>
   Carl Clay, a Queens filmmaker who has made documentaries for
schools and youth groups on how black men should behave when
stopped by police, said: ``Some officers have a level of fear, just
being in a certain community. Their perception is `I'm working in a
jungle.' The people they stop and frisk, they see as `street
trash.' They automatically think, `He looks like a criminal,' which
sometimes really just means he's black and he's doing something a
little unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian said: ``If you send people out in the street and tell
them they're going to approach people in high-crime areas, you have
to give them specific commands on what's allowed by law.'' In his
mind, the four officers who shot Diallo, especially the two who
unloaded their pistols, ``weren't properly prepared for the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Several critics have suggested a reemphasis on ``community
policing,'' the concept of putting more police officers on foot
patrol, with the idea that walking the streets makes them better
acquainted with a neighborhood and thus with how to deal with
people in it.
</P>
<P>
   The officers who shot Diallo testified that they had seen
Diallo's street as being infested with crime. In fact, while drugs
are sold nearby, Diallo's block is fairly middle-class, with
well-kept two-story apartments, cars parked on the street, no
graffiti, and little crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9530 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-POPE-EGYPT-BOS &LR;      02-26 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-EGYPT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE MAKES PILGRIMAGE TO MOUNT SINAI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. CATHERINE, Egypt _ Pope John Paul II came Saturday to Mount
Sinai to rise above the ancient enmities and modern politics of the
Middle East and reflect on the covenant God made here with his
people.
</P>
<P>
   In this millennial year, ``our faith leads us to become pilgrims
in the footsteps of God,'' John Paul said at an outdoor service at
the Monastery of St. Catherine, which dates to the sixth century
AD.
</P>
<P>
   In a garden shaded by olive and almond trees at the base of
Sinai's pink granite slope, the pope spoke of how his personal
pilgrimage was part of a history that began with Moses in a
redemptive story that binds Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.
</P>
<P>
   As a dry gust swept down from the mountaintop, John Paul said,
``That wind carries an insistent invitation to dialogue between the
followers of the great monotheistic religions.''
</P>
<P>
   The steep, two-hour hike up a footpath and ancient stairs that
lead to the summit was out of the question for the ailing but
resilient 79-year-old pontiff. Even pilgrims less than half his age
struggled with the ascent.
</P>
<P>
   He was too frail to climb a set of stairs at the base of the
mountain that would have given him a direct view. Instead, John
Paul circled by plane the craggy summit of Mount Sinai to
contemplate the spot where the Bible says Moses received the Ten
Commandments from God.
</P>
<P>
   The pope, known for his indefatigable desire to travel the world
in the name of God, fulfilled a lifelong dream in coming to Mount
Sinai, Vatican officials said. The pope has described this first
leg of a pilgrimage that will continue next month in Jordan,
Israel, and Palestinian-ruled Bethlehem, as ``the coronation'' of a
22-year reign that has included 90 foreign trips.
</P>
<P>
   The Sinai was the wilderness through which the Israelites
wandered for 40 years in search of the Promised Land. Local legend
holds that the monastery sits on the site of the burning bush,
where Moses received a command to lead his people out of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the monastery, the legendary site of the bush is the base
of a chapel altar. The bush itself, legend holds, was planted in a
sunny corner of a courtyard inside the walls of the monastery. The
pope spent nearly an hour of meditation there, receiving a sprig of
the bush from the monks of this Greek Orthodox monastery.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's spiritual journey marked a quiet change of focus from
the first two days of his three-day visit to Egypt, when he
delivered more contemporary statements on the needs for improved
Muslim-Christian relations. That call resonated in the wake of
Muslim-Christian tensions that erupted last month in the worst
sectarian strife Egypt had seen in decades.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit to Sinai was part of his efforts to build
bridges between the Roman Catholic church and the Greek Orthodox
church, which broke apart in 1054.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit to St. Catherine's, where only 20 monks live
but which is one of the most important sites in Greek Orthodoxy,
was laden with historical significance. But it was not without its
moments of tension.
</P>
<P>
   Greek Orthodox Archbishop Damianos, senior cleric of the
monastery, had refused permission for the pope to hold a service
inside the chapel. After presenting the pope with gifts, including
several of the monastery's icons of Jesus and the Virgin Mary,
Damianos and his monks left the stage and conducted a separate
ritual because the two churches do not have, Damianos said, ``an
ecclesiastical communion.''
</P>
<P>
   After the pope's visit, Damianos was asked if a reunion between
the two churches could ever be achieved. He replied, ``It is
possible, but it would take a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the backdrop of tensions, John Paul seemed focused on
delving into Catholic dogma and the place of the Ten Commandments
in Catholic theology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ten Commandments now make themselves heard through the
voice of the beloved son,'' he said, reading his sermon from a
gilded throne.
</P>
<P>
   ``God revealed man to man himself,'' he said, stopping on the
phrase and repeating it, and looking out at the 1,000 pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was mostly composed of Egypt's minority Copts in this
overwhelming Muslim country. Only about 200,000 of the estimated 5
million Christians are Roman Catholic. Scores of American and
European pilgrims also journeyed into the desert wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was US Army Sergeant-Major Daryl Niles, 41, of
Fitchburg, Mass., who commands a unit within the international
peacekeeping operation in the Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides my kids being born, this is the most exciting moment
of my life,'' he said. ``The message he has sent out for world
peace makes you very proud as a Catholic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
