<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLD-RDFOUR0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods coasts into the finals
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ It won't be the ideal matchup for today's
36-hole final of the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship _
No. 1 in the world, in other words, against No. 2 _ but don't blame
Tiger Woods. He did his part. David Duval's the one who stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Playing as perfectly as he can play, Woods, the world's No. 1
player by more than the rankings indicate, Saturday dismantled Sea
Island's Davis Love III 5 and 4 in the semifinals, going 8 under
par for 14 holes at the La Costa Resort and Spa, to coast into the
finals of the $5 million event.
</P>
<P>
   The upset came in the other semifinal as Ireland's Darren
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, the 19th seed, eliminated No. 2 Duval, 4 and 2, and
ruined a chance for the world's top two players to meet
head-to-head with a million bucks up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the last two European Ryder Cup teams, Clarke, 31,
upended Duval at the top of his game, too. After pounding Scott
Hoch in the morning quarterfinals, Duval never led against Clarke
and lost the lead for good on the 5th hole, where the Irishman hit
his approach to four feet and birdied.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, meanwhile, basically toyed with Love, the world's No. 4
player, who had strung together three matches without a bogey.
Woods shot a front nine of 30 for a 4-up lead and breezed in. He is
a huge favorite today over Clarke in a battle of two players
coached by Butch Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely the best I've played in a while,'' Woods said.
``It's nice to go out there and execute the golf shots the way I
know I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who 24 hours before had relished an opportunity to return
to a role as Woods' main challenger, took a step backward with the
semifinal loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my own fault,'' Duval said. ``I just didn't get close
enough to the hole. I wasn't really thinking ahead. Unlike the
American public who might not know Darren, I'm not foolish enough
to look past him. . . You make 15 pars and a birdie at this point
and you're going to lose. I got what I deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is 6-1 in career 36-hole finals, his only loss coming to
Mark O'Meara, 1-up, in the 1998 Cisco World Match Play in England.
Although 36 holes are not needed to identify the best player in the
world, Woods likes the fairness of the format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because if you get off to a bad start, you can make it
up,'' Woods said. ``The best player that day is going to win the
match. In 18 holes, the best player doesn't necessarily win.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory by Woods would give him wins in all of the World Golf
Championships _ and three straight. While considering them less
than a major championship in importance, he said, ``I think anytime
you get to play against the best players, it's going to be more
special than a normal tour event.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
