<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMISSIONS-REAL-1150(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING SIDES IN THE 6 PERCENT EVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The deed, dated July 20, 1668, conveys a 15,000-acre
swath of northern New Jersey, now including the Borough of
Rutherford, from Tantaqua, a chief of the Lenni Lenape Indian
Nation, to an Englishman, William Sandford, ``for the following
consideration:
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred and seventy fathoms of black wampum, 200 fathoms
of white wampum, 19 watch coats, 17 guns, 60 double hands of
powder, 10 pair of breeches, 60 knives, 67 bars of lead, 1 anker of
brandy, 3 half vats of beer'' and various other items.
</P>
<P>
   The commission on the deal, said Peter Van Winkle, a Rutherford
real estate broker _ tongue slightly inserted in cheek _ ``was
probably 6 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been, because 6 percent has long been the
customary commission,'' said Van Winkle, who offers historical
perspective on such matters. It was in 1692 that his
great-great-great-great-great-great-great-great-great grandfather,
Waling Jacob Van Winkle, founded the Rutherford real estate firm
that still bears the family name.
</P>
<P>
   So how far back does the traditional 6 percent brokers'
commission on residential deals go? ``Certainly as far as I know,''
said Van Winkle, ``and as far as what my father told me, and his
father before that.''
</P>
<P>
   So far back that the 6 percent figure seems etched in stone _ at
least in the minds of many, and maybe most, real estate customers.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not.
</P>
<P>
   And in recent years, some brokers have been chipping away at
that set-in-stone perception _ advertising their willingness to
negotiate commissions or even to offer flat-rate fees _ despite the
fierce and often carefully reasoned resistance of their peers. One
broker in Queens said his firm takes a ``Home Depot, Priceline
approach, where you can name your own price,'' much to the chagrin
of his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   It is a phenomenon impelled, particularly over the last five
years, by a housing market in which listings are precious, prices
are high and homeowners can be demanding _ a classic seller's
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most dreaded words in our industry are `Will you take
less?''' said Barbara Corcoran, chairwoman of the Manhattan
brokerage firm that bears her name. ``The commission we charge as a
firm is 6 percent, but we're constantly questioned.'' Ten days ago
the Corcoran Group held an in-house seminar for its sales agents to
discuss strategies for ``Holding On to That 6 Percent Commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Halstead, founder of Halstead Property Co., is adamant
about holding the 6 percent line. ``If you needed brain surgery,''
he asked, ``would you negotiate a lower price with your surgeon?
You would probably decide you need the best expertise and be
willing to pay.'' Lower commissions, he insisted, mean diminished
interest by potential co-brokers from other firms, leading to
decreased exposure to the market and, consequently, less than top
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, brokers' commissions have been entirely negotiable
since 1950 when, in a case called United States vs. National
Association of Real Estate Boards (predecessor to the current
National Association of Realtors), the Supreme Court ruled that
fixed commission schedules constituted restraint of trade under the
Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokers can never discuss the commission among themselves,''
said Barbara Frechter, president of Glenjay Realty in Forest Hills
and past president of the Long Island Board of Realtors. ``I can
only discuss it with my sales agents, not with another brokerage''
_ which might end up splitting the commission, assuming one firm
takes the listing from the seller and the other finds the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people teach sales classes,'' said Frechter, ``they say,
`X commission,' without the number, because it's such a stringent
law. And in the '80s, when you joined the real estate board, they
showed you a movie and the jail door slams shut to teach you that
you are never to discuss the commission with another broker.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that 1950 Supreme Court ruling, and subsequent legal
opinions that bolstered the high court's original finding, there
have been varying attempts at discounting commissions _ both by
brokers and sellers; most legal, some questionable; some
profitable, others not.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days,'' Frechter said, ``a seller might tell you:
`This is what I want for the house; anything you get above that is
yours.' It's called a net commission. But, by law, you can't take a
listing that way. You have to tell the person what the commission
is up front.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Eileen Scott is a sales agent for Van Winkle. But in
the late '80s, Scott said, ``my husband and I opened a Help-U-Sell
franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fixed-rate commission: $3,450 for a house priced up
to $150,000,'' she said. ``After that it switched to $4,450. That
was it.''
</P>
<P>
   For that set fee, Scott would help her clients sell their homes.
``They would do their own advertising, and also the showings,'' she
said. ``We would put a sign up: `For Sale By Owners, Assisted by
Help-U-Sell.'''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't survive, because of the expenses of running an
office and charging such low commissions,'' Scott said. And the
timing for the Help-U-Sell franchise company was unfortunate _ a
depressed housing market. ``The promises were that we would capture
at least 10 percent of the market, whereas, after the first year,
it was more like 4 percent,'' Scott said. ``By the third year,
after we lost all of our money, we closed the doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Help-U-Sell, which had about 100 franchises, was
bought by American Pacific Financial Corp., and now it has 158
franchises nationwide _ seven in the New York area. ``It was ahead
of its time in the '80s,'' said Rick O'Neil, Help-U-Sell's
president.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Scott and Van Winkle hold a decided preference for
the standard fee. ``Most of our residential commissions are 6
percent, but on occasion we do deviate,'' Van Winkle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter and I agree that if you need to take 5 percent, you take
5 percent,'' Scott said. ``But in the long run, when you consider
the expenses, we'd rather get our 6 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, on the other hand, newspaper advertisements placed
by Fleet Street Properties Co. in Rego Park, Queens, have asked,
``Why Pay More Than 4?''
</P>
<P>
   The logic of the question seemed unassailable to Nicholas
Cerrito Jr. Cerrito, 40, an air freight dispatcher, has lived with
his wife, Marie, and two children in Babylon, on Suffolk County's
South Shore, for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I bought a rental property in North Babylon in 1992,''
Cerrito said. Last year the Cerritos put that rental home on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend told me about Fleet Street, that they only charge 4
percent,'' Cerrito said. ``I had it on the market for $137,000; 30
days later, I closed for $135,000.'' Cerrito was pleased with the 4
percent, rather than 6 percent, commission. The difference, in cash
to him, was $2,700.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Henry is president of Fleet Street Properties. ``We've
been in business here for 54 years,'' Henry said. ``For the past
five years, we're doing this special deal: 4 percent. We put it on
the multiple listing service under LIBOR'' _ the Long Island Board
of Realtors, which lists 1,550 brokerage firms _ ``and we split
50-50 with the selling broker.''
</P>
<P>
   For sellers who would like to negotiate with buyers themselves,
Henry said, ``We have a program where we will list a property with
the MLS'' _ for a flat fee of $199.95 _ ``and they can name the
commission they wish to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry said he recommends that the seller choose a 3 percent
commission, ``because this is what the selling broker would get on
a 6 percent split, and we still have the right to get the 3
percent, if we sell it ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his company's ``Home Depot, Priceline approach,'' he said,
``We're doing a good business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, five years ago,'' he said, ``they threatened us with
lawsuits, the other brokers. We got calls saying, `You're killing
the business. We're not going to sell your listing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not killing anything,'' Henry insisted. ``Now they've
capitulated and they can't get enough of our listings. They seem to
accept that splitting 4 percent is better than splitting nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even splitting 3 percent _ on a property selling for $1 million
or more _ can be profitable, said John P. Noonan, past president of
the Brooklyn Board of Realtors and president of the Park Slope
brokerage firm that bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had this huge increase in real estate values and there's
certainly a lot of room to negotiate and still get a handsome
commission,'' Noonan said, citing several factors bearing on his
decision to accept a commission lower than 6 percent. His primary
consideration would be if the homeowner gave Noonan's company the
exclusive right to sell the home, without the participation of a
broker representing the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal feeling is that if a seller gives an exclusive to
a broker, it's certainly worthy of a reduced commission payment,''
he said. ``You're not competing with other brokers and it's a more
comfortable way of working.'' The listing broker, in that instance,
would keep the entire commission.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being granted an exclusive, Noonan said he would
consider a reduced commission if he had several ``good prospects''
lined up to buy the property promptly, and if the house was
appropriately priced in the current market. ``And certainly if I'm
involved in a bidding war between clients from different brokers, I
would cut a commission to make the deal work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would negotiate commissions on a home priced for
less than $1 million, Henry said: ``We don't see $100,000 houses
any more; if we see anything below $300,000, it's a rarity. So any
of these could be negotiable, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous wrinkles exist in the seller-broker relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, there are two opportunities during the marketing
process for a seller to seek a reduced commission: at the time the
listing agreement is being written, and again when a deal with a
buyer is about to be reached.
</P>
<P>
   At listing time, the broker's resistance to a reduction may be
stiffer, probably prompting the argument that a lower commission
will dampen the interest of all the other brokers who belong to the
multiple listing service.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, at the time the deal is about to be struck, the
broker says to the seller something like, ``Your asking price was
$250,000, we have an offer for $225,000,'' the seller could say,
``Cut your commission a bit and we have a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens occasionally,'' said Michael Finder, a real estate
lawyer in Manhattan. ``A seller might try to persuade a broker to
reduce the commission to conclude the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   A seller has no obligation to accept anything less than the
listed price. Yet, as Finder pointed out, ``once the broker does
produce a purchaser willing and able to pay that asking price, the
seller runs the risk of litigation with the broker if the seller
refuses to proceed with the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some listing agreements tie the commission fee to a specific
asking price, but most commissions are tied to a certain percentage
of the final purchase price. ``Almost always,'' said John Hall,
former chairman of the real property section of the New York State
Bar Association, ``the commission is computed as a percentage of
the selling price, rather than a percentage of the listing price.''
And in some cases, a flat commission amount is agreed upon,
regardless of the selling price, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a theory on all this bargaining,'' said Corcoran of the
Corcoran Group: ``that sellers believe that apartments today sell
themselves _ and they're right.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the torrid market of today, Corcoran said, ``where
brokers truly earn their money is in 10 times the number of
showings and navigating the bidding wars through the feeding
frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   R. Kenyatta Punter, president of the Greater Harlem Real Estate
Board, and of the brokerage firm that bears his name, points out
that commissions may also rise. ``It can be indicative of a
property that is unusually difficult to unload,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, rooming houses are difficult to sell, because
financing is not readily available for that type of building,''
Punter said, ``although they are getting scooped up for family use
in my community.''
</P>
<P>
   In a case like that, a broker might ask for 7 percent, Punter
said, ``vs. a building on a very desirable block, say a brownstone
on Striver's Row or Hamilton Terrace. A broker there may be willing
to take 5 percent because it tends to move quickly, because of
demand in that marquee location.''
</P>
<P>
   Halstead, however, believes that bargaining is bad business _
for both the broker and the seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two tools a seller needs to be certain he's getting
the best price,'' Halstead said. ``One is a battle-hardened,
energetic broker with a full quiver of marketing arrows. The other
is a full competitive commission, because what the seller wants is
all the brokers in town motivated to show his property.''
</P>
<P>
   His company, Halstead said, has 250 agents. Once the listing is
shared with members of the Real Estate Board of New York, he said:
``That brings several thousand agents and their customers in. And
the point is that what the seller wants is as many interested
parties as soon as possible in order to ensure the best price.''
</P>
<P>
   Halstead did the math to illustrate how reduced commissions
squeeze brokers.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, a Manhattan apartment sells for $1 million, the
standard commission would be $60,000 with, most likely, a 50-50
split between the listing brokerage firm and the firm that found
the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, for the listing firm,'' Halstead said, ``of the
$30,000 received by them, 50 percent goes to the sales agent,
leaving $15,000 to address marketing expenses and overhead. For a
$1 million property, marketing expenses could easily be, say,
$5,000 to $7,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Those expenses would include, in Halstead's evaluation, ``the
most expensive agate advertising in the world _ that's classified
advertising _ offered by The New York Times at $18 a line,'' before
quantity discounts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, ``We have to take photographs, put the
property on our Web sites; do a brochure or a fancy oversized
postcard. We have to hold open houses, if the board allows. And we
do mailings to people in the building and in the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   For a multimillion-dollar property, display advertising might be
required in glossy publications like Quest or Avenue, or in The
Times' Sunday magazine, he said, ``and we're talking there, now,
rates of $8,000 for a quarter page.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the economic realities of operating a real estate
brokerage,'' Halstead said.
</P>
<P>
   Just such realities prompted an audacious experiment two years
ago by Long &AMP; Foster, the largest brokerage firm in Washington _ a
standardized commission of 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me give you the Washington plea,'' said Wes Foster Jr.,
the company's president. ``In the last 15 years, the amount of
money the company has left after we've paid our sales agent _ what
we call the company dollar; it's what we use to pay our overhead
and hopefully have something left over _ has dropped from around 45
cents of the whole dollar to 29 cents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a national problem,'' Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``A total, ugly failure,'' Foster said. ``We wish we'd never
done it. It cost us market share, and we backed away quickly, in a
couple or three months. But it stuck with some of the public and
made them angry with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Long &AMP; Foster has since expanded into titles, mortgages and
insurance, ``so that we can give the customer a one-stop shop,''
Foster said, ``and us a chance to make a little more profit.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, he said, the struggle is on to maintain the 6
percent commission, ``which we really need to stay in business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're doing OK because it's a good market,'' Foster
said. ``But I can tell you this: when another slow market comes,
you're going to see real estate companies going out of business
left and right, because the margin is too slim. It's tough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
