<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9542 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-HEBERT-LADN     02-26 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HEBERT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEBERT LOOKS TO EARN BACK RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- After nearly seven years of smooth driving, Guy
Hebert has been in the pits the last week or so trying to get tuned
up for the Western Conference playoff drive.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, who prides himself on playing his best in big games, is
expected to play tonight against Edmonton, but that only after
hours of work with Mighty Ducks goalie consultant Francois Allaire
and some serious self-examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a swift kick in the pants and to gain the respect of my
teammates and coaches back,'' said Hebert, who is 1-2-1 and has
allowed 19 goals in his last four starts.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Hebert sitting on the bench while Dominic Roussel played
against St. Louis and Calgary was a strange sight considering
Hebert's reputation being an iron man of sorts in the final halves
of seasons. He played 69 games last year as he helped lead the
Ducks into the playoffs. Hebert also led a late-season charge into
the 1996-97 playoffs and nearly got the Ducks into the postseason
in '95-96.
</P>
<P>
   Allaire, a studious looking French-Canadian who happens to be
one of hockey's most repected goaltending instructors, has been
acting as a crew chief of sorts for Hebert, who hasn't started
since Feb. 18 when he allowed three third-period goals in a 4-4 tie
versus San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NHL is like Formula One (racing), the car has to be
perfectly tuned up, so you can put your foot on the gas and go,''
said Allaire. ``When you have two wheels on the side of the road,
you are no faster than a Volkswagen.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally a slow starter, the 33-year old goalie got off to an
excellent start this season. He was among the league leaders in
save percentage, goals against average, wins and shutouts through
mid-December. But since suffering a strained neck in a 8-2 loss to
Phoenix on Dec. 22, Hebert's performance has been wildly
inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Challenged by Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg to step up his play
heading into a crucial five-game road trip, Hebert responded by
stopping 158 of 169 shots as the Ducks went 3-0-2. He was
especially brilliant in ties at Buffalo and Philadelphia, kicking
out 94 of 99 shots.
</P>
<P>
   But Hebert, generously listed as 5-foot-11, 186 pounds, was run
over in the last three games of Anaheim's trip. Keith Primeau, the
Flyers' 6-4, 210-pound crashed into him in Philadelphia. The Kings'
Jason Blake got away with a flagrant elbow to Hebert's head in
Anaheim's victory at Staples Center on Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Hebert has stopped only 83 of 102 shots. He admits
his neck isn't 100 percent, but refuses to blame his woes on his
physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm healthy enough to stay in there, then there are no
problems,'' insists Hebert. ``I've had enough excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows excuses mean little at this time of year anyway --
``there's nowhere to hide,'' he said. ``But every night there's a
chance to be a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   For four years Hebert has been a hero more often than not, since
being acquired by the Ducks in the 1993 expansion draft. After
playing only 37 games for the Blues, Hebert has carved a memorable
career in Anaheim, where he owns virtually all of the team's
goaltending records, including games (381), wins (152) and shutouts
(24). Last season he set career highs in wins (31), shutouts (6),
goals against average (2.42) and save percentage (.922).
</P>
<P>
   An easy-going sort as goalies come -- ``for me to play my best I
have to be happy, on an even keel,'' -- Hebert has been frustrated
as of late. He is still msytified at how Vincent Damphousse's sharp
angle shot bounced off his glove in the San Jose and readily admits
``I've haven't been at the top of my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, along with Roussel, have also been the victim of Anaheim
defensive zone breakdowns as the Ducks have given an average of 4.4
goals a game in their last seven contests.
</P>
<P>
   But the only player to be with the Ducks since the franchise
began play in 1993, isn't ready to point fingers at anybody but
himself, especially since he has seen his save percentage drop from
over .920 to .907.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (his time between starts) gives me a chance to look in the
mirror and I realize I haven't done enough to help the team win,''
he said. ``I have to get back on the top of my game.''
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of doing that Hebert said he tried to pick up his
practice intensity instead of relying on the rhythm he might build
between good performances. And nobody helps him pick up that
intensity like Allaire. The goalie gruru also studies tapes of
recent games to pick out any flaws or trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, he works you very hard,'' said Hebert. ``If there
is something major he can pick it out right away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have great intensity of practice to be able to
play a solid 60 minutes without mental or physical lapses,'' said
Allaire. ``If the body is strong, the mental is part is strong too.
</P>
<P>
   For player who has become such a fan favorite at The Pond -- the
chant Guy, Guy, Guy has become a mantra of sorts -- Hebert plays a
very unspectacular style when he is going good. Flashy glove saves
or two-pad slides aren't his trademark, and that's fine by him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in control, the less I'm noticed the better,''
said Hebert, who knows full well that the less his play is a topic
of conversation the better the Ducks' playoff chances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
