<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLITEMS0227-COX     02-26 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLITEMS0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How we rank them
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. New Jersey. The Devils lost only five of their first 32 home
games. No need to ask how important home ice is in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   2. Toronto. Darcy Tucker has given the Maple Leafs some
toughness. A physical defenseman would be the missing piece to a
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   3. Philadelphia. The Flyers aren't overwhelming anybody, but
what do you expect when they can dress in All-Star team in the
trainer's room, with Eric Lindros and Keith Primeau?
</P>
<P>
   4. Florida. Goalie Trevor Kidd is back; unfortunately, the same
defense is in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   5. Washington. Just in case the Panthers thought the Capitals
would fold, Chris Simon sent a message by scoring the overtime
winner the other night.
</P>
<P>
   6. Ottawa. Senators owner Rod Bryden says the team isn't moving.
He didn't say how long that guarantee is good for.
</P>
<P>
   7. Buffalo. Whatshisname's return in goal has the Sabres
climbing back into a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   8. Pittsburgh. Jaromir Jagr's hamstring pull might pull the plug
on the Penguins' playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. St. Louis. The Blues are so good, even enigmatic forward
Stephane Richer looks as if he cares again.
</P>
<P>
   2. Dallas. Goalie Ed Belfour has kept the Stars near the top
despite injuries.
</P>
<P>
   3. Detroit. There might be nothing to the Chris Osgood trade
rumors, but the Red Wings' goalie and the defense in front of him
are struggling.
</P>
<P>
   4. Phoenix. The Coyotes have held together despite missing their
best player, Keith Tkachuk, but they need to add a physical
defenseman before the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   5. Colorado. The Avs still might have the best talent in the
West, but injuries and seeming lack of control by coach Bob Hartley
is starting to wear them down.
</P>
<P>
   6. Edmonton. Kevin Lowe has the young team higher in the
standings than anyone expected. If the goaltending holds up, look
out.
</P>
<P>
   7. Los Angeles. After a brief slumber, the Kings' offense is
rolling again -- seven goals on 48 shots against Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   8. San Jose. Goalie Steve Shields is starting to make the Sharks
regret they traded Mike Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   NO SURPRISES
</P>
<P>
   Florida has been atop the Southeast Division all season but it's
not because of any miraculous comebacks. The Panthers are one of
only two teams that hasn't won a game after trailing after two
periods. Following are the teams who have the best and worst
records after losing the first 40 minutes:
</P>
<P>
   Best W-L-T Worst W-L-T
</P>
<P>
   1. Dallas 7-15-2 28. San Jose 0-19-2
</P>
<P>
   2. New Jersey 4-10-2 27. Florida 0-14-1
</P>
<P>
   3. Ottawa 5-16-2 26. N.Y. Islanders 1-30-2
</P>
<P>
   4. St. Louis 4-13-3 25. Chicago 1-23-1
</P>
<P>
   5. Phoenix 3-12-2 24 Buffalo 1-21-1
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   Canadiens goalie Jeff Hackett went 7-1-1 (including a shutout of
Phoenix) in a span of nine starts _ and illogically, is central to
several trade rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders goalie Kevin Weekes, who flopped in Vancouver, is
3-1-1 with a 1.77 goals-against in his last five starts, including
wins over neighboring Devils and Rangers and a tie with the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   So much for slowing down: Kings winger Luc Robitaille had 10
goals and 19 points in a span of 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs were hoping they could rejuvenate Wendel Clark.
Wrong. After recording only four points in 16 games, he might be
released soon.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers goalie Mike Richter has missed five games with a knee
injury since the All-Star break, which is linked to the team's dip
in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's Joe Sakic has one goal in his last nine games.
</P>
<P>
   BEST GAME
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's 3-2 overtime win over New Jersey kept the Canadiens
as one of the league's hottest teams _ 13-2-2, including a
seven-game win streak. Montreal surprisingly has resuscitated its
playoff hopes, despite limited offensive talent, while the Devils
began to show cracks atop the Eastern Conference (0-3-1).
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches put the opponent's lineup on the board and circle guys
and say, `You've got to be hard on this guy, finish your check on
this guy, make it difficult for this guy.' Players read into that
to go out and get guys and be physical against them. It starts with
the coaches. Borderline players are going to listen to that because
they don't want to work anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dallas center Mike Modano on dirty play in the NHL
</P>
<P>
   WORTH NOTING
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull became so frustrated the other night with Dallas'
sagging power play that he ripped into his own coaching staff. ``It
doesn't help when you've got power- play units that you practice
with and then you go out in the game and the coach puts different
people with you,'' Hull said. ``You don't know what side you're
working. You don't know who's going where on the breakout. There's
a lot more to blame than the players for the power play.'' Coach
Ken Hitchcock had a meeting with Hull but later attempted to defuse
the comments, saying, ``It's no big deal to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Sergei Fedorov missed four games while trying to find
a brace for his right thumb, which has ligament damage. Fedorov,
who has missed 12 games with injuries this season, might need
surgery in the off-season. He has only 17 goals this season.
</P>
<P>
   Center Bobby Holik wasn't concerned when New Jersey went winless
four games in a row. ``That's just part of the season,'' Holik
said. ``We can lose them now. As long as we don't lose them when
the playoffs start.''
</P>
<P>
   Word is that Pittsburgh coach Herb Brooks hates the job so much
he might not make it through the end of the season. If the
``Miracle Man'' leaves, associate coach Ivan Hlinka would be the
Penguins' third boss this season, following the fired Kevin
Constantine. Brooks wants to go back to scouting and his home in
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that San Jose opened a nine-game homestand. The
bad news is that the Sharks opened it with a loss to St. Louis and
fell to 3-9 in their last 12 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Sharks general manager Dean Lombardi on Blues defenseman Chris
Pronger: ``He's the equivalent of a Dominik Hasek for defensemen
right now. He can completely control a game in all phases.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida planned to auction off a dinner for six with Pavel Bure
for $6,500 at a charity function. Then Bure's South Florida
neighbor and ``friend'' Anna Kournikova said she also would attend
the dinner. Dinner with Pavel and Anna _ or Anna and Pavel _ sold
for $12,500.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates on Jaromir Jagr's return from a hamstring pull range
from 10 days to a month. The Penguins are 1-5-1 this year without
Jagr, 13-17-19 all-time.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING BACK
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Constantine, who clashed with some of Pittsburgh's stars
and was fired as Pittsburgh's coach earlier this season, is dealing
with a more flexible bunch these days. Constantine is helping coach
a youth team and plans to run a coaching clinic and youth camp this
summer. ``I know I'm supposed to take this time and not be in
hockey rinks,'' he said. ``But I've got a small addiction.''
Regarding criticism that has been leveled at him from players since
his departure, Constantine said, ``There's no value in (responding
to) any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sakic got fed up last week with the Avalanche's lackluster
play: ``I mean, you can talk as much as you want in the locker room
and everybody's prepared, everybody's ready. And then we get out
there and we don't do it. It's very frustrating. Everybody says,
`Well, we have to learn from this.' But school's over. Hey, let's
get going.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   One reason Vancouver's Donald Brashear has said little about
Marty McSorley's mugging is that he might file a civil suit. Yes,
there is precedent. In 1975, Detroit's Henry Boucha sued Boston's
Dave Forbes after he was hit in the face with the butt-end of
Forbes' stick and suffered a fractured cheekbone. Criminal charges
were filed, but the case ended in a hung jury. Boucha filed a $3.5
million civil suit, and the matter was settled out of court five
years later. In a similar case, Detroit's Dennis Polonich
successfully sued Kansas City's Wilf Paiement in 1978 and won
$850,000.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent defenseman Mark Tinordi is close to finishing his
rehabilitation from ankle surgery in October and could be close to
signing. At least three teams have interest -- Colorado, St. Louis
and Detroit. Tinordi has missed 96 games in the last three years
with injuries, but the Thrashers selected him from Washington in
the expansion draft. Atlanta wanted no other players on the
Capitals' unprotected list, and the team will receive a
compensatory pick in the June draft when Tinordi signs with another
team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
