<HEADER>
A9549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CALIF-COASTLINE-REAL-     02-26 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-COASTLINE-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CALIFORNIA, HOUSING ON A PLATFORM, STORES DOWNSTAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MORRIS NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDONDO BEACH, Calif. _ Developers in this oceanfront city 15
miles southwest of downtown Los Angeles are building a condominium
community with stores at street level and 98 detached homes atop a
second-level concrete platform.
</P>
<P>
   Known as 1800 PCH _ the address is the project's street address
on Pacific Coast Highway _ the project demonstrates the growing
ingenuity of home builders in carving out space for housing at a
time when housing sites for infill development are growing scarce
along the Southern California coastline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fairly innovative to build a residential structure on a
deck,'' said Aaron Jones, the economic development manager of this
city of 66,000 residents. He called the project ``the first genuine
mixed-use development in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-story detached homes in 1800 PCH will range in size from
1,407 square feet with three bedrooms and two and a half baths, to
1,835 square feet with four bedrooms and two and half baths.
</P>
<P>
   The project is taking shape on a steeply sloping site. At the
bottom of the slope is the Pacific Coast Highway, a busy
thoroughfare lined with low-rise residences and retail strips on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The front entrance of 1800 PCH is a row of stores with a total
of 20,000 square feet of space that front the highway. Behind the
stores, and out of view, is parking for both store customers and
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The garage is covered by the platform, which also serves as the
foundation for the housing on the second level. The housing is on
the same level as the top of the slope, where an existing
neighborhood of apartment buildings borders the project.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the design was to create the feeling of a
pedestrian-oriented neighborhood, according to the developers, a
partnership of Braemar Urban Ventures, of Agoura Hills, Calif., and
Shawbeth Inc. of Glendale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Houses are arranged along pedestrian walkways about 20 feet
wide, or in courtyards around gardens. At the center of the site,
there is a 40-by-55-foot formal rose garden. The garden serves as a
sort of ``village square,'' said Robert T. Steinberg, president of
Steinberg Group of San Jose, Calif., the project architect.
</P>
<P>
   For the landscaping, the biggest challenge was to find a way to
introduce plants and grass onto the concrete platform. The solution
was a species of grass that can grow in a few inches of soil, which
lies in shallow trenches in the concrete floor. Boxed ``orangerie''
trees complete the landscape scheme.
</P>
<P>
   One buyer, Alexis Sheehy, said she was impressed by the car-free
character of the project, which reminded her of pedestrian-only
streets in the neighboring cities of Manhattan Beach and Hermosa
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Sheehy, who is a high-school principal, said that
she and her husband were also attracted to a low-maintenance home
after years of gardening. ``We are empty-nesters, and we're just
looking to reduce the effort and the maintenance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The project represents the confluence of several trends in
California home building.
</P>
<P>
   One is to build detached homes that resemble single-family
housing in increasing densities. This practice accommodates rising
land costs, the shrinking amount of available land for development,
and the continued market preference of buyers who want to own
detached homes in an era of rapidly rising housing prices.
</P>
<P>
   A more conventional approach to developing the project would
have been attached town houses on a single level, according to Avi
Brosh, president of Braemar Urban Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   By building homes without garages, Brosh said, he could almost
double the density. He also found he could have a greater profit
margin by selling detached houses with windows on four sides rather
than attached town houses, which typically have windows on only one
or two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the detached home ``opened the project up to a
larger spectrum of buyers, such as families looking for three and
four bedrooms,'' Brosh said.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from about $349,000 to $436,000. The median price
for both detached houses and town houses in Redondo Beach as a
whole is $378,299, according to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The project's design represents a new concept in increasing the
density of detached housing, according to Steinberg, the architect.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to one popular approach, which consists of
clustering houses around a courtyard or a shared driveway, ``we
have tried to take this idea to another level, by developing a
sense of neighborhood and community, and by providing a mix of uses
on the site, including retail and restaurants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In design, the narrow, two-story houses resemble town houses
rather than the ranch-style houses found elsewhere in the city.
Lots range from 21 to 25 feet wide and from 35 to 40 feet deep and
include a small, fenced-in front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never kidded ourselves into thinking that these homes were
single-family homes in a traditional setting,'' said Brosh, the
developer. ``We had to play a little balancing act'' between
accommodating a high density of units, on the one hand, and
satisfying expectations of privacy and comfort on the part of home
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg called the two-story units ``saltboxes,'' noting their
simple, square shapes and pitched roofs.
</P>
<P>
   The 1800 PCH project reflects the city's intention of
encouraging mixed-use projects that combine housing and commercial
space near important commercial areas. Although common in many East
Coast cities, mixed-use development remains an avant-garde idea in
suburban California.
</P>
<P>
   The city, in fact, developed its new mixed-use ordinance at the
same time it evaluated earlier proposals for what became 1800 PCH.
Among the requests made by the city were setbacks to clearly
separate commercial and residential portions of the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Redondo Beach ordinance encourages mixed-use projects, in an
effort to support commercial parts of the city. The 1800 PCH
project is about a quarter of a mile east of a commercial area
known as the Hollywood Riviera, which includes upscale stores and
small office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   For Brosh, the developer, 1800 PCH is a ``uniquely Californian''
variant of residential mixed use. He thinks many Californians would
be resistant to the conventional approach to mixed-use housing,
with stores on the ground floor and housing above on an urban
street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mixed-use is a new concept for California,'' he said. One
challenge is to accustom middle-class Californians to live in
medium- to high-density housing.
</P>
<P>
   However, Brosh added, a denser project would be ``difficult to
do in California today, because it is not a mainstream kind of
product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9550 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKC-GATECH0227-COX     02-26 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-GATECH0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. Tech club team top-ranked
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_ As miracles on ice go, it isn't exactly Lake Placid,
1980. It's Hockey Night in Alpharetta, however, and that in itself
is a small miracle. Or as Al Michaels might've said, ``Do you
believe in electrical-engineering majors on the power play? Yes!''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Georgia Tech hockey is all about rags to riches,''
said Monal Dhabliwala, a sixth-year senior defenseman. ``We went
from 12:45 a.m. practices _ Tuesday mornings _ to Saturday night 8
o'clock games.''
</P>
<P>
   It's actually a Friday night in The Cooler in Alpharetta and the
last home game of a season to savor, a game that began with
Dhabliwala street clothes and sitting in the stands, the logical
place for a guy with a torn knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I made an agreement with Coach,'' Dhabliwala said. ``If it
was a one-goal game, I'd come in.''
</P>
<P>
   So with Vanderbilt leading 1-0 after two periods, Dhabliwala
suited up and skated out for the third period. ``I probably
shouldn't have, but I did,'' he said. ``My last game.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Dawe's, too. After Nick Olander's goal tied it midway
through the period, Dawe scored a minute later on a wraparound for
a 2-1 victory and tied a bow around the best season in Georgia Tech
hockey history.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a way to go out!'' the sixth-year senior center cried. He
wasn't talking about Bobby Cremins' resignation earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Dawe's final goal in The Cooler improved the Jackets' record to
21-3-1, the best in the 27-year existence of the Georgia Tech Ice
Hockey Club. On Friday, Tech, ranked No. 1 nationally in Division
III of the club-level American Collegiate Hockey Association, plays
Navy in the Division III national playoffs in Annapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a hockey club that is precisely that: A club. Not a
varsity sport. Not a scholarship program. A club sport, a group of
25 or so guys who nearly all are engineering majors and who play
hockey for the purest of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the love of the sport,'' said Dawe, 23, an
electrical-engineering major who played high school hockey in Katy,
Texas. ``We get pretty good fan support but not a lot of
recognition from the school. We have to (budget) our personal time,
be full-time students and full-time athletes. These guys don't do
it for the ego, headlines or notoriety. It's for the love of the
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would a kid come to Tech to play hockey?'' asked Greg
Stathis, the volunteer head coach since 1991. ``It's a great
school. But a kid can play at a high caliber of play. And it's
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Must be. How else to explain driving out of town every Monday
night at 10 for an hour's practice at the Ice Forum, then to The
Cooler each Tuesday at 10:15 p.m. for a 90-minute workout? How else
to put up with driving in vans to road games; all games are played
on Friday and Saturday nights, to avoid missing too much
schoolwork. Or sleeping four to a motel room? Or coughing up $150
apiece each semester to help pay for ice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to know how to balance everything,'' said junior
forward Ryan Dawe, Aaron's younger brother and a computer-science
major. ``Your schoolwork, practices, two games on weekends _ I
probably couldn't handle a varsity sport. This club team is just
right. You have time to have other aspects of your life: A
fraternity, a girlfriend, a social life.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like real students who happen to be able to skate and
slide-rule with the best of 'em. That's part of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hockey team, they're really nice guys,'' said pep band
member Jill Womack, a senior who plays trumpet and sang the
national anthem a cappella before the Vanderbilt game. ``We love
the football team, but they don't know our names. The hockey team
knows our names.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not on a scholarship,'' said Womack, among the pep
band members who voluntarily, eagerly, attend games, even on the
road. ``They're regular guys. They're all smart. They're all
engineers. The football team's all management majors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tech hockey club was founded in 1973. In 1979, the Jackets
joined the new Southern Collegiate Hockey Association, consisting
mainly of ACC and SEC club teams, and moved to College Hockey South
in 1997. Now, Tech has a $50,000 budget, including $13,000 from the
school, thanks largely to corporate sponsorships, sales of Tech
hockey merchandise and players chipping in for ice time. This
year's team was helped by several talented freshmen who played high
school hockey and by the return of Shawn Montague. The sophomore
left wing is the best player in the CHS and Tech's leading scorer
for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Tech ended ACHA Division II Virginia Tech's 34-game winning
streak, won two of three games from N.C. State and twice beat South
Florida, last year's CHS champ. Going 2-0-1 against Georgia was,
well, icing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we're a club, we treat it as a varsity sport,''
Stathis said. ``Eventually, we'd like to go Division II or I. But
it's nice to see the program grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially for guys like Aaron Dawe, who was born in Calgary,
Alberta, and discovered hockey there, but harbors no illusions
about his ability. ``I might have been able to play (minor-league
hockey) somewhere but not make a living,'' said Dawe, who recently
accepted a job offer from Nortel Networks. ``So I do it for the fun
of it now. Then I'll make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
