<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-GOVERNORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AN OPTIMISTIC OUTLOOK, BUSH'S COLLEAGUES OFFER UNWAVERING
SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Ark., N.D., Utah)   (rk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Unshaken in their view that George W. Bush will
vanquish his Republican opponent, the nation's Republican governors
rallied Saturday around Bush, a fellow governor, and said they were
confident voters would embrace the man has who won over many
Democrats, minorities and women in his own state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite Bush's stinging defeats in Michigan and Arizona,
they stressed that Bush must focus his campaign on what appealed to
people in the first place: his pitch for tax cuts and education,
and his record as governor.
</P>
<P>
   The governors, here for a meeting of the National Governors
Association, flocked to Bush's side close to a year ago, throwing a
total of 26 endorsements his way. Saturday, they seemed to be
trying to write his campaign platform for him as they defended one
of their own, arguing that it is Bush, not his challenger Sen. John
McCain, who has long connected with a broad cross section of
voters, including Democrats and moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is, he has brought people together in
Texas,'' said Gov. Mike Huckabee, R-Ark., at a news conference.
``Texans are hard to please. They are nit-picky. They're tough
voters to make happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one thing for George W. Bush to defeat an incumbent
sitting governor in Texas,'' he added. ``That was an incredible
accomplishment in 1994. But the real miracle is that he got nearly
70 percent of the vote in his re-election campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   As the governors took turns praising Bush and pronouncing their
optimism, they also acknowledged that McCain, a man who once called
the governors ``greedy,'' has trampled on their plans, at least for
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the governors agreed to endorse Bush _ with his large
war chest, familiar surname and broad appeal _ as the perfect
antidote to Republican malaise. It did not hurt that Bush, an
advocate of greater power for the states, would also help in their
own fight for greater authority. A few governors even joked about
which one of them would serve as vice president in a Bush
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it is McCain who appears to be the man breaking the
Republican mold, the candidate who can successfully attract the
nation's middle-of-the-road voters, and it is Bush who has become
the more conventional Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some frustration out there,'' said Edward T. Schafer,
the governor of North Dakota and chairman of the Republican
Governors Association. ``No one expected the campaign to be this
close or this mercurial.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has defeated Bush in New Hampshire, Arizona and Michigan,
where the Republican governor worked hard to turn out the vote for
Bush. A cavalcade of Democrats voted for McCain in the open
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush obviously will have to right himself, and he
will,'' Michael O. Leavitt, the governor of Utah and chairman of
the National Governors Association, said Saturday. But, he added,
``The name of the game right now is 1,034 delegates, and I believe
George Bush will have them in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governors will talk privately over the course of
the next few days about strategies for helping Bush reshape his
message to reach moderates and independents in their states,
Leavitt said.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that it was not so much the nuts and bolts of a
campaign _ raising money, turning out the vote _ they needed to
worry about as amplifying Bush's attempt to portray himself as a
reformer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose early pitch was one of inclusion and compassion
conservativism, has found himself blemished by his link to Pat
Robertson and an appearance he made at Bob Jones University, which
bans interracial dating and whose namesake once labeled the
Catholic Church as a ``satanic cult.'' While the move helped him
win the primary in South Carolina, where the school is located,
some Republicans have also said they are concerned it has muddied
his message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as governors can paint a clear contrast to senators in
taking care of people,'' Schafer said. ``People look to the Senate
to mess up their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the vast sums of money Bush has spent so far, the
governors said they believed it would pay off in the weeks to come
in states where McCain has invested little cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an entirely new game once you start campaigning in 13
states on March 7th at the same time,'' Leavitt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
