<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETS ARE NO PUSHOVERS FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO _ If the Lakers maintain their current pace of
winning games, this might go down as a trivia question: What two
opponents beat them twice this season?
</P>
<P>
   Hint: They play both teams in the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   That Portland, their opponent Tuesday, has beaten the Lakers
twice is hardly surprising, considering the Trail Blazers' record.
But it's understandable if no one remembers that today's opponent,
the 21-34 Houston Rockets, also took a pair from the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Houston beat them in early November, taking advantage of
Shaquille O'Neal's suspension and Kobe Bryant's broken right hand.
It was a throw-away game.
</P>
<P>
   The one that hurt was the 89-83 loss at Houston on Jan. 30.
Everyone played, everyone was healthy. It's just no one could
shoot, or stop the Rockets' little guards from penetrating for
layups, or kickouts to open shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the most pathetic game we played all year, to be
honest,'' coach Phil Jackson said Saturday, after a practice
session at the new Healthsouth Training Center. ``It was a game in
which our energy was poor, our shooting was awful. ... And we just
didn't finish that game well at all, against a team I thought was
very susceptible.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockets guards Steve Francis, Bryce Drew and Cuttino Mobley
combined for 42 points in that game, but Bryant said the Lakers
have improved their defense since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played agaisnt them, we were going through a stretch
when we really weren't playing our best basketball anyway,'' he
said. ``As of now, we're doing a good job defensively, executing a
lot better defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Home sweet home: Some bugs have yet to be worked out, and
everyone's still unpacking, but Jackson said players are warming up
to the new training facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're liking it a lot, although they see it as a big
change , and all change takes some adjustment to get used to,'' he
said. Jackson wants Healthsouth not to be viewed as a ``drudgery
place'' for work, but ``a place whee they can come and be with
their community of guys. ... It's going to be full of things that
they can do here, between going up (to the management offices) and
negotiating a new contract with Jerry West to complaining to Mitch
(Kupchak) about moving expenses to whatever else that's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Bryant was treated Saturday for a bruised left calf
after getting kicked in the fourth quarter of Friday's victory over
Boston. He's not expected to miss any playing time.
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS vs. ROCKETS
</P>
<P>
   Tipoff: 2:30 p.m., Staples Center
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KNBC-Channel 4; KLAC-AM (570)
</P>
<P>
   Lakers (44-11) update: They've won 10 straight to go with their
previous 16-game winning streak, marking the fourth time in
franchise history that a team has had two double-digit streaks in
the same seas on. The feat was also accomplished by the 1986-87
team (11 games, 12 gam es) and the 1987-88 team (16 games, 11
games), each of which went on to win the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets (21-34) update: They've lost seven of their last nine
games and four in a row. The Rockets are 2-0 at Staples Center (one
win each against the Lakers and Clippers). They're a horrid 2-14 in
NBC-televised games over the last two seasons, but both wins came
against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Howard Beck
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
