<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEMPLE-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF ISN'T ENOUGH FOR MINUTEMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Years from now, University of Massachusetts
players will tell their grandchildren about the time they did what
few folks in college basketball thought they could do. They went
into Temple's Liacouras Center and for 20 minutes left the nation's
hottest team, its coach, and a partisan crowd virtually stunned.
</P>
<P>
   They'll talk about the zone defense that fooled a coach whose
staple is zone defense. How they held Temple to 31 percent shooting
in the first half. How they took a 3-point lead into the locker
room against a team that beat the Minutemen by 27 in Amherst
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Then their grandchildren will ask what happened in the second
half, and each man will quickly, and sadly, change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Just when UMass appeared on its way to the biggest win in
Bruiser Flint's four-year tenure, Temple doused its hopes with
several big plays midway through the second half. The Owls led by
as many as 19 before claiming a 72-54 Atlantic 10 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 13th consecutive victory for conference-leading
Temple (22-4, 13-1), which has beaten all three of its top A-10
competitors (Dayton, St. Bonaventure, and UMass) in its last four
games, as well as previously top-ranked Cincinnati. The win
clinched the A-10 East Division crown for the Owls.
</P>
<P>
   Quincy Wadley led Temple with 21 points, but it was reserve
guard Lynn Greer (17 points) who carried the Owls to victory.
</P>
<P>
   With 17:51 left, he replaced the team's leading scorer, Mark
Karcher, who ended the first half 0 for 6. Temple scored on five
consecutive possessions with Greer in the lineup. With the score
tied at 30, Greer scored 5 unanswered points, including a 3-pointer
with 15:47 left to put Temple up, 35-30.
</P>
<P>
   Greer hit a runner in the paint with 11:26 left to give Temple a
44-34 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating at times,'' said UMass forward Mike Babul,
``because we kept making them work and we were taking 25-30 seconds
off their shot clock. Then at the end, we would either foul or they
would hit a big shot.''
</P>
<P>
   That spelled curtains for the Minutemen (15-12, 9-5), who led by
as many as 7 in the first half thanks to a 2-3 zone that held
Temple starters Karcher, Pepe Sanchez, Kevin Lyde, and Lamont
Barnes to 1-for-11 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew once we got a convincing lead, after we hit a couple of
threes in a row, that they would have to come out of the zone and
start chasing us, and that's what happened,'' said Temple coach
John Chaney. He applauded Flint on the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   That was hardly any solace for Flint, whose volatile complaints
to officials earned him a technical foul _ his first of the season
_ with 11:09 to go. Wadley sank two free throws, and on the ensuing
possession, he got fouled and sank two more, giving Temple a 48-32
lead with 10:22 left.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Flint had long abandoned the zone strategy. Temple,
which had as many offensive rebounds as UMass had total rebounds
(20) in their Feb. 1 meeting, began dominating inside. Consecutive
putbacks by Lyde and Barnes gave the Owls a 61-42 lead with 4:18 to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came up with a few big rebounds and we missed a lot of
free throws,'' said Flint. ``That's crucial, especially when you're
trying to keep (the deficit) to within 4 or 5 points.''
</P>
<P>
   Monty Mack led the Minutemen with 20 points, hitting 5 of 12
from 3-point range. Shannon Crooks and Chris Kirkland contributed
10 points each.
</P>
<P>
   UMass, in a second-place tie with St. Bonaventure in the A-10
East, hosts George Washington Tuesday and visits the Bonnies
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
