<SLUG> BC-BKC-PROVIDENCE-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES AT A LOSS WITHOUT BELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ No exit polls were needed after this one.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Boston College's 45-40 loss Saturday to
Providence College before a Civic Center crowd of 8,938 proved just
how strong a candidate BC freshman guard Troy Bell is for Big East
rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   It demonstrated how important Bell, sidelined for the remainder
of the season with a lateral meniscus tear in his left knee, has
become to the fortunes of BC's beleaguered basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly an indication, good or bad, how much we rely on
him and his ability,'' said BC coach Al Skinner, after his team
clinched the No. 13 seed in the Big East tournament after dropping
to 10-18 overall and 2-13 in conference play. ``You take him out of
the lineup and we score 40 points. I mean, it's a clear indication
of how important he is and it's clear that he's one of the
cornerstones of this program. For those reasons that's why he
should be rookie of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   With Bell in the lineup, the Eagles would have had a good shot
to win Saturday. Without him? Well, they combined with the Friars
to record the lowest scoring game in Big East history.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Harley picked up some of the slack for Bell, scoring a
team-high 12 points, but he was the only Eagle in double figures.
Kenny Walls scored 2 points on 1-for-14 shooting, but had almost as
many rebounds (13) as field goal attempts while senior guard Dwayne
Pina, making his first start in Bell's place, had 2 points, 7
rebounds, 3 assists, and 4 steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unbelievable,'' senior forward Michael Cotton said of
Bell. ``I don't know if there's a better freshman in the country,
honestly. All through this season, he's made all the big shots and
he's played well offensively and defensively. I don't know if
there's a freshman in the country who is more important to their
team than Troy is to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   --In BC's 67-62 victory over Providence Jan. 8 at Conte Forum,
the Eagles hit 20 of 56 shots and got a game-high 28 points from
Bell, who connected on 8 of 17 field goals, 4 of 8 shots from
3-point range, and 8 of 11 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   --Saturday, with Bell in street clothes, BC made a season-low 16
of 62 field goal attempts, converted 1 of 12 from 3-point range,
was held to 9 points in the last 10:52 of the game, and wound up
with its lowest point total since a 58-36 loss at Georgetown Jan.
27, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Providence, which had lost five straight
home games, went scoreless for the first 7:18 of the second half
after trailing at halftime, 21-20. Still, the Friars were not
deterred, mounting a comeback from a 31-23 deficit with less than
10 minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Erron Maxey led Providence (11-16, 4-10) with 16 points and a
career-high 21 rebounds (12 offensive). Donta Wade, who had 13
points on 5-for-14 shooting, drilled a pair of huge treys. His
first trifecta tied it, 35-35, with 4:58 to go. Then, after Xavier
Singletary (5 points, 1-for-9 shooting) knocked down BC's first
3-pointer in two games to snap an 0-for-17 skein, Wade hit another
trey that put the Friars in control for good, 40-38.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the way we played, but our shooting was our only
shortcoming that we had,'' Skinner said. ``When you miss shots that
are good shots, I can't really complain about that. Every other
part of the game, I think we did a pretty decent job considering
the situation we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without Troy Bell.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bell sat with reporters before the game and discussed how his
season had come to an abrupt end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, I kind of feel like everything happens for a
reason,'' he said. ``Maybe something good might come from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell will undergo arthroscopic surgery on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
