<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMEN-MARATHON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK WINS OLYMPIC MARATHON TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ On a morning in which the improbable took 2
hours 33 minutes 31 seconds to become the undeniable, an unknown
37-year-old pathologist came down from Alaska to win the US Olympic
Team Trials for the Women's Marathon Saturday, overcoming startling
heat to leave in her wake a trail of big-name athletes and a
simmering controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just in shock,'' said Christine Clark, a mother of two
from Anchorage who follows 1996 winner Jenny Spangler into Trials
lore as a longshot who made good. ``No one could have been more
surprised than me. I'm certainly a late bloomer.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the slowest winning time in Trials history, run under
relentlessly sunny skies and in temperatures that registered in the
80s at midrace, means that Clark will be the only US representative
in the women's marathon at the Sydney Olympics. For the United
States to send the usual three-woman contingent, Saturday's victor
needed to cross the finish line in 2:33 or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that was an issue,'' said Clark. ``If there was any way
I could have run under 2:33, I would have.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Clark, winner of the 1995 Seattle Marathon and third
at Twin Cities last fall, ran almost seven minutes faster than her
previous best marathon, an astonishing improvement coming out of
the pack as the 22d-fastest in the field, to earn $35,000 and an
Olympic berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It so far surpasses my expectations, I don't know what to
say,'' said Clark, who fortuitously did the bulk of her relatively
low, 70-mile-a-week training on a treadmill in a converted bedroom
with the thermostat set at 70 degrees. ``No one could have been
more surprised than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Second was Kristy Johnston of Shepherdstown, W.V. (2:35:36),
while Anne Marie Lauck of Hampton, N.J., was third (2:36:05).
Libbie Hickman, the favorite, came in eighth in 2:39:57, while Joan
Samuelson, who revealed after the race that she had taken a
cortisone shot in her back on Thursday to ease symptoms of a
herniated disk, came in right behind her, finishing ninth in
2:39:59.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, it was tough in the heat,'' said Samuelson, 42.
``I thought it was going to be in the 30s or 40s down here. I never
could take enough water.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuelson said the disk flareup left her with no feeling in her
toes and no power down her left side. In her last two 13-mile runs,
the most recent on Tuesday, her left leg ``was just slap, slap,
slapping,'' she said. ``I just held my breath at 13 miles
(Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   For the second-place Johnston, it was a day of crushing
disappointment, despite the $30,000 payday, because any other year
second and third place at the Trials would mean a trip to the
Olympics. ``I think we're probably going to fight some of the rules
somehow,'' said Johnston, who has met the Olympic ``A'' standard
but needed Clark to run 31 seconds faster so she, too, could make
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who works three days a week at Providence Hospital in
Anchorage and has two sons (Matthew, 9, and Danny, 6), ran the
first half of the race in the pack that was chasing Lauck, who by 3
miles had taken the lead, and 26-year-old Kim Pawelek. At 11 miles,
Gwyn Coogan (sore left foot) left the pack and dropped out. By the
halfway point, Lauck had built a 42-second lead over Pawelek and
was 54 seconds ahead of the pack. But by 16 miles Pawelek had been
reeled in and by 17 miles Clark was in second, having whittled 15
seconds off Lauck's lead in just a mile. By 18, she was just 11
seconds behind; by 19, a mere four; and at precisely the 20-mile
mark the stranger from Alaska took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just running evenly, and people were coming back to
me,'' said Clark, who runs for Alaska's Team Raven Running Club.
``I didn't really let myself think I could win until the last 2
miles, and then it hit me. I don't think I'll sleep for three
days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 2052EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9558 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-USGYM-AMERICANCUP     02-26 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USGYM-AMERICANCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US COMES UP SHORT IN AMERICAN CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ They're calling it Operation Sneak Attack, the
out-of-nowhere strike that the American men's gymnastics team hopes
will put them on the Olympic medal stand in Sydney. By then, Blaine
Wilson and Jason Gatson will be fully fit again and John
Roethlisberger will be his ageless self.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be standing on the podium with a medal around their
necks,'' predicts program director Ron Galimore. ``I am 110 percent
confident about that.''
</P>
<P>
   But that confidence wasn't there Saturday at Orlando Arena, when
the decimated US squads lost both titles at the American Cup for
the first time in the event's 25-year-history. Cuba's Eric Lopez
took the men's title ahead of Russia's Alexei Bondarenko and
Roethlisberger. And Russia's Elena Produnova, a two-time world
medalist, easily outpointed Morgan White, a 16-year-old from Ohio,
for the women's crown.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Americans expected much more here. Though the US
males had won the last five titles, they took the floor without
Wilson, the three-time champion who's still rehabbing from shoulder
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine, but I'm not in routine shape,'' said Wilson, who
missed last year's world all-around bronze by a thousandth of a
point. ``It's a hard thing to swallow, to have to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   So the home hopes rested with the 29-year-old Roethlisberger,
who'd won in 1995 and 1996 but has been fighting age and injury.
``Obviously, I have some work to do,'' conceded Roethlisberger,
who'll be trying to make his third Olympic team this summer. ``I
don't want to lose to these guys down the road. But this is a step
in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   With four world team members (Kristen Maloney, Vanessa Atler,
Jennie Thompson, and Elise Ray) still recovering from injuries, the
US women had no illusions of winning here. ``Produnova is the best
gymnast in the world right now,'' said US team coordinator Bela
Karolyi. ``She is not a rookie. She is an old-timer.''
</P>
<P>
   Produnova easily won all four events, but White and 15-year-old
Tasha Schwikert hung in gamely. ``A success, a very good start,''
Karolyi concluded. ``Our big cannons are still out there, waiting
for their time to come in. So I feel no frustration about being
second and fourth here.''
</P>
<P>
   The US championships in St. Louis aren't until the end of July,
the Olympic trials in Boston not until mid-August. By then, Karolyi
hopes, he can get enough women healthy and honed enough to make a
run Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do everything we can do to get rid of this perception
that American gymnastics is weaker than before,'' he said. ``We
will be around the medal-contending area. Remember this. Bela said
it. There is the talent there.''
</P>
<P>
   The men, who placed two in the top 10 at the 1996 Olympics and
have added the 19-year-old Gatson (who's recovering from a
blown-out knee), are solid enough to make a run at the top four at
Olympus. But winning a team medal, which hasn't happened since
1984, may take a top-secret plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may say, `You guys won't be good enough to win a
medal,' and they may be right,'' said Roethlisberger. ``But we're
going to go out there and take on anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
