<HEADER>
A9559 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-OklahomaSt.-IowaS     02-26 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-Oklahoma </SLUG>
 St.-Iowa St. -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Iowa State takes charge of Big 12
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AMES, Iowa _ Before the game, Iowa State senior Michael Nurse stood
on the court with tears streaming down his face, as he prepared to
play his final home game for the Cyclones.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, junior Marcus Fizer, who might leave early for
the NBA draft after the season, was so overcome by the emotion of
what could be his final home game that he fell to his knees and
wept.
</P>
<P>
   In the 40 minutes between, the weeping and wailing in the Hilton
Coliseum came from the Oklahoma State Cowboys, who watched almost
helplessly Saturday as Fizer and Nurse led Iowa State to a 72-61
win in a battle for first place in the Big 12 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Fizer scored a game-high 29 points and Nurse added 15 on 5-of-10
3-point shooting as the Cyclones dominated the Cowboys from the
opening tap. Iowa State trailed only once in the game, by one point
less than a minute into the contest, and led by as many as 21
before Oklahoma State scored the game's final eight points to make
the score look respectable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we did what we were supposed to do we were successful, we
just didn't make all the plays and we did not play as smart as we
should have,'' said guard Joe Adkins, who led the Cowboys with 14
points. ``We can't come in here and play a team like this, not play
well, and win on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State, which did not lose any of its 18 games at the Hilton
Coliseum this season, put its home-court advantage to good use
twice in the past week. The 17th-ranked Cyclones entered the week
tied with Texas and No. 10 Oklahoma State, but bettered both by
double digits at home to take control of the conference race, with
just two games remaining (at Texas Tech on Wednesday and at Baylor
on March 4).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this game would be the easiest of the three
(remaining games),'' Iowa State coach Larry Eustachy said. ``That's
not a knock against Oklahoma State, but we had a home-court
advantage and I knew `Hilton Magic' and our fans would help us
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State (24-4 overall, 12-2 in the Big 12) can clinch at
least a share of the league title and the top seed in the
conference tournament with one more win. Oklahoma State (22-4,
11-3) needs two Cyclones losses and wins over Colorado and Oklahoma
to win the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't bet any money on it,'' Oklahoma State coach Eddie
Sutton said. ``I'd be surprised if Iowa State would be beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer said the emotion that hit him came in thinking about the
relief that the conference race was almost over, though he
cautioned that the regular-season championship was not officially
the Cyclones'.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that this Texas road trip is going to be extremely
hard,'' said Fizer. ``This season has been so great, so magical.
It's hard to finally realize that this is the last home game of the
season and Stevie Johnson's and Michael's last home games of their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to go out there and do my best to do
everything I could to help the team win for them in their last
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State, which has not won an outright league title since
capturing the Big Six in 1945, built a 10-point advantage midway
through the first half, thanks to Fizer's quick start. The 6-8
forward displayed his skills again for the slew of professional
scouts in attendance as he drained a pair of 3-pointers, sank a
running jumper in the lane and rocked the rim with a forceful slam
on his way to 16 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins had 10 points to keep Oklahoma State surprisingly close
at the break, but a manageable 37-31 deficit turned into a rout
rather quickly as the Cyclones put together a 21-6 run to start the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   All five Iowa State starters scored in the blitz, with Nurse
leading the way with consecutive treys and Jamaal Tinsley, the
team's worst outside shooter (15 percent on 3-pointers), adding an
omen-like 3-pointer from the top of the key.
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward Desmond Mason had a sluggish effort, scoring only
eight points in 38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for us to win when our best player goes 2-for-11,''
Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such trouble for the Cyclones, as Fizer was one
point shy of his third consecutive 30-point game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is anybody in the country playing better
than Marcus Fizer right now,'' Eustachy said. ``That's why we find
ourselves in the standings where we do. He is a man. He's turned
into a team leader.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is ever so close to leading his team to a conference
title.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
