<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOXOFFS-SIMMSCRAIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAIG, SIMMS UP TO CHALLENGES IN BOXOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ Dante Craig and Michael Simms Jr. joined
some illustrious company Saturday. Craig, of Cincinnati, and Simms,
of Sacramento, became just the 10th and 11th boxers to win the US
Olympic team as box-off challengers.
</P>
<P>
   Craig edged Larry Mosley of Los Angeles at 147 pounds at
Foxwoods Resort Casino, landing a scoring blow in the final seconds
to tie the score, 9-9, and winning on points awarded for scoring
blows, 49-46. The scoring-blows tiebreaker is calculated by
totaling the number of punches recorded by five judges, then
dropping the high and low totals.
</P>
<P>
   Both Craig and Simms, who defeated Olanda Anderson at 178
pounds, had to defeat their opponents twice in succession to
advance to the Americas qualifying March 27-April 1 in Tampa. That
was because their opponents had won at the Olympic Trials a week
ago, leaving the likes of Craig and Simms to battle in a losers'
bracket on their way to a double-elimination box-off.
</P>
<P>
   Since the box-off format was instituted in 1984, the list of
successful challengers had included just Evander Holyfield, Jerry
Page, and Meldrick Taylor in 1984; Kelcie Banks, Riddick Bowe, and
Andrew Maynard ('88); Montell Griffin ('92); and Albert Guardado
and Floyd Mayweather ('96).
</P>
<P>
   Most of those fighters have gone on to successful professional
careers, and Craig and Simms appear headed in a similar direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dante has always been confident,'' said trainer Roy Dale, who
once challenged Carlos Monzon for the world middleweight title in
Rome on less than three weeks' notice. ``He has natural ability. I
told all the guys who came up with him in the Junior Olympics they
would be champs. But he is making a few mistakes still. He can't
wait to counterpunch like that. You need to counter off the
counter, start off the action, because there is no time to wait
around. In the amateurs, they count the blows, and you have to be
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if he had lost, they might have been able to forget about
him as an amateur but they would have to reckon with his name as a
pro. He is tall, fast, strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Craig: ``Coming out of the losers' bracket and winning
twice like that proves it's not a fluke. (Mosley) is a good amateur
but he is the easiest fighter I had. He doesn't take a punch and
doesn't have the stamina for the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to win the Olympics and then become world champion
in the middleweight class. I know I will be a better pro than
amateur. I've been trained like a pro since I started.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms also displayed poise and power in pulling his 11-7 upset.
Simms believed he had to overcome the image of Anderson, a staff
sergeant and member of the US Army World Class Athlete Program, as
a potentially more glamorous Olympics entrant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought USA Boxing didn't want me here,'' Simms said. ``It
was just some thoughts I had inside, and from talking to past
amateurs. It just seemed that way, but I just had to look past it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I had to come out of nowhere. I am America's best-kept
secret. Toughness and a big heart got me this far. It shows that 10
years of hard work pays off. There have been a lot of ups and
downs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Simms-Anderson rivalry is becoming intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Anderson) said he doesn't like me personally,'' Simms said.
``So I'll say the same thing about him. If he doesn't give respect,
he doesn't get it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't stop here for me. I want to take the same steps
Holyfield took.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other box-offs, Jeff Lacy of St. Petersburg, Fla.,
defeated Arthur Palac of Hamtramck, Mich., 10-9, at 165 pounds; and
Calvin Brock of Charlotte, N.C., defeated T.J. Wilson of Tulsa,
Okla., 6-5, at 201-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Palac's father and trainer said his son was a victim of racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows they don't want a white man in the Olympics,''
Ted Palac said. ``There hasn't been a white man on the team since
1988.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
