<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9561 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-Texas-TexasA&AMP;M-HN     02-26 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-Texas-Texas </SLUG>
 A&AMP;M-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas has easy time against Texas A&AMP;M
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUSTIN _ Some day, maybe the Texas-Texas A&AMP;M rivalry that is so
intense on the football field every November will carry over to the
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   That day wasn't Saturday. Not by a long shot. The No. 14-rated
Longhorns toyed with the Aggies 85-58 before 11,451 at the Erwin
Center. The victory was the 14th straight for Texas over Texas A&AMP;M,
the longest streak by either team in the series.
</P>
<P>
   This one was open-and-shut. Texas (20-7 overall, 11-3 in the Big
12) used its depth up front to scorch the undermanned Aggies, who
played without 6-9 senior forward Aaron Jack, home in College
Station with a viral infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to suffer without A.J., because he gives
us some things underneath that some of us can't give,'' said
reserve forward Jason Boeker, who played a season-high 27 minutes
and had four points and five rebounds. ``We tried to step it up,
but those guys are so strong and so big. They're pros. They're
tough to get around.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas center Chris Mihm had 21 points on 7-of-7 shooting from
the field, forward Chris Owens added 20 and forward Gabe Muoneke
had eight points and seven rebounds off the bench. Mihm and Owens
combined for 13 points in the first eight minutes as the Longhorns
set the tone for the game quickly. Overall, Texas had 36 points in
the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get two or three guys going the way we did today, it
pretty much makes us unstoppable down low,'' said Mihm, who had 10
rebounds and recorded his 17th double double of the season.
``They're not able to just sit on one guy. Things open up in the
post.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fast start by Mihm and Owens, the Longhorns led only
19-16 with 11:05 left in the first half when Aggies freshman
Bernard King scored off an offensive rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a pair of 3-point baskets by reserve forward Chris
Ogden and robust slam dunks by Muoneke and Darren Kelly, the
Longhorns went on a 21-7 run to take a 40-23 lead with three
minutes to go in the half. Texas led 46-28 at the half. The Aggies
(7-18, 3-11) never were able to get back in the game, shooting only
28.9 percent in the second half and 32.3 for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, they're so strong,'' said Aggies coach Melvin
Watkins. ``There's no way to compare what they have and what we
have right now. It's tough for us to match up with them right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas guard Will Clay, who had 16 points, carried the matchup
problem for the Aggies to the backcourt. Clay was in King's face
most of the day, holding King to 13 points on 5-of-20 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Clay, a senior from Bryan, used an aggressive style
of defense on King would be putting it mildly. King wore a headband
for the first time this season Saturday, and Clay was wrapped
around King nearly as tight as that headband.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge, but it's my job to go out and guard the
other team's best player,'' said Clay. ``He keeps moving all the
time, so you just have to stay with him and be more aggressive than
he is. There's times when you have to give a guy a hard foul early
in the game to let him know that's the way the rest of the game is
going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing at Iowa State last Tuesday night to fall out of a
tie for the Big 12 lead, the Longhorns needed a breather before
they face Kansas at home Monday. They got just that against the
Aggies, running up a 36-point lead (79-43) midway through the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Melvin and what he's doing, and I
told our kids at halftime that the Aggies weren't going to quit,''
said Texas coach Rick Barnes. ``They played hard the whole way, but
we did an excellent job of keeping our concentration once we got
ahead. There's been times this year where we haven't done that, but
we probably played our best mental game for 40 minutes that we have
all season.''
</P>
<P>
   That diligence allowed the Longhorns to reach the 20-win mark
for the first time since 1996, when they went 21-10. Barnes said
that given the Longhorns' rugged schedule (ranked the third
toughest in the nation in the latest RPI,) the 20-win plateau is
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the schedule we've played and the travel we've had, I'd
say the kids have done a heck of a job getting to 20 wins. None of
those guys in there have ever won 20 games in a season, so it's
something special for them.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, maybe a basketball game between the Aggies and
Longhorns will be something special. For the last six years, Texas
has had its way over Texas A&AMP;M, winning 12 of the 14 games by 10 or
more points and five times by more than 25 points. The Longhorns
won both games this season by 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible feeling to have inside you, losing as many
games as we have by so many points,'' said King. ``But I also know
inside that we're going to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
