<HEADER>
A9562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-ST.JOHN'S-DUKE-NY     02-26 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ST.JOHN'S-DUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S SURPRISES NO. 2 DUKE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ This scramble had no purpose: Bootsy Thornton
drifted to the middle of court. Lavor Postell hopped toward the
free-throw line. Erick Barkley skipped toward the baseline and his
joyous teammates. The horn had just sounded on St. John's 83-82
upset of second-ranked Duke, and the Red Storm players did not
quite know how act.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the 9,314 Blue Devils fanatics who had come to
Cameron Indoor Stadium intent on showing solidarity with the
NCAA-beleaguered team only to find a superb basketball game hijack
their social protest. Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski had asked the
student body to spare Barkley any cutting witticisms. In fact, a
list of alternate cheers directed at the NCAA had been circulated
through the stands.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Storm's purposeful scrambling for 40 minutes did not
give Coach K, the Cameron crazies or anyone else time to thumb
their noses at college sports authority.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, until Thornton was near the 3-point line with 11.9
seconds left in the game, there was only one unifying thought in
this sweltering gymnasium: which team loses a contest in which both
teams shoot nearly 50 percent, both starting lineups score in
double figures, and both teams rarely make a turnover?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, because of Thornton, is not St. John's. With the Red
Storm trailing, 82-81, the left-hander got the ball on the right
wing and was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking: `Hey! They left me wide open,' he said. ```This
is where I've been hitting from,''' said Thornton, who stroked his
21st and 22nd points through the net.
</P>
<P>
   In a game with 12 lead changes _ with acrobatic runs that at
different stages had the Blue Devils up by 12 and the Red Storm up
by seven _ there was plenty of drama left after Thornton's basket.
With five seconds left, the Blue Devils inbounded the ball
underneath their bucket to Chris Carrawell. St. John's had bottled
the player of the year candidate all afternoon, holding him to 11
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm did it one more time. Thornton and Anthony Glover
sandwiched the senior in a double team and forced him to take an
off-balance 22-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the longest five seconds of my life,'' Thornton said.
</P>
<P>
   If the past three weeks under NCAA scrutiny disrupted the Red
Storm, it certainly has not shown it. It is 7-0 during that stretch
and in the last week has beaten No. 13 Syracuse, No. 22 Connecticut
and now No. 2 Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resiliency that our kids showed is the reflection of who
they are, their character, where they have come from and where they
want to go,'' coach Mike Jarvis said. ``Whatever we're doing on or
off the court, it's about doing it as one.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season St. John's and Duke turned in a memorable duel _ a
92-88 overtime victory for the Blue Devils _ at a sold-out Madison
Square Garden. Thornton poured in 40 points during a breakout
performance. The Red Storm needed everybody Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis thought it was too much to ask for his team to repeat
that performance. But with four minutes left in the game and Duke
up, 78-75, he turned to his son and assistant, Mike Jarvis II, and
said: ``This is great. I can't believe this is happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   It happened because every Red Storm player on the court played
for the other. Glover scored 12 points and wrestled with the Blue
Devils' Carlos Boozer. Postell softened Duke's middle with slashing
assaults on the blocks and contributed 16 points. Off the bench,
Donald Emanuel and Chudney Gray combined for nine points, two
steals and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a different style because they have four guys who
handle the ball,'' Krzyzewski said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was Barkley. His 14 points, eight assists and
three steals do not evoke the stone-faced precision he exhibited
throughout a week in which NCAA investigators were interested in
who paid for a portion of his prep schooling in Maine. Krzyzewski
and Blue Devil forward Shane Battier spoke out on the guard's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In fact on Friday, at a tent encampment filled with Duke
students waiting for tickets, Krzyzewski told the crowd that his
good friend, Jarvis, had told him that Barkley was probably going
to have to miss a game before the end of the season because of the
tuition arrangement. He told the students to support Barkley and
St. John's because it was not fair.
</P>
<P>
   When Barkley was introduced the Blue Devil student body
applauded loudly; when his teammates were introduced, the crowd
chanted, ``Fight the Power.'' But cheers of ``Stop the Witch Hunt''
that were listed on the handouts never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Barkley found Battier after the game for a hug and a
whispered conversation. ``I thanked him and Coach K for watching my
back 100 percent,'' Barkley said. ``We're a top-five team in the
country right now on my list and that's what I'd like to talk
about. Enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm made a statement on the basketball floor that was
much more poignant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 2056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
