<HEADER>
A9563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-MONTGOM     02-26 1745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-MONTGOMERIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTGOMERIE DOESN'T LET HIMSELF GET RANKLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Somehow, the presence of Colin Montgomerie
signals to some reporters a duty to get antagonistic. How else to
explain a nonsensical exchange during what should have been a
routine press conference prior to the Andersen Consulting Match
Play Championship?
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie was asked how well he understood the world ranking
system, which he rightfully saw as a blueprint for entrapment.
``What are you trying to get me to say?'' asked Montgomerie, well
aware that it was hoped he'd offer stinging criticism of a points
system that gets knocked all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter kept on, at one point asking Montgomerie how he
would explain the system to his wife, which produced this quip:
``She knows the system as well as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   It should have stopped, but it escalated to the point where the
reporter got sarcastic. ``I don't understand it completely. That's
why I want a genius like you to explain it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Uncalled for, most certainly, and intended only to stir
criticism. That Montgomerie was unable to steer clear of the
questioning without his own touch of combativeness was no surprise,
but it was a line of questioning that never should have started.
``You should know the system,'' said Montgomerie. ``What's the
problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Score one for Monty, though the exchange again cast light on the
world rankings, which have become important in pro golf circles. It
is a system with flaws, and the reporter was trying to get
Montgomerie to say so. Admirably, he did not take the bait.
Instead, Montgomerie offered a simple, but accurate, viewpoint:
``It's a very, very difficult way of trying to judge one's form,
but if no one comes up with a better system, this is the best we've
got.''
</P>
<P>
   So, for better or worse, we have the world rankings,
administered by the International Management Group (unsettling to
some), and used as a basis for extending invitations to World Golf
Championship events, not to mention the Masters. There are
problems, no doubt. Most flagrant is the two-year time period that
is used, thus distorting a player's current form. Mark O'Meara is a
most glaring example. His remarkable 1998 season (Masters and
British Open triumphs) still counts for points; thus O'Meara was
seeded 14th for the Match Play Championship. Obviously, that
ranking is way too high, but as 1998 tourneys lose weight and his
1999-2000 performance (no wins, just three top 10s) counts more,
O'Meara's ranking will plummet.
</P>
<P>
   He won't be the only one. Consider that of the 64 players who
qualified for last year's inaugural event, 14 did not maintain high
enough status in the world rankings to earn invites for 2000. Nick
Faldo, for instance, was No. 64 a year ago; now you can find him
residing at No. 186. Craig Stadler, Scott Verplank, Bill Glasson,
Brad Faxon, Steve Jones, Michael Bradley, John Cook, Ian Woosnam,
and Tom Watson are some of the others who slipped to the wrong side
of 64.
</P>
<P>
   So far, and yet . . .
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of this tournament create a harsh reality, since
some players come an awful long way to play less than one round of
golf. Ireland's Padraig Harrington, for example, was eliminated by
Jesper Parnevik at the 17th hole of Round 1. Although the $25,000
paycheck eased his disappointment, his early exit had to make a
long trip even longer. Though some Europeans (such as Retief
Goosen) chose to make the trip to the United States more worthwhile
by adding next week's Doral Open to their schedule, others (Miguel
Angel Jimenez and Jose Maria Olazabal, for example) are in for a
serious case of jet lag as they head to the Dubai Desert Classic.
For his part, Harrington chose to take the next two weeks off. So,
after being eliminated Wednesday, the Irishman was on the driving
range at La Costa, working on a game that let him down against
Parnevik. ``I was swinging the club terrible,'' said Harrington.
Though he is not a household name, Harrington is held in high
regard by many of his colleagues. A personable man with a great
work ethic, Harrington earned a spot on his first Ryder Cup team in
September and did not disappoint. He teamed with Jimenez to go 1-1
in foursomes, then beat O'Meara, 1 up, in singles. ``It was a good
week and good to look back on it,'' said Harrington, 28.
``Certainly enjoyable up to the very end. Obviously, if we had won,
it would have been the icing on the cake.'' He was ranked in the
top 50 at the start of the year, earning him a spot in his first
Masters. That's the good news. The bad? His rank has since slipped
to No. 57, thus he most likely will not be in the fields at either
the Bay Hill Invitational (March 16-19) or The Players Championship
(March 23-26) . . . Two first-day results that had to sting the
most at the match play event involved Fred Couples and Brent
Geiberger. Couples had a 1-up cushion when he missed a 2-foot putt
at No. 17 that would have halved the hole. Ruffled, he then pulled
his drive well left into rough at No. 18, and watched helplessly as
Joe Ozaki stuck his approach to within 3 feet for the winning
birdie. Geiberger birdied No. 17 to go 1 up, then threw away the
lead with a bogey at No. 18. He followed with a bogey on the 19th
hole to get his ticket home . . . Another tournament tidbit: All
four of 1999's semifinalists (Jeff Maggert, Andrew Magee, Steve
Pate, and John Huston) were bounced in the first round. Magee is
the guy who last year made light of the fact that he had to go buy
socks for Sunday's championship match with Maggert, having packed
for a short stay. This year? Magee certainly didn't need extra
socks, but he told reporters that leaving early was OK because he
was playing for the sixth straight week and needed the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Apples and oranges
</P>
<P>
   Since 20 of the 24 Ryder Cup participants were in this week's
field, Montgomerie was asked if the match play event took on a
similar feel. He cringed. ``No. This is a world event. It's not a
Europe vs. America type of idea. That's once every two years. This
has nothing to do with that.'' . . . The only Ryder Cuppers not
here? The late Payne Stewart and the three Europeans who were kept
out of the lineup until the Sunday singles matches _ Jarmo
Sandelin, Jean Van de Velde, and Andrew Coltart . . . Though eight
of those European players advanced to Round 2 and five got to the
Final 16, smiles are not so prominent because of a simmering
dispute that could boil over shortly. It has to do with a decision
made by PGA European Tour executive director Ken Schofield to
change the eligibility for this summer's NEC Invitational, the
second of four World Golf Championships events. As originally
structured, the $5 million purse would be for members of the most
recent Ryder Cup and Presidents Cup teams, but Schofield, in a
veiled attempt to get European players to commit more to their home
tour, has put forth another set of guidelines for his players.
Instead of the Ryder Cup team, Europe will send the top 12 players
on its Order of Merit as of Aug. 14. Since Sergio Garcia, Paul
Lawrie, Van de Velde, and Parnevik plan to play extensively in the
United States, they very well could fall outside the top 12 on the
Order of Merit, a scenario that has angered all of them.
Reportedly, Garcia is most vocal, which is not good news for
Schofield, since his tour desperately needs the star appeal of the
young Spaniard . . . Tiger Woods blew off some steam when asked to
comment about published reports that he had proposed to girlfriend
Joanna Jagoda. ``I don't know where people come up with this stuff.
It's not true. I'm here to tell you that right now. Let's put an
end to this crap.'' The report first surfaced in a London tabloid,
then got picked up by the New York Post . . . Oh, for a PGA Tour
event without the hideous lift, clean, and place. It is a license
to cheat, and they are far too quick and far too liberal with it on
the PGA Tour. Disturbing sights abound, like the player in a Round
1 match here who was able to move his ball before a crucial putt.
He would have had to putt over 8 inches of fringe. But given a
club's length placement, he was able to choose a different angle
and position his ball just on the edge. By all means, plugged balls
deserve a free lift, but a little mud isn't bad, particularly since
everybody plays the same mud.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Karrie-ing on
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that Woods's winning streak was impressive,
but we perhaps cast our eyes at the wrong golfer (Michael Campbell)
in an effort to find someone just as hot. How about Karrie Webb?
She has been overwhelming in 2000, having won both her starts in
easy fashion. Webb will attempt to make it 3 for 3 in this
weekend's Australian Ladies Masters, and you would have to say her
chances are attractive. After all, she has won the event the last
two years and in 12 tournament rounds at Royal Pines in Gold Coast,
Webb is 56 under par. ``She has no flaws,'' said Peter Thomson, the
five-time British Open champ and Australian golf legend . . . The
LPGA Tour is keeping a close eye on the developments in Canada as
du Maurier Ltd. conducts a search for a sponsor for that women's
major golf championship. Du Maurier is likely to withdraw its
support because of restrictions on tobacco-company sponsorships in
Canada. This year's event includes a $1.2 million purse put up by
du Maurier . . . Betsy King, the LPGA Tour's career money leader,
is closing in on $7 million in this, her 23d season. That's a good
season for Woods . . . Old friend Peter Teravainen, the world
traveler from Duxbury, Mass., finished eighth in last week's Casino
Filipino Open . . . A three-day golf fair at Stow Acres CC winds
down Sunday from 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Merchandise will be available, and
golf professionals will be present to offer advice . . . Organizers
of the Cape Cod Open (June 7-8) and Cape Cod Senior Open (Sept.
25-26) merged efforts to form the Cape Cod Golf Championships
committee. A third event could be added to the summer schedule . .
. The Boston Golf Expo opens a three-day run at the Bayside Expo
Friday (1-9 p.m.) and will again feature equipment, instruction,
health clinics, a driving range and miniature golf course, and
exhibits from retailers and destination bureaus. Saturday's hours
will be 10 a.m.-9 p.m. and Sunday's 10 a.m.-5 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
