<SLUG> BC-RUN-Marathon </SLUG>
 trials-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
No. 22 seed wins U.S. Olympic Trials Marathon
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By STEVE SIEVERT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
COLUMBIA, S.C. _ A mother of two from Alaska who does the majority
of her training indoors on a treadmill stunned America's best
female marathoners by winning the U.S. Olympic Trials Marathon on
Saturday in a personal-best time of 2 hours, 33 minutes, 31
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Little-known Christine Clark, seeded 22nd in the field of 171,
reeled in Anne Marie Lauck at the 20-mile mark, built a 20-second
lead over the next mile and cruised to her biggest marathon win
ever. Clark's time was a remarkable seven minutes faster than she
had ever run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in shock when I caught Anne Marie,'' said Clark, who
qualified for the trials with a less-than-elite time of 2:40:38.
``I was really surprised the favorites didn't catch up to me. I
didn't even think about winning until the last two miles.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory earned Clark, 37, a trip to this summer's Olympics
in Sydney, Australia, a trip Clark wasn't planning on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really going to complicate my life,'' she said
jokingly. ``But it's a good complication.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauck, a 1996 Olympic marathoner, fired the race's opening salvo
by breaking up a lead pack of 20 with a 5:34 fourth mile. By the
half-marathon, covered in 1:15:28, Lauck had built a 42-second lead
on Kim Pawelek. A chase group, including Clark, top-seed Libbie
Hickman, Kristy Johnston, Liz Wilson and Melody Fairchild, was
another 24 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   Lauck maintained a sizable advantage over the next couple of
miles through the Fort Jackson army base, but as the unseasonably
warm weather continued to heat up, Lauck began to wear down. Over
Lauck's right shoulder, Clark was closing in a hurry. At mile 19,
Lauck's grip on the lead was all but gone. Clark was only four
seconds back. A mile later, the lead changed hands for the final
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was more surprised than me,'' Clark said. ``I was
hoping to finish in the top 20, maybe in the top 10, if I had a
good day. I never expected this.''
</P>
<P>
   The race marked the second straight women's trials in which a
little-known runner stole the day. Jenny Spangler emerged from the
pack as the 61st seed to win in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who finished 76th in '96, turned in the sequel to
Spangler this year.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about her chances in Sydney, Clark was glowingly
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my potential is,'' she said. ``I've only
been training seriously with a coach for about a year. I don't
think I've reached my peak.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Houston-area runners went to the starting line at the
trials, but only one finished. Joy Smith of Sugar Land ran 2:54:16,
good for 70th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a challenge from the start,'' she said. ``Sometimes you
wake up and you just don't feel right and that's what happened to
me today. The weather made it even tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Patty Valadka battled hamstring problems and was
forced to drop out at the 10-mile mark.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
