<HEADLINE>
PEDRO, NOMAR PUT SIGNATURES ON MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ They park far beyond the outfield fences,
then make the long walk on the white stone path that leads into the
five diamonds of the Red Sox' minor league compound. They are
hardball pilgrims _ pasty-legged men, women, and children _
carrying cameras, Sharpies, beach chairs, rosters, baseballs,
gloves, bats, posters, and the eternal hopes of Red Sox Nation. You
have never seen so many people wearing shorts, black shoes, and
white socks.
</P>
<P>
   At the site, amenities are few. There's almost no seating; fans
must stay behind yellow ropes; there's no concession food; and four
port-o-potties serve as discomfort stations. But it's all
worthwhile because this is where everyday people have a chance to
make contact with Pedro, Nomar, and the other gods of Fenway lore.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez keeps everybody loose, even the autograph-hungry
masses. Crossing from one diamond to another Saturday, he walked
through the crowd and broke the jawdrop silence with a loud ``Hi.''
In unison, the fans said, ``Hi, Pedro.'' It was a little like the
``Cheers'' routine in which George Wendt walks into the bar and
everybody says, ``Norm!''
</P>
<P>
   The critical moment of the day comes at the end of the grueling
three-hour workout when many players take turns walking to the
ropes and signing autographs. It can be the best and worst part of
the day for Martinez and Nomar Garciaparra because it is impossible
to accommodate everyone and there are always disappointed pilgrims
when a star stops signing. Friday a woman holding a poster stood in
the crowd while Nomar signed for at least 20 minutes. She kept
telling Nomar he was her favorite while he signed for dozens of
kids, elderly folk, and a man in wheelchair. Finally, Nomar wheeled
on his heels and bolted for the clubhouse. The woman made a face
and turned two thumbs down toward Nomar's back.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro has a system to avoid this scenario: ``First of all,
before I start signing, I tell 'em exactly what's up,'' said the
ace of diamonds. ``I tell 'em, `I will sign for a half-hour, but
only if you promise me you won't get mad when I leave. Because I
will have to leave. Otherwise I won't stop and sign. I just keep
going.' But if they agree to that, some of 'em get autographs,
especially kids. I just try to do kids first. Then I do older
couples, people that really need to be helped at the time. Stronger
people I'll do later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard. I have a hard time saying no, but you have to
understand, rules are rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar added, ``The way I look at it . . . I sign every day no
matter what. You can't satisfy everybody and you can't make 'em all
happy. You're always going to miss some people and some of them are
going to be upset. Hopefully, they respect that I'm there every
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a time for it. I don't like to sign when I'm
working _ like when I'm down here going from station to station. I
do it after the workout. I try to take care of all the kids. It's
great. You see their eyes light up. They just want to get you to
sign. It's not like they want to sell it or get it for the value.''
</P>
<P>
   Can he spot the subhuman form of life we've come to know as
``collectors''?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' said Nomar. ``They ask for things a certain way and
then they get mad after you sign, and I'm like, `What? I signed
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro and Nomar, poster boys of the Dan Duquette regime, are two
of the most popular players in the majors. It's a little like the
situation in Seattle when the Mariners had Ken Griffey Jr., Randy
Johnson, and Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro and Nomar did several Sox promotional and charity
functions in Greater Boston during the winter and their celebrity
is growing daily. Elvis and Sinatra. The King and the Chairman of
the Board. Sox publicist Kevin Shea has fielded more than 25
national media requests for Boston's shortstop and stopper.
Everyone from GQ to Newsweek to Gear. Charity requests are pouring
in at record rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand it's part of what they do,'' said Shea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Nomar are gonna be always asked to do stuff,'' said
Pedro. ``It's hard, but what can you do? It's the same now in the
Dominican, but it's OK. It's not bad. If you analyze it after all,
it's not bad. It's good that they love you, that they want you. Bad
would be when they boo you everywhere you go. But this year in
spring training I've never seen so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the stars themselves? Do they ever get autographs?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have certain special kinds of autographs,'' admitted Nomar.
``When I played in Japan in an All-Star Game I asked Sadaharu Oh to
sign a baseball. When I played with Michael Jordan, I had him sign
a baseball, but that was more for my little brother. I had Kevin
Costner sign a ball, but he signed it, `Crash Davis, Durham Bulls.'
Another one he signed, `Ray Kinsella,' from `Field of Dreams.'
That's how I wanted it. I never asked Ted Williams for an
autograph, but I do have a bat and ball signed by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pedro, ``I have balls and bats signed by Ted Williams,
(Dennis) Eckersley, and (Bret) Saberhagen. My first All-Star Game I
got Edgar Martinez, (Mark) McGwire, Frank Thomas, and Tony Gwynn on
the same bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Signed items can be treasured memories _ even for superstars.
And that is why Pedro Martinez and Nomar Garciaparra take time to
sign the baseballs thrust forward by the hardball pilgrims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 2058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9566 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-TROUTWIN     02-26 2213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-TROUTWINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH TRIES TO GET READ ON THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Belichick still remembers the first time he saw what Bob
Troutwine could do. It wasn't his speed, size, or agility, unless
we're talking about his mental agility, that impressed Belichick.
It was the fact that he could read minds. Or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was maybe after my second season in Cleveland that we got
hooked up at the combine,'' Belichick said of the psychologist from
Liberty, Mo., who will be assessing the psychological makeup of 300
players at the combine this week for 10 NFL teams. ``I asked him
for some past reports on guys we'd drafted, and he had most of them
cold. He had a lot of guys right on the nose.''
</P>
<P>
   As for players Cleveland didn't draft, ``He hit the reasons why
it turned out to be a bad fit right on the nose,'' Belichick said.
``And some had some severe problems. I thought he had some insights
we didn't have on guys, so we brought him in so he knew our staff
and our philosophy. I think a lot of Bob and what he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, Troutwine has done for the NFL what he previously
did for years for corporate America: assess clients' potential
employees. With the dawning of free agency and the kind of bonus
money that is now being laid out, the need for as much information
as possible about the potential of a draftee or a high-priced free
agent has grown, and with it a new wing of NFL scouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially there were a lot of skeptics,'' Troutwine said.
``But my findings and my forecasts spoke for themselves. At one
point, I did do interviews with players, but I don't do that
anymore. It's too time-intensive at the combine. Questions are more
efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Troutwine said it is revealing, for example, when he asks a
player if he would rather be a cat or a dog. The athlete's answer,
he maintains, says much about his mindset and NFL potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I developed a 75-question test,'' Troutwine said. ``Most
questions have two choices: true or false or A and B. There's also
a concentration drill that takes about 90 seconds and involves
remembering different colors in a certain order. We send out
engraved invitations to the players with the logos of the 10 teams
we represent. Most are very cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one question is indicative of anything. But after they
answer all of them and we assess them, trends develop, and we begin
to learn about the players' motivations and personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dog or cat question is one we feel has a lot of symbolism.
A dog is man's best friend. A cat is more independent. Players who
go for dogs tend to like structure, and being part of a team is
more important to them. Cats are guys who are more comfortable
being a more solo contributor. You have to let him feel like he's
making the decisions. Picking a cat or a dog is not the kiss of
death. Saying you'd like to be a poodle might be a little
problematic, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Troutwine assessed Ryan Leaf and Peyton Manning
for the Indianapolis Colts. It was his assessment that Leaf would
have far more problems coping with early failures than Manning and
that he might not react well under mounting pressures from the
media and the public. His assessments were right on the money. He
also said Manning's attention to detail was far superior to Leaf's.
Manning became a star in his second season, while Leaf has
immolated himself and is trying to start over.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Troutwine told Colts general manager Bill Polian that
Edgerrin James was a better match for his team than Ricky Williams
because James's personality was more adaptable to having a bigger
star _ Manning _ on his team. Williams, Troutwine felt, needed to
be the center of his team.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts went for James for an assortment of reasons, not just
the assessment of a psychologist from Missouri, but it was a part
of the picture. It is a part that has grown to the point at which
the Chiefs, Chargers, Seahawks, Packers, Colts, Bengals, Bears,
Eagles, Jaguars, and Panthers are all using him and, Troutwine
hopes, perhaps the Patriots will soon join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know him, but I have people in the personnel
department who swear by him,'' said Packers general manager Ron
Wolf of Troutwine. ``With the kind of money we put into these guys
today, you want all the information you can possibly get. This is
another thing that allows you to get into the player a little more
prudently. We use it in case of red flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he does is a hard sell for anyone my age who came up
through the NFL the way I did. I wasn't brought up with these kind
of things. It was about how you play football, not the other
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's more how will they fit into society, especially up
here in Green Bay, where it's a little different. It's a tool. To
say it helps you draft is wrong. It doesn't. It's another little
piece of the puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a puzzle Troutwine has been putting together for corporate
clients for years, ever since he left Tulane with a Ph.D in
psychology. But 17 years ago he turned his interest to pro football
after a short stint as a receivers' coach at William Jewell
College, a highly regarded NAIA school. His business has grown
rapidly ever since.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to work with corporations, but this week he will
focus all his efforts on the annual league combine, where all the
top college talent will be weighed, measured, tested, interviewed,
and now psychologically assessed.
</P>
<P>
   He and his assistants have already attended the Senior Bowl,
Blue-Gray Game, Hula Bowl, Gridiron Classic, and East-West Shrine
Game to test and re-test the nation's top seniors. Now he will do
it one last time, write up reports on all the players, and send
them out knowing they will affect the football futures of many of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opinions are within my territory,'' Troutwine said. ``Fit is
an important part of every job situation. Because you don't fit
with one organization doesn't mean you can't excel with another.
But if you make a mistake with a guy who doesn't fit your style or
what you want to do, you take a step back, and so does the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   As Belichick, Wolf, and other NFL coaches, general managers, and
personnel men will attest, a step back in the day of multimillion
dollar signing bonuses is something no team can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency scorecard
</P>
<P>
   The first signings are in, and the NFL is proving again there's
not much sanity when it comes to free agency. No one is happier
about it than guys like Kivika Pittman and Orpheus Roye.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman and Roye were two young free agents who came on the
market this year with little on their resumes but what is
euphemistically known as ``upside potential.'' As Bill Parcells
used to say, ``You know what potential means? Potential means you
haven't done a damn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to apply in both cases, but this morning, each
guy is worth millions after signing stupendous contracts with the
Denver Broncos and Cleveland Browns. Pittman and Roye were signed
despite having the kind of years that might get a player fired if
he were an eight-year veteran instead of a four-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman signed a seven-year deal worth $28 million, but it is so
back-loaded the last two years that it's really a five-year
contract worth $15 million, including a signing bonus of $3.15
million. What did he do to earn this kind of money? He made 3 1/2
sacks last season as an oft-injured defensive end in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   As for Roye, he signed a six-year, $25 million deal after making
the same number of sacks for the Steelers. Those signings, as well
as the earlier five-year, $24 million deal inked by Philip Daniels
to jump from Seattle to Chicago, not only set the market for
defensive linemen, they made it clear to one long-time agent that
the free agent environment has changed in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're rewarding mediocrity now,'' the agent, who requested
anonymity, said.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the case, although once again, the biggest
checks went out early, and there may not be many more big ones
soon. One team that is getting drilled is the Rams, who have lost
center Mike Gruttadauria to Arizona (four years, $8.6 million),
right tackle Fred Miller to Tennessee (six years, $24 million).
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rams have to rebuild 40 percent of their offensive line
less than a month after winning the Super Bowl, underscoring the
fact that the era of dynasties is over in the NFL. The poaching now
starts quickly on any team that is even moderately successful.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago and New Orleans appear to have helped themselves with
volume, at least. The Bears added what were generally regarded as
two of the top 10 free agents, Daniels and cornerback Thomas Smith,
who, although he has only six career interceptions, was considered
the best available cover corner on the market by many personnel
directors.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints, meanwhile, have finally decided to play football
with a quarterback, signing Cincinnati's mercurial Jeff Blake to a
four-year, $17.2 million contract. They also added receiver Joe
Horn from the Chiefs, plus two corners to help their defense, and
they re-signed center Tom Ackerman. If Blake can come close to his
form of a few years back in Cincinnati and can combine with running
back Williams smoothly, New Orleans could have a powerful,
two-pronged offensive attack.
</P>
<P>
   With other teams, things are spotty. Tennessee's situation is
typical. Tackle Jon Runyan was the top-rated offensive lineman
among veteran free agents, and he jumped from the Titans to the
Eagles for a six-year, $30 million deal. Then Tennessee brought in
Miller for $6 million less to fill his spot. This was viewed as no
worse than a wash for Tennessee, although the Eagles believe
Runyan's power blocking will help revive a dormant offense. At the
high rate they're paying him, it better.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams have focused their efforts on re-signing their own
players, as the Patriots did with Pro Bowl safety Lawyer Milloy.
But often, those signings cost them elsewhere. In New England,
retaining Milloy resulted in the dumping of high-priced but
slipping veteran stars such as tight end Ben Coates and tackle
Bruce Armstrong, with no replacements on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   That is the nature of things in the NFL these days, where
potential is paid higher than production once a player's peak years
have passed. There is no loyalty in either direction any more. When
a player can score big, as Runyon, Daniels, and others did this
year, he leaves. When a team needs to dump an aging star with a
bigger salary than upside, it does, as Buffalo did with Bruce
Smith, the Hall of Fame defensive end who signed immediately with
the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Redskins, they invested more than $50 million to
shore up their defense by adding Smith, safety Mark Carrier, and
linebacker Kevin Johnson to a team that showed last year it could
score big-time but needed to find a way to stop opponents from
returning fire even faster. If these three can help do that, maybe
the Redskins will be this year's big winner in the free agency
game. If not, owner Dan Snyder will fire somebody. You can count on
that.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who signs whom, however, you get the feeling that
in the end, the biggest winners in this game are often the teams
that don't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me, how many of these guys have gone on to other
teams with big contracts and played better?'' Tennessee executive
Jeff Diamond asked.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, frankly, is not many.
</P>
<P>
   Quick kicks
</P>
<P>
   Lester Hayes's toothache has turned into a real pain. According
to the former All-Pro cornerback of the Oakland/Los Angeles
Raiders, last April he finished a charity autograph signing for the
Children's Miracle Network in Reno and came down with a terribly
abscessed tooth. Four hours from his home in Modesto, Calif., he
went to the first dentist he could find but didn't have his wallet
or enough cash to pay him. In unbearable pain, he says, he drove to
a pawn shop and hocked his Super Bowl XVIII ring for $800, got a
receipt that said he had four months to pick it up at that price
plus 10 percent interest per month, got his tooth fixed, and went
home. When he still hadn't picked up the ring by Super Bowl week,
Palace Jewelers put it up for auction on eBay, and within 24 hours
the bidding was up to $11,000. Hayes got wind of things and tried
to buy it back for $16,000 from the pawn shop owner, but she
refused, saying it would destroy her credibility in future eBay
auctions. Eventually, the ring went to an anonymous bidder for
$18,200, and now Hayes is trying to sue on a technicality, claiming
he should have been notified before the ring was put up for sale.
The moral of this story is one of two things: Always floss after
eating, or don't forget to pick up your things . . . Randall
Cunningham refused to take a major pay cut in Minnesota and may
find himself among the unemployed soon, while Viking punter Mitch
Berger landed the biggest signing bonus for a punter in NFL
history. Berger joined Cleveland's Chris Gardocki as the
highest-paid punter when he signed a five-year, $6 million deal,
but Berger's $1.65 million signing bonus was a record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
