<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-KIWIS-AMCUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALAND TAKES CHALLENGE SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ If Team New Zealand goes on to win the
America's Cup in the next couple of days, it will, in a season of
firsts, set another mark.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will New Zealand be the Cup's 30th winner, it will be
the first nation outside the United States to successfully defend
the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   If we discount the wacky Big Boat/catamaran race of 1988 as a
mere blemish on Cup history, then New Zealand is the first sailing
team to successfully defend the Cup since 1980, when Dennis
Conner's Freedom campaign became the last winning defense by the
New York Yacht Club.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this important? Ever since New York lost the Cup in 1983,
the theory has taken hold that it is easier to drive a camel
through the eye of a needle than it is to win and then successfully
defend the Anerica's Cup. The record:
</P>
<P>
   --1986, Freemantle. After defeating NYYC in '83, Australia's two
defense syndicates (Australia and Kookaburra) were pathetically off
the pace and were beaten by Conner's Stars &AMP; Stripes, 4-0. It is
assumed by most that New Zealand's ``White Magic,'' which lost to
Conner in the Louis Vuitton Cup, 4-1, would have also beaten
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   --1988, San Diego. This 4-0 Stars &AMP; Stripes catamaran win over
the renegade challenge by New Zealand's 120-foot monohull is
discounted from history because the ``race'' was between such
disparate boats without a class.
</P>
<P>
   --1992, San Diego. Stars &AMP; Stripes was easily beaten by Bill
Koch's America3, which easily beat Italy's Il Moro de Venezia for
the Cup. Il Moro, helmed by Paul Cayard, beat New Zealand in the
Vuitton finals.
</P>
<P>
   --1995, San Diego. Team New Zealand's Black Magic beat the US
entry of Conner's syndicate sailing Young America's boat (with
Cayard driving). It was a 5-0 win, the most lopsided in history, as
New Zealand won all 25 marks and extended in all 30 legs.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the record book, the logical theory arises that the
challengers have much more competition than the defenders on their
way to the America's Cup match.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this set of races, in which 11 challengers began
competing in round robins in October. Each challenger raced each
other three times through the round robins, with the best six
advancing to the semifinals for another round robin.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after those 40 races, Prada beat AmericaOne in the closest
Vuitton finals in history, 5-4, and entered the America's Cup match
with 49 races under its belt.
</P>
<P>
   Team New Zealand, on the other hand, has had nothing but racing
between its two boats, NZ57 and NZ60. Throughout the Cup season,
the Kiwis have assured everyone that 22-year-old Dean Barker,
skipper of NZ57 and skipper Russell Coutts's heir apparent, has
been pushing the A team on NZ60 just as hard as any challenger
could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me,'' said Sir Peter Blake, the syndicate's figurehead
leader, ``these guys push each other plenty hard. We're going to be
as fast as we can possibly be.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake's words were dismissed as prerace rah-rah fight talk. How
could Team New Zealand possibly be as battle-hardened as Prada,
especially after the Italians' excruciating win over tough guy
Cayard and AmericaOne?
</P>
<P>
   Well, as New Zealand contemplates putting Barker and the junior
varsity aboard NZ60 for their first America's Cup race, the
challengers see in horror that Blake was right.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, in a remote corner of the South Pacific, a tiny nation
of 3.8 million has produced the boat technology and sailing skill
to stand a full head above the best designers and sailors from the
United States, Europe, and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have just raised the standard,'' said Nippon skipper
Peter Gilmour. ``We were all shooting at the standard New Zealand
set in '95, and many of us got there. The problem is that they
moved on to a new level, and if we shoot for that next time, they
will have gone beyond us yet again.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how New Zealand got to such a commanding level by going it
alone will doubtless be analyzed for the next three years until the
next Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, its design team, led by Laurie Davidson, got outside
the box, just as Australia's Ben Lexcen did when he came up with
the Australia II breakthrough winner in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is not only that NZ60, a big, powerful boat with a
meter more waterline, runs away and hides when the wind pipes
stronger than 15 knots. In the lighter ranges, she also holds her
own nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory to chew on in the final days of America's Cup 30
is that Cayard may be correct: With so many challenger syndicates,
the gene pool was dragged down by its lower end more than it was
heightened by its top performers.
</P>
<P>
   Team New Zealand began with excellence coming out of '95 and
spawned nothing but more excellence. The truth is that the races
the Kiwis don't win with boat speed, they do with superior teamwork
and afterguard tactics.
</P>
<P>
   And if Gilmour is correct in his assessment, then the ultimate
question is whether New Zealand can match the New York Yacht Club's
record for holding onto the Cup: 132 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
