u s BC-GLF-MATCHPLAY-DUVAL-B     02-26 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MATCHPLAY-DUVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL AND DREAM FINAL MEET MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Half of the dream matchup avoided being
tripped up by a falling pine cone Saturday morning. The other half
could not avoid a steamrolling gentleman who has been described as
a ``big teddy bear.''
</P>
<P>
   So what we have in Sunday's 36-hole final of the Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship at La Costa Resort and Spa is
Tiger Woods against Northern Ireland's Darren Clarke, with David
Duval relegated to a consolation match against Davis Love.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be what TV folks had hoped for, but don't call it a
shock, said Duval after his 4-and-2 thrashing by Clarke in the
semifinals. ``I wasn't fool enough to look past him. I got what I
deserved,'' said Duval, the world's second-ranked player whose
first real head-to-head battle with No. 1 Woods will have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Woods was grateful to get past Paul Lawrie in the
morning, in a quarterfinal match punctuated by misfortune at the
10th. Beneath a tree after an errant drive, Woods got to the top of
his backswing when his club grazed the tree. Down came a small
branch _ ``I got hit on the head with a pine cone'' _ and the hole
was lost, Woods having violated a rule by improving his swing path.
Two down, Woods casually scooped up his ball, halved the 11th, then
won the next three holes to put a stop to any thoughts of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, Woods was nothing short of brilliant in
putting the hammer to Love with a 5-and-4 blitz that was a
combination of power, finesse, and pure imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Woods eagled the 526-yard second, then birdied the fourth,
fifth, eighth, and ninth for a 6-under-par 30 trip out. There was
no slaughter rule in effect, so Woods went to the back with a 4-up
cushion and one thought on his mind: ``I needed to execute golf
shots and keep applying pressure to Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure? How about unmerciful glitz, too. Like his second shot
to the 541-yard, par-5 12th. Woods had driven well right into the
rough, perhaps his only bad shot of the afternoon, and a tree
blocked his path. No worries. Not when you are the one human being
capable of shaping a 6-iron from 221 yards around one tree, then
another, to a green that should not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was phenomenal,'' said Love, who despite putting up a
55-hole stretch without a bogey was helpless as Woods rolled in his
second eagle of the afternoon to go 5 up. When the match ended two
holes later, Woods was 8 under, which you may think is pretty good.
Silly you. ``I could have been 14 under or better,'' said Woods,
and though he smiled, it was hard to say whether he was kidding.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clarke, he was joking early during the week when he told
Woods that ``I am 1-0 against you,'' referring to a four-ball
triumph last September in the Ryder Cup Matches. But there were
partners then, and Sunday Clarke is on his own. Going one-on-one
against Woods, he said, is a formidable task because ``he is the
best player in the world. That's pretty obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but what should not be lost is the fairly
impressive way in which Clarke stormed from 3 down to beat Hal
Sutton in the morning, then dismantled No. 2 in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Duval had easily been the best player on the course during the
morning, dishing out a 5-and-4 beating to Scott Hoch, a six-birdie,
bogey-free blitz that was so efficient that the loser said he had
no chance. ``Where's Tonya Harding when you need her?'' said Hoch,
who was all square through six before Duval birdied five of the
next seven holes to put the issue to rest.
</P>
<P>
   What Duval couldn't do was carry that momentum into the
afternoon, as the only birdie he made going out against Clarke was
a bomb at the fourth to square the match. It would be the final
highlight of Duval's tournament, however, as Clarke hit it stiff at
the fifth to go 1 up and regain control.
</P>
<P>
   Duval put up a parade of pars _ 12 of them _ but slipped further
behind as Clarke birdied the par-4 10th and par-5 12th. The
frustration took its toll on Duval at the 13th, where after yanking
his approach from the middle of the fairway well left of the pin,
he slammed his club into the turf. His mood did not improve minutes
later when his birdie chance rolled past the hole and Clarke, in
tighter and on the same line, made his.
</P>
<P>
   At 4 up, Clarke had his ticket to an improbable final match that
will pay $1 million to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big teddy bear,'' said Butch Harmon of Clarke, with
whom he has been working for more than a year. Which gives Harmon
two pupils in Sunday's final match, for he has been with Woods
every swing of the way for nearly seven years now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a lot of fun,'' said the teacher, ``but when
Woods is on, he can't be beaten.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
