<HEADER>
A9569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBARAIL0227-COX     02-26 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBARAIL0227-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The power struggle
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. Indiana Pacers: The work off the bench from little-known
forward Austin Croshere has been significant. The Pacers have won
more blowouts than anyone except the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   2. New York Knicks: Hard-nosed defense keeps them in most games,
but it's difficult to get consistent offense. Also, a lack of
interest against weaker teams is alarming.
</P>
<P>
   3. Miami Heat: Best road team in the conference, but still not
intimidating at home. Offensive struggles show against teams with
tough defensive mindset.
</P>
<P>
   4. Charlotte Hornets: It is truly impressive that they have
remained rock-solid emotionally after Bobby Phills' death. Derrick
Coleman has been brilliant, and Anthony Mason as point forward has
worked.
</P>
<P>
   5. Philadelphia 76ers: By playoff time, Allen Iverson and Toni
Kukoc will be comfortable with each other and their ranking should
be higher. They're tops in the league in tight games.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   1. Los Angeles Lakers: They get top billing because they have
the best player, Shaquille O'Neal. It also is impressive that they
hold teams to a league-low shooting percentage (40.8).
</P>
<P>
   2. Portland Trail Blazers: Quick: Who's the best defensive team
in the league? Yep, these guys. And with all that offensive talent,
that kind of D makes them extremely tough.
</P>
<P>
   3. San Antonio Spurs: How long can they survive without a true
small forward? So far, they've fared just fine, thank you. With
them, it all starts and ends with defense and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   4. Phoenix Suns: Penny Hardaway seems healthy, finally, and his
play has opened up the game for everyone. But reserve forward
Rodney Rogers has been the Suns' best player lately.
</P>
<P>
   5. Utah Jazz: Karl Malone and John Stockton just keep on going.
Utah knows how to play as a team, and it often overcomes individual
talent on other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE RISE
</P>
<P>
   _ Seattle point guard Gary Payton: Since the All-Star break,
Payton has been on a torrid stretch, exemplified by the 41 points
in three quarters against Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phoenix forward Rodney Rogers: The firepower he's provided off
the bench has been big in the Suns' rise in the West. Even in his
low game of the week, Rogers had 17 points in 17 minutes against
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   _ Charlotte forward Derrick Coleman: The much-maligned Coleman
capped a string of brilliant play with a 32-point, 12-rebound,
5-assist and 3-steal effort against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   FREE-FALLIN'
</P>
<P>
   _ Golden State guard Larry Hughes: Once he gets comfortable, he
probably will star for the Warriors. But he has yet to find his
shooting eye, as in his 2-for-16 effort against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seattle's Vin Baker: Not long ago considered one of the best
power forwards in the league, Baker mostly has been ordinary. He
bottomed out with a 2-point effort in 30 minutes against Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING BACK
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lakers ran off six in a row on the road, with the only
serious threat being a nationally televised victory at Philadelphia
during which Kobe Bryant shut down Allen Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Commendably, the New York Knicks responded to an NAACP boycott
of South Carolina by pulling their training camp site at the
College of Charleston as long as the Confederate battle flag flies
atop the Statehouse dome.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Georgia Tech star Stephon Marbury was brilliant amid a
consistent chorus of boos in his return to Minnesota after forcing
a trade to New Jersey last season. Marbury had 39 points in a rare
Nets road win. ``I just have fun on the court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   _ With the Hawks unable to move Isaiah Rider before Thursday's
trade deadline, it bears watching what the club will do with the
talented but troublesome shooting guard. They have considered
releasing Rider, an idea that might gain momentum if he continues
to be the kind of distraction that has affected the team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Milwaukee coach George Karl just might blow a gasket _ or
strangle a player _ if the Bucks continue their recent fall. They
dropped all the way to eighth in the conference by losing seven of
10 games, including four in a row. Two of those defeats came at
lowly Washington and at home to awful Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   _ Toni Kukoc makes his first return to Chicago as a Philadelphia
76er on Saturday. It will be interesting to see the reaction Kukoc
gets, as he was a key part of the Bulls' last three titles but not
as integral as Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING SPREE
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the league's best and worst bargains among NBA
players this season (relatively speaking, of course):
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose, Indiana: $2,437,500 _ Bargain
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Bradley, Dallas: $7,560,000 _ Overpriced
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Taylor, L.A. Clippers: $1,367,400 _ Bargain
</P>
<P>
   Scott Williams, Milwaukee: $3,750,000 _ Overpriced
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson, New York: $11,910,714 _ Overpriced
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Rogers, Phoenix: $2,000,000 _ Bargain
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker, Seattle: $9,000,000 _ Overpriced
</P>
<P>
   Juwan Howard, Washington: $15,000,000 _ Overprice
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
