<HEADER>
A9571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES0227-C0X     02-26 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES0227-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talk about your tough workplace
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How about the Vancouver Grizzlies, where the next
owner has his own guys scouting, sometimes double-booking games
where current general manager Stu Jackson already has scouts on
site? Dick Versace, the so-called consultant hired by incoming
owner Michael Heisley, has put together a shadow scouting staff
that already is scouting college games. Versace's team of scouts
has Grizzlies' personnel arranging credentials. One of the most
recent examples was last Sunday when Cincinnati played Temple.
Larry Riley, Vancouver's director of player personnel, was on hand
for the Grizzlies. But Mitchell Anderson, a former NBA player who
played for Versace at Bradley University, also was accredited.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jason Caffey of Golden State did not want to be moved before
the trade deadline, and certainly not to Milwaukee. On Wednesday,
report published in the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel said the
Warriors were talking to the Bucks about a possible trade involving
Caffey. Caffey did not want to go to the Bucks _ under any
circumstances _ and made it known after his team beat the Bucks
91-86 in Milwaukee. ``There's no way I want to come to Milwaukee,''
Caffey said. ``I called my wife last night, and she started crying
when I told her about Milwaukee.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Pat Riley's honeymoon in Miami is over. He is getting bashed
on radio call-in shows for stubbornly refusing to even consider
deals for non-scoring forward P.J. Brown. One columnist labeled
Riley's master plan a failure and called on him to start over: Keep
Alonzo Mourning and trade everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   _ After Kevin Garnett played a game-high 35 minutes in the
All-Star game Feb. 13, Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said he was
going to try to find time to rest Garnett. Over his last five
games, however, Garnett has logged 45, 40, 41, 46 and 40 minutes.
He averages 40.1 minutes a game, sixth in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of the excise tax of 2002 killed the trade market _ no
surprise with the cap scheduled to go to $35.5 million for 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   _ Portland leads the league with a salary-cap total of
$73,898,705, with New York second at $71,340,801. The Indiana
Pacers are third at $54,158,605 and the Lakers fourth at
$54,123,533. The tax will be assessed at $1 for every $1 over the
cap.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
