</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NOMARGLOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING COMES BETWEEN GARCIAPARRA AND HIS GLOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ This is a glove story, and as such, it
contains the usual elements: passion, romance, heartbreak, and
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my baby,'' Nomar Garciaparra said, nuzzling his cheek
against his glove while a photographer shot away. ``I'm going to go
to sleep with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He was kidding (we think) about the glove occupying the pillow
beside him. But say this for the Red Sox shortstop: He's faithful
to a fault. Let someone else opt for younger, fresher, sexier, more
supple. Garciaparra doesn't even look at the new models.
</P>
<P>
   His glove is all about wrinkles and worry lines, comfort and
familiarity. It's the very definition of age over beauty, the
lived-in over the never-touched.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the glove peddlers appear at spring training camps,
showing off the latest fashions in leatherwear. Saturday morning,
the Rawlings people were here. Most players have a contract with a
glove company. Garciaparra? He's been using the same worn piece of
leather since his sophomore year at Georgia Tech, eight years ago.
And he protects it jealously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody touches my glove,'' Garciaparra said. ``You can't put
your hand in my glove. You can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   This glove, Garciaparra only wears in games. He has a backup
just as old. Something breaks, a lace comes undone, or the webbing
frays, Garciaparra fixes it himself.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it lying around? Perish the thought. Garciaparra never
takes his game glove out of the Sox' clubhouse during batting
practice. His glove sits beside him on the bench. His backup glove,
he places under the dugout bench _ in the exact same place _ before
every game.
</P>
<P>
   See him between pitches out on the field? He's always biting on
the dangling laces of his glove. They're for his lips only.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't even make my glove anymore,'' Garciaparra said of
the SSK infielder's glove he wears. ``You're not going to find one
anywhere. You won't find the same leather. They don't use it
anymore. Even if you found a similar model, they use a different
tanner, different leather.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find a glove you're comfortable with, you stick with it. I
make my living with this glove. The model number? N-O-M-A-R.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaz was like that. Carl Yastrzemski used the same glove almost
his whole career. Sox hitting coach Jim Rice now has Yaz's glove.
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin is another one. The Sox third baseman has been
using the same Mizuno glove for eight years, too. It doesn't look
like it has the same mileage as Garciaparra's, but that's because
this used to be Val's backup model. The glove he used to use, the
one he first wore in the minor leagues in 1990 and with which he
turned an unassisted triple play against the Mariners in 1994, that
one was stolen the following year.
</P>
<P>
   It still pains Valentin to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The triple play glove, it was in my Toyota Land Cruiser,''
Valentin said. ``They stole the car in New Jersey, right out of my
in-laws' driveway. My biggest loss that day? The glove, without a
doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin covers the outside of his glove with pine tar. Why?
``Because at night, there's dew on the grass and the ball gets
wet,'' he said. ``It helps me with my grip. I learned that from
(ex-Sox catcher) Tony Pena.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox outfielder Darren Lewis changes his glove every other year.
``I don't want my glove too loose, because I don't want the ball
popping out of my glove,'' he said. ``Outfielders, we're a little
different than infielders. A lot of times we're running full
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who has a Gold Glove for defensive excellence, shares a
little secret about his Rawlings glove: ``If you're a Gold Glover,
they use a little better leather,'' he said. ``It's not the same
leather as other gloves. It's like if you're a home run or batting
champion. The wood they use for your bats is a little harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rowe is the Red Sox trainer, a line of work he first got
into in 1985, when he was trainer for Beloit (Wis.) in the Single-A
Midwest League. When you're a trainer in the lower minors, you do
more than tend to ankle sprains and pulled muscles. You become the
glove doctor, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have equipment managers in the minor leagues,''
Rowe said. ``The trainer does that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows all the tricks. ``Little quirky things,'' he said,
``like breaking a glove in by dipping it into the whirlpool, then
sticking it in a dryer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players cover their glove in Alboline, a hand cleanser used
for massages, then stick it in a dryer. Others opt for the
microwave. Not a good idea, Rowe said. ``It cooks the laces. Take
it out of the microwave, and it snaps all the laces. Plus there's
metal in gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Other players have been known to place their gloves in a
hot-pack machine. There's a pounding tool, often a metal ball or
even a baseball attached to a rod, which is used to whack the
pocket of a glove. ``Some guys just look for the biggest bat they
can find and pound the heck out of their gloves,'' Rowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Those big first baseman's mitts? Rowe will often cut a sheet of
orthoplastic _ the kind he uses to make pads _ place it in the
glove, then sew it up. Catcher's mitts, which take such a pounding,
require constant TLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason (Varitek) always takes care of his own,'' Rowe said.
``He's very self-sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Repair tools to tighten the laces or repair a broken one?
There's a darning needle, of course, a threader, a hemostat (the
instrument doctors use to put in sutures), and an Army survival
tool _ ``You know, the kind that has pliers, a hole punch, a can
opener, and a leather punch,'' Rowe said. ``I've got a zipper bag
with 15 years' worth of stuff in it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are definite rules of etiquette in one's glove life. ``You
never put your hand in someone's glove unless you ask him,'' Rowe
said. ``You have to respect that there's a perfect hand fit there
after someone's taken so many ground balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Rowe said, there's a special relationship between a player
and his glove. ``Some guys never want to give up their glove until
it's ready to fall apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Has he ever known a player to name his glove? Rowe laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not anyone who has ever told about it,'' Rowe said. ``But I'm
sure there have been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
