</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMCUP-SKIPPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIPPERS ON VERY DIFFERENT PATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ With Race 3 at hand and a wind building
over the Hauraki Gulf course Friday, the competing boats _ and the
men who steer them _ headed out for what was a crucial race.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Italians won and been down just one race in the
best-of-nine series, reason to believe in ``Pradamania'' would have
lived. But when Team New Zealand won by 1 minute 39 seconds to take
a 3-0 lead, it became the Force _ inevitable, insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   The skippers, Russell Coutts and Francesco de Angelis, face very
different circumstances, and do so with contrasting styles and
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Where de Angelis is quiet and sometimes so calm that teammates
wish he would say more to direct them, Coutts is sometimes brash,
diffident, and even cantankerous to a press corps he finds
irritating.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: After Race 1, Coutts and tactician Brad
Butterworth decided to pass the postrace news conference. Instead,
crew members Simon Daubney and Warwick Fleury appeared before an
outraged press corps that demanded to know where the top guns were.
</P>
<P>
   After Race 2, Coutts appeared with Butterworth and very quickly
snarled at the press for putting such demands on them. ``We are a
team,'' said Coutts, ``anyone from Team New Zealand represents us
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The guffaws were audible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, watching from his place on the dais was de Angelis, a
tall, slim figure. De Angelis and tactician Torben Grael have been
at every postrace press conference since the Cup began in October.
But asked later about his thoughts on Coutts's intransigence, de
Angelis would not rise to the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no opinion. He does what he thinks is best for this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   His friends _ and the Italian public _ call de Angelis ``Il
Barone'' because of his cultured ways and unflappable style. A
student of biology, de Angelis, 39, did not start sailing until he
was a teenager, and then became fanatical, his friends say.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 27, he won the J-24 Worlds and went on to win
five World Championships. As a young sailor trying to improve his
technique, a coach once told him: ``Train, train, train, and don't
speak. I have achieved goals for 20 years without speaking
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   This shows a contrast to American rival Paul Cayard, who in one
race during the semifinals seemed to have shouted the loudest to
the on-board umpires and caused a foul to be called in the Italian
boat.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, de Angelis has sailed with Cayard and was working on
his Whitbread round-the-world campaign before Prada syndicate boss
Patrizio Bertelli approached him with an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Having never match-raced in his life, he was paired with Grael,
a three-time Olympic champion, and the two have formed an
inseparable partnership in the cockpit of Luna Rossa.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, US Cup veteran Rod Davis was brought on to coach
the two on match-racing moves _ a kind of high-speed chess game on
the water between 25-ton yachts. Because he is a perfectionist who
overlooks nothing, Davis said, de Angelis has been a fast study.
But mistakes in this game are glaring. When they come, said Davis:
``It's like watching your kids play soccer. Sometimes you just have
to look away and ask later what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   De Angelis and wife Corinna have two children attending school
in Auckland.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts sometimes gets so focused with sailing that he becomes
oblivious to people around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People sometimes think I'm deaf,'' he said, ``but I'm just
thinking about other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Coutts has been on the radar screen of New Zealand sailing
heavies since he was a child. Twice he was World Youth Sailing
champion, and at age 22, he won an Olympic gold medal. That was two
years before his country's first assault on the America's Cup, then
being sailed in Fremantle, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   From that point, Coutts was the heir apparent to Chris Dickson,
and moved easily into the backup skipper's role in 1992, then into
the skipper's role in 1995 _ the year Team New Zealand won the most
lopsided America's Cup series in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to do a lot of thinking before a race,'' said Coutts.
``I'm not just trying to focus. I prepare for a race by
visualizing. We're a bit older, and I have learned a lot in the
last four years. But I'm a little more tolerant now than I was
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Coutts, 37, believes this may be his last Cup. ``Life is not a
training run. I'll do this while I enjoy it. You should only do
things while you're having fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
