</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BBNOTES-RADKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX HAVE PLACE FOR TWINS ACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Brad Radke is 27 years old, big, strong,
durable, and dependable. Three years ago, he was a 20-game winner.
In each of the last two seasons, playing for one of the bottom
feeders in the American League, he won a dozen games, and last
season in 218 2/3 innings he had a 3.75 ERA, fourth best in the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   Radke is eligible for free agency after this season. He and
agent Ron Simon have broken off negotiations with his current
employer, the Minnesota Twins, because the team refuses to allow
Radke the right to demand a trade after the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   Radke is in Fort Myers, Fla., on the other side of town from the
Red Sox camp, knowing one more veteran starting pitcher might be
the piece to put Boston over the top against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox Nation to Dan Duquette: Make the deal now, if not
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Were it only so simple. For one, the Twins have not abandoned
hope they can sign Radke. The sides reportedly are $5 million
apart, with the Twins' last offer at three years, $21 million, and
Radke seeking three years at $26 million. Twins general manager
Terry Ryan has said he won't budge on the no-trade language; Simon
has said he can't make a deal without it. ``I can't put him with a
team that might be pathetic for four years,'' he said when talks
broke off.
</P>
<P>
   Simon is in Fort Myers, which is just a coincidence, according
to Ryan. ``He has a vacation home and he comes down here every
spring,'' Ryan said. ``But I suspect we'll talk while he's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Radke is not commenting.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Ryan can't get the extension done, he is not tipping
his hand. ``It's not something I wish to discuss publicly,'' he
said. ``There's going to be talk about a guy like Radke who has had
that type of success, but ultimately it comes down to what are we
going to do, and that I'm not willing to discuss publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins are your classic small-market, low-budget team. They
have had seven consecutive losing seasons. They lost 97 games last
season using 17 rookies, often starting six. They had a $16 million
budget, a fifth of what the Yankees spend. Radke gives Minnesota a
legitimate ace, but with an extension, he also would blow the
budget, and gain all the leverage with a right-to-trade clause.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins have reasons to do a deal. But the Red Sox are hardly
alone in their interest. The Reds, Devil Rays, Rockies, A's, Mets,
and Phillies have been mentioned as suitors. When the Sox talked to
the Twins at the winter meetings, the price for Radke was deemed
too high by at least one Sox official. ``If we had given them what
Terry wanted, we wouldn't have a farm system left,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That would suggest the Twins are asking for a Dernell Stenson in
return, or a Wilton Veras or Steve Lomasney, or all of the above.
It probably will take at least three players to make a deal. The
Sox could put together a package that would include one or two arms
out of the Brian Rose/Juan Pena/Tomo Ohka/Sunny Kim mix, plus a
position player or two.
</P>
<P>
   Even that might not be enough to make the deal this spring. Ryan
will play his suitors off one another, knowing he can wait until
the July trading deadline when even more clubs might be in the hunt
for a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the silver lining for Sox fans: Everybody wanted Pedro
Martinez, too, and Duquette was able to offer the right combination
(Carl Pavano, Tony Armas Jr.) to Montreal. Can he do the same this
spring? Don't bet against it.
</P>
<P>
   More swap talk
</P>
<P>
   The John Rocker trade rumors won't go away. The latest is Rocker
to the Devil Rays for closer Roberto Hernandez, or Rocker and
lefthander Bruce Chen to the Expos for closer Ugueth Urbina and
Pavano. The Indians, who come into the season projecting Paul Shuey
as the closer _ he's the guy who gave up Troy O'Leary's
tie-breaking, three-run home run in the deciding game of the
Sox-Tribe division series _ are also said to have interest in
Rocker. The sentiment in the Braves' clubhouse is that Rocker will
be dealt . . . The Mariners haven't abandoned their pursuit of
Angels outfielder Jim Edmonds, but may have widened talks to
include Garret Anderson . . . Rockies GM Dan O'Dowd acknowledged
that the Angels called to see if Colorado has interest in Edmonds
in exchange for a starting pitcher . . . The Rangers reportedly
have interest in Mets lefthanded reliever Dennis Cook . . . Looking
the part: Who says the Reds aren't sensitive to the fashion tastes
of incoming players? When Deion Sanders first arrived in 1997, he
coaxed the team into cutting its sleeves and wearing a vest. Last
season, when Greg Vaughn came from San Diego, the team permitted
facial hair. And now, with the arrival of Ken Griffey Jr., earrings
will be allowed for the first time. No danglers, please. Studs
only. Hal McCoy of the Dayton Daily News notes that it was former
Reds owner Marge Schott who once proclaimed: ``Only fruits wear
earrings.'' Catcher Eddie Taubensee, for one, doesn't plan to take
advantage of the chance to get his ears pierced. ``I'm not going to
wear one, even though my wife has some nice ones in her jewelry
box,'' he said. ``It would be hard for pitchers to take a catcher
seriously when he is wearing an earring.'' Meanwhile, new managers
Buddy Bell (Rockies) and Don Baylor (Cubs) are tightening the rules
in their clubhouses. The Rockies once again will wear sport coats
and slacks when they travel. No beards. No jewelry on the field.
Clubhouse games of cards and dominoes must end an hour before
players are to be in uniform. Golf clubs will not be allowed on
road trips, unless there is an off day during the trip. And players
are expected to be on the top step of the dugout when the National
Anthem is played. In Chicago, some of Baylor's rules include no
cutoffs or gym shorts at the ballpark, no scraggly goatees or
beards, and no baseball caps worn backward, a la Griffey. ``This
club is very visible and appearance has a lot to do with things,''
Baylor said. ``To me, it's part of attitude. Look professional.
Look like you're a major league player, not a rock star.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixed signals
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in Boston's camp, where Duquette and Jimy Williams took
Martinez's late arrival in stride, Baylor is irked by Sammy Sosa's
absence. Sosa said he was stricken with the flu while in Las Vegas
for a home run hitting contest, then returned to the Dominican
Republic. He was scheduled to arrive in Arizona Sunday. ``It is a
big deal,'' Baylor said last week. ``I imagine a lot of guys in
that room probably care. You don't want to put one guy before the
team.'' Yet, Sosa being AWOL didn't keep Baylor from naming
Sluggin' Sammy one of four team captains, joining Mark Grace, Rick
Aguilera, and Kevin Tapani . . . No player heard his name connected
to trade rumors more in the last several years in LA than first
baseman Eric Karros, which is why it came as a great relief last
week when the Dodgers gave him a three-year, $24 million contract.
The deal includes a no-trade clause for the first two years. By
that time, he will be a 10-5 player (10 years in the big leagues,
at least five with the same team), which entitles him to veto any
trade. He agreed to waive that provision for peace of mind. With 34
home runs and 112 RBIs last season, Karros ranked behind only Mark
McGwire, Jeff Bagwell, and Todd Helton among National League first
basemen. Karros has 211 lifetime home runs; 18 more and he passes
Ron Cey as the leading home run hitter in LA Dodgers history . . .
Slump-ridden White Sox slugger Frank Thomas has brought former Red
Sox hitting coach Walt Hriniak to camp to help him break out a
two-year funk. The White Sox also have Paul Konerko taking ground
balls at third. Manager Jerry Manuel says he could play there in
certain matchups. Konerko is a first baseman, but played a full
season at third in the Dodgers' system three years ago . . . With
Darryl Strawberry almost certain to be bounced for at least a year
after his latest drug test, The King, Jim Leyritz, will get more
at-bats as the Yankees' designated hitter. Leyritz had offseason
surgery to repair a torn rotator cuff in his left shoulder.
Ideally, the Yanks would like a lefthanded hitter in that spot, but
right now, only switch-hitting Tim Raines, who is 40 and recovering
from lupus, fits that profile. Shane Spencer also figures in the
mix for the Yankees, who are not inclined to rush top first base
prospect Nick Johnson. Johnson hit .345 at Norwich (Eastern League)
last season. The Yankees haven't exactly leaned on their DH the
last two seasons. They ranked 10th in DH RBIs last season, and
eighth the year before . . . Mets pitcher Bill Pulsipher, who had
an unexplained collapse that left him unconscious on his bathroom
floor Wednesday, admitted he takes a dietary supplement without the
team's knowledge. He also said he uses the antidepressant Prozac .
. . San Diego GM Kevin Towers, who helped take the Padres to two
division titles and a World Series, then had to take the team apart
because of financial considerations, has been rewarded with a
three-year contract extension through 2003. Towers's latest deal
was for outfielder Al Martin, who comes from the Pirates and will
be asked to bat leadoff for San Diego. The Pirates dumped Martin's
salary, allowing them to install Wil Cordero in left field and
highly touted prospect Chad Hermansen in right. Hermansen hit 32
home runs for Nashville (Triple A) last season . . . McGwire was
more than happy to see public attention shift from his home run
exploits to Griffey. ``When the (Griffey) trade was done, I
thought, `Now, I can sit back and blend in,' '' McGwire said . . .
Braves manager Bobby Cox didn't know Steve Avery was out of a job
until pitcher John Smoltz mentioned it last weekend. A few days
later, the Braves signed Avery to a minor league deal. Avery
pitched two seasons for the Sox, spent last year with Cincinnati,
and is coming off arthroscopic shoulder surgery . . . The Phillies
are happy that first baseman Rico Brogna, only a month after
arthroscopic knee surgery, has been cleared to play when the
exhibition season begins this week. Less encouraging was the news
that closer Mike Jackson, released by the Indians after last season
because they thought he might break down, had sore knees after two
days of fielding drills.
</P>
<P>
   Good soldier
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, upon arrival in Angels camp: ``I'm excited about this
team. I heard all this stuff about me wanting to get traded, but
I've never not finished something I started. We're going to get
this right here. I'm not about to jump ship. I hope there wasn't a
perception that I'm not happy to be here.'' That may be so, but
former teammate Chuck Finley, for one, says the Angels would love
to dump Vaughn and his $80 million salary. Vaughn told reporters he
wasn't worried about the shaky state of the franchise. ``It doesn't
matter what direction this franchise is going. I have nothing to do
with that,'' he said. ``I'm not a general manager. I'm here to play
the game and that's it.'' . . . Pencil in former Sox pitcher Jamie
Moyer as Pedro's opponent when the Sox open against the Mariners in
Seattle April 4. Mariners manager Lou Piniella already announced
that Moyer is his pick. This will be the first time since Erik
Hanson in 1991 that Seattle's Opening Day starter will be someone
other than Randy Johnson, who started the Mariners' first game from
1992 through '96 and in '98, or Jeff Fassero, who pitched the
opener in 1997 and 1999 . . . Lefthander Justin Thompson, a main
component in the deal that sent Juan Gonzalez from Texas to
Detroit, almost certainly will begin the season on the disabled
list. Thompson had arthroscopic shoulder surgery in August and the
Rangers plan to bring him along slowly this spring . . . The latest
bidder to buy the Royals is Facundo Bacardi, the great-great-great
grandson of the liquor family. Bacardi, 33, doesn't have deep ties
to the community, or to the Royals. He was born in Chicago, grew up
in Florida, lives in Atlanta, and only last week paid his first
visit to Kauffman Stadium. He insists he has no plans of moving the
team if he succeeds in buying the club. WalMart magnate David Glass
remains the front-runner to buy the Royals . . . Orioles second
baseman Delino DeShields came off the top rope with this quote
aimed at fired manager Ray Miller: ``I've played for probably the
best manager in baseball, Felipe Alou,'' DeShields said, ``and I've
played for maybe the worst one.'' . . . The Blue Jays took David
Wells behind closed doors after the irrepressible one was quoted as
saying the club had received ``crap'' in offseason trades,
especially the one in which they shipped former Cy Young Award
winner Pat Hentgen to the Cardinals. Manager Jim Fregosi said he
was concerned at how Wells's comments would affect the fans,
especially with the Blue Jays already taking a PR hit for dealing
All-Star outfielder Shawn Green. Wells had nothing to say after the
meeting. Said Fregosi: ``We did not muzzle him. We don't operate
that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
