<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-MATCH-PLAY-NYT &LR;      02-26 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MATCH-PLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARKE GIVES DUVAL A JOLT, AND WILL FACE WOODS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Darren Clarke is the last man standing
between Tiger Woods and another conquest.
</P>
<P>
   After two victories Saturday, including a 5-and-4 pummeling of
Davis Love III in the semifinals of the Andersen Consulting Match
Play Championship, Woods stormed into Sunday's 36-hole championship
match. Clarke, the No. 19 seed from Northern Ireland, became Woods'
unexpected opponent in the final by beating David Duval, 4 and 2,
in the other semifinal match, spoiling a showdown between Woods and
Duval, the world's top two ranked players.
</P>
<P>
   While Clarke hopes for an upset Sunday at La Costa Resort &AMP; Spa,
he will face a daunting obstacle in Woods, who looked primed to win
for the third time this year and for the seventh time since last
August. After squeaking past Paul Lawrie, 1-up, in a difficult
quarterfinal morning match, Woods showed Love the exit door with a
dominant performance that left Love no chance.
</P>
<P>
   How good was Woods? On the front nine, he had an eagle and four
birdies. And on the back nine, he added another eagle set up by an
extraordinary shot, a 6-iron out of the rough from 221 yards that
he intentionally hooked, working the ball through an alley between
two trees and onto the green.
</P>
<P>
   After making a slight swing adjustment between his morning and
afternoon matches, Woods put on a devastating display, the world's
best performing at his best. And if Woods remains on top of his
game Sunday, Clarke may feel as helpless as Love felt Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tiger Woods is at his best, nobody in the world can beat
him, and the other players know it,'' said Butch Harmon, Woods'
coach, who also coaches Clarke. ``That's not a put-down of the
other players. He's just that much better than everyone else. That
was textbook golf this afternoon. When he plays his best, he's
unbeatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval would have loved an opportunity to beat Woods, but Clarke
did not cooperate, showing why he has been a member of Europe's
last two Ryder Cup teams. Clarke never trailed against Duval,
taking the lead for good on No. 5 after hitting his approach shot
to four feet, which set up a birdie. Clarke went 2-up on No. 10,
hitting another superb approach shot to five feet, then making
birdie. On the next hole, Clarke went 3-up when he made another
eight-footer for birdie, and Duval could see where their match was
headed.
</P>
<P>
   On No. 13, Duval slammed his club into the ground after pulling
an approach shot, and then after missing the following 25-foot
putt, Duval kicked the ground in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between his 5-and-4 victory over Scott Hoch in the
morning and his match against Clarke, Duval lost his sharpness. He
made only one birdie against Clarke, and most of Duval's approach
shots were off target, leaving him long putts for birdie that he
failed to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nobody to blame but myself,'' he said. ``I didn't get
it close enough to the hole.'' Asked if he was looking forward to a
potential match against Woods, Duval said: ``I wasn't foolish
enough to look past Darren. I'm familiar with his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, seeded fourth, was confident entering his match with Woods
after defeating Miguel Angel Jimenez, 3 and 2, in a morning
quarterfinal match. But Love could not elevate his game to Woods'
level.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods felt pressure in the morning, falling 2 down to Lawrie
through 11 holes before be rallied by winning three consecutive
holes to take the lead for good. Lawrie, the reigning British Open
champion, will remember this match for a while. He had a legitimate
chance to oust Woods, who continually missed fairways and was not
at his best. And Lawrie also received a major break on the 10th
hole, when Woods lost the hole on a penalty, the most bizarre
moment of the day.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting his drive on No. 10 into the right rough
underneath a tree, Woods clipped the branch on his backswing as he
attempted to hit the ball. Woods stopped in midswing as a pine cone
fell on the back of his head. A rules official arrived, and Woods
explained what had happened. At that point, it would have been
unfair for Woods to take another swing, because the branch that he
hit had been moved. Woods was informed that in match play, the
penalty for his infraction was loss of hole _ a bad break for Woods
and a gift for Lawrie. Already 1-up, Lawrie moved 2-up, fueling the
chance of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods regrouped with a key par-saving putt of six feet on
No. 11, then he won No. 12 with a birdie. At that point, Lawrie
began to stumble, and he made bogey at No. 13 and No. 14, and that
quickly, Woods had the lead again. On No. 17, Lawrie failed on a
late opportunity to tie the match when he missed an 18-foot birdie
attempt that slid just past the hole. The match ended on the par-4
18th hole, when both players made par after Lawrie hit a poor
second shot that sailed into the right rough.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke, 31, showed resiliency Saturday, winning a difficult
morning match against Hal Sutton, 1-up, a match in which Clarke was
3-down after four holes. But the 36-hole final will test the
stamina of Clarke, who is overweight. ``All that working out in the
off-season is going to pay off,'' Clarke said in jest, patting his
stomach. ``I better play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon has urged Clarke to lose weight, and he hoped this
encounter would push Clarke toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darren is going to be a great player, but he'd be even better
if I could get him to lose 20 pounds,'' Harmon said. ``I think this
experience will help motivate Darren.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clarke acknowledged that it would take more than motivation
to defeat Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best player in the world; that's pretty obvious to
everybody,'' Clarke said. ``I'm going to have to play particularly
well to beat him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
