<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-HOCKEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL HAS LEVERAGE IN THIS OLYMPIC MATCHUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest snag in getting NHLers back to the Olympics in 2002
is a last-minute arm twist by the Russians, Czechs, Swedes, and
Finns to get more money from the league for the players they lose.
If they don't, the Euros are threatening to keep their NHLers out
of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The league says it will be happy to talk money when the
agreement with the international federation ends next year. ``But
we will not be blackmailed,'' said NHL spokesman Frank Brown. ``The
Olympics are the Olympics, and transfer fees are transfer fees.
They're separate issues. There is a left hand and a right hand, and
they will not shake.''
</P>
<P>
   League commissioner Gary Bettman said as much to IIHF president
Rene Fasel when they met in New York earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the NHL doesn't have to give the Europeans
compensation, and both sides know it. And the league has more
immediate leverage: It can keep its players out of this year's
World Championships to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   The cutting edge
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A for how goofy figure skating rules have become is
15-year-old Sasha Cohen, who now has to win a medal at next week's
Junior World Championships to compete in the real World
Championships at the end of the month. Because she turned the
minimum age of 15 after last year's July 1 cut-off date, Cohen
needs to fit through the loophole that allows junior medalists to
compete regardless of age (which is how Sarah Hughes was eligible
at 14 last year). The whole point of the age rule is to limit the
physical and psychological demands on young girls. In fact, it
increases the demands by nearly doubling the number of events they
must skate. If the International Skating Union had its way, Cohen
would have been in Japan last week for the Four Continents event
before heading to Germany for the world juniors.
</P>
<P>
   Goofy ISU rules aren't limited to figure skating. The
federation's format for the World All-Around Speedskating
Championships is so bizarre as to be inexplicable. Only 12 skaters
get to compete in the final event (the 5,000 for women, the 10,000
for men), but they aren't necessarily the top 12 after three
events, since the ISU gives extra weight to the results of the
3,000/5,000 to protect Europeans who don't sprint well. That's how
US skater Derek Parra was bumped from this month's final in
Milwaukee even though he ranked 11th. And how Switzerland's Martin
Feigenwinter (who was 24th in two races) and Germany's Frank
Dittrich (22d and 23d) made it. ``That's just the way the rules
are,'' shrugged Parra. ``We knew that coming in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Speeding up process
</P>
<P>
   With Christine Witty back on form after a miserable autumn, the
United States has an outside chance for a medal at the World Sprint
Speedskating Championships in Seoul, where Canada's Jeremy
Wotherspoon and Germany's Monique Garbrecht are favored to retain
their crowns. Odds are better, though, that she'll make the podium
in the 1,000 at next weekend's single-distance championships in
Nagano. Same odds for the short-trackers at Saturday's world team
championships, where the Americans haven't won a medal since 1996.
The US squad includes Brookline's Dan Weinstein, Natick's Caroline
Hallisey, and Arlington's Sarah Lang . . . Harrowing tumble for
14-year-old Naomi Nari Nam, who finished eighth at the US
Championships after finishing second to Michelle Kwan last year.
That not only puts her out of contention for next season's Grand
Prix, it cost her an assumed berth on the US Junior World
Championships team, which will include Jennifer Kirk of Newton, the
best local women's prospect since Nancy Kerrigan . . . It's
rubber-room time for US bobsledder Brian Shimer. After missing an
Olympic four-man bronze at Nagano by .02 seconds, Shimer missed a
world bronze this month by .04. After seemingly having a medal
locked up, Shimer aggravated a calf injury and ended up eighth in
the last of four runs.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the team?
</P>
<P>
   With the Olympic trials in Boston less than six months off, the
USA Gymnastics people still haven't finalized their selection
process for the team. Part of the problem is the Aug. 25 roster
deadline and unresolved questions about how late alternates can be
subbed. ``We want the best team on the floor,'' said federation
president Bob Colarossi . . . The controversial computer-scoring
system used in amateur boxing could be on the way out, as a growing
number of fighters and coaches claim the results often bear little
resemblance to scoring punches thrown. The most recent plaintiffs
are brothers Glenn and Nonito Donaire, who staged a sit-down strike
in the ring at the US Olympic trials in Tampa after both lost to
light flyweight world champ Brian Viloria. ``I know how to use the
computer,'' said Viloria with a shrug. Critics claim the judges,
many of them golden agers, are too slow to push the button that
registers points. USA Boxing agrees and will push to have the
system scrapped. The irony is, the computer was brought in largely
because US light middleweight Roy Jones Jr. got jobbed in the 1988
Olympic finals . . . After sweeping past the Poles and Czechs and
various club teams in last month's European tour, the US Olympic
women's basketball team heads to Sao Paulo and Rio de Janeiro next
month to take on Sydney medal contenders Brazil and Cuba. The
Americans are 26-1 since September, the only loss coming in
November to the Tennessee varsity in Knoxville . . . By his hat ye
shall know him: golfer Greg Norman will be one of the 10,000
bearers for the Olympic torch relay for Sydney, along with
109-year-old Jack Lockett, Australia's oldest man. The Salt Lake
City relay will be the longest in Winter Games history _ 14,000
miles, with 11,000 bearers over more than two months . . . Why is
the international table tennis federation making the ball bigger?
To make the game more telegenic. The difference is from 1.5 to 1.6
inches in diameter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 2107EST &QL; 
