<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-PITINOTRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO PUTS CAP ON TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, sports fans, what you see is what you get.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were one of 27 teams that made no moves last week,
and Rick Pitino sounds as if he is going to stick with what he has.
It will go against his history to do so, but he only had to look at
what was happening in the East to stay the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this team,'' he said. ``I don't think we're far away.
We are going to have to add to this team to be a little more
athletic, a little bit better at the defensive end. But I don't
think it's anything major. We do have to make improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   That's another way of saying you're capped out, which the
Celtics are, and don't have many tradeable assets, which also is
the case. The team is painfully young, which is the way Pitino
built it, and the NBA is a league that devours its young.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Celtics simply are not a very good team. The
alternative to making trades is to keep on growing, as Derek &AMP; the
Dominoes once sang, and hope things get better. It will take
patience and perseverance, two of Pitino's favorite words these
days, and that's not even a lock. But that's the course he
apparently has chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Celtics) are still a fairly young team,'' Scottie
Pippen said when Boston passed through Portland. ``They're not
going to have the patience to work, thinking they're going to crack
us.''
</P>
<P>
   True. But Portland, like most of the good teams, is in the
Western Conference. As Pitino noted, ``the East is not like the
West. You add one or two players to a team in the East, and you can
make major improvements. Look at what Philadelphia did with (Toni)
Kukoc. Any number of teams can say that. It's a lot better to be in
the East.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent tumult in the conference supports this. The top three
teams are Indiana, Miami, and New York. In two years, those teams
could be falling hard. Milwaukee is in a horrible skid; it has lost
at home to Vancouver and Golden State and plays even worse defense
than the Celtics do. Detroit will have to convince Grant Hill it's
worth sticking around for the long term, and its argument is pretty
skimpy.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Philadelphia and Orlando look to be
contenders for some time (provided the Magic hit pay dirt this
summer), and there's always the Bulls, who, lest we forget, are 2-0
against the Celtics this season with basically a CBA roster.
They've got money to spend as well.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino has taken a lot of (justifiable) heat for continually
tinkering with the roster. It's hard to build anything when it's
constantly being taken apart. He made his bed. For once, he's
decided to sleep in it.
</P>
<P>
   Nothin' doin'
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, David Stern is smiling. Somewhere else, David Falk is
not smiling and is thinking, ``I told you so.'' The glacial
movement last week as the trading deadline came and went spoke
louder than any trade talk regarding how teams have their hands
tied by the new collective bargaining agreement. One deal was made:
a third-string point guard (Anthony Johnson) was dealt to Orlando
for a conditional second-round pick. The league wanted an agreement
that enabled clubs to keep their own players. It got that. But with
the restrictions in the document, it also got something else: a
situation in which teams can't move players they don't want.
``David Stern is happy,'' Pitino said after the deadline passed
and, for his first time as el jefe of hoops in Boston, he did
nothing. ``With the cap and the rules, you have fewer people
changing uniforms. That's what he wanted, and that's what he's
getting.'' Restricted player movement is, of course, precisely what
Falk and his minions said would happen with this agreement. Players
who may have had a certain marketplace value in the old system _
Danny Fortson, for instance _ are going to find the money is either
not there or only partly there. In addition to the cap regulations,
there also is the luxury tax on the horizon. Outside of a few
deep-pockets guys, most owners are not going to want to spend money
if it triggers the tax, which is still more than a year away. The
result was the slowest trading deadline in 13 years, reminiscent of
the days when there was no true free agency. There is now, in name
only. But the players aren't the only ones who will find the doors
closed. Teams such as Cleveland (Shawn Kemp) and Washington
(everyone) will find it just as difficult to move players for all
of the above reasons. Not even the wizardry of Michael Jordan is
going to change that . . . Something we didn't think possible might
actually happen: This year's Clippers team might be the worst in
the franchise's illustrious history. The benchmark is the 12-70
unit of 1986-87. Having already won 11 games, this year's squad may
be able to squeeze out two more wins. And if this year's team is
bad, can you imagine next year's? Listen to what two key soon-to-be
free agents, Mo Taylor and Derek Anderson, had to say. Both wanted
out. Neither got his wish. Taylor: ``I was kind of pressing my
luck, relying on the Clippers to get something done. There's no
love lost. I can play the final eight weeks.'' And then there's
Anderson: ``I can't wait to get out of here. Same old story. Things
are so bad right now.'' Taylor was so convinced he was going to the
Knicks as part of a three-way deal that he stayed on the team bus
in Minneapolis until the trading deadline expired. Falk said there
would be ``several teams'' willing to pay the $71 million maximum
for Taylor. We'll see about that. The Clippers and the Bulls were
the two teams significantly under the cap that could have
facilitated things. (Orlando has to wait until August). Said
Toronto coach Butch Carter, ``It doesn't help when the two teams
that can help are impossible to deal with.'' Don't be surprised if
the Celtics make a move for Anderson, who could fit in well and
played for Pitino at Kentucky. They only have the middle-class
exception to offer, but Anderson may have to settle for that . . .
Fortson certainly went from disposable to indispensable in a hurry,
didn't he? The Celtics' excuse of signability in dealing Fortson
was nonsense; how can it be when they haven't even talked? If they
can't re-sign him, it's because of poor budgeting, not Fortson's
unstated demands. But at the same time, Fortson's agent, Raymond
Brothers, needs an introduction to Reality 101, NBA style.
Brothers's main experience is in football; Fortson is his only NBA
client. And while Brothers is absolutely correct about Fortson's
worth vis-a-vis Tony Battie, it's irrelevant. Fortson has no chance
to get that kind of money ($25 million) on the open market. None.
There are three teams with any kind of money to spend: Chicago,
which doesn't need a power forward; the Clippers, who don't know
how to spend their money; and the Magic, who have their eyes on
bigger things. Fortson, basically, is a middle-class exception
waiting to happen. That's not fair. But that's life. He may take a
little less for guaranteed minutes, something he will never have in
Boston. But if he's in it for the dollars, the Celtics may well be
his best _ and only _ shot. In that respect, it's hardly a gamble.
It's just hard to understand why the Celtics felt they couldn't
re-sign him when they know the market, too.
</P>
<P>
   Good guy reward
</P>
<P>
   It was nice to see Miami picked up certifiable good guy Bruce
Bowen. It was the Heat, of course, who gave Bowen his first chance
(one game) at the end of the 1997 season. The Celtics, with general
manager Chris Wallace beating the Bowen drum, brought him to
Boston, and he quickly became one of Pitino's favorites. Of course,
just as quickly, he became expendable . . . The Grizzlies are about
to change ownership in the next couple of weeks, with Chicago
businessman Michael Heisley taking over. Heisley is relying now on
the advice of ``consultant'' Dick Versace, who had a brief stint as
the Pacers' head coach and figures to play a prominent role in the
Grizzlies' organization (he's already assigned scouts for the NCAA
Tournament). That is not good news for current GM Stu Jackson, the
only GM in the Grizzlies' five-year history. Jackson has made
mistakes, but he also has solid support from franchise icon Shareef
Abdur-Rahim. In addition, new coach Lionel Hollins has the backing
of Abdur-Rahim and the other players, so if Versace does come in,
he had best tread lightly. Left unsaid is why Heisley has chosen to
ally himself with someone who's been out of the loop for so long.
There's family history between the two, but this is business . . .
No one was less surprised than Golden State boss Garry St. Jean
when his star player, Antawn Jamison, went down for the season last
week after knee surgery. No team has been hit harder by injuries
than the Warriors, who, incredibly, did not have their projected
starting lineup in place for a single game this season (and still
won't now that Jamison is gonzo). ``I'm just telling the guys to
try to have fun and play hard the rest of the way,'' St. Jean said.
``You never like to use injuries as an excuse, but this season has
been crazy.'' The jinx continued this past week when Larry Hughes
went down with an ankle sprain. He missed the game last Wednesday
in Milwaukee, but the Warriors still won, 91-86, thanks to what may
have been the most remarkable line of the season _ a career-high 37
points and a season-high 21 rebounds from Donyell Marshall. ``He
was an animal. He was a monster,'' teammate Mookie Blaylock said.
``I've been trying to get the animal to come out of his cage. He
did it tonight.'' . . . It took 55 games, but the Portland Trail
Blazers finally got a 30-point game from someone. Damon Stoudamire
took the honors Thursday against Orlando. Prior to that, Portland's
high game was a 27-pointer from Steve Smith Jan. 27 . . . Mike
Bibby on Kenny Anderson: ``He's like Mike Tyson. When he has his
head on right, he's one of the top five point guards in the
league.'' . . . Who said this? ``I think the key is to let these
guys continue to have time together, grow, learn each other, and
try to improve.'' Pitino? Nope. Portland GM Bob Whitsitt. That
sounds like Tiger Woods saying there's still a lot of room for
improvement in his game . . . Keep an eye on the Wizards the last
two months. They get to keep their own draft pick if it is among
the top three, and you know Jordan doesn't want to lose that. But
if it falls to No. 4 or lower, it goes to Jordan's nemesis, Chicago
GM Jerry Krause, who picked it up in the three-way deal involving
John Starks, Kukoc, and Hughes. Can you imagine Jordan having to
surrender a No. 4 pick to Krause? Jordan already is making noises
about going with ``younger'' players down the stretch, which will
undoubtedly improve his chances of getting a top three pick because
the Wizards won't win. Entering the weekend, Washington had the
fourth-worst record behind the Bulls, Clippers, and Warriors . . .
So, Horace Grant, you played for the Bulls and the Magic, the two
key teams that will have the cap room this summer and will come
courting. Which one would you choose? ``The Bulls have some pieces.
But Orlando, those guys play hard every game, and they have cap
room, too. I had a great five years in Orlando. It's a class
organization. I'm still making it my home, and I would never say
one bad thing about anyone down there, not Rich (owner DeVos) or
John (GM Gabriel) or anyone. The whole organization treated me
well. Whoever gets the chance to go there will be very happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
