</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-MCSORLEYBACKLASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE STICKING IT TO NHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What was Marty McSorley thinking? Perhaps the question should
be, was he thinking?
</P>
<P>
   When last heard from, the Bruins defenseman said he was
attempting to goad Donald Brashear into another fight. After the
tattooing Brashear gave him earlier in Monday's game in Vancouver,
that should be ample proof that McSorley wasn't of sound mind. But
rather than drop his gloves or apply a gentle tap on the shoulder _
excuse me, Mr. Brashear, would you suggest the rhumba or the tango?
_ he opted for the more direct salutation of a two-hander to the
side of the head.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the approach lacked something in, shall we say, subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   With one ugly swipe of his stick, McSorley became the latest,
and perhaps most notorious, NHLer to turn the game into society's
pinata. ``Slapshot'' Redux. Oh, if only the lovable Hanson brothers
could come back and spoof the rest of North America's professional
pastimes, hockey might one day be able to crawl out from under the
talk show and op-ed carpet bombing that erupts every time someone
like McSorley makes real life imitate art.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other sport, hockey, especially the NHL, is a
lightning rod for the politically correct and the quick-triggered
media. I wonder: If Pedro Martinez and Roger Clemens engaged in a
high-risk, and potentially lethal, exchange of beanballs this
summer, would a media horde storm Bud Selig's office? I doubt it.
If the NFL sees the likes of Jack Tatum paralyze an opponent again
with an open-field crackdown, will the pundits decry football as a
North American evil, a scourge on society? Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   But hockey is always there for the kicking. Especially in
America. My theory for that is two-fold: (1) Most of America views
it as a ``Canadian'' game and, because it isn't our creation, of
course it is flawed and inferior (this applies to soccer, too); and
(2) the basic rules of the game, especially the minutiae of
two-line offsides and the befuddling icing calls, just don't make
sense (this applies to soccer, too). It's an import. It's a little
confusing. Who wants to invest the time to understand it? And when
someone acts way out of line, it's nothing short of evil.
</P>
<P>
   How did John Rocker ever omit the Rangers, Islanders, and Devils
from his venomous spew? Someone really should ring up ol' RedNeck
and tell him what wondrous opportunities await the next time he
slithers out of the bayou.
</P>
<P>
   There is no defending what McSorley did, and people should be
disturbed and angry for his attack on Brashear. But that ire should
be appropriately directed at one place _ squarely on the chin of
Martin James McSorley _ and left there.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is a great game. And if you're going to throw up its
institutional tolerance for fighting as your foundation to deride
it, then come back to me when baseball eradicates the brushback
pitch, when football once and for all stops the use of a helmet as
a weapon. Personally, I find the NBA unwatchable, but I will admit
that it's probably the cleanest and least dangerous of the bunch.
(Now if that's why I find it so unappealing, maybe I need more
therapy than my multiple personalities believed.)
</P>
<P>
   Allow me this one entertainment crossover. These folks who get
in such a dander over hockey, how do they explain society's
acceptance of the film industry? Pornography and violence (the
latter disguised as the ``action'' genre) make up a huge portion of
the flick biz. It's an industry that thrives on debasing
(especially females) and dismembering (carnage is rarely gender
sensitive). But as a society, we barely blink an eye (perhaps for
fear of missing a single frame).
</P>
<P>
   Is it because film is fantasy? Hey, don't believe for a second
that sports is anything less.
</P>
<P>
   TV wades in the same cesspool of porn and violence, just
slightly toned down, but, on average, every household in North
America must keep one TV warm about 10 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   But think for a second. What's more American than movies and TV?
What's easier to understand? Just sit back and enjoy the show.
</P>
<P>
   Please, go ahead, condemn McSorley. I'll even buy arguments that
the league could have issued a stiffer suspension than the
league-high 23 (at minimum) he received. Mayhem has no place in the
NHL. It has no place anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're worried that your kid might have picked up the
wrong message from what McSorley did, then I suggest you sit down
with your kid (what, you thought Charles Barkley was going to do
it?) and explain that victimizing people has no place in society _
be it the sidewalks, sports, or cinema. Your son or daughter then
probably will say, ``Hey, isn't this the same speech you gave me
about Bill Clinton?''
</P>
<P>
   The legal game
</P>
<P>
   McSorley isn't expected to comment until he finds out where the
Canadian legal system takes him. One reason the league acted so
quickly, and refused McSorley's request to delay Wednesday's
hearing for 48 hours, was the hope that investigators in British
Columbia would interpret it as a sincere and speedy measure to keep
the NHL house in order. It has been more than a decade since an NHL
player was put through the paces of due process for a stick
infraction. Dino Ciccarelli, then with the Minnesota North Stars,
was sentenced to one day in jail and fined $1,000 for smacking
then-Leaf defenseman Luke Richardson over the head with his stick
in a game Jan. 6, 1988,at Maple Leaf Gardens . . . With no fewer
than eight defensemen, including ex-Bruin Grant Ledyard, the
Senators are expected to do some wheeling and dealing before the
March 14 trade deadline. Two other blueliners expected to be
shuffled soon: Tampa Bay's Petr Svoboda and Montreal's Vladimir
Malakhov. Both become unrestricted free agents July 1. Detroit
probably will make the most aggressive offer for Svoboda, and no
doubt the Panthers would love to place Malakhov behind countryman
Pavel Bure. The Habs reportedly would want Czech defenseman Robert
Svehla in return . . . Toronto general manager and coach Pat Quinn
is expected to relinquish the front half of his title at the end of
the season, and the successor could be either Nick Beverley, now
the club's personnel director, or ex-agent Bill Watters, faithful
front-office employee who now acts as special assistant to club
president Ken Dryden . . . Ex-Bruin Dave Reid, who signed on with
the Avalanche as a free agent this season for a cut-rate $475,000,
had a 2000-01 option worth $500,000 picked up last week . . .
Between them, Phoenix goalie Nikolai Khabibulin and Ottawa center
Alexei Yashin will have thumbed their noses at a combined $6.5
million this season. Fun with numbers: Someone who makes $50,000 a
year would have to work 130 years to earn that sum. OK, I lost my
head and forgot the 1.7 percent annual cost-of-living bump . . .
Amid the perpetual fire sale on Long Island, it appears ex-Bruin
defenseman/coach/assistant GM Mike Milbury made a steal with the
acquisition of netminder Kevin Weekes, picked up in the swap that
delivered a struggling Felix Potvin to Vancouver. Weekes, who went
into the weekend with a 3-1-1 mark and a 1.77 GAA in his last five
decisions, is considered on ``the fast track to the No. 1
goaltender job,'' according to coach Butch Goring. That would
leapfrog him over highly-touted rookie Roberto Luongo. And don't
forget: Milbury also picked up capable forwards Dave Scatchard and
Bill Muckalt in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Other notables
</P>
<P>
   Many compilations of NHL suspensions published over the last few
days neglected to include the 16 games Eddie Shore was tagged with
following his Dec. 12, 1933, cross-check that nearly killed
Toronto's Ace Bailey at the Garden. On a percentage basis, it
remains the stiffest suspension delivered by the NHL. The league in
those Original Six days played a 48-game regular season, the
suspension therefore leaving Shore sidelined for 33 percent of the
schedule. McSorley's 23-game hiatus amounts to 28 percent of the
82-game regular season . . . In the midst of sizzling rumors that
he'll be traded soon, Montreal netminder Jeff Hackett turned back
27 Phoenix shots last Tuesday for his first shutout of the season.
Now the Habs have two top-flight backstops, Hackett and Jose
Theodore . . . Don't figure on the Red Wings making a play for
Keith Tkachuk prior the trade deadline. But don't bet against
either Philadelphia or the Rangers making a huge play for him. The
Blueshirts would make the most sense. They easily could absorb the
$8.3 million he will make next season, and it would be especially
appealing if New York GM Neil Smith could convince his Phoenix
counterpart, Bobby Smith, to delete one of his higher-priced free
agents (say, Sylvain Lefebvre or Stephane Quintal) in the swap.
More appealing to Smith would be the less-expensive likes of Jan
Hlavac and/or Radek Dvorak _ two forwards with considerable upside
. . . McSorley, who was working for a pro-rated $600,000 this
season, was due about $140,000 prior to his suspension. In
accordance with the CBA, slightly more than 50 percent ($72,000)
will go to a fund benefiting needy players. McSorley, though no
longer able to work, still will receive slightly less than $70,000
between now and the April 9 conclusion of the regular season. Who
says crime doesn't pay? McSorley made millions over his career. He
would earn high marks here if he now designated his remaining pay
to charity, preferably to one designated by Brashear . . . Look for
Montreal's Brian Savage, out some four months now with a fractured
disk in his neck, to return to the Habs just before the trade
deadline . . . Anyone else notice that the Leafs began to slip
right around the time they brought in rent-a-wreck Wendel Clark (2
goals, 4 points, 15 games)? That's not to suggest he's the reason
for the fall, but it underscores, once more, the relative
worthlessness of looking to old guys to supply a character
kick-start. Clark didn't click with either Detroit or Chicago. Why
would the magic come back in a third tour with Toronto? Quinn, last
week to the Toronto Sun when asked about Clark's play: ``It
probably doesn't matter how I feel, in a public sense.'' Now
there's a ringing endorsement . . . When word broke Thursday that
Pittsburgh superstar Jaromir Jagr was hospitalized with a thigh
contusion, every Bruins fan had to think back to the thigh
contusion _ and subsequent ossification _ that sent Cam Neely
spiraling toward retirement. For those who care to remember, the
Neely contusion came courtesy of an Ulf Samuelsson hit delivered at
the Igloo . . . Hey, if Larry Bird would like to buy the Celtics,
how long before Bobby Orr makes a bid for the Bruins?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
