<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-ROADTRIP-     02-26 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-ROADTRIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO PUTS POSITIVE SPIN ON TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had only won four road games all year,'' said Rick Pitino.
``We won two and we thought we should have won a third in
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to indulge in overkill at this point, is there?
We all know the Celtics aren't either the old Big Three Celtics of
the '80s, the old, old Havlicek/Cowens Celtics of the '70s, or the
old, old, old Russell/Cooz Celtics of the '50s and '60s. These guys
are what they are, a lower-echelon team whose big fantasy is to
play one lousy playoff game. Not being all that good doesn't make
them bad people. But it is downright sad and pathetic listening to
the president and coach of the team attempt to put a happy spin on
a club that has lost 12 of its last 16 games, regardless of venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very good trip,'' Pitino said. ``It was a good trip
because we played some good ball games.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah _ good. Seattle _ good. Vancouver _ good. But Golden State?
Yuck. Portland? Please. They were down 17-3 almost immediately and
when Portland found itself tied at 29, the Trail Blazers simply
stepped on the accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   And as for their first visit to the Staples Center . . . Don't
be fooled by the fact that the Lakers didn't win by 40 Friday
night. In one sense, the Lakers insulted their ancient rival more
by the sheer carefree contempt with which they played the entire
game, throwing up silly shots and just generally playing to the
crowd, secure in the knowledge that the Celtics were present solely
to play the Washington Generals role. So what if the final spread
was only 13 (109-96)? It was a 99.9 percent wire-to-wire triumph
(one tie at 4, lasting 11 seconds) in which the Celtics were never
closer than 4 in the final 45 minutes or closer than 10 in the
final 38-plus.
</P>
<P>
   In the final three games of this six-game Western trip, the
Celtics were an absolute all-or-nothing team, never holding a lead
against Portland, never trailing against a lethargic Vancouver
squad, and then never leading against the Lakers. Granted, the
Trail Blazers and Lakers are the two best teams in the league, but
to see the vast difference between what they represent and what the
Celtics now represent was very sobering.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you don't need to hear Pitino say, ``We played very
well,'' against Portland. Compared to whom? The Connecticut College
of Broadcasting? If that inferior performance is ``playing very
well,'' then the standards of what constitutes basketball
excellence in Boston have sunk lower than the South Station Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's give them their due. The Celtics were positively noble
in the first game of this trip Feb. 15. They went into the Delta
Center, spotted the Utah Jazz a 14-point third-quarter lead, and
then rode the glittering fourth-quarter performance of Kenny
Anderson to victory in a high-level battle of hoop one-upmanship
that excited everyone involved, even the referees.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of show that had you thinking a) ``Hey, maybe
they're better than we thought'' and b) ``Kenny Anderson must think
he's 19 again. It was the kind of performance that had you thinking
that this might turn out to be a very good trip after all.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. The Jazz game was on a Tuesday. The next game,
against the weak Warriors, was scheduled for Friday, Feb. 18.
Perhaps there was too much time off, time during which the Celtics
might have decided they were a juggernaut. After being handed a
15-point second-quarter lead by a bumbling Golden State squad, the
Celtics crumbled at the first sign of difficulty, going into their
dreadful quick-shot offense, a malady that is invariably coupled
with an inability to retreat on defense. The 36-13 third quarter
was a disgrace to the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Inconsistency being their official middle name, they played much
better in Seattle the next night, remaining in the game right down
to the final 20 seconds, when Antoine Walker first missed a lefty
attempt and then bricked a layup when the ball came right back to
him.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland putdown last Monday was followed by a curious game
in Vancover Thursday. The Celtics caught the Grizzlies in the
infamous first game home following a long road trip and received
another break when Bryant ``Big Country'' Reeves, who once dropped
40 on them, sustained an ankle injury six minutes into the game.
Playing with reasonable intelligence and cohesion, they ran a
miniclinic, jumping into a 25-11 first-quarter lead and then
slipping into cruise gear for the second win of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, and the following evening was another matter
entirely. The Celtics had actually played the Lakers well back on
Dec. 20, utilizing an effective full-court press and forcing the
Lakers to make some big fourth-quarter plays in order to win the
game. The Lakers needed no such late heroics in this game, moving
from that early 4-4 tie to a 30-17 first-quarter advantage that
resisted technical analysis. It just happened. It was a case of a
talented, confident team showing complete, and justifiable,
contempt for a listless foe whose minds had already flown the 3,000
miles home.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino didn't try any verbal razzle-dazzle on the subject of
this game. ``They were kind to us,'' he admitted. ``It could have
been a lot worse, and it would have been without their frequent
substitutions.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if the Celtics have any hope of coping with
Shaquille O'Neal, who helped himself to 28 effortless points and 15
even more effortless rebounds against the likes of Vitaly
Potapenko, Tony Battie, and even Danny Fortson, who, at 6 foot 6
inches, had more chance of gaining the Republican presidential
nomination than he had of stopping Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   But Pitino knew he wasn't going to stop Shaq. What he needed was
an overall team effort that reflected both talent and thought, and
which would be applied at both ends. So what did he get?
</P>
<P>
   ``We took too many quick shots, and they led to Laker
transitions,'' he said. ``We have got to learn how to play more
intelligently. One of these days someone here is going to get hit
over the head and think about what's a good shot and what's a bad
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's more, all right. ``If you want to make the
playoffs,'' Pitino continued, ``you've got to be selfless, you've
got to play like a team, offensively and defensively, and the only
focus on your mind has got to be winning, and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also mentioned that his team can't handle back-to-back games,
which, he said ``are what the NBA is all about.'' Ready for this?
The 1999-2000 Boston Celtics have now lost the second game of a
back-to-back situation 16 straight times.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Pitino was reduced to saying he is ``optimistic'' about what
lies ahead, partly because his competition (Detroit, Milwaukee,
Toronto, etc.) is currently in a collective funk.
</P>
<P>
   Is this what you want to hear? ``We are the Boston Celtics. We
stink less than the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, that's where the 16-time NBA champions are as
they come home to face the Dennis Rodman Traveling Circus Monday
night at the FleetCenter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
