<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COX-DEMOCRATS-HISPANI     02-26 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-DEMOCRATS-HISPANICS-$ADV27 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE HAS STRONG ADVANTAGE WITH HISPANICS IN BIG STATES
 &HT;    740&AMP;add. With HISPANICS-DATA. For release Sunday, Feb. 27.
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Democratic primary voting nears in the four
biggest states _ Texas, Florida, California and New York _ Vice
President Al Gore appears poised to reap the support of the large
Hispanic communities in all four.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has courted Hispanic voters from the very beginning of his
campaign. His original intent was to blunt the Hispanic appeal of
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who he expected to face in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Bill Bradley has mounted an unexpectedly strong
primary challenge, Gore's groundwork is set to pay extra dividends,
because the former New Jersey senator has done little to court
Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore effort has been exhaustive:
</P>
<P>
   His first campaign appointment was Jose Villarreal, a San
Antonio lawyer who is his national treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign set up a Hispanic working group that touted the
economic gains of Hispanics under the slogan, ``Ganamos con Gore,''
or ``We Win with Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   He lined up endorsements from 521 key Hispanic politicians in
California, Texas, New York and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   His political allies floated rumors of a possible Hispanic
running mate: Energy Secretary Bill Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   He offered a Spanish version of his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   He seasoned his speeches before Hispanic audiences with a
healthy dose of beginner Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   And the White House pitched in with periodic events showcasing
administration efforts on behalf of Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the Hispanic vote tends to be Democrat. Clinton got
61 percent nationwide in 1992 and 72 percent in 1996, and Gore has
tapped into the same network for his campaign this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's extra efforts to cement that vote were sparked by
Bush's success in his 1998 re-election campaign, when he got nearly
50 percent of Texas's Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, Gore's strategy is likely to give the vice
president an edge over Bradley next month in the key Democratic
presidential primaries in California, Texas, New York and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently has Bradley actively campaigned for the Hispanic
vote. The day after his bare-knuckles debate with Gore at the
Apollo Theatre last Monday, he visited Public School 24, a new
Spanish-English dual-language elementary school in the New York
working-class neighborhood of Sunset Park.
</P>
<P>
   He used the appearance to question Gore's commitment to health
care coverage, education reforms and economic development. He also
received the endorsement of a local Hispanic city councilman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know much about him,'' Katherine Cardona said of
Bradley. She knows a little more about Gore, but mostly that he has
been Bill Clinton's vice president for the last seven and a half
years. ``And I like Clinton,'' she added. ``So maybe Gore could do
as good a job as Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardona is the kind of voter Bradley needs if he is to overcome
Gore's lead in New York.
</P>
<P>
   She is 34. Her grandparents moved the family to New York from
Puerto Rico. She is the mother of two children, both in public
elementary school. She works in sales at Manhattan Latin Music
Center, a wholesaler of CD's and videos. Her husband, Silva, works
as a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to speak, but nobody was listening,'' Cardona said.
``But now the politicians are starting to pay attention to Latinos.
They see the country is big and is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hispanics currently make up about 11 percent of the U.S.
population, a proportion that is expected to grow to 25 percent by
2050. They will outnumber non-Hispanic blacks by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But only in the 1998 congressional elections did Hispanics start
to wield the influence expected of such a fast-growing population.
</P>
<P>
   In the hotly contested New York Senate race, for example, 82
percent of Hispanics voted for Democrat Charles Schumer, who ousted
Republican incumbent Al D'Amato. Similarly, in California, Gray
Davis received 78 percent of the Hispanic vote to help him defeat
Republican Dan Lundgren in the gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanic voters have become a powerful focal point for
candidates,'' said Henry Cisneros, a former Clinton cabinet member,
former San Antonio mayor and now president of the Spanish-language
television network Univision Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``A presidential candidate cannot win the election ... without
winning Latino votes,'' said Leo Briones, a Los Angeles political
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign has made little effort to reach out to
Hispanics. Last weekend, for example, he was the only one of the
major candidates for president who did not send a representative to
the Mexican American Political Association's 41st annual Education
and Endorsement Conference in California.
</P>
<P>
   And while campaign literature in Spanish is available from
Bradley, his campaign Web site has no content in Spanish beyond the
candidate's biography.
</P>
<P>
   Biography may, in fact, be Bradley's problem in the Hispanic
community.
</P>
<P>
   Few white American politicians have spoken as eloquently as
Bradley about the country's racial divide. And Bradley's commitment
to issues of importance to Hispanics is, at the very least, the
equal of Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's perspective is mostly the product of his 10 years
as a professional basketball player, a white man living in a
largely African American world.
</P>
<P>
   As a recent editorial in The Record newspaper in Bergen, N.J.,
suggested, ``had Bradley been a baseball player, and shared locker
rooms with more Latinos, perhaps things might have been
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
