<SLUG> BC-MASON-ARRESTED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-KNICK MASON IS CHARGED WITH ASSAULT IN BAR BRAWL
</HEADLINE>
  (UPDATES, revisions thruout) 
(nk) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anthony Mason, the former New York Knick who now
plays for the Charlotte Hornets, was charged with assault early
Saturday after he and a group of friends were involved in a barroom
brawl that left three people injured, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who has a criminal record on assault and other charges in
New York, was arrested with four friends about 5 a.m. Saturday in
Harlem, after the police were called to a Manhattan Avenue bar, law
enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with third-degree assault after he was questioned
by officers from the 28th Precinct, said Officer Chris Cottingham,
a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He was arraigned Saturday night and freed on $1,000 bond pending
a hearing March 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets were in town to play the New Jersey Nets Saturday
night at Continental Airlines Arena, but the arraignment delayed
Mason until after the 7:30 start of the game. He played midway
through the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's friends _ William Leary, 26; Anthony Kelly, 24; Mason's
cousin, William Duggins, 26; and Paul Boling, 34 _ were also
charged with third-degree assault, Cottingham said. The four live
in Springfield Gardens, Queens, where Mason grew up, the officials
added. Mason now lives in North Carolina. It was unclear if any of
the five were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, 33, who arrived in the New York area late Friday, got to
the bar sometime after midnight, the officials said. The officials
said that the fight broke out around 4:20 a.m. after Mason and his
friends began arguing with three other patrons at Perks, an upscale
and often crowded Harlem bar at the corner of Manhattan Avenue and
123rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   After breaking up the fight, the police determined that Mason
and his friends were responsible, the officials said. They were
taken to the 28th Precinct, about a block away. The three victims,
all men between 30 and 32, were treated at the scene for cuts,
bruises and other injuries, the law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The law enforcement officials said the fight started when Leary
bumped into one of the victims in an area of the bar where people
were dancing. The victim apologized, the officials said, but Leary
challenged the man to a fight that eventually spilled into the
street.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 a.m., the police had the fight under control and were
questioning victims and suspects, including Mason. He was arrested
after one of the victims accused Mason of punching him, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At the courthouse at 100 Centre Street in Lower Manhattan, where
Mason was later arraigned, Don Cronson, Mason's lawyer and agent,
said that Mason was talking on a telephone when the fight broke
out. Cronson, who spoke with Mason at the 28th Precinct station
house, said, ``Anthony was trying to separate people and get them
into a limo and away from the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Lewis, 44, a longtime friend of Mason's who was at Perks at
the time of the fight, said the basketball player was ``trying to
break up the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to get into the limo,'' Lewis said. ``Then a group
of about 25 people started jumping people, I got hit in the face, I
turned around and swung, then I got into the car. Mason went back
in to get my coat.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident comes a little more than two years after Mason and
Duggins were charged with the third-degree rape of 14- and
15-year-old girls at a party in Laurelton, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who admitted to consensual sex with the girls and called
the rape charges silly, pleaded guilty to two misdemeanor counts of
endangering the welfare of a child in June 1998. At the time, the
Queens district attorney's office said that the charges of rape and
sexual abuse were dropped after DNA testing did not link Mason to
the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who had been traded to the Hornets in 1996 and was
visiting New York when the incident occurred, was ordered to do 200
hours of community service with the homeless at the Progressive
Baptist Church in Charlotte, N.C. Duggins pleaded guilty to
statutory rape and to endangering the welfare of a child and was
sentenced to five years of probation and 800 hours of community
service.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the New York police charged Mason with gun possession
and he was sentenced to probation and community service.
</P>
<P>
   Mason was twice accused of assaults at the China Club, a trendy
Manhattan nightclub. In April 1996, three people filed a $54
million lawsuit, charging Mason with attacking them at the club.
Two weeks earlier, the police had been called to the club after a
New Jersey woman contended that Mason hit her. Charges were not
filed in that incident.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, he was charged with assault, menacing and
resisting arrest after a fight with two New York police officers
over a summons. The police said it took 10 officers to subdue
Mason, who, team officials say, is 6 feet 8 inches tall and weighs
280 pounds. He pleaded guilty to disorderly conduct and was
sentenced to 120 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks later, Mason was traded by the Knicks along
with Brad Lohaus to Charlotte for Larry Johnson, even though Mason
had averaged a career-best 14.8 points the previous season. Mason
has played in the NBA for 10 seasons, five with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Cronson, his agent, said that Mason had ``been good for a good
while now, but still, he comes to New York and wolves are howling
at the moon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
