<SLUG> BC-COMMERCIAL-REAL-1075(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIRING BUILDINGS FOR HIGH-SPEED INTERNET ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is little doubt what business the Intellispace
company is in. Right at the entrance to the company's offices at
1156 Ave. of the Americas, at 45th Street, there are racks of
telecommunications equipment that stand between the reception area
and the executive desks.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing traditional about the equipment or the
company's approach to the telecommunications business. It is all
related to the development of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Intellispace is one of dozens of companies to which building
managers are turning to prepare their properties for the high-tech
future, providing telecommunications services to their tenants.
From Bell Atlantic to the newest startup, each seems to have a
different technical approach and economic model, with most
providing a mix of local and long distance voice service plus video
and Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet connections have become increasingly important,
particularly for the young companies, usually referred to
collectively as dot-coms, that conduct virtually all their business
on the Internet. According to figures compiled by Insignia/ESG, the
real-estate services company, 75 percent of all the commercial
leases executed in Midtown South in the month of January this year
were by such technology-related companies.
</P>
<P>
   While most personal-computer users are content to rely on
dial-up modem connections with Internet service providers, despite
the occasional difficulty in gaining access, for companies
developing businesses on the Internet, continuous, reliable, high
capacity connections are essential. Other concerns in the field
include OnSite Access, Allied Riser and Eureka Broadband.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just at the beginning of a technological revolution,''
said Marc Josephson, the founder and chairman of Intellispace. ``It
is very difficult to do both voice and the Internet, so we just do
Internet.'' Not everyone might agree with this assessment, but
Josephson has chosen the Internet-only approach to differentiate
his company from competitors.
</P>
<P>
   He said that designing a system for the Internet optimizes the
connections for Internet use rather than trying to add Net services
to a system designed to carry voices. And, he said, standard voice
and data services may one day be available over the Internet in a
manner less costly than the present system.
</P>
<P>
   Josephson said he became convinced about the commercial future
of the Internet when he connected the building at 55 Broad St. in
the summer of 1995. The building, owned by the Rudin family, had
been sitting empty. It has since filled with Internet-related
tenants and become a leading example of how technology can help
cure real estate ills.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Intellispace has wired Rockefeller Center, the Jacob
Javits Convention Center and 190 other buildings containing over 55
million square feet of space. Recently it reached an agreement with
Hartz Mountain Industries to wire 18 properties in New York and
northern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Manhattan buildings wired by Intellispace are about 40
managed by Williams Real Estate for third-party owners. But
Williams executives said they are still trying to choose among the
vendors for buildings owned by the principals of Williams. ``We are
still trying to choose the right carrier,'' said Robert Getreu, a
senior managing director of the firm. ``We want the most
flexibility for the tenants and a full package of services.''
</P>
<P>
   As a property manager, he said, he tries to differentiate among
the many companies offering communications services using three
criteria: the financial capability to deliver promised services,
the range of services offered and the technology being used.
</P>
<P>
   Intellispace's approach is to equip a building for very high
speed communications and then sell each tenant the capacity it
needs. It installs a device called a router, which is capable of
handling 100 million bits per second of information and runs
individual optical fiber connections to each tenant.
</P>
<P>
   By way of comparison, a simple voice telephone line can carry
56,000 bits per second.
</P>
<P>
   Although all the traffic in a building goes through the same
piece of equipment, Intellispace officials say internal controls
prevent one client from seeing another's messages. Each customer
has its own dedicated fiber connection to the router, they add.
</P>
<P>
   The company makes the installation at no cost to the landlord,
who nevertheless must provide space for the router and space in the
vertical shafts in a building, called risers. Finding riser space
can sometimes be an issue, particularly in older buildings, real
estate executives say.
</P>
<P>
   ``As building managers we are concerned that we may fill the
risers with so much telecom wiring that when we want to do
something for a building there will be a problem,'' Getreu said.
</P>
<P>
   Intellispace also makes deals on a nonexclusive basis, so other
Internet communications companies can offer competing services to
tenants, easing landlord fears that tenants will be reluctant to
lease space in a building with only one Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   The landlords also share in the revenue produced by tenants' use
of the system, typically receiving 10 percent of revenues once a
certain threshold has been reached. After an initial charge of
about $2,000 for wiring a tenant's space and establishing the
connection, a typical monthly fee for 1 million bits of capacity _
which would be typical for a dot-com with about 15 employees _ is
about $1,000, said Bob Froberg, Intellispace's senior vice
president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   He said the system is flexible and can add capacity quickly if a
company grows or just has a short-term need. If a company using 5
megabits of capacity suddenly needs 50, he said, the change can be
made in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Intellispace executives say they are targeting the dot-com
companies in the buildings they have wired and selling them
reliability.
</P>
<P>
   The company runs a minimum of two fiber connections out of each
building and links them to two high-capacity fiber ``rings'' around
Manhattan that connect to long-distance carriers such as Level 3
Communications, Cable &AMP; Wireless and GTE Internetworking. A third
ring is due to go in operation within 60 days, company officials
said, adding to redundancy.
</P>
<P>
   The system is designed so that if any circuit is interrupted,
all the traffic is switched to one of the backups.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although this system bypasses the traditional telephone company
switching system, Froberg noted that Bell Atlantic built the
company's fiber rings in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dot-coms live on the Internet so they need high-speed,
dedicated service,'' Froberg said, adding that the ability to scale
up the amount of service is important as well. ``But other
businesses are seeing the need for employees to have access to the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   For a company that is selling the future, it is using
well-established marketing techniques. It is mounting a print
advertising campaign on the city's subways and commuter railways.
And it is using a direct sales force _ live people talking to other
live people _ to persuade landlords to allow their buildings to be
wired and tenants to sign up for service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do things like host a breakfast in the lobby of a
building to explain what we are offering,'' Froberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently received a $35 million investment from
Chase Capital Partners, an affiliate of Chase Manhattan Corp., and
Weston Presidio Capital, both venture capital operations.
</P>
<P>
   Intellispace officials say they are using the funds to expand
regionally and, they hope, nationally. The company has opened
offices in Philadelphia and Princeton, N.J., and is preparing to
open offices in Boston; Stamford, Conn.; and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are using the investment to expand rapidly,'' Josephson
said. ``In 2000, we expect to be in Baltimore, Richmond, Atlanta,
Chicago, Dallas and San Francisco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
