<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9588 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-SCIOSCIA-LADN     02-26 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SCIOSCIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIOSCIA'S STYLE: KEEP IT SIMPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- There is no truth to the rumor that when Mike
Scioscia held his first full-squad team meeting the other day, he
preached bleeding periwinkle blue, and paying homage to the big
Angel in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   No, the new Angels manager is his own man. And even though Tommy
Lasorda was his big league manager for 13 seasons with the Dodgers,
Scioscia won't copy Lasorda's or anybody else's style. However, he
has learned much from Lasorda and others who have tutored him over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a little part of a lot of people,'' said Scioscia, 41.
``Roy Campanella, Del Crandall and John Roseboro were big
influences on me at an early age. Not just giving me a foundation
for being a catcher, but what it takes to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy magnified it with communication. He'd get a guy to
compete at a level higher than that guy thought he could. And he
made guys love to work hard. Tommy had a tremendous passion for the
game and was a great instructor. He gave you the confidence you
could be better. He was a tireless worker with endless
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia's managerial approach is simple -- ``I'm myself,'' he
said. ``I talk to them like you'd want to be treated yourself --
with respect and communication. I'm not going to program myself to
be something I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty simple person, I'm not anything complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia often talks about his ``limited skills'' as a player.
Yet he got the most out of himself and he parlayed it into a
successful major league career. It is what the Angels are hoping he
can do for them -- get the most out of the players he has.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have been considered a team with talent in recent
years, but it hasn't translated into any playoff appearances. At
best, the Angels are contenders in August, pretenders in September.
</P>
<P>
   Angels general manager Bill Stoneman selected Scioscia from a
group of qualified candidates including some with major league
managerial experience. Scioscia's level of managerial experience
reached triple-A Albuquerque, where he went 65-74 in the Pacific
Coast League last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far he's been great,'' Stoneman said. ``He's an upbeat
person, and that came out right from the first interview with him.
Nothing's changed that. He also understands the game well. And his
thoroughness and preparation are something that's impressed
everybody here.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he was a catcher, Scioscia's ability to work with
pitchers is a bonus. He recalled being a 21-year-old rookie and
having a conversation with Don Sutton, at the time a sage
38-year-old veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I made a suggestion to him he kind of looked at
me like, `Yeah, right,' '' Scioscia said. ``But later on, he
listened to me and began to trust me. He'd ask me, 'What do you
think we should do here?' That's the kind of trust that is the
foundation of an organization. That's what we're putting together
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Angels players agree. Whereas former manager Terry
Collins was a respected baseball mind, he didn't communicate with
his players well. Scioscia, though, seems to be more in touch with
the modern-day player and their egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``His communication skills are great,'' said Matt Walbeck, who,
along with the other catchers in camp, has spent the most time with
Scioscia. ``He gets people loose and laughing and having fun.
That's a big part of his job. But he also demands that you work
hard. There's not a lot of time for idle chit-chat. It's a great
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent time in a totally different business,'' Stoneman said
of his years in the banking business. ``When you're in management,
communication is really important. Baseball is not any different.
Mike is a good communicator. He seems to make the players and staff
feel very comfortable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
