<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9669 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DIALLO-JURY-NYT     02-26 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-JURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JUROR SUGGESTS PROSECUTION WAS THE REASON FOR ACQUITTAL
</HEADLINE>
  (With NYPD-DIALLO) 
(rk) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jurors stood firm Saturday in their pledge to remain silent on
how, and why, they had acquitted the four police officers charged
with murdering Amadou Diallo. But one member of the panel, speaking
generally about how they had reached their decision, pointed to the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The juror, who insisted on anonymity because, she said, she
feared for her safety, said the panel's acquittal of the officers
was based on the evidence and the legal charges as explained by the
judge, and not on personal feelings about what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone is not happy with the verdict, they need to look at
the prosecution, and that is all that I'm going to say,'' the juror
said in a brief telephone interview. ``If they find fault with the
verdict, that's where they need to look _ at the prosecution. We
could only go on what was presented to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The juror refused to elaborate on what she found lacking in the
evidence presented by the Bronx district attorney's office, which
had brought murder charges against the officers, who fired 41 times
at Diallo in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   She would not discuss what she or other jurors thought of the
defense, nor would she say specifically how much the testimony of
the police officers mattered in their decision. ``I'm not going to
give you what I thought of them,'' she said. ``We went through all
evidence that was presented to us.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Robert Johnson, the Bronx district attorney,
defended the prosecution's handling of the case Saturday. ``We
tried the case to get to the summation with the strongest case
possible,'' the spokesman, Steven Reed, said, adding, ``We felt we
put on the strongest case that we could.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the jury, made up of four blacks and eight
whites, maintained their silence about the deliberations Saturday.
Reached by telephone or at their homes, several said that they had
given specific instructions to the judge, Justice Joseph C. Teresi,
that they did not wish to speak to the news media about their
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all decided not to discuss it,'' the forewoman, Arlene
Taylor, said through the screen door of her home in East Berne,
near Albany. ``I'm not going to discuss it. I'm tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Another juror, Thomas Knowles, answering the door at his upstate
home, said that the group was considering issuing a statement or
speaking publicly Sunday, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hell,'' he said, referring to the barrage of
interview requests from reporters. He would not comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Timothy DeTraglia, a juror and the monsignor at
Christ the Light American Catholic Church in Albany, said he would
abide by the jury's decision to remain quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at the church, he said that he had checked with several
of the jurors Saturday, and together, they resolved not to
elaborate on the verdict. ``I do feel it was a fair deliberation,''
he said, adding that the difficulty of making the decision spoke
for itself. ``We spent 21 hours doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   And a man who identified himself as the husband of another
juror, Valerie Brown, and answered the door at her home, said that
Brown would not answer any questions. But, he added, ``If you want
to find out what happened, go ask the prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   The juror who spoke anonymously said she had been deluged not
only by media inquiries but by numerous callers over the last week
who had just hung up on her. Afraid for her safety, she installed a
caller identification box on her telephone. She did not anticipate
any of this, she said, when she answered the summons to serve on a
jury. ``I went there to serve but definitely not to have my rights
infringed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the verdict, she noted several times that the panel
asked the judge to read back and clarify each of the charges. ``In
a court of law, it doesn't matter what you feel,'' she said. ``I
can live with the decision I made on a legal standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the jury did not concern itself with the potential
public reaction. ``I pray it will never play any part in a jury
deliberating on a case,'' she said. ``That's not what the law
states. You have to go with the evidence presented before you.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``A man lost his life. That should not be
forgotten.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9825 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RUN-COWTOWN-MARATHON-     02-26 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-COWTOWN-MARATHON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPRISE ENTRY FROM MEXICO TOPS COWTOWN MARATHON RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The spotlight might have shone on Olympian
Keith Brantly in yesterday's Cowtown Marathon, but a 30-year-old
late entry from Mexico stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   Santos Ortega, who had been in Dallas since Thursday but who
didn't register until about 10 minutes before the race, erased the
oldest Cowtown record, blazing to victory in 2 hours, 17 minutes,
35 seconds. The record of 2:20:13 had weathered challenges since
1980, when Roger Martindill of Hamilton, Ontario, set it.
</P>
<P>
   But Ortega showed up on a cool, overcast morning at the Fort
Worth Stockyards with the record in his sights.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told his manager that he was coming here to break the
record for the $1,000,''said Dallas resident Joe Badillo, who helps
manage Ortega. A $1,000 bonus is awarded for a course record.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega, of Toluca, didn't have a clue that an Olympian was in
the field. In fact, he said he had never heard of Keith Brantly,
the 28th finisher in the 1996 Olympic Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful the knowledge could have spurred him to a better
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega started fast and had no serious challenger as he became
the fourth consecutive Mexican runner sponsored by El Conejo (''The
Rabbit'') Bus Lines to win at Cowtown. He took the lead for good
after seven miles, and everyone else became distant shadows when
the sun broke through the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Brantly was using the 26.2-mile run as part of his training for
the U.S. Men's Olympic Marathon Trials in May and said he never
thought about trying to catch Ortega. Brantly finished a distant
second in 2:33:46.
</P>
<P>
   Brantly actually was worrying almost as much about a friend
competing in the Women's Olympic Marathon Trials in Columbia, S.C.
He got regular updates on his cell phone during his run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a friend call me about four or five times,'' said
Brantly, who was carrying his phone in a back pocket. Although his
friend didn't qualify, Brantly was ecstatic with his run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really pleased,'' he said. ``This was a great training
run. I can't tell you what a relief it is to run this far and feel
so good. I've struggled the last two years with a hamstring injury,
and I hadn't run a long run of more than 20 miles in almost six
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Brantly was feeling good, he knew catching Ortega
was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was getting to 12 miles, I saw him coming down another
street, and he already was past 13 miles. And he looked good,''
Brantly said. ``I think his time is great on this course. This
course is pretty close to being as difficult as Pittsburgh,'' where
Brantly won the U.S. National Marathon title in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega, who also won the eight-mile Turkey Trot in Dallas in
November, said he had received a description of the Cowtown course
by '98 winner and teammate Remedios Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me the first 10 miles were hilly,'' Ortega said.
</P>
<P>
   The hills didn't seem to bother Ortega, who reached the halfway
mark in 1:09. However, Ortega said he became confused after looking
at his watch, and believed he was not on pace to break the record.
So, he sped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never looked at my watch again after I got confused,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ortega didn't know he would break the record until turning the
corner to Exchange Street and seeing the clock at the finish line
almost two-tenths of a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   When he finished his fifth marathon, Ortega had almost matched
his best time of 2:17 set two years ago Austin, and had his first
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would do about a 2:19,'' he said. ``I'm happy.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 2217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0220 </DOCNO>
