<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9858 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER27-COX     02-26 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Bush still No. 1 to GOP voters
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite his loss in Tuesday's Michigan primary, George W. Bush
is maintaining large approval margins among Republicans nationally
and in all-important California, polls showed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Among likely Republican voters in California's March 7 primary,
a Time/CNN poll found the Texas governor leading Sen. John McCain
48 percent to 23 percent. Unlike the Michigan primary, in which
Democrats and independents boosted McCain to victory, the
California contest allows only Republicans' votes to count toward
delegate selection. The state's 162 delegates are the biggest prize
of the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   A Newsweek magazine poll found Bush enjoying a 56 percent to 27
percent lead nationally among registered Republicans and those
likely to vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The Time/CNN poll involved 1,009 likely California primary
voters, contacted Thursday and Friday, and has a margin of error of
plus or minus 3.1 percentage points. Newsweek surveyed 750 people
on the same two days, with an error margin of 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley says he's a genuine reformer
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to woo independent-minded voters in Washington state,
which holds its primaries Tuesday, Democrat Bill Bradley said he's
a more genuine reformer than Republican hopeful John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain is a reformer and I'm a reformer,'' Bradley told a
campaign crowd in Bellingham last week. ``We both want campaign
finance reform. There's no question about it. But when it comes to
the environment, there's a vast difference between John McCain and
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley criticized McCain for calling a West Coast
salmon-recovery effort ``pork barrel'' spending, and said he had an
84 percent vote rating from the League of Conservation Voters,
compared with McCain's 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's sound bytes
</P>
<P>
   On the stump Saturday in Silicon Valley, Vice President Al Gore
said he will target California's Bay Area as the first place
``anywhere in the world'' that eliminates the disparity in access
to computers and the Internet between the well-to-do and low-income
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children who are denied the chance to master computers today
will miss out on opportunities in tomorrow's economy,'' he said in
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Gore touched on several issues important to the high-tech
industry. ``We need basic research and development, funded by the
federal government, to provide a constant stream of new ideas and
insights that can be used by the high technology industries,'' he
said. ``We need policies to continue the moratorium on taxation of
the Internet. We need to make the research and development tax
credit permanent.''
</P>
<P>
   Territories choose Bush
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush won the first four of more than two dozen
delegates to the Republican National Convention being chosen in
four presidential contests being held this weekend in U.S.
territories.
</P>
<P>
   Guam, American Samoa and the Virgin Islands each had four
delegates at stake during separate caucuses Saturday. Bush won all
four in the Virgin Islands. Republicans from Puerto Rico will
commit 14 delegates today at their winner-take-all primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain targets Virginia
</P>
<P>
   With polls indicating a tightening race, Sen. John McCain
increased campaign appearances and advertising in Virginia in an
effort to overtake George W. Bush in Tuesday's primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made a heavy weekend purchase of television time in the
Washington, D.C., area to reach its northern Virginia suburbs, the
state's most populous region. Until now, he had limited his state
TV ads to less expensive markets. Bush has been advertising heavily
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign added a rally this evening in Alexandria to
his plan for a town hall meeting Monday in Virginia Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls showed Bush leading by eight to 11 percentage
points, down from more than 20 points a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gore gives fan an excuse
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore didn't want Melinda Gallien to get in trouble for
playing hooky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was supposed to be at work an hour ago. My pager's been
going off the whole time,'' the young woman, a Hilton nameplate on
her lapel, said as she waited to shake Gore's hand at a San Jose,
Calif., campaign stop.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wrote a note to her boss: ``To John Southwell: Please
excuse Melinda Gallien for being late. She was with me making our
democracy work. Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
