A9864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HORNETS-MASON-1ST     02-26 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HORNETS-MASON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASON FACING ASSAULT CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
 (UPDATES, revisions thruout) 
 (With MASON-ARRESTED) 
(nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Running through drills at their
shoot-around Saturday morning, the Charlotte Hornets appeared no
different from any other team on any other day. But perhaps more
than any other team, the Hornets could handle the latest
development without flinching.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets arrived at Continental Arena before 10 a.m.,
receiving the news from coach Paul Silas that Anthony Mason was in
a Manhattan police station, facing an assault charge and an
uncertain future. Mason, his cousin and three friends were arrested
outside Perks Bar in Harlem about 5 a.m. after a fight that left
three other men injured.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, the former Knick who was traded to Charlotte in 1996
after several run-ins with the police, missed the tip-off for the
Hornets' game with the Nets because of his arraignment in
Manhattan. He was charged with third-degree assault, a misdemeanor,
and released on $1,000 bond this evening.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Mason got to Continental Arena, nearly four minutes
had elapsed in the first quarter. He made it to the bench during
the second quarter and entered the game with 6 minutes 24 seconds
to play in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest in a series of difficulties for the team, the
most visible of which was the Jan. 12 car crash that killed guard
Bobby Phills.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the season started, Derrick Coleman wrecked his
Range Rover on Oct. 27 in an accident that left his teammate
Eldridge Recasner with a collapsed lung. Coleman was charged with
drunken driving, but was later acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Recasner later was charged with fourth-degree assault at a
Seattle airport ticket counter after his sister and mother were
involved in a car accident and, believing that his sister might not
survive, he snapped at an airport employee.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Hornets' owner, George Shinn, has had his share of
trouble. Shinn was sued over allegations of sexual assault. He was
found not liable in a sordid trial, and two weeks afterward, the
woman's husband committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Silas was asked where Mason's arrest ranked among the team's
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of low on the Richter scale as far as I'm
concerned,'' Silas said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman could only shake his head at the news. Despite his own
history of troubles, he had been playing the best ball of his
career. As he bounced his 3-year-old son, Derrick Jr., on his lap,
Coleman struggled to explain how the team has still managed a 30-23
record through the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything that we've been through this year, we've
managed to stick together as a team and that's helped all of us
through it,'' he said before the game. Of Mason in particular,
Coleman said, ``We're more concerned about his well-being than
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   As word of Mason's arrest filtered in at the Nets' practice
site, Kendall Gill spoke of how an athlete is often in difficult
situations. He said that athletes had to be aware of that hazard
but that it was sometimes hard to walk away when confronted with
situations almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful when you go into bars, grocery stores,
even when you walk along the street,'' Gill said. ``You never know
when somebody is going to come up and try to start something with
you, say something smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Silas said he had concerns about Mason's being out so late. The
Hornets arrived in the area late Friday night, and the police said
Mason got to the bar after midnight. The police said the fight was
started by Mason's friends about 4:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not very comforting to know that one of my players was
out that late, but they're grown men and you can't put a harness on
them and keep them in,'' Silas said. ``They should know better.
He's got to learn sooner or later that people are out there looking
for him, and regardless of whether he was at fault or not, it's not
a good situation to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason has a criminal record on assault and other charges in New
York, but Silas indicated surprise at the latest incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all indications, I didn't think that anything like this
would happen,'' Silas said. ``He's a model citizen of late, playing
well, lost a ton of weight, said he wasn't drinking anymore. So you
have to take him at his word. Perhaps he wasn't and he was just out
having a good time and these things happen, but he should know
better. I have to find out exactly what happened and then I'll
either let it go or he'll feel my rage.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
