<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGOTTEN DICKSON IS HEALTHY AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -- His name is Jason ... Jason Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   Remember him? The All-Star pitcher in 1997, who led the team in
innings pitched and tied for the team lead in wins and shutouts?
That Jason Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson missed all of 1999 recovering from surgery to repair a
torn labrum in his right shoulder. But he's back now, and healthy.
And out to prove he can be the same pitcher that went 13-9 in '97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a forgotten man,'' Dickson said. ``There were a lot of
articles written this winter about who would be in the rotation,
but it was like I was non-existent. But I've thrown several times
in camp and they can see how I'm throwing the ball. I think they're
starting to remember me again.''
</P>
<P>
   After throwing 203 2/3 innings in 1997, Dickson pitched with a
sore shoulder in 1998, but managed to go 10-10. In the spring of
'99, it was discovered he had a torn labrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed it was tendinitis,'' Dickson said. ``I didn't know
what a torn labrum felt like. But what I thought was tendinitis
never went away. I battled through '98, but in spring training last
year I couldn't throw and I finally said something.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense of relief that something was wrong. Because
then I knew it wasn't that I wasn't good anymore or I had lost my
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson said his shoulder is fine now and he doesn't see any
reason why he can't pitch again like he did in '97. But he has to
win a spot in the rotation first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can contribute a lot to the starting rotation,'' he
said. ``I know my arm is solid again and I'm throwing like I used
to throw. I'll do what I can to make sure they don't forget me
again.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Scioscia's philosophies of managing is stablizing the
catching position and emphasizing the importance of the catchers
working with pitchers. It's something he learned with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the Dodgers -- they've had Roy Campanella, John
Roseboro, Steve Yeager, myself and Mike Piazza,'' Scioscia said.
``This is what they hammered into us for four decades, and you see
the success they've had in the organization. That's what we're
doing here now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hit 20 to 25 home runs a year, but if you couldn't
catch, they'd give you a third baseman's glove. In order to catch
you had to know the pitchers and work well with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad ''hit the (heck) out of the ball'' Saturday in his
first session of live batting practice, according to manager Mike
Scioscia. Erstad has been bothered by an inflammed left shoulder.
... The Angels will play their first intra-squad game of the spring
Tuesday. Scioscia is expected to announce the starting pitchers for
the game today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-26-00 2245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-Rockets-Lakers-HN     02-26 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-Rockets-Lakers-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lakers vulnerable against Rockets
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
One would imagine that after four straight losses, the last team in
the world the Rockets would want to see on their schedule is the
Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers feature the three-pronged attack of Shaquille O'Neal,
Kobe Bryant and Glen Rice, a trio that averages 66.5 points per
game. And this is the same team that has won 10 straight, including
a six-game sweep of a recent Eastern Conference road swing. Yeah,
those Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they really are playing great,'' said Rockets coach Rudy
Tomjanovich. ``I think we're the last team to beat them. They have
a great race going in the Pacific there (with Portland). Shaq's
always a big concern, and there's no way we're going to be able to
stop him. Maybe we can knock down his efficiency a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then you have Kobe with his athletic plays, and then of
course you have Rice with his outside shooting. I think in the last
couple of weeks he's really exploded a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   But you have to wonder if that same Lakers juggernaut isn't just
a bit leery of seeing the Rockets hit town, especially for today's
nationally televised game. After all, the Rockets have beaten the
Lakers in two of three games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try and stop Shaquille, Kobe and Glen,'' said
Steve Francis, who has averaged just under 22 points against the
Lakers. ``That's definitely a big task, but I think we have the
personnel who can do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any opportunity that we get, we just have to come out and play
aggressively because they're aiming for the best record in the
league while we're just trying to continue to get better every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if they played the Lakers more often, the Rockets would be
much better. According to Hakeem Olajuwon, the NBA is all about
matchups, and the Rockets seem to give the Lakers problems in that
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to bring him (O'Neal) out (from under the basket),''
Olajuwon said. ``That opens the floor so you can create. We have a
lot of guys who can put their heads down, drive and create. If Shaq
comes, then you can kick it out; if he doesn't, then make something
happen (inside). When you open the floor, then you force them to
play defense one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the team (the Rockets) is (built), with Steve
especially and then Cuttino (Mobley), and the way we move the ball
with pick-and-rolls, we make Shaq move. If we are successful in
doing that, then we have a very good chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Which they have done twice this season, something only Portland,
which shares the best record in the NBA with the Lakers, has done.
The Rockets lost to the Lakers 89-88 at Compaq Center on Nov. 10,
but came back two days later to rout the Lakers 97-81 at Staples
Center. They played again Jan. 30, with the Rockets pulling out an
89-83 win.
</P>
<P>
   And they're going for win No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to think about the things we did to beat them,''
Francis said. ``We beat them twice, and the one time we lost to
them it was by one point. I think that just as much as we're aiming
for them, they're aiming for us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been serious subplots in almost every game
between the teams this season. In the first meeting, Charles
Barkley, hoping to snap the Rockets out of an 0-4 start, bounced a
ball off O'Neal's head, sparking a wrestling match that forced both
to miss the rematch in Los Angeles because of suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Also missing those two games was Bryant, who had broken a bone
in his right hand and sat out the first five games of the season.
But Bryant played in the January game, scoring 17 points. But with
Shandon Anderson and Mobley hounding him all over the court, Bryant
hit just six of 22 shots from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   And now Anderson will chase Bryant again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, that's just the way it is out here in the West,''
Anderson said. ``These (shooting) guards are always looking to
score, but out here in the West they're really hard to stop, like
Kobe. You have a big scorer every night. I never seem to get a
break.''
</P>
<P>
   And the other part of the puzzle is the defense of Walt Williams
on Rice. Huh? Walt Williams? Defense? But it's true. In the three
games he's played against the Rockets, Rice, one of the top
shooters in the league, has made only 11 of 34 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player who can score from a lot of different
places,'' Williams said of Rice. ``I just try to keep the ball out
of his hands and not let him get into scoring position. That's just
me playing against him for a lot of years and knowing what he likes
to do. I know his tendencies.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Rockets know the Lakers' tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very tough team, but for us, we just want to go out
there and play as a team, do the best we can and play our own
game,'' Olajuwon said. ``If we play our own game, then we have a
very good chance of winning the game.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
