<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUSED NETS CLOSE OUT THE HORNETS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ For once, it wasn't the New Jersey Nets
who were embroiled in questions and controversy. Instead, they
played with poise and even exhibited a killer instinct Saturday
night as they pulled away for a 104-93 victory over the Charlotte
Hornets.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nets finished the game with an 18-6 run in which the Hornets
struggled even to get a shot off. On the other end, the Nets took
turns slamming in dunks that had Charlotte ducking out of the way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets, who have endured a season filled with tragedy and
turbulence, did not blink at the latest news, which came at their
morning shoot-around, that the starting forward Anthony Mason had
been arrested. While he went through processing in Manhattan,
charged with third-degree assault following an early morning bar
fight in Harlem, the Hornets took the floor without Mason at the
start.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Ellis was in the starting lineup, but Mason arrived at
Continental Arena midway through the first quarter and took the
floor midway through the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he comes he'll play,'' Hornets coach Paul Silas had said
before the game. ``That's what he's getting paid to do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nets ignored the unusual circumstances and focused on this
game. The Nets improved to 22-33, still believing that they are not
out of the playoff hunt, 4 1-2 games out of the final Eastern
Conference spot, but starting a hard road trip Monday in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the game, a duel ensued between the Nets' former and
present franchise frontcourt players, Derrick Coleman and Keith Van
Horn. Coleman had 24 points and 10 rebounds, but Van Horn, playing
with uncharacteristic aggressiveness, had 29 points on 12-of-16
shooting and 11 rebounds. He even rose in the fourth quarter to
block a turnaround jumper by Coleman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it was a block by the 6-foot-5-inch Kendall Gill against the
6-10 Coleman that helped secure the victory. After Coleman grabbed
a rebound of his own miss and attempted a dunk with just over two
minutes remaining and the Nets leading, 97-90, Gill soared from
behind and swatted away the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Two free throws on the other end by Stephon Marbury, who
finished with 21 points and 15 assists, finished off the Hornets,
who are 30-24. Gill added 23 points and nine rebounds for the Nets.
Mason completed his long day with just six points, all from the
free-throw line, missing his only two shots from the field in 28
minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mason finally arrived in the arena with 8 minutes 3 seconds left
in the first quarter, walking to the locker room accompanied by his
agent, Don Cronson. With 8:52 to play in the half, Mason, by then
in his uniform, walked to the bench, and he entered the game with
6:24 left.
</P>
<P>
   But he had little effect. The Hornets trailed, 37-34, when Mason
entered the game and were still behind by 56-50 at halftime. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Mason's absence, Coleman carried the Hornets, scoring 16
points and grabbing six rebounds in the first half. Coleman has
sometimes been at the center of turbulence. But in the Hornets'
troublesome season, he has emerged as the star he was expected to
be since his career began as the No. 1 overall pick of the Nets in
1990. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 19 games the Hornets had played before Saturday night
since the death of guard Bobby Phills on Jan. 12, Coleman had
averaged 20.8 points on 50.7 percent shooting, 9.9 rebounds and 2.2
blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just been on a tear here lately,'' Silas said. ``All I
know is he's producing and he kind of relishes the fact that we
count on him and he can produce.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, whose numbers had been in decline over the past four
seasons, joined the Hornets last year for a five-year, $40 million
contract, largely on the recommendation of Silas, who was an
assistant during Coleman's time in New Jersey. But Coleman dropped
30 pounds and has played with aggressiveness and maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody changes,'' Coleman said. ``It's just growing up more
than anything. I try not to worry about things that I don't have
any control over. I just come out and play the game of basketball
and just enjoy it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coleman has still had his moments. He started the season by
totaling his Range Rover in an Oct. 27 accident in which his
teammate Eldridge Recasner was seriously injured. Recasner
sustained a partially collapsed lung and returned to play only this
week. Coleman was charged with drunken driving, but was acquitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
