<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9877 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF--MATCHPLAY-HNS &LR;      02-26 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF--MATCHPLAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Woods roars into final, but Clarke eliminates Duval
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Perhaps David Duval made the smart move
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to be part of the buffet line that Tiger Woods
picks over at his leisure. At least you have a chance he might drop
the silverware. Or maybe he won't be hungry.
</P>
<P>
   But it's something quite different to get served up to Woods
when he's at his savage best, salivating with confidence, going for
a World Golf Championships Slam of sorts and armed with a margin
for error on top of it all.
</P>
<P>
   That will be Darren Clarke's mission today instead of Duval's.
</P>
<P>
   Woods held up his end of the bargain Saturday, winning his
quarterfinal and semifinal matches at the Andersen Consulting Match
Play Championship. All he did was go 8-under-par through 12 holes
in the afternoon while dusting Davis Love III 5 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   Confident? Just ask Woods' coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wakes up in the morning confident,'' said Butch Harmon.
``And he goes to bed at night confident.''
</P>
<P>
   In between, he just beats the tar out of people in his favorite
format, match play.
</P>
<P>
   And while there will be no dream matchup between Woods and Duval
today, it could be yet another confirmation that Woods has no equal
at this point in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Duval fell 4 and 2 to Clarke, the roly-poly Northern Ireland
native, during the semifinals as Clarke made six birdies to only
one for Duval, who earlier in the day had stomped Scott Hoch 5 and
4 in the quarters.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there seemed a more unlikely person to stop the Woods
steamroller, it is Clarke. He will present a striking contrast to
the slender, strong Woods today as he carries his ample,
apple-shapped body around 36 holes at the La Costa Resort.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Clarke will have to do is negotiate Woods'
bubbling self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (his confidence) is pretty good right now,'' Woods said.
``That pretty much sums it up. This is the best I've played in a
while, which is nice. It was nice to go out there and execute the
golf shots the way I know I can and make a few putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Harmon: ``It's pretty hard to play better than he did
(Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   After two eagles and four birdies in the afternoon, which
followed a less-precise 1-up win over Paul Lawrie in the morning,
Woods could allow himself to smile about getting to the finals of
the $5 million tournament. Today's winner will take home $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   While Woods seems to be getting better with each round of this
tournament, he also will have the luxury of playing a 36-hole
final, rather than the 18 holes of the first five rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said at the start of the week that anybody can beat anybody
over 18 holes,'' Clarke said. ``Over a 36-hole match, you're more
likely to get the best player to win. And, obviously, looking at
the rankings, Tiger is No. 1 and I'm No. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'd say his chances would be increased over 36 holes.
That's the way it should work.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's a little pre-emptive gamesmanship. Whatever,
Clarke said he plans on showing his face today despite long odds
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to play particularly well to have a chance
to beat him,'' Clarke said. ``Actually, I'm not sure how I'm going
to cope.''
</P>
<P>
   That last remark was in response to a mention of his
less-than-flattering physique. Harmon said he felt fatigue could be
a factor in today's final because of Clarke's lack of conditioning.
``Darren's a little overweight and we've been giving him (grief)
about it all week,'' Harmon said.
</P>
<P>
   Responded Clarke: ``He's been calling me all sorts of names. I
have to get into the gym, unfortunately. It doesn't appeal to me
much, but I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was going to bed early Saturday night, Clarke
replied: ``No. Just goes to show after all the hard work I've put
in this winter, my right arm is definitely stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   A few pints couldn't hurt against Woods, who obliterated Love on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Love had whipped Miguel Jimenez in the quarterfinals 3 and 2
when Love had five birdies and no bogeys. He had not made a bogey
in more than two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods dismantled Love with an eagle-3 at the second hole and
birdies at the fourth and fifth for a 3-up lead. Love won the sixth
hole with a 15-foot birdie putt, but Woods ended up shooting 30 on
the front nine and never let Love gasp for breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect him to do all that,'' Love said. ``He was
phenomenal. He never got himself in trouble and I never put any
pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Love didn't help himself when he missed a 15-foot birdie putt on
No. 7 that could have cut his deficit to one and may have tightened
the screws on Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of game and a lot of confidence right now,''
Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clark was doing a similar takedown of Duval. He took
the lead for good with a birdie on the 10th and made a short birdie
putt on the par-5 12th to go 3-up and send Duval into the
consolation match today against Love.
</P>
<P>
   For Woods, he will be going for his third $1 million payday.
Woods won the final two WGC events of '99, the NEC Invitational and
the American Express Championship. A win today would give him three
in a row on the global stage, a roundabout WGC Slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I play against the best players in the world, it's
going to be more special than a regular Tour event, just because
normal Tour events don't have the best players in the world,''
Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   None of whom have been able to handle him this week.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
