<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-SPY-1STLD-WRITE     02-26 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-SPY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFYING EXPULSION
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Fla, Md., Cuba, Switzerland) CUBAN ENVOY IS DEPORTED AFTER (UPDATES head, story with Imperatori being taken to Canada) 
(DW) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Cuban diplomat ordered expelled last week by
the United States on spying charges gave up his diplomatic immunity
Saturday and challenged U.S. officials to arrest him so that he
could prove his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI thwarted the attempt by the diplomat, Jose
Imperatori, to argue his case from a jail cell by taking him
straight to Ronald Reagan National Airport for a flight to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman for the State Department, James Rubin, said that
Imperatori would be flown to Cuba from Canada on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori, who was not handcuffed, did not say anything as he
was escorted from his apartment by FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary confrontation _ coming at a time when the
United States and Cuba are embroiled in a dispute over whether to
return a Cuban boy to his father in Cuba or allow him to stay with
relatives in Miami _ broke the normal standards of diplomatic
conduct, by which diplomats who become entangled in charges of
espionage and are told to leave the country would depart
voluntarily. Imperatori had said earlier through his lawyer that he
would not voluntarily leave the United States by Saturday
afternoon, the deadline he had been given. As a result, Rubin said
Saturday night, Imperatori ``has been expelled from the United
States for not voluntarily departing by the appointed time.''
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori was identified by the Cuban interests section, which
represents the Cuban government in the United States, as the
diplomat who was accused of having been in contact with the
American immigration official charged last week with spying.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has insisted that Imperatori did nothing wrong and met with
the official on routine business.
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori's lawyer, Kurt L. Schmoke, a former mayor of
Baltimore, said at Imperatori's apartment in Bethesda, Md., that
Imperatori would cooperate with any investigation and would be
willing to return to the United States to testify in the spy case.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Cuban interests section, Fernando Remirez de
Estenoz, said at a news conference Saturday that the arrest of the
American immigration official and the expulsion of Imperatori were
connected to the custody battle over the Cuban boy, Elian Gonzalez.
The State Department has called such a link ``utter nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrest and expulsion order, Remirez said, took place just
days before a court case concerning the boy, although the United
States contends that the charges involving Imperatori and the
American official ``went on for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The immigration agent, Mariano M. Faget, is a senior official in
the Miami office of the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
Remirez said that the accusations made against Imperatori and Faget
were false.
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori said in a letter to the head of the diplomatic
mission, Remirez:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am addressing you to submit my resignation, as of this
moment, to my position and functions in our beloved interests
section and to the prerogatives therein. I have decided to stay in
America, assuming all the necessary risks and consequences, to
struggle against the slanders that hurt my honor, and that of the
interests section in Washington and my own homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement read by Felix Wilson Hernandez, the deputy chief
of the diplomatic mission, Imperatori said: ``I have become the
victim of a major slander. I have been wrongly accused of doing
intelligence work in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He said one factor compelling him to waive his diplomatic
immunity and stay in the United States was his wish to disprove the
accusations against Faget.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government had issued an expulsion order for Imperatori
last Saturday, giving him until 1:30 p.m. Saturday to leave or face
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Although he could have avoided arrest by staying inside the
interest section _ an embassy in all but name that operates under
the auspices of the Swiss Embassy in Washington _ he chose instead
to spend Saturday at his apartment, where it would be easy to
arrest him. Schmoke pointedly gave out the street address and
apartment number at a televised news conference saturday .
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori was first accused of espionage after the FBI arrested
Faget and charged him with espionage on Feb. 17
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
