<DOCNO> NYT20000226.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9897 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DIALLO-PROTEST-860(2T     02-26 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-PROTEST-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCHERS RALLY AGAINST DIALLO VERDICT, TAUNTING THE POLICE ALONG
THE WAY
</HEADLINE>
   (With NYPD-DIALLO, DIALLO-JUDGE, and DIALLO-JURY) 
(rk) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a day of relative quiet, a Midtown Manhattan
rally to protest the acquittal of four police officers in the
shooting death of Amadou Diallo turned into a fast-moving march
Saturday, with more than 2,000 protesters sweeping down Fifth
Avenue and one large group marching about four miles to City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The group of sometimes angry but mostly peaceful demonstrators
grew along their meandering route as some bystanders, saying they
were troubled by the verdict, joined the march. The roughly
five-hour trek, marked by taunts directed at the police and a few
scattered scuffles, began shortly after 3 p.m. at 59th Street and
Fifth Avenue across from the Plaza Hotel, where some protesters
climbed onto the dry Pulitzer Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   One group that later marched to City Hall was met by a cordon of
hundreds of helmeted officers who formed a line behind the
wrought-iron fence that rings City Hall Park. There, the
protesters, standing on the broad sidewalk, directed their anger
and frustration at the officers who stood between them and City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Some held their wallets in the air, yelling, ``This is not a
gun,'' referring to testimony by the four officers who said they
shot Diallo because they mistook a wallet he held for a gun. The
four, who fired 41 bullets, hitting Diallo 19 times, were acquitted
Friday in the Feb. 4, 1999 shooting of the 22-year-old immigrant
peddler from Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd chanted ``Impeach Giuliani.'' One man
screamed, ``19 times, you sick murderers, you should be ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Takiya Stewart, 24, of Brooklyn, said she had just bought a
sweater for herself and a hat for her son at a Gap store on West
Fourth Street in Greenwich Village when the protesters marched by.
``We were shopping in the Village and we saw the protesters and we
decided to join them,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Galinsky, 35, who works for an Internet company, said
that he received an e-mail message last week that simply read,
``Four officers acquitted. 59th and Fifth. 3 p.m. Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel, like as white person I had to show up to show that
it's not just a racial issue, it is a human issue,'' he said.
``There needs to be accountability and as a white person, I wanted
to show that I support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, as the mostly young, multiracial crowd
marched down Fifth Avenue, hundreds of officers stood shoulder to
shoulder in front of stores like Bergdorf Goodman and Tiffany's.
</P>
<P>
   The large procession filled the avenue, prompting the police to
shut down traffic, and some groups of demonstrators broke into a
run. The move forced a column of police vans, patrol cars and
motorcycles, lights and sirens blaring, to race ahead of the crowd
to halt traffic so protesters did not mix with moving cars.
</P>
<P>
   With their numbers eventually climbing as high as 2,500, by some
estimates, the demonstrators tried to turn west at 42nd Street and
march to Times Square. But their path was blocked by a phalanx of
police officers, standing shoulder to shoulder, that stretched
across the thoroughfare.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few scattered scuffles, including one at Bryant
Park, when some someone in the park hurled something at the police.
The police said Saturday night that 87 protesters were arrested,
mostly for disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the demonstrators appeared well organized, with walkie
talkies equipped with headsets that they used to communicate with
one another and keep track of the police and different parts of the
protest group.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the city Saturday, residents reacted mostly with
calm, sadness and, in many quarters, a determination to take
constructive steps so that the death of Diallo would not be in
vain.
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem Saturday morning, the Rev. Al Sharpton, who had
escorted Diallo's parents through the events of the last year,
spoke to a gathering of about 300 peaceful but shaken people,
urging them to use the verdict as a rallying cry in the fight
against police brutality. At his side was Kadiatou Diallo, Diallo's
mother, who thanked the crowd for its support and said it was time
for her to return to the people who need her most, her three other
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think something has to be done, because people have to live
together with the police,'' Diallo said. ``We don't want to see
this happen ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   At a City Hall news conference Saturday morning, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani praised New Yorkers for remaining calm after the verdict,
which cleared the officers of all crimes, from murder down to
reckless endangerment of bystanders. Accompanied by Police
Commissioner Howard Safir, the mayor called on the Department of
Justice to decide quickly whether it would bring federal civil
rights charges against the four officers, insisting that no such
federal charges were warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``To try these men a second time for charges they have been
found not guilty, you would have to find a gross miscarriage of
justice in the way the trial was carried out in Albany,'' the mayor
said. ``I have watched a good deal of the trial myself, and
listened to lots of impartial experts, and it seems to me this was
a full, complete and fair trial.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Largely, it was a day like any other Saturday, with most New
Yorkers, even along Wheeler Avenue in the Bronx, where Diallo had
lived and died, going about their regular chores and activities.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors and the police officers in the case continued their
vow of silence, for the most part refusing to talk with reporters
and staying out of public view.
</P>
<P>
   As he had after the verdict was announced on Friday, Giuliani
appeared somber, speaking in an uncharacteristically soft voice,
and repeating his earlier condolences to the Diallo family. But he
devoted more of his comments Saturday to a defense of the police,
and praise for the jury trial system.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said a departmental investigation of the Diallo shooting,
which had been prevented until now by the criminal case against the
four officers, would begin. All four officers will remain assigned
to desk jobs and will not be allowed to carry firearms until the
investigation is concluded, said Marilyn Mode, a department
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation could lead to the dismissal of one or all of
the officers if they are found to have violated departmental
guidelines on discharging weapons. Safir refused to say how long
the investigation would take, but Mode said she expected it would
be completed in a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem, Sharpton said the verdict was a new beginning in the
fight against police brutality. He called for a federal
investigation of the case and said the verdict was simply a detour
on the way to justice.
</P>
<P>
   At the headquarters of his advocacy group, the National Action
Network, as he gave his weekly radio address, Sharpton told the
crowd that excessive force had been used when the four officers
fired 41 bullets at Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was Rodney King multiplied by lead,'' he said, referring
to the 1991 beating by Los Angeles police officers of a black
driver.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton spoke of the need for a federal review of the case, to
see whether the prosecution had been properly conducted and whether
the jury had received proper instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amadou Diallo and all of us have the right to stand in the
vestibule,'' he said. ``And what this verdict said is that we don't
have the right to stand in our own home.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton urged concerned citizens to meet at the United Nations
at 1 p.m. Sunday, calling the shooting death an international
rights violation.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Sharpton and Diallo have called for crowds to remain
calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who want us to take to the street so other
reckless cops can take target practice on our children,'' Sharpton
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo thanked those assembled for their support. She said that
for her, the most painful part of the four-week trial had been
listening to officers recount how her son had remained standing
after they fired at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the bullet has no effect on my son's body, that they say
he was standing still after they fired 41 bullets at him, that was
the most difficult time for me,'' she said, ``because even if
someone slaps your son, you would be hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   At 1157 Wheeler Avenue, where Diallo was shot, about 50
demonstrators held signs and passed out fliers denouncing police
brutality. They represented a variety of groups, including a
Marxist group, the Spartacist League, the New Black Panther Party
and a group calling itself Refuse and Resist. One group,, the
Rising Voices Coalition, called for the Bronx district attorney,
Robert Johnson, to resign for failing to win convictions against
the officers.
</P>
<P>
   The police, meanwhile, milled about on the corner of Wheeler and
Westchester Avenues, a bustling thoroughfare in the Soundview
neighborhood of the Bronx, where Diallo was killed. The
demonstration was decidedly calmer and less eventful than protests
in the neighborhood on Friday night, after the verdict had been
read.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Newark, 200 people rallied at the corner of Broad
and Market Streets, sponsored by the People's Organization for
Progress, and later marched to the Peter W. Rodino Federal
Building. Lawrence Hamm, coordinator of the group, called for a
general strike on May 19, the birthday of the slain Muslim leader
Malcolm X.
</P>
<P>
   Amiri Baraka, the Newark poet and editor of Unity and Struggle,
a monthly newspaper, criticized the verdict, and the decision to
move the trial to Albany. ``That's the Klan's court,'' he said.
``The Klan have gone indoors. The Klan wears blue uniforms now.''
</P>
<P>
   The police officers acquitted in the shooting _ Sean Carroll,
37, Edward McMellon, 27, Kenneth Boss, 28, and Richard Murphy, 27 _
did not speak publicly about the case Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
