<HEADER>
A9902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DIALLO-JUDGE-NYT &LR;      02-26 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIALLO-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIT TO DEFENSE LAWYERS TESTS EVENHANDED IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (With NYPD-DIALLO, DIALLO-JURY, DIALLO-PROTEST) 
(rk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the hours after their sweeping courtroom triumph on Friday,
the lawyers who defended the four police officers in the Amadou
Diallo case gathered at the Albany bed-and-breakfast that has been
their home for the past month. They soon had an unexpected guest:
the trial judge, Joseph C. Teresi.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers would not comment on the visit to the
bed-and-breakfast, the State House, but a person familiar with it
said that Teresi, of the state Supreme Court, had thanked the
lawyers for their cooperation during the trial and said they were
welcome to try a case in Albany any time. The person said the
lawyers had not invited the judge, and the officers, who were with
their families, were not present.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi made no similar overture to the prosecution, according to
Steven Reed, a spokesman for the Bronx district attorney's office,
a fact that is certain to raise eyebrows, and perhaps ire, given
the widespread criticism of the verdict. The Rev. Al Sharpton and
others have cited the wide latitude the judge gave the defendants
in claiming legal justification for their actions as one possible
factor in the trial's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said, ``We find it hard to believe, but if it's true it's a
matter that should be reviewed by the Commission on Judicial
Conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresi could not be reached for comment Saturday night. But an
Albany official who has known the judge for many years said, when
told of the visit, that it was in keeping with his character. ``He
is a really compassionate guy, and once it was no longer
prohibitive to do that I guess he would like to express some
emotion to the officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say the judge's visit was not unethical _ but
rather ill-advised. ``There is no judicial ethics rule that was
violated by talking'' to the defense lawyers, said Stephen Gillers,
a vice dean and professor at the New York University School of Law,
``but it creates a bad taste so soon after the verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit was one of several actions by the judge on Friday that
seemed to undercut the even-handed and even-tempered reputation he
had established during the course of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   He began the morning by announcing that he had barred a
reporter, Julia Campbell of FoxNews.Com, from the courtroom and
courthouse because a court officer found a tape recorder in her
bag. Teresi announced in court that he would return the tape
recorder only if Campbell's supervisor came up from New York City
to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Refet Kaplan, managing editor FoxNews.Com, said Saturday: ``It
was an honest misunderstanding. We realize that in these kinds of
high-profile trials officers of the court often work under a great
deal of pressure. Judge Teresi called us yesterday afternoon before
the verdict came in to discuss the situation. We appreciated his
call and we consider the matter closed.'' The tape recorder was
returned without a trip to Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi demonstrated no love of the media during the trial. He
refused, for example, to allow reporters to view the exhibits in
the trial, which are normally considered part of the public record.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, Teresi refused to allow David Bookstaver, the
communications director for the Office of Court Administration, to
leave his chambers for about a half-hour after the jury reached a
verdict, and before it was announced in the courtroom, according to
a courthouse official. The official said he believed the judge had
been worried that the verdict would leak before it was read in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Two sheriff's deputies took away Bookstaver's cellular phone and
would not let him leave the judge's chambers until about 20 minutes
before the verdict was read, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstaver would not comment on the incident except to say it
was ``unacceptable,'' and that he was seeking legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the verdict leaked out anyway. The courthouse
official said that an Albany law enforcement official gave at least
one member of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association who was in the
back of the courtroom a heads-up on the verdict before it was
announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
