<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-26 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-COLEY-NY     02-26 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-COLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA WINS IN KNOCKOUT OVER COLEY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Derrell Coley did a lot of talking before his fight
against Oscar De La Hoya Saturday night at Madison Square Garden.
He fumed that he had been ignored. He said he was going to destroy
De La Hoya, because De La Hoya had made him wait so long for a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   But anger and talk can get a boxer only so far. Ultimately it
comes down to talent, skill and punching power as De La Hoya proved
Saturday night by knocking out Coley with a crushing left hand to
the body at the end of the seventh round before a crowd of 13,814
at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya (32-1) controlled the fight almost from start to
finish and it became evident that Coley (34-2-2) was in over his
head. The victory sets up the possibility of a rematch with Felix
Trinidad, who handed De La Hoya his only professional loss in a
controversial majority decision in Las Vegas on Sept. 18. Trinidad
will fight David Reid, the World Boxing Association
superwelterweight champion, in Las Vegas on March 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only the beginning,'' De La Hoya said. ``I said my
plans for me were four fights, four knockouts. No disrespect to
Coley, he was the first. I've got three more knockouts coming this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley was tentative to start, and in the first couple of rounds
it seemed he could not figure out what he wanted to do. De La Hoya
was not using his jab, but he was putting his punches together in
combinations, and he was landing effectively to Coley's body. De La
Hoya was catching most of Coley's punches on his gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Coley woke up in the fourth round and landed a straight right
hand that rocked De La Hoya. The crowd went wild. But De La Hoya
came back and wobbled Coley with a left under the chin. De La Hoya
continued the barrage, but he could not finish off Coley. By the
sixth round De La Hoya had found his jab and was putting it to good
use. Coley's right eye had begun to swell from the constant
pounding of De La Hoya's jab. It ended in the seventh round with De
La Hoya's powerful shot to Coley's stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got me with a body shot right down the middle,'' Coley
said. ``He didn't do anything that surprised me. But I wasn't as
strong as I thought I was going into the fight. I could have got
up, but I didn't have it in me. I was too weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Coley said he could not see out of his right eye and he could
not breathe. The bout against Coley, the World Boxing Council No. 1
contender, was an eliminator for the championship. If Trinidad wins
the bout against Reid, he will have to vacate the WBC welterweight
title or fight De La Hoya in a rematch. Under the framework of a
deal that was worked out between Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter,
and Don King, Trinidad's promoter, De La Hoya could keep the WBC
welterweight title if he won or lost the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Coley had trained for about three months for this bout and he
had promised to make De La Hoya pay for making him wait 19 months
for the opportunity to fight him. The question was whether Coley
could harness that anger and use it to fuel him to victory. He
couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   In the co-feature bout of the night, Arturo Gatti (31-4) lived
up to his nickname, Thunder, with a devastating knockout of Joey
Gamache (55-4) at 41 seconds of the second round in a
junior-welterweight bout. Gatti had knocked down Gamache twice in
the first round, sending him through the bottom rope with a hard
right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti landed a vicious left hook to the jaw after the bell
sounded. Gamache came out shaky in the second round and Gatti
nailed Gamache with a left hand that backed him up. Gatti threw a
right uppercut that snapped Gamache upward, then he followed with a
left-right combination that sent Gamache falling backward to the
floor. The back of Gamache's head hit the canvas as he fell and
Referee Benji Estaves waved the fight off as soon as Gamache hit
the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti, who officially weighed in at 141 pounds on Friday,
entered the ring weighing 160 pounds. According to CompuBox punch
statistics, Gamache landed just 12 punches in the short fight.
Gamache walked out of the ring, but was taken to St. Vincent's
Hospital for a precautionary CAT scan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect the fight to end that quickly,'' Gatti said.
``I feel stronger than ever. After the first round I knew I was too
strong for him. The jab opened up opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatti said he wanted to fight for a world championship at 140
pounds by November, possibly against Kostya Tszyu, the WBC
140-pound champion.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
